<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA ROUTS MARYLAND AND MOVES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - A month ago, UCLA lost at Arizona State by 29
points. Two weeks ago, the Bruins were on the brink of NCAA
Tournament elimination. Nine days ago, they squeaked past
Washington State, the worst team in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they're in the Sweet 16 - and playing like a national
championship contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just incredible,'' Bruins forward Rico Hines said.
``That's the only word I can think of. It's incredible how we've
responded the last month. People thought we had given up. Instead,
we did some soul-searching. We knew we were better than we showed
in Arizona, and we've come out and proven it. Now, we feel like
we're unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll get no argument from third-seeded Maryland, which
watched helplessly as the Bruins rolled to a 105-70 second-round
victory Saturday before 26,358 in the Metrodome - a victory as
stunning as it was devastating.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 UCLA will play No. 2 Iowa State on Thursday in the Sweet
16 at The Palace of Auburn Hills (Mich.).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anyone could beat UCLA tonight,'' Maryland
forward Terence Morris said. ``It would be pretty tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Bruins point guard Earl Watson the best player on
the floor, he was perfect: no turnovers, four steals and a
school-record 16 assists. He also made four consecutive 3-pointers
in surreal two-minute stretch early in the second half, pushing
UCLA's 16-point halftime lead to 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew coming into the game that I couldn't turn the ball
over,'' Watson said. ``I had six turnovers against Ball State. I
came out more conservative, more solid, and it allowed me to focus
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (21-11) were awesome in the final 30 minutes against
Cal and brilliant in the season-finale against Washington. But they
haven't played this well in the tournament since the 1995
championship charge, when Ed O'Bannon's team smashed Mississippi
State by 19 points in the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the 1997 Bruins, who won the Pac-10 title and came
within eight points of the Final Four, put on a show like this. And
that team wasn't flirting with tournament elimination on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' forward Jason Kapono said. ``In the middle of
the Pac-10 season, people were counting us out. They said we were
pansies and we didn't work hard. But we've proven them wrong. We're
in the Sweet 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything worked for UCLA, nothing for Maryland. Big men Jerome
Moiso and Dan Gadzuric combined to make 12-of-14 shots, score 27
points and grab 15 rebounds. Wing men JaRon Rush and Kapono made
five 3-pointers and scored 25 points. The Bruins shot 72.4 percent
in the first half and 62.5 percent for the game. They had 28
assists. Gadzuric made his free throws. Even slumping shooter Ray
Young buried a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was a breakthrough game,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin
said. ``I thought our halfcourt offense was as sharp as it's been
all year.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the antithesis of the matchup in Puerto Rico in Nov.
'98, when the high-flying Terps thrashed timid, grounded UCLA.
Saturday, the Bruins did the dunking, with four alley-oops in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lobs and dunks mentally take away from the other
team's rhythm,'' Watson said. ``They've been there all year, and
I've been throwing them all year. It's really nothing new. They
just got completed.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA broke the game open with a 15-2 surge to close the first
half. It started when Matt Barnes tipped home a Rush miss. A
Maryland turnover became Gadzuric's double-pump layup. Instead of
calling timeout, the Terps played on, and Taj Holden missed an
ill-advised jumper. Before Maryland crossed midcourt, Watson found
Rush for an alley-oop. Suddenly,the three-point lead had expanded
to 40-31, and the Terps frantically called timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA was really sharp,'' Terps coach Gary Williams said.
``They looked quicker tonight than they ever did on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   The timeout did no good. Maryland committed two consecutive
turnovers, and with 2:22 left Gadzuric kissed a difficult
turnaround off the backboard. The lead was 42-33.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' nifty baseline drive slowed the Bruins' momentum for all
of one minute. Then Moiso scored from the low post and Watson hit
Rush with yet another alley-oop. A few seconds later, Watson stole
the ball from Morris and found Young in the corner for a 3-pointer.
His swish gave the Bruins a 49-33 halftime lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
