<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DREAM COME TRUE FOR ONE BRUIN 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - Brandon Brooks figured the first basket of his
UCLA career would come in the final seconds of a regular-season
rout against a Pac-10 patsy, like Washington State or Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Not against third-seeded Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not in the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is a dream come true,'' Brooks said. ``And
getting a dunk in the tournament is even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' dunk, with 2:49 left, was one of many highlights in UCLA
's 105-70 victory over Maryland. But his background makes it
special: Brooks, a freshman, was the starting goalie on UCLA's NCAA
champion water polo team. He joined the basketball Bruins as a
walk-on early in the sea son because they needed a big body for
practice. He had played sparingly in seven games before Saturday.
His resume consisted of one free throw.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be talking about the dunk from Westwood to Honolulu,
Brooks' hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the ball about the free throw line,''he said. ``I took a
couple dribbles downcourt and looked around, and I saw I was ahead
of everybody. That's when I started looking at the rim.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect? Perhaps: Asked if this was UCLA's best game of the
season, Bruins coach Steve Lavin hedged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stanford still kind of sticks out because of the conditions _
being at Maples Pavilion, playing the No. 1 team in the country on
their Senior Day, with our backs to the wall,'' Lavin said. ``It
was a kind of single-elimination, Russian-roulette, NCAA
Tournament-kind of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a breakthrough in terms of our transition attack.
Defensively, we had some pretty impressive sequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick start: To some extent, the Bruins follow forwa rd Jerome
Moiso's lead. When he plays well, especially early, they do, t oo.
</P>
<P>
   Against Ball State, Moiso played tentatively and made 5-of-14
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he was aggressive and effective, scoring UCLA's first
two baskets and making 7-of-8 shots for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time,'' Moiso said. ``At this point, you can't
expect the game to come to you. You have to go get it. That's what
I'm trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to see the ball, and when I do, I can get going pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem solved? In recent weeks, freshman Jason Kapono has
struggled in the first half and played well in the second.
Thursday, for instance, he was scoreless in the first and had 17
points in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' Kapono said. ``I'd like to think
it's that I'm a crunch-time player. Or maybe I'm not in rhythm in
the first half. Or maybe I don't try hard enough. Or maybe I'm
trying to be a passer in the first half and a scorer in the
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapono found a balance against Maryland, with two 3-pointers and
three assists in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: UCLA was a four-point underdog Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins set a school record with 14-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Watson's 16 assists broke the school record set by Darrick
Martin against Pittsburgh in 1991. It also tied an NCAA Tournament
first - and second-round record.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth-largest tournament victory in UCLA history.
The largest was a 49-point win over Wyoming in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are 6-0 against Sweet 16 opponent Iowa State,
including 3-0 in the tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
