u s BC-OLY-FIGURESKATING-KIR     03-19 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FIGURESKATING-KIRK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15-YEAR-OLD JUMPS INTO OLYMPIC PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH DENNIS, Mass. _ There are times when it all seems like one
big blur. Jennifer Kirk goes to Germany a couple of weeks ago
hoping just to stay on her feet. She ends up winning the World
Junior Figure Skating title and suddenly finds herself on the road
to Olympus. Huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all been so quick,'' marvels the 15-year-old Newton
native, who trains at Tony Kent Arena here amid the sand and scrub
pines of the Cape. ``It's taken some time to sink in. Just because
I landed two programs . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Kirk poked her head up from the pack of teens
who are going to chase Michelle Kwan all the way to Salt Lake City
in 2002. Just like that, she adds herself to the list of contenders
for next year's US elite world team.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Kirk was a novice, crowding around a TV with
friends to watch Tara Lipinski win the gold medal at Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch and you imagine yourself doing that,'' she says.
``Now, it's become more of a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The imaginary becomes possible just that quickly in women's
skating, where 13-year-olds can become prime-time stars and
15-year-olds can become millionaires. And possibility vanishes just
that quickly, too. Kirk understands that, which is why she's
keeping her toe picks dug firmly into the present.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as she got back from Germany, gold medal in hand, Kirk
went back to Harwich High School to resume her sophomore year.
She'll still be there next season, taking assignments with her when
she competes overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of skaters are home-schooled, but I don't want that kind
of a life,'' Kirk says. ``It's too much on skating. Anybody can get
injured at any time. What do you have to fall back on? Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's slippery out there, as skaters like to say, and this
winter's darling can fall out of the spotlight as quickly as it
takes to splatter a double axel.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a young skater,'' muses Evy Scotvold, Kirk's coach, ``six
months is an eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's wondergirl was Naomi Nari Nam, the 13-year-old
daughter of Korean immigrants who leaped up from nowhere to finish
second behind Kwan. This year, she tumbled to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   This year's wondergirl was Sasha Cohen, the 15-year-old daughter
of a Ukrainian mother and American father who also leaped up from
nowhere to finish second behind Kwan. All she needed to claim her
ticket to next week's world championships in France was win a
medal, any medal, at the junior event.
</P>
<P>
   ABC followed Cohen all week, filming the lead-up to what
everyone figured would be a walk-through. But she didn't even
survive the short program, falling on both the triple lutz and the
double axel. Kirk climbed out of second place to overtake Deanna
Stellato and amaze herself as much as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The title capped a breakthrough season for a girl who didn't
begin skating until she was 9 after watching the 1994 Olympics in
Lillehammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the whole Nancy-Tonya thing,'' Kirk says. ``Nancy was
so great and I admired her so much for what she went through.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk had been a gymnast and a Boston Ballet dancer who performed
five times in ``The Nutcracker'' (``lamb twice, polichinelle once,
party girl twice''). But once she got a taste of skating at the MDC
rink in Watertown, Kirk found herself hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I skated like every place in Massachusetts where there was
ice,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk ended up at the Skating Club of Boston, then migrated to
the Cape to work with Scotvold and his wife, Mary, who had directed
Nancy Kerrigan to a pair of Olympic medals. What they saw
immediately was a precocious leaper and natural performer who
soaked up instruction like a sponge.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went from a double lutz to a triple salchow in two
weeks,'' remembers Evy. ``It was the most amazing thing I ever
saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Kirk was third at the novice nationals, and could
have won. Last year she was third at the junior nationals, and
should have won. Sara Wheat, who did win, was resigned to second
after watching Kirk skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside, I felt I won,'' says Kirk, who lost because two judges
put her fourth. ``I know now it really didn't matter. But then it
was like someone punched me in the stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk could have taken another shot at the US junior crown this
year, but thought it pointless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to move up and get going,'' she says. ``All the other
girls were doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nam and Sarah Hughes, both younger than Kirk, were already
competing at the elite level. Wheat and Cohen were moving up.
Stellato was taking the giant step from novices. Why wait?
</P>
<P>
   The step was bigger than Kirk had bargained for, even though she
had all the triple jumps she needed. When she turned up at
Cleveland for last month's US championships at Gund Arena, Kirk
admitted to being overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was so big and everyone was so good,'' she said. ``I
just felt so little.''
</P>
<P>
   Buried in 11th after falling in the short program, Kirk came out
for Saturday's prime-time finale, saw a nearly full house buzzing,
and realized that all of America was watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came into the dressing room after warmup and she burst
into tears,'' Mary Scotvold says. ``She said, `I can't go out
there. There's too many people.' But within five minutes, she
bucked right up.''
</P>
<P>
   Just pretend your friends are around the boards watching,
Scotvold told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go back on the ice,'' Kirk concedes. ``But
after the first jump the people were clapping so hard, I thought,
`They're all here to watch me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk ended up seventh, and might have been fifth had she not
fallen on the triple flip. She wasn't alone there; Kwan had fallen
on an easier jump in the short program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made me feel better,'' Kirk says. ``I'm not the only
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, when the championships are at the FleetCenter, Kirk's
friends will be around the boards watching. And she'll be decidedly
more ready for prime time. She'll have a second triple-triple
combination and possibly a tougher one. She'll have more nuanced
artistry. She'll have gotten more international exposure. She could
be ``the next Nancy.'' She could be at Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   Could, could, could. It's all conditional, Kirk realizes. A girl
named Sydne Vogel won the world junior title three years ago. Where
is Vogel now?
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City is still two years off, which is why Kirk is
still studying her biology and geometry. Because it's slippery out
there.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Kirk and Hughes and Nam and Cohen and Wheat and
Stellato are chasing Kwan. But they're being chased, too. Two of
America's top three novices, Colette Irving of Winchester and
Louann Donovan of Medford, train with Kirk at Tony Kent Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep looking in back of you and in front of you,''
says Kirk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
