<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWBACKS ADD AN OLD-FASHIONED TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ For one of them, it is over already. He will never wear
his college uniform again.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of four seasons, Brian Cardinal of Purdue and
Eduardo Najera of Oklahoma have elevated their sport. Each has
brought muscle, coordination, shooting skill, determination,
brains, and, most of all, heart to every single basketball game.
Neither has ever taken so much as a second, let alone a day, off.
</P>
<P>
   They are so similar, and yet so different. Each is 6 feet 8
inches and change. Each is ruggedly built. Each can score inside
and out. Each would stand in front of an 18-wheeler to take a
charge. Each would run through the locker room door without opening
it if it was necessary to help win the game.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a major personal difference. Kneepad-wearing Brian
Cardinal is pure red, white, and blue. He is right out of a World
War II movie. He is a product of the heartland. His dad, Rod, is
the basketball trainer at the University of Illinois. He embodies
all the old-fashioned virtues coaches love to preach.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Eduardo Najera didn't speak English. There
wasn't much need for it in his hometown of Chihuahua, Mexico. Today
he barely has an accent. But there is no way Brian Cardinal, or any
American, could relate to the path that led Eduardo Najera to this
NCAA tournament confrontation with the player he most resembles in
college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps the best subplot in the entire first two days of
the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play a lot alike,'' said Purdue coach Gene Keady. ``They
dive on the floor. They take charges. They hit threes. They score
inside. They go all out. They are very similar in the way they play
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson saw it in a bit
more colorful vein.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I close my eyes and think of Eduardo and Brian,'' Sampson
rhapsodized, ``I picture the Revolutionary War with the fife and
drum. One of them has the drum, the other has the fife. Being
Eduardo's coach, I see him starring as the drummer. I see Brian
with his fife, wearing a white headband with blood all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are throwback guys,'' Sampson continued. ``We hear a lot
about throwback guys, but these guys really are throwback guys.
They could have played in earlier times. It's a compliment to them
that they play in this time, but these are guys who would look good
in tight shorts. There are a lot of guys today who wouldn't look
good in tight shorts. They wouldn't even wear them. But Eduardo
would wear them. Brian would wear them. That's what makes them
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else makes them special in Sunday's game. Together
they have played in 254 college games. Each is a battle-tested
senior. Each came into a scary situation, wondering whether he
could ever fit in. Each redshirted as a freshman. Each made a nice
impression in his first year, but not enough to suggest he would
become a star. Each has gotten better and better. Each is viewed as
the emotional center of his team. And each is totally grateful for
having the full range of experience a complete college career can
provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last five years have been the best of my life,'' said
Najera. ``I have had so much fun. I've matured. I've experienced so
many things that it's hard for me to explain. Those guys who go
straight to the pros after one or two years, they miss so much, and
they can never get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys who go straight to the pros miss pretty much
everything,'' echoed Cardinal. ``Not just the basketball, but
college life in general. I've had so many great experiences. I've
traveled overseas twice. I've been to Maui. I've had many great
NCAA experiences. I'm very thankful to have been in this
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Strictly speaking, there are differences in their games. Najera
runs the floor and puts the ball on the floor better than Cardinal.
Cardinal is probably a bit more reliable outside shooter. He has a
veteran's confidence; witness a cold-blooded 3-pointer with just
over a minute left that put Purdue ahead by 3 in its 1-point
victory over Dayton Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of basic versatility in a midsized body, and in
terms of bringing every physical, mental, and emotional resource to
the table, they are the same player. Each is as admired by his
teammates for who he is as for how he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the type of guys who will knock each other down and
then pick each other up,'' said Oklahoma center Renzi Stone, who
has known Najera for four years and strongly considered attending
Purdue. ``That's the way truly great competitors should be. It's
definitely not going to be nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Brian,'' said Najera. ``He plays
hard. He does what it takes to win. I feel I'm the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Najera is a great player,'' countered Cardinal. ``Very strong.
Very physical. It's going to be an intense battle between us.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar NBA situation, we could look forward to as many as
seven of these knock-down, drag-outs. But in the NCAA tournament,
we get only one. It's times like this when a VCR becomes an
indispensible ally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
