<HEADLINE>
CUBAN DEFECTOR RELISHES OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Jorge Diaz took 15 minutes of batting
practice with Rafael Palmeiro and Ivan Rodriguez on Saturday, spent
another 15 minutes taking ground balls from Bucky Dent and seemed
thrilled with every second of it.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Diaz proclaimed the experience a dream come true,
which is understandable considering he is the only known former
Cuban national player to defect not once but twice from that
country's Communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I didn't think it would happen,'' Diaz said after
his first workout with the Texas Rangers. ``Thank God it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, a second baseman who arrived in Florida on Thursday after
signing with the Rangers on Feb. 28, now faces the challenge of
making it to the majors. He hasn't played in an organized game in
almost three years and general manager Doug Melvin said getting
Diaz into an exhibition game will be difficult with only two weeks
left in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz most likely will start the season in Triple A where he will
have to prove he belongs in the major leagues. But after all he
went through to get to the United States, that might be the easiest
part of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficult times are over,'' said Diaz, using Rangers scout
Sammy Melendez as an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``The Spider'' because of his defensive reputation,
Diaz played four years with Villa Clara during Cuba's regular
season and another three years for Centrales in their All-Star
Series. But his life was changed forever in July 1997 when he was
suspended indefinitely from baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz's crime was talking by telephone to former Villa Clara
teammate Rolando Arrojo, who had defected earlier that year and
signed with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They considered him a security risk,'' his agent Joe Kehoskie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to play baseball again, Diaz attempted to defect in March
of the following year. He and several others, including Mets
infielder Jorge Toca, floated off the island in a 12-foot boat.
</P>
<P>
   The currents took them to the Bahamas where they were picked up,
detained and, with the exception of Toca, returned to Cuba. Diaz
was not treated kindly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little easier for him because he was high-profile
baseball player,'' Kehoskie said. ``He just couldn't disappear like
a lot of people disappear. But it wasn't a picnic. He was brought
in for interrogation by the state security people every three days.
Sometimes he was brought in three days in a row when there was a
political event going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just hanging on with his family and scraping by.
Sometimes friends gave him meals. Arrojo sent him money, but that's
a tricky business. When we first met him he was all skin and
bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz decided to defect again. His reasons were clear although he
refuses to speak out against Cuban dictator Fidel Castro because he
has family still on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing to lose,'' Diaz said. ``I went through a very
hard time. Once you leave the country, when you come back, you're
marked as a defector. You're considered no good, especially with
the people who are for the Cuban government. People point at you
and say, `there's a defector.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This time, in August 1998, the plan was a little more
coordinated, and he escaped by yacht, first to Honduras, then
Mexico, Nicaragua and finally Costa Rica where he was granted
residency in February 1999. He and Osmani Garcia, who also signed
with the Rangers, moved to the Dominican Republic in October and
were working out there.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers gave Diaz a $50,000 signing bonus, far below the
millions paid to pitchers Orlando Hernandez, Livan Hernandez,
Arrojo and Danys Baez. Diaz was a .283 hitter in Cuba with good
speed but little power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on the shelf a long time, and major-league baseball
really hasn't figured out the Cuban position player,'' Kehoskie
said. ``I know this may sound crazy but he's close. He's much more
advanced than a lot of people give him credit for. His bat is going
to need time, but I've not seen five better defensive second
basemen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will begin determining that now and Diaz said,
``they've given me this opportunity, and I'll do anything
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He has already shown that. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
