<HEADLINE>
ROY IS CHAMPION OF BOURQUE'S CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Patrick Roy was traded to the Colorado Avalanche
that fateful day _ Dec. 6, 1995 _ after publicly announcing he had
played his last game for the Montreal Canadiens, it was hard to
imagine seeing Roy in any uniform other than the bleu, blanc, and
rouge.
</P>
<P>
   When Ray Bourque was sent West to that same destination, asking
to be moved after nearly 21 years in a Bruins uniform, it was even
harder to imagine him in anything but black and gold.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed fitting that Roy, Bourque's Olympic and All-Star
teammate, chaired the welcome wagon committee in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Roy wouldn't go so far as to say Bourque is playing like a man
who has just been released from jail, but it's not that much of a
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like 34 years old,'' said Roy, making a sly reference
to his own age. ``It's fun to see the way Ray is playing right now.
He looks younger. Sometimes when you get moved, it brings a little
fun and sometimes it's good to make a change. We're all afraid of
making change, but when it happens, sometimes you think it might
give a second wind to your career.''
</P>
<P>
   This year in Boston, Bourque, at 39, clearly looked like a man
at the end of the road. Though he remained as gracious as always,
he smiled less, kept to himself more, and on the ice, he looked as
if the weight of the world were on his shoulders. A former teammate
said he watched in agony as Bourque grew sadder and sadder.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Avalanche, Bourque is surrounded by talent and is
playing with more energy, more enthusiasm, and so much hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see the way he's playing right now,'' said Roy.
``You see him play against you or play with him in the Olympics but
when you see him play every night, you see him so solid
defensively. He's taking a little bit of chances but he's so good
defensively. One on one, he's hard to beat. He's made some great
plays on the blue line and his shot is so accurate, it's fun to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   The additions of Bourque and Dave Andreychuk have bolstered the
Avalanche's chances of making a ferocious Stanley Cup run. But Roy
was as shocked as Bourque when the trade was made, because most on
the Avalanche thought Bourque was bound for Philadelphia, as he had
requested.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were not in the hunt,'' said Roy. ``When we
heard the news, we were very excited. It brought a lot of
excitement to the team and maybe it was the kind of spark that we
needed. Since he's been here, we haven't lost, and the team is
playing better and better every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our chance to win the Cup right now,'' said Roy, a
three-time Vezina Trophy winner who has three Stanley Cup rings
from 1986, '93, and '96.
</P>
<P>
   Roy is no small part of Colorado's equation. Going into the
weekend, he had a record of 27-19-8, on pace to reach 30 victories
for the 10th time in his 15-year NHL career. With 439 career wins,
he is chasing Terry Sawchuk's NHL mark of 447.It has only been in
the last three or four years that he started paying close attention
to the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking maybe it would be possible when I reached
300 wins when I was in Colorado,'' said Roy. ``I thought maybe it
would be touchable. When you look at it, it's hard to believe,
especially when you start your first season, that you're going to
one day be close like I am right now. When you're starting your
first year, you say, `That's a little far, and I'll be very happy
if I can survive 10 years in this league.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roy, who was always fond of his visits to Boston, has followed
the hockey situation here, especially with regard to the future of
Pat Burns. Burns coached Roy for four years in Montreal, and though
they didn't always see eye to eye then, Roy has a somewhat
different perspective now. ``Pat Burns is a very, very good
coach,'' said Roy. ``All the years he was with us in Montreal, I
certainly learned a lot from the way he was coaching. People are
hard on him in Boston right now but I think he does a very good job
in that situation. He's certainly one of the best coaches is this
league and he's certainly one of the best coaches I ever had. It
was always a pleasure to play under him. Maybe there were things I
didn't understand (about) what he was doing and I regret today but
overall all I can say is I have a lot of respect for this man as a
coach and as a person as well.'' . . . It is impossible not to be
horrified by the graphic video that shows Toronto defenseman Bryan
Berard getting struck in the face by the stick of Ottawa forward
Marian Hossa. Berard, just 23, is facing exploratory surgery on his
right eye, which has a 3/4-inch cut, and he could lose sight in it
if the retina cannot be reattached. The incident has prompted a
renewed debate about face shields. Some players, such as Bruins
defenseman Don Sweeney, wouldn't go without one. ``I just felt with
the way I play, at my size and my height, I just caught too many
accidental things,'' said Sweeney. ``I used to practice a little
bit without one. Now it's even worse. It's not so much that the
intent is ever there, but you've got too many accidental things
coming your way. The shield for me just took care of those things.
Everybody goes through a little bit of a stigma about it, like
you're hiding behind it or it's not a brave thing to be wearing it
and stuff like that.'' Sweeney, who is pound for pound as tough a
player as there is in the NHL, would much rather endure the verbal
abuse than deal with the dire prospects facing Berard. ``You do go
through that period where guys are giving you a hassle about it,
like `Take off the phone booth' or some comment that comes your
way, but why take it off?'' said Sweeney. ``With Berard, obviously,
you just feel sick. You get a real empty feeling in your stomach
when you hear anything about it.'' The issue hits home with Sweeney
more than others because one of his prematurely born twins is
having vision problems. ``Obviously, I'm a little sensitive because
of what my boys have gone through,'' said Sweeney. ``It's just
crazy unfortunate for Berard. You just feel bad for him.'' But
Sweeney doesn't necessarily favor an edict from the league
requiring shields. ``It should be everybody's choice still,'' he
said. ``You do look at guys who do come in and ask, `Why would they
take that risk?' It just brings up that question. But I wouldn't
look down on anybody for taking it off or putting it on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was raised in Ludlow, so even though San Jose general manager
Dean Lombardi toils on the West Coast, he still keeps an eye on the
hockey in his native state. He has followed the Bruins' travails
this year, and as a fellow executive, he thinks Harry Sinden is a
little misunderstood here. ``One thing about Harry he doesn't
really get enough credit for, is he really does care,'' said
Lombardi. ``Sometimes it doesn't come across because of the hard
line with the money. Sometimes he gets ticked off and maybe says
some things. But deep down, he really cares about hockey. I think
he's really concerned about where some things are going. I don't
think, having grown up in Massachusetts, that you always appreciate
that until you see him every day and go to (the GMs) meetings and
see him operate.'' Vancouver GM Brian Burke likened the experience
of being on committees with Sinden to the E.F. Hutton commercials
in which everyone leans in to hear what one person is saying.
Lombardi said it sometimes takes a minute to absorb Sinden's point.
``A lot of times he'll say something and at first you'll go,
`What's he talking about?' '' said Lombardi. ``And then you sit
back and think about it and say, `Oh yeah,' and everybody goes,
`Why didn't I think of that?' Other times, you'll think, `Where's
he going with this?' and then you think, `Damn, he's right.' '' . .
. The Kings, who looked as if they were poised to do some damage in
the Western Conference playoffs, were dealt a gigantic setback when
they lost Ziggy Palffy with a sprained right shoulder. Palffy, one
of the most dynamic forwards in the league, is expected to be
sidelined 2-4 weeks. He was tied for the team lead in scoring . . .
21 days until this sorry season ends in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
