<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FUSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR REVOLUTION, A POINT WELL TAKEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ The revamped Revolution rallied to make
a positive start to their fifth MLS season Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. They
played the Miami Fusion to a 1-1 tie, and became the first
beneficiary of a league policy that rewards a point to each team
for drawn games, in concert with FIFA rules.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution experienced major difficulties in the first
half, especially from striker Diego Serna, who scored in the 61st
minute. Coach Fernando Clavijo made key tactical adjustments in the
second half, and the Revolution equaled on a goal by Imad Baba in
the 80th minute.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Revolution had asserted themselves in midfield with
the addition of 22-year-old Costa Rican William Sunsing on the
right wing and striker Eduardo Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked that when we got down we kept playing and nobody lost
their head,'' said Clavijo, the fifth head coach of the Revolution.
``Little by little we will get to know each other better. For a few
minutes we got out of what we want to do, but we kept our
composure. But this is only one of 32 games. I've said all along
that we have the talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution struggled in central defense, though their
problems were caused as much by the elusiveness and persistence of
Serna as their own deficiencies. In fact, the combination of Brian
Dunseth and Ivan McKinley appears to have matured since they were
last paired in '98, though McKinley was cautioned late in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the Fusion were applying consistent pressure on
goalkeeper Jeff Causey, who made a point-blank stop on Andy
Williams midway through the half. But in the second half, Leonel
Alvarez and John Harkes began pressuring Miami's defensive
midfielders, and Sunsing opened the attack on the right wing in
place of Johnny Torres.
</P>
<P>
   Right back Rusty Pierce, playing his first MLS game in place of
Mike Burns, limited Eric Wynalda and displayed poise until
departing with leg cramps midway through the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado replaced Mauricio Ramos in the 74th minute, joining
Wolde Harris in attack. Harris, whose ability to retain possession
and dribble through defenders keyed the Revolution offense in the
first half, combined with Hurtado and Sunsing to nearly decide the
contest in the 88th minute. But Harris was stopped by goalkeeper
Jeff Cassar on the edge of the goal area as a torrent of rain
scattered a crowd of 8,782.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have first-timed it, but I took a long touch and it
was a slippery surface,'' Harris said. ``But we played well and
it's a matter of time for us to play even better. I would love to
have (Hurtado) up top with me because then the defense can't only
key on me. For most of the game, the defense was looking only for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo said Hurtado and Sunsing have a chance to start next
week at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   This was the third consecutive Revolution season opener to
finish 1-1 in regulation. The Revolution lost to D.C. United (1998)
and Miami ('99) in shootouts.
</P>
<P>
   But the league switched this season to a 10-minute golden goal
overtime, and the Revolution nearly capitalized. They missed the
victory by inches as Harkes's 25-yard drive from straight on in the
second minute of overtime somehow curled off the left side of the
net. Harkes, who replaced Burns as captain, had a strong game and
helped hold the Revolution together in midfield.
</P>
<P>
   Baba and Ted Chronopoulos also showed improvement in their fifth
season, and combined for the goal as Chronopoulos curled a free
kick from the left and the Fusion left Baba open. Baba calmly
volleyed a hard, low shot just inside the post for his first goal
since Sept. 19, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed a lot of character fighting back,'' Harkes said.
``We were more together than we were last year and now we have to
come together more. If we are patient and take care of the final
ball better, we will be OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
