<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS CAN'T SEEM TO GET THEMSELVES UNTANGLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For those fans of the New Jersey Nets _ yes, there are
some _ this past week was a killer. Here was a team priming for a
playoff run while getting prepared to welcome back Jayson Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on one of those innocuous moves at practice, it all fell
apart for the apparently cursed Williams. His right knee, the one
that sidelined him all season, held up. His left foot did not. He
broke his toe, and he's gone for the year. It remains to be seen
whether the team goes with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it all means,'' sighed coach Don Casey. ``I
guess it must mean that God is telling me to go play golf. But I
don't play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one more slap in the face to a team that had very
legitimate playoff aspirations. There also was the early-season
loss of Kerry Kittles, the shuffling of positions, the strange play
of Keith Van Horn and, of course, the implausible 2-15 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off dysfunctional,'' Casey said. ``I think we all
look back now and say, `How did we ever go 2-15?' But that's over.
We've recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that dreadful start, the Nets are 26-21. They are fighting
with the Celtics and others for a playoff spot. They've got a point
guard in Stephon Marbury, who, according to Rick Pitino, is playing
as well as, or better than, any point guard in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bad news. Williams stepped on the foot of Even
Eschmeyer and the next thing Casey knew, his center was limping and
having a serious talk with the trainer. That is not what he wanted
to see. He knew then something was amiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big thing was that we were disappointed more than
anything else,'' Casey said. ``Everyone saw how hard he worked.
Everyone saw how well his knee was holding up. It's a shame, it
really is. He went over and above what he needed to do and you
wanted him to make it back for all kinds of reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Nets have Marbury, Van Horn, and Kittles, they
have only one All-Star: Williams (from the 1998 game). Take his
$12.375 million salary off the books and the Nets go from having
the fifth-highest payroll ($52-plus million) to the 19th ($40-plus
million).
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is missed as much for what he does off the court,
particularly as a mental bodyguard for Van Horn. That is why Casey
wants Williams to be with the team for as many games as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a rallying-around type guy,'' Casey said. ``We want to
make him feel wanted because he's just devastated about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Nets are to get into the playoffs, they'll have to finish
ahead of the Celtics, because Boston has the tie-breaker. They've
learned to play without Williams all season _ his return kept
getting pushed back _ and Casey is thinking about dusting off
Gheorghe Muresan, who is playing well in practice.
</P>
<P>
   The coach can't do any more long-term thinking than that. He's
not under contract for next season. Rumors have been flying all
season about a top-to-bottom, Steinbrenneresque shakeup in the
organization. Casey said he's heard nothing about his future, but
it's impossible to miss the obvious: The team has made progress
despite all the hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The latest one seems a bit of overkill. But the Hoop God isn't
fair; just ask the Warriors' Garry St. Jean or the Cavaliers' Randy
Wittman. The Nets have been resilient if nothing else, and the
final month will be another test.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson was asked about Chicago's Elton Brand for Rookie
of the Year and shook his head. ``Steve Francis is my man,'' said
Anderson. Is this a bonding thing among point guards? Well, sort
of. ``In general, it's always big first and small second in the
league,'' Anderson explained. ``Nowadays, they're getting a grip on
how important a point guard is, that he can turn an organization
around. When the little guy does something, it's more because we're
so undersized. It's a big man's game. To do what he's doing, as a
rookie, is great. He should get looked at not only as a great
talent, but because of the size he's doing it at. I think all of us
should get looked at like that. A lot of people don't understand
that we take serious physical abuse going in and out of the lane,
penetrating, going for rebounds, getting pushed. It's hell on a
little guy's body.'' . . . Francis, by the way, was summoned to a
meeting with commissioner David Stern and other league bigwigs at
the NBA offices when the Rockets passed through New York. The
reason: to impress upon him how important is it for young players
in the league to carry it into the new century with dignity,
respect, and George Sanders-like manners. Of course, Francis is
still Francis. Before Houston played the Bucks Thursday, he said he
was looking forward to going against another motormouth, Sam
Cassell. ``I'm going to light his butt up,'' Francis said. ``I
don't want to make it personal, but I'm going to light him up.''
Well, Francis had 22 points on 7-of-16 shooting. Cassell had 22
points on 7-of-14 shooting. Sounds like a standoff to me. The Bucks
won the game . . . Two nights after Sean Elliott's remarkable
return from a kidney transplant, the Spurs got spanked at home by
the Mavericks. In between the emotional victory over the Hawks and
the stunning loss to Dallas, Elliott talked about his comeback.
``It's worth it to me for a lot reasons,'' he said. ``It's not just
about myself. In a way it is, because there's a part of me that
wants to prove it to myself and I want to satisfy something in
myself. But there's another part of me that wants to make a
statement for a lot of people who have gone through my situation,
or other people who maybe aren't having kidney transplants, but
have faced illness or adversity and think they can't recover from
what they're going through.'' As for his rehab, Elliott said he
didn't exactly follow the Drew Carey Fit For Life Plan. ``I didn't
make my comeback wolfing down a cheeseburger, fries, and a 32-ounce
beer every day and sitting around,'' he said. ``I went out and took
care of my body and people don't see that aspect of it, so maybe
that needs to be talked about a little more.'' Elliott has moved
into the starting lineup, which has helped ease the constant
ovations. He played only eight minutes in the 22-point loss to
Dallas and had 2 points, 4 rebounds, a blocked shot, and a
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone has gone public on a lot of topics in, of all
places, Penthouse Magazine. You can read the interview in the April
issue, which, of course, is why people buy Penthouse . . . Dee
Brown has not had an easy season in Toronto. But the latest episode
may top them all. He was put on the IL with what was a ``wink,
wink'' upper respiratory ailment. Well, eventually word got out
that Brown was supposedly out of shape and he did not take kindly
to that spin. Brown and coach Butch Carter met for four hours to
try to smooth things out. Carter tried to take some heat by saying
he should never have brought Brown back after recent knee surgery.
Charles Oakley came to Brown's defense, calling the affair ``total
bull.'' That's how Brown sees it. But more important, he wants to
get back on the court because he's a free agent and needs to show
prospective employers he's able to play . . . Gotta love the Jazz.
They are assured of a winning season for the 15th consecutive year,
one shy of the record set by the Lakers, who went from 1976-77
through 1991-92 with a winning record. The Celtics went 19 straight
seasons (1950-51 through 1968-69) without a losing year, but in
1954-55, they went 36-36. ``The Jazz do it the way it's supposed to
be done, simple,'' says center Olden Polynice. ``There's nothing
flashy. We're probably the only team that follows the NBA
guidelines. We don't have guys with braids, running around, looking
crazy, shoelaces untied. Jerry Sloan treats everyone the same. As
long as you work hard, you'll be fine. It was hard for me at the
beginning. The little things like having your drawstring tucked in.
That drives him crazy if it's out. There was one game when Greg
Ostertag was going in for a layup and Jerry was yelling at him to
put his drawstring in. I'm thinking, `Let him make the layup
first.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitino is now looking for athletes (in addition to veterans, a
big man, and a scorer off the bench). One reason: His team has
trouble against quicker teams like Detroit, which has won five
straight from the Celtics over the last two seasons. ``It's why
they give us problems,'' he said of the speedy Pistons, citing
Jerry Stackhouse, Grant Hill, and the ultra-energetic Jerome
Williams. ``We have some fine basketball players: (Paul Pierce,
(Antoine) Walker, (Adrian) Griffin, Kenny. They're basketball
players, but I wouldn't distinguish them as great athletes. (Tony)
Battie has the potential to be a very good athlete. Antoine has
tremendous growth as an athlete. Paul has growth. Griff and Kenny,
well, what you see is what you're going to get.'' . . . Williams
should get some serious and well-earned consideration for the Sixth
Man Award, especially if Detroit continues to play well under
George (What, Me Worry?) Irvine. Former Georgetown coach John
Thompson did the Celtics-Pistons game last Monday on TBS and
offered these thoughts on his former player: ``Jerome has a
tremendous work ethic and what's in his favor is he does the things
in the game that people don't want to do. He will defend. He will
rebound. He will hustle. He can do things rebounding-wise that
reminds me of Dennis Rodman. You can't teach those things. It took
a while for Jerome to believe that. I think he perceived himself as
a point guard, as a swingman bringing the ball down the floor. All
the glamour stuff. But once he started focusing on rebounding and
defending, that got him more playing time.'' Thompson said Williams
was one of those players ``who fell through the cracks,'' because
he wasn't good enough either in high school (Magruder in
Germantown, Md.) or junior college (Montgomery County, Md.) to
attract a lot of recruiting interest. He was the 26th player taken
in the 1996 draft . . . The Bucks have opened the door for the
Celtics and Nets. The reason: They don't play defense, which is not
in keeping with a George Karl team. ``I guess they'll want me for
offensive clinics this summer,'' cracked Karl. ``Now I'm going to
be paid for my offense. I've gone from being a smart coach to a
dumb coach.'' How does he feel as he watches his team attempt to
defend? ``It drives me crazy,'' he said. ``We don't stop people.
The true great teams stop and score. They do both. When you're with
a good team, you gotta be able to win any way. You gotta be able to
win ugly, win good, win pretty, win fast, win slow, win big. Teams
are going to throw things at you and you have to adjust. It's not
real hard, the last time I checked. Sometimes our players really
don't understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
