<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-CORDERO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCARY EPISODE HAUNTS CORDERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ When Hollywood finally learns baseball is
ripe for a TV series, the star in the pilot should be Marty
Cordova. He's muscular, dark-haired, and handsome, and has one heck
of a tale to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad 48 hours,'' is how Cordova looks back at last
Wednesday and Thursday. ``Worst 48 hours of my baseball career.
Weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein the tale.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova was back with the Red Sox Saturday, his ribs sore, his
mind a tad less confused than it was midweek, but still in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   He is _ and he is not _ a member of the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Therein the subplot.
</P>
<P>
   Let's first cut to the action, the opening scene, in which Red
Sox manager Jimy Williams and various Boston and Pittsburgh
trainers are in short left field of a small minor league field in
Bradenton, Fla., signaling for a stretcher. Red Sox shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra had just gotten to his feet after colliding with
Cordova, but there was Cordova, still on the grass, unable to get
up.
</P>
<P>
   And worse.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Gasping.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way I'm going out on a stretcher,'' thought Cordova. ``I
said, `I'm OK,' but I turned over to try and get up and I couldn't
breathe. I'd never been hurt where I couldn't breathe like that.
I've had the wind knocked out of me where if I breathed in, it
hurt. But this time I couldn't breathe in or out.''
</P>
<P>
   And the stretcher was being carried to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to be put in any stretcher,'' said Cordova. ``I
always laugh at guys who fall down when they foul a ball off their
foot and they're hurt? I always say, `I'm never going to go off the
field like that.' So, no stretcher. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Cordova, tough guy. Flash back to some painful moments in
Cordova's career with Minnesota, when he would be in pain, but not
evidently so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got hit by a pitch, I'd go to first right away no matter
how badly it hurt,'' said Cordova. ``I broke my wrist in spring
training once _ broke it in half _ and I just got up and walked
off. But this time I couldn't breathe. It was weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Cordova had to get off the field somehow. And the Red Sox,
particularly a distraught Garciaparra, whose knee had banged into
Cordova's ribs while the two were chasing a popup, saw the problems
Cordova was having breathing and were anxious. Not to mention
scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Damn, there's something wrong with my chest,' ''
Cordova said. ``So I lay there for a moment and I didn't want to
move until I could see if I could get my breath. Then I was able to
sit up, and I just wanted to get off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   After about five minutes on the grass, Cordova was able to get
up and walk away before being taken to Manatee Memorial Hospital,
just a fungo from McKechnie Field.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to the subplot.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova was playing in the game just because Williams was being
nice (``I can't say enough how well Jimy Williams has handled
this,'' said Cordova) and just because playing might melt some of
the anger he felt from the previous day. That was when Cordova
learned that Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette was not signing
him to a major league contract as Cordova had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not particularly the best day in my career,'' said
Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   Some players might have sulked. Others might have ripped their
uniform to shreds. But go hell-bent for a popup in an exhibition
game?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I am,'' said Cordova. ``I always play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, back to real life.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova's sore ribs will keep him out of action for another day
or so (``I hope to be back hitting Tuesday'') and he's still in
limbo. He doesn't know whether he'll be a member of the Red Sox or
any other team.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said Saturday that Cordova ``is still a viable
option.'' And Cordova said his agent has contacted other teams, but
``I don't know anything. I'm the kind of person who doesn't want to
know until it's definite. So I don't know what's happening with my
agent. I told him not to tell me anything until he has something
certain.''
</P>
<P>
   One minor point before Cordova does his pilot for the TV series.
First, he'd like to know all details of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``How hard did Nomar get me?'' Cordova asked, some details of
the crash still fuzzy. ``Was it really hard?''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh. Hard enough to show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
