<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAYHILLINVITATIONAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE IS FINDING A WAY AT BAY HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ As the golf world has slowly become Tiger
Woods's personal possession, there has been one consistent voice
determined not to fade quietly into the background: Davis Love.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in the third round of the Bay Hill Invitational, Love
proved that he hasn't relented one bit. That as fruitless as it
seems sometimes, he again will challenge Woods. Love made his
statement with a dynamic 9-under-par 63 that equaled the course
record and vaulted him over 14 players into second place at
14-under 202. That the man in front is Woods (67_200) is of no
surprise to Love _ who is painfully familiar with the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody starts beating you, you start thinking about
that,'' said Love, whose round included a 40-foot birdie putt and a
pair of chip-ins _ one for eagle, one for birdie. ``He thrives on
that. But we just have to learn to compete with him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a test for which Love has studied three times, without
success. Woods's first PGA Tour win (October 1996) came at the
expense of Love in a Las Vegas Invitational playoff. Last fall,
Woods beat Love in a low-key PGA Grand Slam event, but when the
stakes were raised for the Andersen Consulting Match Play
semifinals in February, the result was the same _ ``I just got
smoked,'' said Love, a 5-and-4 loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always used to say to the players out here, this guy (Woods)
is nowhere as good as he's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that Love's assessment has come true, he has more:
``He's the No. 1 player in the world. There's no getting around
that. He's going to be hard to beat. There's no getting around
that, either. But I've been saying for the past few months (while
Woods was putting together a six-tournament winning streak) that
someone has to knock him down in the dirt to show him that he can
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   To do so, it may take something like another 63 because Woods,
attempting to win for the third time this season, is as close to a
sure thing as there is in golf when he's leading. In his brief but
spectacular pro career, Woods has had the lead or a share of it 16
times through 54 holes. He has won 15 of those times. Nothing he
did in Round 3 Saturday indicated he'll let this one get away.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day 11 under, one ahead of Mike Weir, Woods bogeyed
the par-3 second. A minor burp, because he drilled an 8-iron inside
of 3 feet at the third, made birdie, and led by three as Weir (72)
made bogey. It set Woods off deeper into red numbers. Weir's
second-round 64 was a distant memory when he made the turn in 36,
and though he got it to 12-under through 17, a double-bogey on the
closing hole dropped the Canadian into third, six behind.
</P>
<P>
   Love, who hasn't won in two years, pretty much made this into a
two-player race thanks to a series of dramatic shots that proved
good fortune and skill are tough to beat.
</P>
<P>
   He trailed by five shots when he drained that no-brainer at the
11th. When he chipped in for eagle at the 12th and followed with a
sand wedge to 6 feet for birdie at the 13th, he was 11-under and
breathing down Woods's neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at the leaderboard,'' said Woods, nine groups
behind Love. ``Under these conditions, I thought it was difficult
to shoot a low round, but Davis proved otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With an asterisk,'' said Love, who birdied the par-4 15th even
though he chunked his approach short of the green, then eagled the
517-yard 16th after drilling his 5-iron approach to 12 feet. ``You
know, I did chip in twice. So you take those away and, well 65 is
still a very, very good round.''
</P>
<P>
   No argument, said Woods, who was more proud of his par saves at
the seventh, 10th, and 13th than the three birdies he made coming
in. The saves came at a time when Love was climbing the leaderboard
with frightening ease, and served notice that Woods would have to
be caught; he wasn't going to fall back.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you need to do,'' said Woods of those
up-and-downs. ``You can't always hit the ball great.''
</P>
<P>
   And you can't keeping winning head-to-head against the same guy,
can you? Woods paused, knowing his track record against Love is
flawless.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can look at it two different ways,'' he said. ``You can
say he's due, or you can say there is an advantage (for me).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With John Daly and Dennis Paulson in the lead group, it appeared
to be a track meet. The duo played in a shade over three hours,
though the quick pace obviously did not bother Paulson, who
finished birdie-eagle-par-birdie in a round of 68. Daly, after
turning in 35, made two doubles on the back to come in with 40_75 .
. . Steve Flesch has made the cut in all eight starts this year . .
. Olin Browne and Billy Andrade, who played with Woods the first
two days, found themselves paired for Round 3. Each played well,
with Browne reeling off four straight birdies starting at the
fourth in his round of 68_209. Andrade, who made the cut for just
the third time in eight starts, shot 69_210.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
