<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH WAY TO TURN WITH CART? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ You'll excuse PGA Tour officials if they appear
confused. In golfing terminology, they are in between clubs, unsure
of which to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a court battle with Casey Martin for the second time in
two years seemed to leave the PGA Tour with one logical option:
quit while it was behind. Surely, pursuing such a case against a
kid who has lined up one notable ally after another would be a
public relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Martin, who suffers from Klippel-Trenaunay-Weber
Syndrome, a circulatory problem in his lower right leg, probably
expected to hear this past week that the PGA Tour's Policy Board
had decided not to argue its case to the Supreme Court. Not quite.
Instead, commissioner Tim Finchem said Wednesday that the Tour was
still between clubs. ``The board has determined to defer a decision
of whether to seek a Supreme Court review,'' said Finchem.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it appears to be a case of not knowing when to
quit, but in Finchem's defense, there is reason to wait. One day
after a 9th US Circuit Court of Appeals (San Francisco) upheld
Martin's first victory _ which allowed him to use a golf cart in
PGA events _ a 7th US Circuit Court of Appeals
(Indiana-Illinois-Wisconsin) upheld a lower court's ruling that the
US Golf Association did not have to grant a cart to an Indiana club
pro named Ford Olinger.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Finchem sure is.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell, what we have is a situation where we have two
cases of identical facts under the American With Disabilities
Act,'' said Finchem, himself a lawyer, though that didn't stop him
from shaking his head at times. ``The two courts came out on
diametrically opposed sides of the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Olinger, whose degenerative hip disorder led him to
request a cart for US Open qualifying, have said they would appeal
_ first in a re-hearing with the 7th Circuit, then to the Supreme
Court. (Finchem said the Tour definitely would not ask for a
re-hearing with the 9th Circuit because ``based on what we've seen
out of the 9th Circuit, we're not excited about asking them for
another opinion.'')
</P>
<P>
   Finchem made a point of saying, ``This case has less and less to
do with Casey Martin,'' a comment that made the Tour rookie
bristle. Martin told reporters that since he's the one who fought
for the right to a cart, the case certainly is still about him.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to admire about Martin, and he deserves to be held
up as a courageous hero, but Finchem has a legitimate concern.
Similar cases were handled entirely differently by two courts,
which leaves the PGA Tour (and any other sports league) still
wondering about the very heart of its argument: Can it set its own
policies and govern its sport?
</P>
<P>
   So while the PGA Tour sits and waits, the USGA has a dilemma. It
voluntarily allowed Martin use of a cart in US Open qualifying the
last two years, but after its court win over Olinger, will it say
no to Martin this time? A spokesman for the USGA said an
announcement would be made in late April.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer revealed that he gave serious thought to not
playing in his Bay Hill Invitational, one of two PGA Tour events in
which he still takes part (the other is the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic). ``There was some question,'' said Palmer, ``simply
because my game, number one, is not good enough, and two, I'm not
playing that well on the Senior Tour.'' Still, friends insisted he
play, and when he gave it more thought, it turned out to be an easy
decision. Palmer is 70, he has been mourning the death of his
beloved wife Winnie the past few months, and at times his struggles
on the course are difficult to watch. After opening with an 82 at
Bay Hill Thursday, Palmer trudged off, looking very much like a guy
who wouldn't be back as a competitor in 2001. But, as always, he
was the definition of class, character, and grace as he walked from
the green to the clubhouse. He signed nearly everything shoved at
him by fans and didn't hesitate to answer reporters' questions . .
. Palmer was paired with Colin Montgomerie for the first two
rounds, a circumstance that pleased him greatly. How, Palmer was
asked, did that come to be? ``Well, I suggested it,'' said Palmer
with a grin. ``I didn't put any pressure on.'' . . . In a
roundabout way, Palmer was asked if he thought Tiger Woods at 35
would be as effective as he is now after another 10 years of trying
to meet all the demands on his time. ``My advice would be to just
keep on working and enjoying it _ once you stop enjoying it, don't
do it,'' said Palmer, who related a story about his series of
matches in the 1960s with Gary Player and Jack Nicklaus, both
younger than he. Player and Nicklaus, said Palmer, both insisted
they wouldn't be playing competitively when they reached 45, but
today, Nicklaus and Player _ 60 and 65, respectively _ are
``playing more golf than they have ever played in their life.'' . .
. Asked if there will be any special significance to this year's
Masters, his 46th, now that he is a member of Augusta National,
Palmer kicked his enthusiasm into an even higher gear. ``I have a
very definite feeling,'' he said. ``I have written a note to the
powers at Augusta and said that since I am now a member, I'd like
to play the members' tees.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most players will still say they don't like the fact that PGA
Tour winners aren't exempt into the Masters. The decision to give
world rankings more weight was made a year ago, and Finchem was
asked if the Masters folks consulted with his people. ``Consult
might be a strong word,'' said Finchem. ``They invite us to comment
and we do, but they feel very strongly about the field size and
having all their champions being able to play.'' And to those who
criticize tournament officials, Finchem offers this: ``I certainly
wouldn't want to be one to argue that it detracts from the quality
of the impact of the Masters.'' . . . Sergio Garcia confirmed what
was a poorly kept secret: He will play in the inaugural Ballesteros
Cup in England the week after the Masters. Though he originally
committed to play the MCI Heritage Classic, Garcia relented because
``Seve called me.'' The tournament will pit Continental Europe vs.
Great Britain/Ireland in match play. Garcia had threatened to skip
it as a protest against European PGA Tour executive director Ken
Schofield. They are at odds over guidelines for qualifying for this
year's NEC Invitational. Did he consider calling Seve Ballesteros?
``I think if somebody wants me to play in one tournament, I think
the tournament has to call the player,'' said Garcia, who at times
seems years removed from the innocent youngster who captivated the
golf world last summer . . . How times have changed: Next week's
purse for The Players Championship is $6 million. In his career,
Nicklaus is credited with $5.6 million in prize money. Next week's
winner will receive a check for $1,080,000, which is more than half
of Palmer's career prize money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Vijay Singh shot 68 to share the first-round lead at Bay
Hill, it wasn't a shock because his scoring average before the cut
(69.07) ranks 14th on Tour. But if a disturbing trend continues, he
doesn't figure to win the tournament. His third- and fourth-round
scoring averages (70.71, 71.71) rank 86th and 125th, respectively.
Singh opened with a 65 at Doral two weeks ago, but faded to T-36,
and he has but two Top 10s this season . . . Gary Koch, a former
winner at Bay Hill, was forced to withdraw, thus opening up a spot
for Sandy Lyle. But Koch did not go home. He simply put away the
clubs and picked up a microphone, working the tournament for NBC .
. . Mike Nicolette was asked about beating Greg Norman in a playoff
at Bay Hill in 1983, but he stopped the reporter short. ``I ended
up winning, but Greg three-putted,'' said Nicolette. ``Beating is
when you make a birdie. He lost.'' . . . No ego problems for
Nicolette. ``Most people think I'm Corey Pavin,'' he said. ``If
you're not up on your golf trivia, you have no idea who I am.'' . .
. At the recent Massachusetts Golf Association spring conference,
Jeanne-Marie Boylan was introduced as the 20th person from
Massachusetts to be named to the USGA's executive committee. A
Milton native and three-time women's state amateur champion, Boylan
has served on the USGA's women's committee for several years. At
the spring conference, Boylan represented the USGA and presented a
grant of $25,000 to the MGA to help support its golf camps in
Springfield, Cambridge, Lowell, and Chelsea . . . You may be
looking down the road to something else, but for some, the official
2000 amateur season kicks off with the annual Seagulls event at
Hyannisport the first two weekends in April . . . One of the fun
events of the season will take place May 19 at Duxbury Yacht Club:
the Ouimet Eight Club Tournament. Why eight? That is how many
Francis Ouimet carried in 1913 when he stunned the golf world with
his US Open triumph at The Country Club. The event will be a net
best-ball of four and applications are due May 8. For information,
call 781-891-6400 . . . It will be with great sadness that the
golfers of Kernwood CC in Salem tee it up in coming weeks, for
their friend Peter Oppenheim, a 15-time club champion, died last
week at the age of 51. A member of the MGA Executive Committee,
Oppenheim made it into match play of the State Amateur five times
and once qualified for the US Amateur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
