<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-MAVERICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKER, CELTICS TURN INTO ROAD WARRIORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If you've got an incurable case of Bracket Fever, or
are fretting over who's going to close for the Red Sox, you might
want to take a step back and look at what the Celtics are doing.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing short of amazing given where they were not too long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics looked a lot like a lottery lock two weeks ago after
losing 15 of 19. They have, to be precise, turned it around.
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, playing a very warm Dallas team (consecutive wins
over Phoenix, Indiana, and San Antonio), the Celtics came away with
a stirring 104-99 victory. It was their seventh win in eight games,
their second straight road win, and represented the first time
since Nov. 3 they've managed to win back-to-back games anywhere.
They had previously lost 17 straight on the second night of
back-to-backs.
</P>
<P>
   It was another tour de force for Antoine Walker, who had 29
points (10-of-15 shooting, including 4 treys), 10 rebounds, and 6
assists. It also was another big night by the oft-maligned bench,
which got big games from Eric Williams (18 points), Tony Battie (8
points, 10 rebounds), and Dana Barros (11 points).
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the Celtics closed to within a game of the eighth
playoff spot. One game. They also are six games under .500; they
haven't been that close to the water line since winning in Utah
Feb. 15. They've climbed back into it due to a much-improved
defensive effort, much-improved play from the bench, and the
overall celestial play of Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a weapon right now,'' Rick Pitino said of Walker.
``He's playing like one of the premier players in the game, and
we're very excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   They should be. Walker was coming off a sparkling show in
Atlanta, but that was against the comatose Hawks. This was a
different story. The Mavericks actually play like they care, even
though they're out of the playoff hunt in the talent-loaded West.
Dallas got a routine 28 from Michael Finley, and an unexpected and
career-high 25 from Greg Buckner, who matched his season total with
five treys. Dirk Nowitzki added 21, but missed all five of his
treys, including a critical boinger in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics never trailed after an 11-2 second-quarter run.
Dallas tied the game early in the third and did not go quietly,
even after Walker's layup (off a nice feed from Kenny Anderson)
with 3:38 left made it 98-87. Two minutes later, the Mavericks had
the deficit to 5 and, with less than a minute to play, it was down
to 99-96.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pierce then stepped into the breach. He had only 15 points
due to limited time (foul trouble) and has mostly been yapping
about his beloved Kansas Jayhawks the last few days. But he hit a
big second-chancer (Anderson snuck in for an offensive rebound
after his own miss) over Erick Strickland with 19.8 seconds left to
make it 101-96. After a Finley trey made it 101-99, Pierce calmly
swished two free throws with 8.3 seconds to play to settle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good, real good,'' said Williams. ``We know we still
have work to do, but we feel like the team is starting to jell.
We're coming together at the right time. We've just got to keep it
going.''
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to be a difficult task with the next stop Monday
night in Phoenix. But the Celtics feel nothing is out of their
grasp right now. ``We are playing the best basketball we've been
playing all year,'' said Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has taken over the pack-mule role, carrying the team
during this run. He is averaging almost 28 points a game in the
past five games. But what's making him lethal is his all-around
game. He's also averaging 6 assists, which is the number Pitino
said he'd like to see Walker average this season. He's averaging 8
rebounds and he's shooting 54 percent from the field and 77 percent
from the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antoine is keeping everyone involved,'' Pitino said. ``They
know that if they give him the ball, and cut and move, that they'll
get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Give and take. All for one, one for all. It's all looking so
easy now you wonder why it took as long as it did. But the point is
that it's here, now, and the Celtics think it's going to last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
