<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS START HOT, END COLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite its $400 million sticker price, the
Clippers have managed to transform Staples Center into the Outhouse
of Pain.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the blueprint didn't include a few escape windows.
</P>
<P>
   With such structural limitations, only the Clips were able to
bail out during Saturday's 104-83 loss administered by the
Sacramento Kings before 18,964.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this clouting even more painful than normal was a
blown 23-point, second-quarter lead and evidence of Clipper
nastiness when they didn't have the ball. Yeah, their typical
poodle-in-a-junkyard defense had enough first-quarter bite to limit
the Kings to eight points, a franchise record for one quarter by
the home team.
</P>
<P>
   But the event returned to its regularly scheduled planet in the
second quarter, and the Clippers - playing their fourth game in
five days - posted their 53rd defeat in 67 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (38-27) were led by center Vlade ``The Inhaler'' Divac
and Peja Stojakovic who each put up 20 points. Point guard Jason
Williams, who sold most of the tickets, spent the evening in a
relative coma (8 points, 1 assist).
</P>
<P>
   Derek Anderson, the future free agent who now plays as if he
should have a bar code tattooed to his deltoid, had 25 points for
the Clippers. Lamar Odom produced 18 points, 9 rebounds and 6
fouls. Eric Piatkowski contributed a career-high 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson outscored the Kings by himself in round one, knocking
in 5 of 8 shots from the field for 10 of the Clippers' 24 points
and two more than the visitors could manage. Odom contributed
7points and 6 rebounds during the period, as the Clips appeared to
be in decent shape despite coughing up 7 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Webber found the range in the second quarter, putting up 8
points, while Darrick Martin threw in 6 off the bench, helping he
Kings close to 45-41 by intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson had 16 in the first half, but Odom had 3 fouls to go
with his 9 points. His runner in the lane provided the Clips'
biggest lead, 36-13, at 8:31 in round two. The Clippers had a 40-18
edge when he went to bench as punishment for foul play with 5:41
left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The siege continued in the third, with the Kings grabbing a
47-45 lead on a bucket by Vlade Divac at the 10:17 mark. Sacramento
built its biggest third-quarter lead, 68-63, on a drive by Williams
at 1:32 of the third. But Piatkowski's steal and buzzer-beating
3-pointer earned a tie at 68 at the end of three.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings started the final stanza with an 11-1 run to win this
one in a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Clippers waived forward Mario Bennett, who was signed
to a 10-day contract March 7. Bennett played in one game and
clocked three minutes. He missed the last two games due to soreness
in his recently repaired left knee. ... Bennett's spot on the
active roster was filled by Keith Closs, whose lower-back woes
pushed him to the injured list. ... Tyrone Nesby returned to the
team Saturday after missing Friday's loss at Denver. Nesby remained
in L.A. to be with his mother who suffered two strokes. ... The
Denver trip was made complete by illness to Odom, who gave an
indication of his availability for the evening by throwing up
during the first quarter. Odom had 10 points and 4 rebounds in 24
minutes vs. the Nuggets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
