<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-STJOHN'S-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA RIDES OUT RED STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Whoa. Not a good day for the big seeds in the West, eh?
</P>
<P>
   First, Wisconsin takes out top-seeded Arizona up in Salt Lake
City. About 2 1/2 hours later, the No. 2 seed was also sent home as
the Gonzaga Bulldogs took charge in money time to topple Big East
champion St. John's, 82-76, Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at the McKale Center.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the then-unknown `Zags came oh-so-close to knocking
off 1999 Big East champ Connecticut in the regional finals. This
time the West Coast Conference titans got the job done behind the
clutch play of senior guard Matt Santangelo, who scored 26 points,
18 of on 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Senior poise and senior ability won this for Gonzaga, which
didn't take its first lead until the 2 1/2-minute mark of the
second half, but assumed command in the final 8 1/2 minutes,
frustrating St. John's with a superb all-around display of
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga broke the final tie (54-54) on a Mark Spink layup with
8:20 left. Santangelo followed with his fourth 3-pointer, and St.
John's never got closer than 3 again.
</P>
<P>
   But long before Santangelo stuck in the final daggers, Gonzaga
had taken control on the inside. St. John's had gone a long way
this year with a front line that topped off at 6 feet 7 inches, but
size finally caught up with them in the second half when 6-9 Casey
Calvary, foul-hampered in the first half, powered in for some easy
baskets that seemed to break the Red Storm's spirit. With the
inside game established, Santangelo was freed up to deposit some of
his signature bombs. So Gonazga, the 10th seed in the West, moves
on to play sixth-seeded Purdue Thursday in Albuquerque. No longer
should anyone, anywhere, doubt the legitimacy of this team.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue advanced by virtue of a 66-62 triumph over Oklahoma. It
was pretty much the same senior story, as the Boilermakers got
superb clutch play from senior guard Jaraan Cornell and senior
forward Brian Cardinal to advance into the Sweet 16 for the third
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's certainly huffed and puffed, and there were probably
times when the Red Storm players thought they were going to blow
down the Gonzaga house. But that was just not going to happen. St.
John's led by only 3, 36-33, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had a wire-to-wire advantage in the first half,
scoring the first 6 points of the game, even as Calvary was busy
picking up two personals in the first 1:39. The Big East champs
would lead twice by 9 (the last at 34-25) and twice by 8, but the
resilient boys from Spokane have been through too much during the
past two seasons to be fazed by anything as piddling as those
deficits.
</P>
<P>
   And you had to suspect that the 'Zags were feeling pretty good
at the half, considering that leading scorer Richie Frahm had laid
a nice 0-0-0 goose egg.
</P>
<P>
   With Frahm silenced, Gonzaga needed a boost from Santangelo, and
the cagey vet delivered with a desperately needed 13 that included
three 3-pointers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0019 </DOCNO>
