<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UMASS-FLINT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCES SAY FLINT'S JOB SAFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bruiser Flint is expected to remain as head coach at
the University of Massachusetts, two sources close to the
basketball program said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   UMass officials are scheduled to meet with Flint Sunday and his
future at the school ``looks positive,'' one source said. ``It's
more than OK,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   Flint's status as head coach had been a matter of speculation
since UMass lost to Siena in the first round of the National
Invitation Tournament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   University chancellor David Scott Saturday praised Flint for
fielding a winning team free of off-court troubles, with players
who graduate. But Scott said the school still has concerns about
financial issues, such as sagging attendance, and added that a
decision regarding Flint will be made ``within a week or so.''
</P>
<P>
   And while that decision could come as early as Sunday, the
program hangs in the balance despite calls from noted alumni such
as Julius Erving and Bill Cosby to endorse Flint's return.
</P>
<P>
   Flint is left with little to say about his future to current
players and prospects. He has talented junior college player Jackie
Rogers on campus for an official recruiting visit, and the player
is said to be waiting to see if Flint will stay on as coach before
he makes his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my players not to worry about it,'' said Flint.
``They're kids, and I know they want me to be the coach. They've
expressed that. I don't want them to make any decision in haste, so
I told them I will discuss things when everything is said and
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint, who is 71-56 with three postseason appearances in four
years, scoffed at rumors he might be asked to make a staff change,
saying, ``No one has asked me do do that.'' He also denied rumors
he has been offered a buyout, and declined to comment on the
possibility of him being reassigned to another position within the
university.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, who met separately with Scott and athletic director
Bob Marcum on Friday, has a base salary of about $132,000, with
incentives that push it to around $450,000. A buyout would call for
the school to pay him for the rest of this year, plus $175,000 for
each of the two remaining years.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the wait is unnerving, Flint said, ``Of course. It has
to be. I just want to know what's going on. I'm just going about my
job, and I won't stop working.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said removal of a person from a position at UMass such as
head basketball coach would come only following the recommendation
of a department head, which in this case would be Marcum. As of
Saturday, he had not received any such recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Marcum scoffed at a report that he had had a verbal
confrontation with professor John Bracey and Ricardo Townes,
assistant vice chancellor for campus activities, with regard to
Flint's future. ``The only thing I can tell you is that they
approached me before the Siena game and asked me why am I not
supporting Coach Flint, and I said, `Yeah, right, I'm not
supporting him. Right,' and I walked away,'' said Marcum. ``Who in
the hell do they think gave him the (contract) extension?''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the vocal support Flint is receiving, you would
think a decision on his future would be a formality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you look at the overall picture, Coach Flint is
quite commendable,'' said Scott. ``He has taken us to the
postseason in three of his four years. He is 71-56, and that can't
be seen as a bad record. He has done well with players in terms of
graduation. His program has had no trouble with him as coach. And
all of these things are important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the chancellor would not say that those attributes add up to
a vote of confidence. ``There are other issues to consider, such as
attendance at games,'' he said. ``A program's success has to be
judged, to some extent, by participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a concern to us. It is not the only thing, but it is an
important aspect. Sometimes (a drop in attendance) is the coach's
fault. Sometimes it's the fault of the team. Sometimes the fault is
the dynamics and behaviors of fans. But it is something we have to
be concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott acknowledged Flint's sensitive timetable _ such as the
fact that he has a recruit on campus who is awaiting word on the
coach's future. ``He needs to know. In yesterday's meeting, he
talked and I listened,'' said the chancellor. ``We talked about the
program's future. I told him we have not come to a decision yet but
a lot of what he had to say was important to our overall
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott said he is concerned that fans might have reached
unrealistic expectations about the program, believing it must make
the NCAA tournament every year. He also acknowledged that Flint was
handed a huge burden his first season, when UMass was coming off a
Final Four run and was embroiled in controversy after then-star
center Marcus Camby admitted to receiving cash and gifts from a
would-be agent. ``I'm sure other coaches in his profession used
that against him in recruiting,'' said Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with all that said, the chancellor still pointed to
attendance at the Mullins Center, which averaged 5,836 this season,
down from 8,499 a season ago. ``One has to be realistic,'' said
Scott. ``We're running a big program. We have 29 sports and we have
gender equity concerns. We have to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott said the coach's fate is not solely tied to sagging
attendance figures. ``This is not a place where an administration
makes judgments solely on attendance or anything else,'' he said.
``We give people an opportunity to build programs and establish
themselves. I think our record dictates that we don't make
judgments just because of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about lingering talk that the possible removal of Flint,
who is African-American, might divide the school along racial
lines, Scott said, ``I have a strong commitment to building
diversity on this campus in all areas. I think it is important to
have visible diversity in athletics as well as other areas. It is
important to the university to make those efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   If sources close to the basketball program are correct, it might
not turn out to be an issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
