<HEADLINE>
ONE WRITER'S CHOICE FOR HALL OF FAME ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Hall of Fame ballot has arrived. The announcement
of the inductees will be made during Kentucky Derby week, and
enshrinement will take place at the National Museum of Racing at
Saratoga, N.Y., in August.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible, a jockey must have ridden for 15 years; a
trainer must have conditioned thoroughbreds for 25 years; a
contemporary horse must have been retired for five years; and a
horse of yesteryear must have been retired for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a look at the nominees, and how one turf writer voted:
</P>
<P>
   JOCKEY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Earlie Fires, Julie Krone, Jack Westrope.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: 1. Fires; 2. Krone; 3. Westrope.
</P>
<P>
   Krone, the most accomplished of female jockeys, will be the
fashionable pick, but this voter thinks Fires is a superior rider.
There is no bias here against Krone. When she was good, she was
very, very good. Krone retired in 1999, her skills greatly
diminished by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Fires is still going at age 53. He was the nation's leading
apprentice in 1965, and has won more than 6,000 races. Because he
has been based in the Midwest, he has never gotten the recognition
he deserves. No one is better on a front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   If Krone, who won 3,545 races, doesn't get elected this year,
she will soon. She won more races and earned more money in purses
($81.8 million) than any other female rider, and she is the only
woman to win a Triple Crown event, capturing the Belmont on
Colonial Affair in 1993. Even though favored Prairie Bayou broke
down in that race while making a big move, Krone still deserves
credit for putting on a rousing come-from-behind ride. Krone had
courage, and she would go through a small hole. That sense of
bravado led to many spills, which shortened her career.
</P>
<P>
   Those who dislike Krone feel she received favorable treatment
from stewards, and, more importantly, garnered more publicity than
she deserved. At the height of her game, she may have had trouble
fitting in with the top 10 male jockeys, some of whom barely got
mentioned. This writer has voted for Fires before, against tougher
competition. This writer would also vote for Krone in the right
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Westrope was the leading jockey in the country in 1933. He was
killed when his mount threw him into the rail during the running of
the Hollywood Oaks in 1958. He may have been a better rider than
both Fires and Krone, but how many are left to know?
</P>
<P>
   TRAINER &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Neil Drysdale, Richard Mandella, Willard Proctor.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: 1. Mandella; 2. Drysdale; 3. Proctor.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella has been terrific over the last two decades, in a class
with D. Wayne Lukas, Bill Mott, and relative newcomer Bob Baffert.
His starters have earned more than $75.5 million, and he has
saddled 100 stake winners. He has trained the likes of Kotashaan
(1993 Horse of the Year), Gentlemen, Wild Rush, Siphon, Sandpit,
Best Pal, Phone Trick, and Afternoon Deelites. He also conditioned
Dare And Go, who ended Cigar's record-tying 16-race winning streak
when they met in the 1996 Pacific Classic. If you've watched him
work, you know how good he is.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, who trained 1992 Horse of the Year A.P. Indy, will
certainly be elected soon, if not this year. He has won five
Breeders' Cup races, and could be a very big deal this year, as he
has several talented 3-year-old colts, including War Chant.
</P>
<P>
   Proctor, who died in 1988, trained for more than 40 years. He
was a jockey in the 1930s. Again, who knows? Maybe the Hall of Fame
needs an old-timers committee, as Major League Baseball has.
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY MALE HORSE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: A.P. Indy, Precisionist, Unbridled.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: 1. A.P. Indy; 2. Unbridled; 3. Precisionist.
</P>
<P>
   A.P. Indy was hampered by injury, but he was a great racehorse.
He ran only 11 times, winning eight and earning nearly $3 million.
He won the Santa Anita Derby in 1992 but was scratched the morning
of the Kentucky Derby because of a foot problem. Missing the Run
for the Roses cost him in the fame game. The son of Seattle Slew
came back to win the Belmont Stakes, and, at age 4, he won the
Breeders' Cup Classic and earned the Golden Eclipse. Simply put, he
was a monster.
</P>
<P>
   Unbridled was brilliant when he was in the mood. He took the
Kentucky Derby and the Breeders' Cup Classic in 1990. However, he
had a lot of off days and won only 8 of 24 races. He is worthy of
election but is no match for A.P. Indy.
</P>
<P>
   The versatile Precisionist was competitive from 6 furlongs to 1
1/4 miles. He was very good, but not as good as the other two
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY &QC; 
FEMALE HORSE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Flawlessly, Mom's Command, Winning Colors.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: 1. Winning Colors; 2. Mom's Command; 3. Flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Winning Colors is one of just three fillies to win the Kentucky
Derby, scoring in 1988 to join Regret and Genuine Risk. That alone
puts her in the Hall. Forty Niner may have won that Rose Run with a
better ride from Pat Day, but Winning Colors lasted at the wire.
The same season, Winning Colors staged a memorable duel with the
undefeated Personal Ensign, arguably the greatest filly of all time
(hello, Ruffian), losing the Breeders' Cup Distaff when Personal
Ensign caught her in the last stride. Winning Colors won just 8 of
19 starts, but she won the one that counts _ a rarity for a female.
</P>
<P>
   This voter requested that Mom's Command, owned by local
sportsman Peter Fuller and winner of the 1985 Triple Tiara, be
nominated after an absence of a couple of years, but I can't vote
against a Kentucky Derby victor. Hopefully, Mom's Command will get
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Flawlessly was a tremendous turf mare, but no match for the top
two.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE OF YESTERYEAR &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Bowl Of Flowers, Cougar II, Needles.
</P>
<P>
   The vote: 1. Needles; 2. Cougar II; 3. Bowl of Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Needles took the 1956 Kentucky Derby, was second in the
Preakness (to Fabius), and won the Belmont. Cougar II was a grass
horse, and Bowl of Flowers was a filly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
