<HEADLINE>
FATHER-IN-LAW CLEARED POLI FOR TAKEOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bill Parcells was asking the hard questions,
the way a father-in-law can. He was asking about the new job and
where the man who'd just married his daughter thought he was going
with it. He was asking tough questions, which is something Parcells
is better at than most people in the NFL which is why he wins more
often than most people in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Now came the moment Scott Pioli had to come up with the answers.
Only problem was, this was also his boss asking tough questions
about a new job in a new city, a job working for a guy Parcells had
come to despise and for a team Pioli's present employer had come to
view the way the Red Sox view the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   As Parcells waited, the young New York Jets' director of pro
scouting thought about his friend Bill Belichick up in Foxborough,
who had rejected the Jets' plan for him to replace Parcells as head
coach and taken a job with the Patriots, an act that led to warfare
between the teams before a deal was made that cost New England its
No. 1 draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick then asked Pioli, whose work he'd grown to admire, to
come with him as assistant director of personnel, a promotion by
any standards. He was asking Pioli, for all intents and purposes,
to come help him beat the Jets twice a year. But the Jets had
initially denied Belichick permission to talk with Pioli for that
reason _ and probably a few less noble ones.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tit-for-tat spat that the Jets probably knew they
couldn't win, but Pioli didn't want it to go that way. Instead, he
sat with his father-in-law and discussed the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me some difficult but very fair questions,'' Pioli
explained recently about last month's dilemma. ``He asked me
questions that made me think. He wanted me to think through what I
was doing and he had a responsibility to the Jets which I
understood. I was under contract.''
</P>
<P>
   After the discussion, Parcells was satisfied, and within 24
hours, Pioli was a Patriot _ and a mortal enemy of the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people thought this was all about the Jets vs. the
Patriots and Bill's situation up here but I don't know enough about
that rivalry,'' said Pioli. ``Unlike Bill, I hadn't been with the
Patriots before. I didn't have enough background with the personal
things to understand anything about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the anxiety was my own internal anxiety. Bill did not
make it personally difficult for me. He didn't make it too
difficult a situation. I wanted to do what I felt was best for me
and my wife without disrespecting family. I wasn't going to
disrespect Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Pioli wasn't aware permission had been denied for
Belichick to speak with him but he found out because Parcells told
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accepted that as his right,'' Pioli said. ``Business is
business. I was under contract with the Jets, just as I was in
Baltimore when I went to the Jets. But this was not a lateral move.
A lateral move is not the way I think you conduct your business
when you're under contract. That would have been disrespectful to
Bill and to the Jets and I wouldn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be fair to the Jets but they knew I had an
opportunity out there with New England. This was a decision more
about opportunity and responsibilities, not personal relationships.
Once I made the decision, I knew it was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioli knew it was the right decision because he knew Belichick,
who had befriended him years ago while he was an All-New England
defensive tackle at Central Connecticut and Belichick was a rising
face on Parcells's New York Giants coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Pioli would visit the Giants' training camp and later would help
Belichick when the coach went to scout college players at Syracuse,
where Pioli was a graduate assistant. A relationship and a respect
grew, and when Pioli decided to leave a coaching job at Murray
State in 1992 to take a scouting position with the 49ers, he got a
call that led him to make a decision few sane men back then would
have.
</P>
<P>
   Pioli chose to move to Cleveland when he could have lived in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill heard I was pursuing a job in personnel with the 49ers
and he called me from Cleveland (where Belichick was the Browns'
head coach) and asked why I hadn't called him,'' Pioli recalled.
``I had committed to an interview in San Francisco but then I flew
directly to Cleveland. When I got there, there was a message
offering me a job with the 49ers and Bill said, `You've got a job
here, too.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There were greater responsibilities in Cleveland, even though
it was an entry-level position. It was just prior to the free agent
explosion, and as pro scouting became a bigger thing, I was there
to learn and get involved with the salary cap and contracts plus
scouting players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were things I loved about coaching, but I think I'm
better in player evaluation than coaching the X's and O's. I loved
what I was doing immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Browns moved to Baltimore after the 1995 season, Pioli
went with them, even as Belichick was fired. The front office had
been gutted as well as the coaching staff, and because of that,
Pioli's responsibilities grew. As his expertise increased, his
relationship with Belichick remained close, so close that when
Belichick became the Jets' head coach, he asked the Ravens for
permission to talk to Pioli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the first time Bill became head coach of the Jets he
called,'' Pioli said with a laugh, referring to the few days
Belichick was the boss before Parcells ironed out a deal with
Patriots owner Bob Kraft that allowed him to jump his contract and
go to New York following New England's 1996 Super Bowl season.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Pioli ended up in New York, where he met Dallas
Parcells. The two fell in love and got married less than a year
ago, and now Pioli has followed his mentor and friend to New
England, where his job will be simple: Find Belichick the players
he needs to beat the Jets, something the Patriots haven't been too
adept at since Parcells left New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons this job was attractive is I know Bill and
understand his philosophy,'' Pioli said. ``I understand the kind of
players he needs for his system and that makes it easier to be
successful. Personnel people need to understand the coach's
philosophy because once you do you have a greater chance of
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is one of the hardest-working and most meticulous people
I've ever been around. And one of the most loyal. We work well
together.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, they are doing it with Bill Parcells's blessing,
too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is a slow time of year around the NFL, but one bit of local
news emerged last week when Needham native Mike Tannenbaum was
promoted by the Jets from salary cap guru to director of pro player
development. Although his name is not well known to the public, he
is one of the sharpest young contract men in the business and a
good part of the reason the Jets have been able to avoid the
crippling cap problems predicted for them since the day Parcells
signed Curtis Martin as a free agent . . . A sad story came to an
end Thursday when 49ers offensive line coach Bobb McKittrick died
after a long battle with cancer. The 64-year-old McKittrick was
brave and upbeat to the end, a fighter from his days in the Marines
to his final days in the NFL. He was the architect of one of the
ablest offensive lines of the 1980s and '90s and had much more to
do with the 49ers' long run of offensive success than he was ever
given credit for. The way he handled his repeated battles with
cancer and his steadfast insistence on coaching to the end was an
example of what courage and grit are all about. He will be missed
by the 49ers and by everyone who ever had the pleasure to sit down
with him for a few hours and listen to how football was supposed to
be played or a life was supposed to be led . . . Free agent Tedy
Bruschi is a good guy wandering in a wilderness he doesn't seem to
quite fathom. Bruschi was close to signing a reported two-year, $3
million deal with the Patriots that included a $1 million signing
bonus. That is a far cry from his starting point of seeking a four-
to five-year deal averaging $2.5 million a season and including a
$3 million bonus. Those were numbers he was never likely to
receive, but what is worse is that he left on the table a five-year
offer worth $9 million that included a $1.5 million bonus in Green
Bay. That averages out to $1.8 million a season, which means if he
ends up in New England under the present parameters, he will have
cost himself $600,000 over the next two years. More importantly,
Bruschi seems to think the market will increase as time passes, but
history indicates that it decreases after the initial burst of
activity. His hope remains Cleveland, because it has the cap room
to do what it wants, but the fact is if it wanted to do something
big with Bruschi, it would have been done already. So, if he's
smart, he'll grab what he can today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 0206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
