<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY ORGANIZERS RUNNING IN THE RED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Though the Lords of the Rings gave them an enthusiastic
thumbs-up during a recent visit Down Under, the Sydney organizers
are facing a hefty budget deficit with the Summer Games only six
months off.
</P>
<P>
   After wildly overestimating both ticket and sponsorship income,
the organizing committee, SOCOG, is nearly $125 million in the red
after promising a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be a profit,'' beleaguered committee president
Michael Knight finally conceded.
</P>
<P>
   To keep things from getting even worse, the government has taken
over budgeting for every competitive venue.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that all of the facilities are ready to go. And
International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch,
as always, is predicting that the Games will be ``the best ever.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New US Olympic Committee chief executive Norman Blake didn't
waste any time flexing his muscles. Less than a month after taking
over from former executive director Dick Schultz, Blake also nudged
Schultz out of his transitional job as head of OPUS, the joint
marketing arm of the USOC and the Salt Lake organizers. The idea is
to have Blake use his own corporate contacts to rustle up more
sponsors . . . Still on the hook is IOC vice president Kevan
Gosper, who is being investigated by the committee's new ethics
commission after bid documents showed he and his family took a ski
trip to Utah before Salt Lake won the 2002 Games. Gosper, who
insists he reimbursed the bidders, has stepped down from the ethics
panel, which has turned over the case to a yet-unnamed
``independent expert of high reputation.'' . . . Disappointing
reentry by skater Todd Eldredge, who ended up fourth at the Four
Continents championship after winning the short program. Eldredge
not only missed his quadruple jump, he also scaled back three other
jumps. Eldredge knows he'll have to have the quad down solid by
next season to have any hope of making the US team. All three men
who beat him at Four Continents (Canada's Elvis Stojko and China's
Li Chengjiang and Zhang Min) landed the quad . . . Another free
pass to the world skating championships for alternate Angela
Nikodinov. Last year, she went to Helsinki because US runner-up
Naomi Nari Nam was too young to compete. This time, she goes to the
Riviera because runnerup Sasha Cohen failed to win a medal at the
world juniors . . . Newest members of the US Figure Skating Hall of
Fame are Debi Thomas (former world champion and 1988 Olympic
medalist), Scott Allen (youngest US men's champ at 14 in 1964),
six-time US women's titlist Gretchen Merrill of the Skating Club of
Boston, and Frank Zamboni, who invented the ice-cleaning machine.
Named to the world Hall is Ron Ludington, who won five US titles as
pairs coach and the 1960 Olympic bronze as a competitor . . .
Terrific showing by Brookline's Dan Weinstein, who skipped classes
at Harvard long enough to place fourth at the recent world
short-track speedskating championships in England. Weinstein, who
had a rock-bottom seeding after missing virtually all of the World
Cup season, also won three medals in individual races and set an
American record in the 500 meters. Top US woman (in 11th) was Amy
Peterson. The US men finished fifth in the earlier team
championships in the Netherlands, where the women (with Natick's
Caroline Hallisey and Arlington's Sarah Lang) were seventh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Silver lining for US long-track speedskater Christine Witty, who
finished second overall (and won both 1,000-meter races) at the
recent world sprint championships after struggling during the early
season because of overtraining. And a predictable finish for
rookies Nick Pearson (16th) and Joey Cheek (18th), who made the US
men's team after Casey FitzRandolph was injured and Kip Carpenter
missed his trials race with a broken skate. As expected, Canada's
Jeremy Wotherspoon and Germany's Monique Garbrecht retained their
crowns. Witty followed with a bronze in the 1,000 (the only US
medal) at the world single-distance championships . . . Not that it
was a surprise, but Austrians _ Hermann Maier and Renate Goetschl _
swept the World Cup overall skiing titles for the first time since
Karl Schranz and Gertrud Gabl did it in 1969. The Herminator also
became the first to crack the magic 2,000-point mark. ``My first
year I would have been happy with 400 points,'' mused the
27-year-old Maier. ``Now I have five times that. It's incredible.''
. . . Maybe the Americans should dig up Lillehammer's Olympic
downhill course and haul it around the World Cup circuit with them.
Daron Rahlves, who'd never won a Cup race, grabbed back-to-back
downhills this month on the same Kvitfjell run where Tommy Moe won
the 1994 gold medal and where Kyle Rasmussen recorded the last Cup
win by a US male five years ago. Meanwhile, slalom ace Kristina
Koznick came alive down the stretch, with a silver at Are and a
gold at Sestriere . . . Encouraging showing by the US skeleton
sledders at the world championships in Austria. Jim Shea and Tricia
Stumpf both won bronzes in the belly-flop sport, which will be a
medal event in Salt Lake City . . . Not that US biathlon has become
a one-man team, but all $78,500 of the USOC's Podium 2002 grant is
going to Jay Hakkinen, the best prospect since Josh Thompson in
1988. Hakkinen had a promising showing at the recent world
championships in Oslo, with three top 35 placements . . . Best
recycling project of the new century is the start and finish
platforms at Lake Placid's new combined bobsled/luge run, which the
US Plastic Lumber folks made from a million recycled milk jugs
reinforced with fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last chance for the US women's field hockey team to make it to
Sydney comes at this week's final qualifier in England, where the
Americans must place in the top five in the 10-team field. To make
matters worse, they're in a tough preliminary pool with Germany
(World Cup bronze medalist), Spain (1992 Olympic champion),
Ireland, and India. The US, which was 1-2-2 against the Irish in a
recent tuneup series in California, can't be any lower than third
in its pool to advance. On the squad are seven returning Olympians
plus local players Tara Jelley of Greenfield and Kristen Holmes of
Raynham . . . Though gold medalists Shannon Miller and Dominique
Moceanu weren't invited to Bela Karolyi's latest gymnastics boot
camp last week, they could still petition their way to July's
national championships in St. Louis based on their resumes. ``I'm
positive they would get the green light,'' says Karolyi. ``But they
better come and perform. They will not make the Olympic team if
they are not proving it on the floor.'' . . . No surprises on the
US synchronized swimming team for Sydney. Tammy Cleland-McGregor
and Heather Olson are gold-medal veterans from 1996, and newly
naturalized Anna Kozlova competed for the Unified Team (i.e. Soviet
Union) in 1992. The remaining members _ Carrie Barton, Bridget
Finn, Kristina Lum, Elicia Marshall, Tuesday Middaugh, and Kim
Wurzel _ have been with the team since Atlanta . . . Gold medals
will be the least of what the Belarussian athletes will be
competing for Down Under. ``Just produce the result and you'll have
an apartment and dozens of thousands of dollars and you'll provide
for yourself for the rest of your life,'' promises president
Alexander Lukashenko. ``I'll buy you anything you need, be it guns,
boats, swimming trunks, even undershorts. But God forbid if I hear
any complaint or question on the eve of your departure for
Sydney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
