<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-WRITETHRU-     03-19 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY WINS OPENER 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ For verbally attacking the referee's following the
Galaxy's 2-0 loss to D.C. United in November's MLS Cup, Galaxy
coach Sigi Schmid was slapped with a $1,000 fine and a suspension
for Saturday's Major League Soccer season opener with Colorado at
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Schmid was far from the field for this one,
because he would have come out of his shoes when a questionable
call resulted in a Colorado penalty kick, erasing a 1-0 second half
lead for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Schmid's health, a make-up call minutes later
allowed Greg Vanney to convert a penalty shot in the 74th minute,
giving the Galaxy a 2-1 victory over the Rapids in front of 24,831.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapids, riddled with injuries, played defensive for most of
the night, nearly walking away with a draw. But in the end, the
Galaxy's dominant play was rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we were going to give up possession because we
had a lot of inexperienced players on the field,'' said Colorado
coach Glenn Myernick. ``What do you do as a coach? You back up,
give them possession in areas of the field that don't count and see
if you can counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost pulled this one out, but I still thought we came in
here and battled very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, talking afterward, was disappointed the Galaxy couldn't
convert a few more chances, but he was satisfied with the overall
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the run of play, it was a deserved win for us,'' said
Schmid. ``The game was pretty much the way I thought it would be. I
felt they would play fairly conservative and sit in the back. If we
finished some of our chances in the first half it would have opened
up the game and been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it was a first game and first games you always have
nerves,'' he continued. ``I still think we could be quicker, take
people on sooner and be more dynamic in what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   After Cobi Jones gave the Galaxy a 1-0 lead in the 60th minute,
the series of questionable calls followed.
</P>
<P>
   First, Paul Bravo appeared offside on a deep pass into the
Galaxy penalty area. Then, Bravo tried to dribble by Galaxy
goalkeeper Kevin Hartman, but the two were tangled. As the ball
rolled away, referee Ricardo Valenzuela whistled a penalty kick,
calling a tripping penalty on Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   Bravo converted the penalty kick, tying the game 1-1 in the 64th
minute, ending Colorado's MLS record 743 minute scoreless streak
that dated back to last season.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps feeling a little guilty, Valenzuela awarded a penalty
kick to the Galaxy minutes later, whistling Colorado defender
Marcelo Balboa for an innocent-looking tackle to Cienfuegos in the
penalty area. Vanney converted the the shot, giving the the
game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   For a change, Schmid, Myernick and Galaxy assistant coach Ralph
Perez were unanimous that the referees had a lot to do with the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take this (question) because I want to see Sigi at our
next game,'' said Perez, when asked about the referee's decisions
on both ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're at the worst seat in the house, but after watching the
replay, it appeared that he (Bravo) was offside and if you talk to
our guys, I'm sure they will tell you they didn't think we took him
(Bravo) down,'' said Perez. ``That's soccer, I'm sure if you talk
to Myernick, he'll tell you he didn't think there was a penalty the
other way. But that's soccer and you have to live with these
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite constant pressure, the Galaxy couldn't take advantage of
a couple early chances and one late in the opening half.
</P>
<P>
   Jones freed himself from two Colorado defenders along the right
side, but his cross drifted back toward the penalty spot. Clint
Mathis back-pedaled, getting just enough of his head to send a
looping shot toward the Colorado net, but it bounced off the
crossbar in the seventh minute.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Cienfuegos picked up a loose ball in the
penalty area and split two Rapids defenders, but his shot
ricocheted off the near post.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Mathis combined later to give the Galaxy another good
chance minutes before the half.
</P>
<P>
   From 40 yards out, Jones sent a cross to the middle of the
penalty area for Mathis. Running away from the goal, Mathis snapped
a back-header to the far post, but Rapids goalkeeper Adin Brown
lunged to his left to tuck it in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
