<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-WILLIAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS' METHODS MIGHT EVEN MAKE ORANGE BLOOD CURDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're an Orangeblood, yes, Ricky Williams is one of your
own, and that is worth something.
</P>
<P>
   But all Heisman Trophies aside, has this guy gone nuts, or what?
</P>
<P>
   The Rastafarian-locked one was on the wrong side of the news
again last week, this time slamming New Orleans _ the city, the
team, the secretaries (''They'll rat on you''), even the new head
coach, whom he's met exactly once.
</P>
<P>
   The first temptation is to write this off as yet another episode
of indiscretion by a still-very-immature California kid, who was
possibly taken advantage of by a slick magazine writer (John Ed
Bradley) who gave him that
hey-I-was-a-player-and-I-know-where-you're-coming-from line.
</P>
<P>
   But it's time that people quit making excuses for Ricky
Williams, the one-time pride of the Texas Longhorns. He is 22 years
old, and there are high school kids who show more poise, more
social sophistication and more simple common sense than Williams
seems to have.
</P>
<P>
   In the current issue of ``Sports Illustrated'', he told Bradley,
``I'd fire everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They should move the team to San Antonio. Change the name. I'd
live in Austin. I'd rather live in Austin than San Antonio. New
Orleans is a great place to hang out, but it's not a great place to
live and to work. ... When I was hanging out there, I had the best
time of my life. But when I had to go to work there, I hated it.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't elaborate. Bradley, a former college lineman,
described Williams' suburban New Orleans home as something of an
upscale pig sty. Food on the floor. Dirty clothes piled everywhere.
Except for a weekly visit to Hooter's, Williams seldom ventured
anywhere, preferring to stay home and wait for friends from Austin
to visit him.
</P>
<P>
   His rookie NFL season was, by most standards, a failure. He
seemed to stay injured _ an elbow, an ankle, a toe. After a senior
season at Texas in which he scored 28 touchdowns, Williams in a
Saints uniform scored only two. He gained 884 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-year, $68 million contract that he signed was so laden
with clauses based upon performance, Williams reportedly earned
just $225,000 in salary last season. He reached only one of the
ill-conceived contract's 25 incentives.
</P>
<P>
   On draft day then-coach Mike Ditka had raised brows _ and fans'
expectations _ by trading all of the Saints' draft picks (plus
first and third-round picks this year) for the rights to select
Williams. As a sign of their new bond, the two appeared in wedding
garb _ Ricky wearing the bridal dress _ on the cover of a national
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the 3-13 season, even Ditka was no longer
blindly defending his ``bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that because the Saints have never had a star
player, no one there knew how to treat him.
</P>
<P>
   Not likely. How much book learning do you need to know how to
treat a lazy, overrated dog?
</P>
<P>
   No stars? Earl Campbell and Archie Manning were once Saints, as
were Hall of Famers Doug Atkins and Jim Taylor. A ridiculous
argument.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the entire NFL career of Ricky Williams has been
pretty much ridiculous, from the big trade, to the wedding gown, to
refusing to do interviews unless he had his helmet and face shield
on, to curling up in the fetal position in his locker after the
game in Baltimore, to these latest bizarre comments.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that in college, while the Texas PR machine was
cranking out tall tales about Ricky commemorating his heroes and
helping old ladies cross streets, the dispatches all made reference
to what a ``genuine'' person he was.
</P>
<P>
   He was so genuine that he spurned advice and enlisted rapper
Master P to negotiate his NFL contract, a deal that Williams now
thinks the Saints should tear up and ``correct.'' And he was so
genuine that upon meeting the Saints' new coach, Jim Haslett, for
the first time last month, he was offended because Haslett had the
nerve to ask Mr. Heisman if he had been working out.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   On the Ricky Williams Web site _ ``my official Web site,'' it
says _ visitors were invited to weigh in on the ``Sports
Illustrated'' article. And they did, dozens worth, with comments
such as ``quit whining, you crybaby,'' ``shut up and put up,'' and
``I hope you get drilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Haslett conceivably could trade him, if he thought he could get
equal value and somehow escape the $8 million salary-cap charge
that it would cost the Saints. But it isn't likely.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams and the Saints are forever wedded, in more ways
than one. He hardly acts old enough to even know it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
