<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLOYD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISORS SUCH A PAIN, BUT SO IS LOSING AN EYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Next time,'' Stars winger Brenden Morrow always says when his
mom, Lucille, pleads with him to wear a half-shield protective
visor while playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's worried something is going to happen to me. ... I've had
a couple of close ones, a skate right by the eye, a puck in the
eye, too,'' Morrow admits. ``Each time I said next time I get
stitches I'll put one on.''
</P>
<P>
   Only ``next time'' comes and he never does.
</P>
<P>
   And as Toronto defenseman Bryan Berard, 23, learned, sometimes
``next time'' is too late.
</P>
<P>
   Berard was injured eight days ago when Ottawa's Marian Hossa
followed through on a slap shot and caught him on the eye with the
stick. Optimism remains because Berard can distinguish light from
dark, but doctors say chances that he'll regain sight in the eye
are slim.
</P>
<P>
   Without sight in the eye, his chances of continuing his hockey
career are also slim.
</P>
<P>
   Tragic. Horrible. Terrible. Scary.
</P>
<P>
   You name it. NHL players have said it about Berard's injury.
</P>
<P>
   But while Berard's injury had everyone in the NHL talking about
wearing visors, the reality is it hasn't convinced anybody to wear
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like them,'' Stars winger Brett Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't like them until he had his nose flattened by an errant
stick earlier in the season, forcing him to wear one for his safety
when he returned. Then, he really didn't like them. The full cage
shield he had to wear because doctors wouldn't let him return
without it was gone after two games.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't alone either.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor had to wear one earlier in the
year to protect an eye injury. But as soon as he was allowed to
take it off, he did. The list goes on and on ...
</P>
<P>
   Yes, close calls have a way of making players think about
wearing a visor.
</P>
<P>
   But, the reality is that they rarely do.
</P>
<P>
   OK, sometimes they do. A close call prompted Stars center Guy
Carbonneau to wear one for almost eight years. He had been skating
in practice in Montreal when he was hit with a stick in the eye. It
scratched his cornea. When he returned a week later, it was with a
visor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd play a game and I'd look at the visor afterwards and there
were always black marks,'' Carbonneau remembers. ``And I'd say
`Wow, that could be my eye.'''
</P>
<P>
   But you're probably saying to yourself, I've seen Guy Carbonneau
play. He doesn't wear a visor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got tired of it,'' Carbonneau explained.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped wearing it right before coming to Dallas. His reasons
are like the ones you hear from most of the players. Visors are hot
and sweaty. They increase the amount of stick work in the league.
You can't see the puck at your feet.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning sounds as if it makes a lot of sense until you
consider that Bryan Berard might not be able to see at all.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, when you think about it that way, Lucille Morrow makes a
lot more sense.
</P>
<P>
   Next time, after all, may be too late.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON: TONY AMONTE
</P>
<P>
   Blackhawks winger Tony Amonte has 75 points this season (38
goals and 37 assists), which ranks him fifth in the NHL behind only
players like Pittsburgh's Jaromir Jagr and Florida's Pavel Bure.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he says he considers this season a complete failure.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the fact that his Blackhawks have 66 points in the
standings, which ranks them fifth-worst in the NHL, ahead only of
teams like Atlanta and the New York Islanders, goes a long way to
explaining his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are on a losing club, nobody is really successful, and
that's the bottom line,'' Amonte said. ``When you are losing,
numbers don't matter except for maybe, `Could I do more to help the
team win?`''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, bad teams are especially hard to stomach for good
players.
</P>
<P>
   Who would've blamed Amonte if he had been asked to be traded to
a contender before last week's deadline? The Hawks were, after all,
having a fire sale, with players like Sylvain Cote and Doug Gilmour
getting out of town just in time.
</P>
<P>
   There were rumors about Amonte, too.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he wanted to stay, wants to stay and help return the
Blackhawks to contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they want to win,'' Amonte said. ``I know (owner) Mr.
(Bill) Wirtz wants to have a winning club and put a winning team on
the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning is one thing. Winning a Stanley Cup is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   Amonte, 29, wants to win a Stanley Cup. He never has. He says
plenty of time remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still am young and I think I'll have a couple of more
chances in my career,'' Amonte said.
</P>
<P>
   Amonte also realizes while the Blackhawks have won a couple of
games lately, including some impressive victories against
contenders, that doesn't mean they are ``that'' close.
</P>
<P>
   And if they were, they might be even tougher to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would mean we should've been doing it all year,'' Amonte
said. ``We should've, too. The group of guys we have isn't too
different from the group of guys we started with.''
</P>
<P>
   ROAD TO THE STANLEY CUP
</P>
<P>
   The start of the Stanley Cup playoffs is 31/2 weeks away, and
here's a look at who's who and what's what on the path there: WHO'S
HOT
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: They are 7-2-2 in their last 11 games. The Wings are
heating up at just the right time.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO'S JOE SAKIC: He has 11 goals and seven assists in the
past nine games. Colorado needs him firing on all cylinders if
they're going to advance far in the playoffs. WHO'S NOT
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY: They're 4-5-1 in their past 10 games. What does it
say about the East's chances for a Cup when its best hope is the
struggling Devils?
</P>
<P>
   RANGERS' THEO FLEURY: He has 15 goals this season. Didn't the
Rangers sign him to get them to the playoffs?
CUP FRONT-RUNNER
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Yes, Chris Osgood still is in goal, but the rest of the
team is looking pretty good.
CUP DARK HORSE
</P>
<P>
   THE STARS: Don't count out a chance for a repeat just yet. The
Stars have shown amazing resiliency this season.
THE TOP 3 LIST Here's the top three explanations for why the
Buffalo Sabres have gone from Cup finalists to likely missing the
playoffs:
</P>
<P>
   3. The signs were there, but they didn't shake it up until it
was too late.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mr. All-Everything, Michael Peca, has only 17 goals and 19
assists.
</P>
<P>
   1. No Dominik Hasek. Repeat. No best goalie in the NHL for most
of this season. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
