<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PETTY READY FOR WINSTON CUP DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Teen-ager Adam Petty said patience is a
virtue that doesn't mix well with who he is and what he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I learned how to be more patient last year. But at 19
years old, being patient in a race car is really, really hard,''
said Petty, the fourth-generation NASCAR driver who plans to make
his Winston Cup debut at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your emotions get going when you get in that seat and you get
pumped up about seeing the lead. You say, `Hey, man, I want to get
there. I got to get there. I'm going to do whatever I can to get
there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough to get in your head to be calm.''
</P>
<P>
   The grandson of NASCAR legend Richard Petty, Adam is the first
fourth-generation athlete in any professional sport. If he does
crack the 43-car field for the DirecTV 500 on April 2, Adam will
race against his father, Kyle Petty, for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, I'm real comfortable at Texas,'' said Petty, a
second-year competitor in NASCAR's Busch Grand National Series,
where he is driving the No. 45 Sprint Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``We
went there with the Busch car and qualified third (last March). But
I was a little impatient and didn't run good in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty crashed after 84 laps and finished 39th in his TMS Busch
debut. But he returned for a NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series event in
one of King Richard's Dodge Rams last summer, accumulating
experience on the 1.5-mile quadoval.
</P>
<P>
   The Cup race at TMS is the first of five Petty plans to run in
2000, keeping him eligible for the 2001 Raybestos Rookie of the
Year chase. Adam's graduation to NASCAR's premier series will
coincide with Petty Enterprises' switch from the Pontiac Grand Prix
to the new Dodge Intrepid R/T program.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with great-grandfather Lee Petty, the clan has enjoyed
a storied relationship with DaimlerChrysler. At this stage of his
career, however, Adam is more interested in logging lap after hot
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not being cocky or anything, but I think I can go out
there and drive a Winston Cup car,'' Adam said. ``My ultimate goal
is if the race is 500 laps, to go out there and run 500 laps. If
it's 300 laps, go out there and run 300 laps. Keep the fenders on
it, and just learn as much as I can.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1515 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-UCLA-SIDE-LADN     03-19 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA STAFF KEPT IT SIMPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS - As game plans go, this was a da Vinci. UCLA's
coaches had a short list of goals to beat Maryland - nothing
unusual, all standard fare - and the Bruins executed them
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same stuff we've been preaching to the guys all
season, and we just hit on all cylinders,'' said Bruins assistant
Jim Saia after the 105-70 second-round victory Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Maryland's defense live and on film, the Bruins saw
nothing that necessitated drastic changes.
</P>
<P>
   If fast-break opportunities existed, UCLA went to the rim. If
not, point guard Earl Watson was instructed to back off and run the
halfcourt offense. As they have throughout their eight-game winning
streak, the Bruins ran the 1-4 high attack Saia and coach Steve
Lavin implemented in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins did not, however, anticipate as many alley-oop passes
as Maryland allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with the lob passes is that Earl and JaRon (Rush)
have been playing together since AAU ball, and they have a feel for
each other,'' Saia said. ``Earl was putting them on the button.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins did make one subtle change from their first-round
game against Ball State: instead of settling for 3-pointers, they
got big men Dan Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso involved early and often.
The duo combined to make 9 of 9 shots and score 20 points in the
decisive first half.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Bruins contained Maryland's fast break and
prevented slashing point guard Steve Blake from creating offense
through penetration. They also shadowed Juan Dixon, Maryland's
leading scorer and one of the top shooters in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon did not score for 10 minutes, then had 10 points in a
four-minute stretch midway through the first half, then went
scoreless as the Bruins pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be physical with him and limit his touches,''
assistant coach Steve Spencer said. ``He wasn't able to get in the
paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Bruins stopped Maryland's favorite play: a flex
pick that creates easy shots for Dixon, center Lonny Baxter and
forward Terence Morris in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Two players are aligned on the baseline;
the man closest to the basket turns and sets a screen; the other
player rubs his defender off the screen and flashes into the lane
for a six-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got good pressure on the (passer), which is something we've
done well for the last few weeks,'' Spencer said. ``When you get
good ball pressure, it's harder to make the pass into the lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland shot 37.1 percent for the game - 10 percent below its
season average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
