<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-CENTERS-EVOLUTION     03-19 1501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CENTERS-EVOLUTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTER SPECIES: THE EVOLUTION OF THE NBA BIG MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMEWHERE IN THE VERY REMOTE FORESTS OF SPRINGFIELD, MASS. _
Thanks for your attendance and welcome to the NBA's newest theme
attraction, ``Fantastic! Park''.
</P>
<P>
   I'm your pith-helmeted tour guide, Dr. James Naismith, here to
escort you on an educational fast break through the evolution of
basketball's biggest and baddest creatures, the center. Your two
$100 courtside tickets, lifetime Personal Seat License and purchase
of a mid-level luxury suite entitles you Homo Sapiens to join us as
we track the metamorphosis of NBA centers from the Neanderthal
nuances of George Mikan to the state-of-the-art skills of Tim
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare to be amazed at the irrefutable evidence proving Charles
Darwin's ``Tree of Life'' theory is alive and well on the hardwood,
with each new era of stars merely branching out from its roots.
</P>
<P>
   Right this way. And, as a reminder, no feeding the players and,
even more dangerous, no autographs. IN THE BEGINNING
</P>
<P>
   Our journey begins at the first NBA game in 1946, 55 years after
I hung the first peach basket. On your left, that's 6-foot-8
Toronto Huskies center George Nostrand. Considered such a freak at
the time, any fan taller than Nostrand got into the game free.
Today, of course, 6-8 players are point guards, dwarfed by the
league's 34 7-footers.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is the first truly dominant mammal to pace the parquet,
a 6-10, 245-pound bundle of awkward intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Mikan became the NBA's first superstar by making sweeping hook
shots with either hand. In an era in which final scores rarely
inched above 70, Mikan produced the league's first four 50-point
games. His dominance produced five championships for the
Minneapolis Lakers and prompted rules changes geared at him that
outlawed goaltending and widened the lane from six to 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a marvel at the time, Mikan's traits would be dissed
by modern big men. Like the fact he used to travel to cities days
ahead of his team to drum up interest for upcoming games, refused
to dunk because ``it's too embarrassing for other players,'' and
signed a first contract for five years, $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Giving more credence to Darwin's ``strongest shall survive,''
Mikan's dominance eroded along with his knees and the arrival of a
bigger, better ooze of Cretaceous chromosomes. You'll find the
decade of the '60s, ruled by two giants who despised, yet
respected, each other _ Wilt Chamberlain and Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   While players like Walt Bellamy made 30-rebound nights routine
and Nate Thurmond recorded the first quadruple-double in history,
Russell and Chamberlain accelerated the transformation of big men
from awkward-to-awesome like no two in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain was perhaps the most ferocious offensive center
ever. While Mikan dominated with finesse, Wilt was a 7-1, 275-pound
terror. He still owns 56 NBA records (Michael Jordan has five).
Despite making only half his free throws (51 percent) and having
only one offensive move (the ``Big Dipper'' finger roll),
Chamberlain produced the top three highest-scoring games in league
history, topped 50 points 45 times in one ``season'' and averaged
23 rebounds per game in his career.
</P>
<P>
   To get a perspective of how much bigger and better Chamberlain
was than his opponents, imagine a rookie in today's league standing
8-foot, 400 pounds with the skills of a small forward. Despite the
evolutionary advancements in size and skill, there's not a
warm-blooded vertebrate in the paint today who could consistently
muzzle Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   And that feisty, gangly left-hander brave enough to torment
Chamberlain? That's none other than Russell, who revolutionized
defense as Chamberlain transformed offense. Russell led the league
in rebounding five times, averaging 22.5 for his career, and once
grabbed 32 rebounds in a half _ a league record.
</P>
<P>
   Russell ultimately won his rivalry with Chamberlain, leading his
team to 11 championships in 13 years. Almost as impressively,
Russell forced Chamberlain to develop a fadeaway jump shot. SKY'S
THE LIMIT
</P>
<P>
   Next stop is the '70s, where big men expanded their domination
by isolating their talents. Centers like Willis Reed thrived by
relying on heart as much as physical skills, Dave Cowens survived
physical limitations with relentless hustle, and shorter centers
like Wes Unseld (6-7) earned MVP honors by shake, shake, shaking
his enormous booty.
</P>
<P>
   But while the '60s were defined by one rivalry, the '70s were
engulfed by one shot _ Kareem Abdul-Jabbar's sky hook.
</P>
<P>
   Using the single most lethal, unstoppable shot in basketball
history, Jabbar flicked his way to a record 38,387 points in an
unprecedented 20 seasons. Once he began the smooth motion of the
shot out to 18 feet, opposing prey was at his mercy. So effective
and economical was his shot, that Jabbar was named MVP of the
Finals at age 38.
</P>
<P>
   Jabbar's skillful shot seemingly was only an evolutionary
asterisk that got lost in the NBA's DNA. Inexplicably, the sky hook
is extremely rare in modern big men, though it counts just as much
as today's more popular two-handed dunks complete with hanging on
the rim and mugging to the television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Now see under those trees, stretched out in the shade doing
nothing? That coagulation of bony elbows and knobby knees is better
known as Shawn Bradley, Ralph Sampson, Chuck Nevitt, Tom
Boerwinkle, Swen Nater, Ralph Drollinger, Gheorge Muresan and
Manute Bol. That group was blessed with extraordinary height, but
few other skills necessary to combat NBA centers. Yet every time we
think their breed is near extinction, another Chris Anstey or
Dwayne Schintzius shows up in a box score.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed _ you can't teach height. That's
why, skilled or not, most 7-footers will never find their careers
6-foot under. HIGHER ORDER
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to our last stop, where you'll recognize the sleek
modern mix of brawn and ballerina. In other words, these are not
your father's father's centers.
</P>
<P>
   This higher order of big man first arrived with Hakeem Olajuwon
in the '80s. A stark contrast to Moses Malone's bull-headed desire
and brut force, Olajuwon was the league's first 7-foot dancer. He
ran the court effortlessly, and was one of the first players to
combine two, or even three, moves into one effective shot. His
``Dream Shake'' jumper is one of the defining shots in big man
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Players like Patrick Ewing, David Robinson and Alonzo Mourning
followed the pattern, each possessing the strength to devour
opponents near the basket, but also the skill to consistently make
shots on the perimeter. Their careers, however, are fading faster
than Dennis Rodman. Ewing may still be powerful enough to get
comped at Atlanta's ``Gold Club'', but he and Olajuwon are hobbled
by injuries, and it's just a matter of seasons before the league
belongs to two drastically different types of center.
</P>
<P>
   On your right is Shaquille O'Neal, a renaissance big man. He's a
throwback to the days of Wilt Chamberlain, a one-trick plow horse
with a game based on strength and slam dunks. At 7-1 and 330
pounds, he would tower over George Mikan by three inches and 100
pounds. Mikan also never starred in a movie, topped $50 million in
endorsements or recorded a couple of rap CDs.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Neal has as many low-post moves as a mailbox and shoots
free throws flatter than Midland or Odessa, Tim Duncan is the
prototype big man for the 21st century. Not only can Duncan win
games with his defense, rebounding and blocked shots, he also adds
an unprecedented quality to his offensive arsenal _ the ability to
drive to the basket with the dribble.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to chuckle at the thought of Mikan _ or Chamberlain or
Malone, for that matter _ trying one of Duncan's cat-quick
cross-over dribbles.
</P>
<P>
   No matter their specialty _ be it Jack Sikma's fadeaway, Bill
Laimbeer's 3-pointers, Robert Parish's high-arcing floaters,
Darrell Dawkins' dunks, Dikembe Mutombo's blocks or Arvydas
Sabonis' passes _ big men before the 7-foot, 255-pound Duncan were
basically stationary players. Duncan, however, can alternate
possessions of drilling a 20-foot jumper, scoring on a right-handed
post-up dunk, lofting in a left-hand hook, and finishing off his
defender by pump-faking on the perimeter to set up a dribble drive
and a pull-up 6-foot bank shot.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is substance revolutionary, so is his style. Quiet and
unassuming in an age when centers' heads are bigger than their
ancestors' only because of their egos, Duncan is a hybrid
Frankenstein who has 162 double-doubles since '97. O'Neal, next on
the list, has only 118.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, still yet to talk his first trash, is by far our most
advanced species. Cloning procedures are well under way. But we'd
better hurry.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate of big-man evolution, even Duncan will someday be
outmoded and eventually extinct. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
