<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-ELECTIONS-0320     03-19 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-ELECTIONS-0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THOUSANDS OF PROTESTERS SURROUND RULING PARTY HEADQUARTERS,
DEMAND PRESIDENT LEE'S RESIGNATION
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI _ It would be unthinkable in communist China: thousands
of angry Chinese citizens gathering en masse, lobbing eggs at the
headquarters of the ruling party, calling for the party chairman to
step down, shouting at the city's mayor as he addressed the
emotionally-charged crowd.
</P>
<P>
   This was the scene in Taipei a day after the Nationalist Party
suffered a stunning defeat in Taiwan's presidential elections, not
only coming in a distant third but failing to carry a single county
or municipality.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were angry, they said, not because they lost but
because they were betrayed by their party's own leader: President
Lee Teng-hui, who is also chairman of the Nationalist Party.
</P>
<P>
   It is widely thought Lee, who has been president of Taiwan since
1988, privately urged party faithful to vote for the opposition
candidate, Chen Shui-bian, who was elected president Saturday with
39 percent of the vote. Lee denied it several times during the
campaign, but the rumors persisted, based partly on the perception
that Lee secretly harbors the goal of an independent Taiwan, much
like the opposition Democratic Progressive Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``By day he's in the Nationalist Party, but by night he works
for the Democratic Progressive Party,'' said Hwang Chu Fang, a
housewife who was furious with Lee. ``He cheated the party and he
cheated the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a party spokesman, Lee said he would step down as party
chairman in September. But it wasn't soon enough for the angry
masses, who remained at the party headquarters, a 13-story building
next to the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall, well past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As president and chairman, he should apologize for losing,''
said Chang Chung Rong, an engineer, as he watched the police
spraying water cannons in an effort to disperse the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have vowed to return to the building every day until
Lee steps down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. should be concerned if there's going to be a central
authority,'' said Tom Gold, a University of California-Berkeley
professor of sociology and expert on Taiwan. ``How is this going to
be defused? There's going to be a collapse of public order here.''
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Chen, who will be inaugurated May 20, called for
calm Sunday, urging people to return to their normal lives. He
reached out to his political rivals as well, both on the island and
abroad. He has called for building multi-party coalitions and has
invited Chinese leaders to visit Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   As far as easing tensions with China, any of the three major
candidates would've been better than Lee, whose ``strategy has been
to delay, stall, abort'' talks, said Shelley Rigger, an American
expert on Taiwanese politics in town to observe the elections.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have been working with Chen since it became
clear several years ago that he'd be a figure in Taiwanese
politics, said Gold. He said China's muted response to Chen's
victory _ basically that it would wait and see what the new
president does _ is a hopeful sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to clear the air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's victory was made possible by a split in the Nationalist
Party. Lee refused to allow James Soong to be on the ticket,
insisting on his unpopular vice president Lien Chan. Soong launched
an independent populist campaign, winning a good deal of support
from longtime party members.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters Sunday had voted for Soong. A few were
even Chen supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sympathize with them,'' said Ivy Tsai, a health policy
researcher who voted for Chen. ``This party has frustrated too many
people. Lee is too corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley, professor of political science at Davidson College in
North Carolina, doesn't believe Lee actually tried to get Chen
elected but said he made strategic errors that allowed for Chen's
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just been around too long, become too dictatorial,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has been praised both in Taiwan and abroad for overseeing
widespread democratic reforms in Taiwan, but since he became the
first directly-elected president four years ago, corruption in the
party has overshadowed his other achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust the government any more,'' said Wendy Fei, a
make-up artist.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds were largely cooperative, but when several black
sedans with party officials left the building in the afternoon,
some enraged protesters attacked the cars, pummeling them with
their fists, flagpoles, motorcycle helmets and anything else at
their disposal. They succeeded in smashing a few windshields while
police stood by.
</P>
<P>
   An angry mob chased senior party adviser Hsu Li-teh down the
sidewalk, kicking, punching and beating him with poles. They
knocked him to the ground, but he was able to stand up and scurry
into a building.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, they had gathered in front of Lee's official
residence just a few blocks away, not dispersing until almost 7
a.m. (local time) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to the party headquarters Sunday afternoon,
blasting air horns, chanting slogans and launching a brief rain of
raw eggs at police while they waited for Lee, who was convening an
emergency party meeting with party officials. Crowds thinned around
dinner-time, after the party officials left, but swelled again to
several thousand by night-time.
</P>
<P>
   Taipei Mayor Ma Ying-jeou, a Nationalist Party stalwart who
announced he was resigning from the party central committee, came
out to talk to the protesters, calling for calm and saying he would
talk to Lee. He stayed for more than an hour, answering written and
oral questions from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Around midnight, Ma returned to announce to a smaller crowd that
Lee had a slight cold and had gone to bed. Chants of ``Lee Teng-hui
step down'' changed to ``Lee Teng-hui get out of bed.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
