</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN-AMERICAN-FOLKART _``Souls Grown Deep,'' the 1996
Olympics exhibition of art by Southern African-American self-taught
artists, was a landmark survey of its subject, and a revelation.
Now comes ``Souls Grown Deep,'' the book. Sure to be a landmark as
well, the hefty tome is the first of at least three volumes that
aim to provide a comprehensive exploration of this complex art
form. At 544 pages, with reproductions of works by 100 artists and
photographs of environmental art as well as 40 artist profiles and
essays by 35 contributors, Volume 1 is an impressive start. (Fox,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DINOSAURS _ CORTADERAS CAMP, Argentina _ In science, truth is
what scientists manage to agree it is. A case in point, which
tangentially involves Atlanta's Fernbank Museum of Natural History:
Conventional wisdom has long held that giant meat-eating dinosaurs
like Tyrannosaurus rex operated pretty much on instinct. They fed
themselves about as automatically as, say, Venus' flytraps _ and
with the same social skills. But maybe not. Contrary evidence comes
from a dig here in the Argentine desert, sustained in part by the
$1.25 million Fernbank is paying for models of two giant fossilized
dino skeletons unearthed nearby. Paleontologists Phil Currie and
Rodolfo Coria have found new evidence that giant meat-eating
dinosaurs weren't as dumb as we've thought. They were apparently
smart enough to live in family groups, with adults nurturing their
young. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ELEGANT-UNIVERSE _ ATLANTA _The newest wonderboy in theoretical
physics is Brian Greene, a 37-year-old professor at Columbia whose
engaging personality and crystal clear prose have attracted a
growing lay audience. Some call him the successor to Carl Sagan.
Greene will speak at Georgia Tech on Thursday, promoting the new
paperback edition of his book ``The Elegant Universe.'' One of
Greene's specialties is superstring theory, which he will
illustrate by means of video tape. In 1990 Greene and a colleague
discovered mirror symmetry, which opened new fields in mathematics
and physics. later, they discovered topology change, showing that
the fabric of space can tear, refuting Einstein's theory that space
can stretch but not tear. ``The Elegant Universe'' was nominated
for a 1999 New Yorker book award, named a nytimes Notable Book of
the Year and received the 1999 Phi Beta Kappa award in science.
Skube is attending the talk and video presentation at Tech tonight,
and talking to Greene tomorrow. After dusting off his high school
physics book (he got an A in the class, he assures me), Skube
promises to make this accessible and enlightening. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   GILMORE _ AUSTIN _ Jimmie Dale Gilmore won't have many more
weekends at home this year, what with the recent release of his
``One Endless Night'' CD and the miles that must be put in to prove
its magnificence. The 54-year-old singer hasn't released a new
album in four years and has never put one out on his own label, a
tactic that can either prove independence _ like John Prine _ or
blur one's visibility, as it did for the former Prince.
(Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
