<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-AMERICAN-FOLKART0320-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volume explores `Souls' of folk art
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _``Souls Grown Deep,'' the 1996 Olympics exhibition of
art by Southern African-American self-taught artists, was a
landmark survey of its subject, and a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes ``Souls Grown Deep,'' the book. Sure to be a landmark
as well, the hefty tome is the first of at least three volumes that
aim to provide a comprehensive exploration of this complex art
form. At 544 pages, with reproductions of works by 100 artists and
photographs of environmental art as well as 40 artist profiles and
essays by 35 contributors, Volume 1 is an impressive start.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first volume is an introduction to the field,'' says
Atlantan William Arnett, who has championed the art for 15 years
and conceived the book in 1987. ``We want to bring people up to
date.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, it sets out a historical context. Scholars note
African influences on African-American artists. Early forms of
African-American object-making _ funerary art, charms, quilts _ are
discussed as antecedents. U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), who
contributes an essay, sees the connection between the civil rights
movement and the flowering of this art in ``this whole desire to be
liberated, not just from physical barriers but being free of spirit
and free of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for the American community to know
about this art,'' Lewis says. ``It's ordinary people being very
creative, doing what they can using their hands and minds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Souls'' is encyclopedic but not an encyclopedia. Instead of
organizing the book alphabetically or chronologically, Arnett and
son Paul, who are executive editors, chose to arrange the profile
section according to the materials the artists use: stone, wood
(including roots), paper, canvas, found objects.
</P>
<P>
   They took great pains to include essays from authors with a
broad spectrum of viewpoints and specialties. All of them came to
Atlanta to review the Arnetts' extensive collection of the material
and met as many of the artists as possible. Artists write where
possible, or are interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Planned for wide distribution in late spring, the book is
already getting a strong response. It aroused unusual enthusiasm
when the Museum of American Folk Art debuted it at the Outsider Art
Fair in New York in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 100 books and sold every one of them,'' says Marie
DiManno, director of museum shops for the New York facility.
``People are coming in the shop just for the book. They're asking
to be notified when the second volume comes out. Dealers, students
_ everyone is buying it. It's becoming a must-have.''
</P>
<P>
   The book can be ordered online for $95 at
www.soulsgrowndeep.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
