<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ELEGANT-UNIVERSE0320-     03-19 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELEGANT-UNIVERSE0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A physicist at `cosmology's cutting edge'
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One night when Brian Greene was 9 years old, his
mother fixed spareribs for dinner. He has been a vegetarian ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were so horrible,'' he says, sitting in the lobby of the
Ritz-Carlton, ``I declared I'd never eat meat again.'' And with
that he proceeded to rummage about in the refrigerator, where he
found the makings of a salami sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you know salami's meat too,'' his father said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 29 years since, Greene, a physicist at Columbia
University, has learned his way around more than just the
refrigerator. He wants to understand nothing less than the universe
itself, its smallest invisible kernels of energy as much as its
unfathomable distant galaxies.
</P>
<P>
   When his book ``The Elegant Universe'' became a best seller last
year, the media all but canonized Greene as the successor to the
late Carl Sagan _ an engaging, telegenic theoretical physicist who
can communicate the wonder and mysteries of the cosmos. From ABC's
hourlong ``Nightline in Primetime'' to a bit part in the upcoming
Dennis Quaid movie ``Frequency,'' Greene is showing up everywhere.
At 38, he is the rising star of superstring theory.
</P>
<P>
   He looks almost too boyish for the part _ impish in his wit,
casually chic in black jeans, an enthusiast of tofu.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago he went completely vegan, adding eggs and dairy
products to ribs, sausage and porterhouse steaks. Most people know
you can fill your belly rather nicely at the Ritz-Carlton, but what
about Brian Greene?
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a cab to this place called the Sunflower Cafe last
night,'' he says, face brightening, ``and had pad thai. I want to
tell you, that was one of the best meals I've ever had.'' He sounds
as if he wishes you had been there to share it.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is at cosmology's cutting edge and yet is, in his own
way, normal as the next guy. He is an occasional jogging partner of
George Stephanopoulos (they were Rhodes scholars together at Oxford
University) and has written dialogue for John Lithgow's character
in ``3rd Rock From the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   But an hour with him persuades you he is not content merely to
be rich and famous. Sagan _ fairly or unfairly _ came to be seen by
many physicists as a popularizer who cultivated his audience more
assiduously than any scientist should.
</P>
<P>
   If some people consider Greene a budding media star, he is not
among them. At both Columbia and Cornell, he teaches a course
called Physics and Geometry, and says nothing excites him like the
possibility of discovering something that eluded Einstein the last
30 years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black holes are out there, no question. They exist,'' he says.
There is a note of both assertion and anticipation in his words, as
if the final discovery, the one that would explain everything, is
within mortal reach.
</P>
<P>
   In a talk last week at Georgia Tech, Greene spoke of the great
conundrum of science: The two pillars of modern physics are
incompatible with each other. One is Einstein's general theory of
relativity, which describes the universe on the largest scale _ the
stars, galaxies and beyond. The other is quantum mechanics, which
describes the unseen universe of subatomic particles _ electrons,
quarks and, perhaps, elements yet unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experiments show it's right on the money,'' he says of
Einstein's theory of relativity. But other experiments prove, with
just as much accuracy, that quantum physics is likewise
unassailable.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that, as currently understood, the two cannot
both be right.
</P>
<P>
   And so workaday physicists _ and even very good physicists _
plow the field they know. They do big physics or they do little
physics, and sometimes have little patience for one another.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes superstring theory to say that two departments of
the most prestigious branch of modern science not only require one
another but _ through the most arduous mathematics imaginable _ can
make a happy marriage of it.
</P>
<P>
   Not just happy, Greene says, but inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Superstring theory _ it refers to infinitesimally small
subatomic noodle-like units of vibrating energy _ thus dares to
bridge general relativity and quantum mechanics. Many, including
Nobel laureates, called it folly for 20 years. They don't anymore.
</P>
<P>
   By their nature, Greene says, physicists ``will not be satisfied
until they feel that the deepest and most fundamental understanding
of the universe has been unveiled. This is what Stephen Hawking has
alluded to as a first step toward knowing `the mind of God.'''
</P>
<P>
   Greene isn't so immodest as to think he would find it all by
himself _ science almost never works that way _ but the thrill of
discovery energizes him. Physics, he explains, is about just that _
the energy that underlies everything that is. It may or may not
stop with strings. ``There is tantalizing evidence,'' he says,
``that there might be something smaller yet.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour before his talk, he ate a lunch of curried tofu, guava
nectar and barley malt, and listened as a Tech physicist much older
than himself expounded a theory of creation that Greene clearly
thought unlikely. When the theory reached a point where first
causes had to be waived, Greene said, ``Are you satisfied with
that?''
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough, you gathered, to know just that the strings
exist. Greene wants to know ``who plucks the strings and what they
are playing _ rock or Bach, or something else?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOYD-FARMS0320-COX     03-19 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-FARMS0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make or break year for farmers
 &HT;    By Ginger Livingston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONETOE, N.C. _ Before preparing sweet potato beds for the
seedling harvest and beginning work on dormant farm equipment last
Friday, Wayne Harrell talked with his insurance adjuster.
</P>
<P>
   Six months since September's flooding, Harrell is still haggling
over his losses. He found out Friday morning that he will have to
hire a lawyer and go to court to pick an arbitrator to settle his
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five to 30 percent of every day I spend dealing with
the flood,'' said Harrell, an Edgecombe County farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd's flooding caused $550 million in agriculture
losses statewide. Before farmers like Harrell and his
brother-in-law, Willie Owens, can prepare for this year's growing
season, they're still trying to recover from last year's
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems keep going on and on, it's like a running
river,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a make or break year for many farmers, agriculture experts
say. Commodity prices remain low and the flooding stripped away any
cushions farmers had to protect them if yields are low this year.
And that's a distinct possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them have that extra cushion if there is a bad
production season this year,'' said Mitch Smith, director of the
Pitt County Cooperative Extension Service. ``We are going into (the
growing season) at a greater risk than we have historically.''
</P>
<P>
   One farmer from the Pitt County town of Fountain is unwilling to
take that risk.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old man quit farming this year after 29 years in the
fields. He asked that his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you want people to know you were almost beat down?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   The farmer only lost 50 acres of soybeans to floodwaters, but
the heavy rains associated with Hurricane Floyd and the series of
other tropical rainmakers last year reduced his yield. Coupled with
low commodity prices, the farmer couldn't pay off his credit line
for the first time since he started farming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always wish next year will be better, but I got to the
point where I wasn't going to fool myself any longer,'' he said.
``My banker said, 'As a friend I hate to see you quit, but from a
business standpoint I think you're right.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are no firm statistics on how many farmers quit this year.
</P>
<P>
   'Every day it seems we have another story of someone who had
decided not to farm this year,'' Smith said. ``It's going to take
us a long time before we fully know how this has affected us and
will continue to affect us.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers may increase after this growing season if crop
prices remain low, Smith and other experts say.
</P>
<P>
   There is no unusual increase in farmers quitting, said Gene
Charville, president of East Carolina Farm Credit, the region's
largest farm lender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1990s were generally pretty good for agriculture, which
means most farmers have entered this adversity in good financial
shape, and it will help them get through adverse times like last
year,'' he said. ``But they can't continue to weather these
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 growing season is critical for the Harrell and Owens
Farms of Conetoe.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by Floyd and Ernestine Harrell in 1955, the 5,000-acre
operation is now run by Harrell; his brother, Carl; brother-in-law,
Willie Owens and their wives. Their parents also remain involved.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell and Owens estimate their operation lost $1.5 million to
the flood.
</P>
<P>
   With crop insurance and federal aid, the family reduced the loss
to $300,000. If more aid becomes available, as expected, the loss
can be further reduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary losses are only part of the story, Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole lot of pain beneath those figures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, his wife, Pamela, and their two children lost their home
in the flood. The mortgage was paid off eight months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The operation is also fighting its insurance company for a
settlement on the farm equipment and buildings that were damaged by
the flood. Fearing repercussions, Harrell declined to name the
insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``(A friend) told me I'd get sad, I'd get mad and then I'd get
glad. I didn't think I'd ever get over the mad part,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been difficult watching the family struggle, said Roy
Stancill, a family friend and their crop insurance agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these boys first got flooded it looked bad and they
weren't sure if they could keep going,'' Stancill said. ``But they
got their crop insurance and the government kicked in and last time
I saw them they were in a better mood now.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrell and Owens said their moods fluctuate. But their
treatment by the insurance company has infuriated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I'm hearing, in general, is farming in general is
being targeted not to settle. They look at tractors and they think
they are invincible. But there is a whole lot more electronics and
computers on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The company offered $15,000 settlement for a $175,000 peanut
combine.
</P>
<P>
   The claim was sent to arbitration, but the parties can't agree
on the arbitrator. They found out Friday morning the court must now
appoint an arbitrator. That requires hiring a lawyer to represent
them, Harrell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're caught in limbo and they won't settle and now is the
time to be planting,'' Harrell said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has offered a myriad of excuses, he said. It offered
$1,800 to pay off a $3,000 tobacco barn. The reason: tobacco quotas
were cut last year so barns cost less, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without an insurance settlement the Harrells and Owens has been
forced to pay for expensive repairs. Meanwhile, things keep
breaking down just as they gear up for planting season.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the work, like taking all the tires off their 27 peanut
trucks so they can repair bearings, they do themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts are slowed because they have to take time off to
deal with other flood issues.
</P>
<P>
   An employee is setting up a new mobile home and has needed time
off. Owens is building a new house and needed time to complete the
paperwork, file property titles, select a builder and inspect the
work. All the siblings have taken time to help their parents repair
their flood-damaged home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you farm and don't have time to start with, and this
lands in the middle of the planting season, this is time of year
you can't make up,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   Farming wasn't always been such a risky proposition, said the
Fountain farmer who quit this year. When he started it seemed like
a good bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I was in public work and as far as the pay scale
went farming looked good,'' the farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started farming in 1970-71, you could buy gas for 24
cents and corn was bringing about $3.75 to $3.80 (a bushel) and
soybeans was $7 to $8,'' he said. ``Today we're looking at
$1.45-1.50 gas and we sold beans for less than $5 and some boys
sold corn for less than $2.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the economic climate of the 1980s ended many family
farms, the Fountain farmer and his neighbors were somewhat
insulated because of profitable tobacco production.
</P>
<P>
   But starting in the mid-1990s tobacco quotas were cut. The
farmer saw his income plunge $200,000 over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The farmer spent three months debating if he should remain in
agriculture. His decision came in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first year in 29 years I couldn't pay my credit
line,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A credit line is the cash farmers borrow every year to fund
their farming operations in the upcoming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've carried debt at other times, but I could always pay off
my credit line before going to the bank,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While his banker offered to help with financing, the farmer said
he worried about going deeper in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feared filing bankruptcy because if I have a debt I like to
pay it off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a combined debt of about $200,000, the knowledge that his
tobacco quotas would probably be cut again and the almost-certain
knowledge that crop prices were not going to dramatically increase,
the farmer decided to call it quits.
</P>
<P>
   He sold his equipment and tobacco barns to pay off the debt. He
also sold 88 acres of farmland he and his wife purchased several
years ago. They had wanted to hold the land and then sell it to
fund their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a pond on it that I enjoyed carrying the grandchildren
to, but we tried to look at it as we were blessed to have it to pay
off our debt instead of filing bankruptcy,'' he said. ``I had two
daughters I walked down the aisle and (the sale) was harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week the farmer began his new career as a trainee salesman
for a local agri-business operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't used a computer before in my life and yes, it is
hard,'' he said. ``I quit school in the eighth grade. Back when I
was in school lots of kids helped on the farm and they weren't
encouraged to stay in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
