<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-POPE-CHRISTIANS-0320-     03-19 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-CHRISTIANS-0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARAB CHRISTIAN MINORITY ANXIOUS FOR PAPAL SUPPORT
 &HT;    (550&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JIFNA, West Bank _ Local Christians, who have kept their
religion alive here in the place where it was born, seek a morale
boost from this week's visit of Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, Christians have nervously watched their
influence drop with the upsurge in Jewish and Muslim populations.
They know that many Westerners scarcely know they exist. They hope
the Pope will bring them some recognition here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will encourage the Christians, the local people here,''
said Samer Salameh, a 32-year-old Roman Catholic from this small
West Bank town. ``It is to be respected by both sides, the Jews and
the Muslims _ to show we are not weak, that we have people
supporting us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pope is scheduled to arrive in Amman, Jordan, Monday, where
he will spend just over 24 hours and deliver a Mass in a sports
stadium. Tuesday, he heads to Jerusalem, for the start of a six-day
pilgrimage to the Holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   Officials continued with preparations Sunday. Workers built
stages for, churches are setting aside spots on hundreds of buses
to take worshippers to the Pope's masses in Bethlehem and near the
Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   They were also painting over a Nazi Swastika and other graffiti
painted on the Pope's Jerusalem helicopter pad _ which police say
is likely the work of Jewish extremists.
</P>
<P>
   But, among Christians throughout Israel and the West Bank,
preparations took on a festive feel.
</P>
<P>
   Posters and bumper stickers were up on church walls and shop
doors, welcoming the 79-year-old pontiff. In Bethlehem, motorists
flew the yellow-and-white Vatican flags from stands mounted in car
windows.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 150,000 to 180,000 Christians in Israel
and the Palestinian-controlled West Bank. They comprise about 2
percent or 3 percent of the population, down from about nine
percent 50 years ago. The majority of local Christians live in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Just under half the local Christians are followers of the Pope _
either in the Roman Catholic or Greek Catholic, or Melkites,
churches. The rest are from eastern Orthodox churches, along with a
small number of Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Jifna has gone from being all Christian to a mix of 800
Christians and 200 Muslims. About a thousand Christians from Jifna
now live in California. Salameh, a university lecturer in computer
science, says he feels a ``mission'' to remain.
</P>
<P>
   Other once-Christian towns have already become mostly Muslim,
including Bethlehem. Bethlehem residents claim there are more
Bethlehem Christians in Santiago, Chile, than the 20,000 or so
still here.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts give a number of reasons for their emigration. Like
other Palestinians, the Christians in the West Bank have faced
Israeli occupation that has choked off commerce and prompted
violent uprisings. Christians have more money and contacts abroad,
easing emigration.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of their bind between two stronger powers,
Christians in the Israeli city of Nazareth were infuriated last
year when Israel approved plans for a mosque near the plaza of the
Basilica of the Annunciation. The church is where tradition states
that the Virgin Mary was told she would give birth to the son of
God.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Muslim activists, staging weeks of protests,
had strong-armed the Israeli government over the objections of the
local Christians.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   While few Christians claim they are victims of official
persecution, they do claim that they have trouble getting jobs or
buying land from Muslims. Sometimes, they say, they are called
heretics, by Muslims. Meanwhile, with Jews, Christians say they
face the same barriers as other Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Pope is expected to urge Christians to maintain their
presence among their fellow Palestinians and the Holy sites.
Christians frequently say their religion's emphasis on love and
forgiveness is an important message for the Middle East. They worry
that their churches could become empty museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moral support is very important,'' said Jerusalem Greek
Catholic Archbishop Lutfi Laham. ``He will tell them, 'You have a
responsibility to your society.'''
</P>
<P>
   But some Christian Palestinians worry that a papal visit without
a strong pitch for Palestinian rights could anger their Muslim
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a strong statement from the Pope that will make it
clear that the people who are oppressed and living under occupation
are the Palestinians,'' said the Rev. Naim Ateek(CQ), a Protestant
Palestinian theologian. ``If the Pope does not do it, some of us
are going to be embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the visit appear intent on sensitivity toward the
Muslims. The Pope will visit the Dheisheh Refugee Camp in
Bethlehem, a neighborhood of 10,000 Muslims and no Christians.
</P>
<P>
   He will deliver a Mass on Bethlehem's Manger Square Wednesday,
which will likely coincide with the mid-day Muslim prayer time.
Officials organizing the event said Friday that they expect that
the Pope will pause when the mosque on the square broadcasts the
eight-minute call to prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
