<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COX-LOOKAHEAD-0318     03-19 4165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-LOOKAHEAD-0318 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX WASHINGTON BUREAU LOOKAHEAD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDs: Stories are listed on their publication date.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY, March 18
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-POPE-$ADV18 _ JERUSALEM _ Advancing Pope John Paul's
long-anticipated visit to the Holy Land the last 10 days of the
month. We take an in-depth look at what may be the last trip for
this pontif _ the most well-traveled pope ever, and the only pope
known to an entire generation. He is in failing health, and one
wonders if this is his mecca. What do Christians here think of his
coming? Are special preparations being made by the Israeli,
Jordanian and Palestinian governments? What places will he visit,
and why? (Kaplow).
</P>
<P>
   With itinerary box attached at end of story.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN RELIGION EDs: MOVED Tues., March 14, in both
International/Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: In Taiwan, presidential elections are held.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, March 19
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ELECTIONS-0319 _ TAIPEI _ Spot coverage of the Taiwan
elections. Developing. (Chao).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Beacause Taiwan is 12 hours head of eastern standard time,
a first story will move by 1 p.m. EST Sat., followed by a 1STLD by
9 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-WINE-$ADV19 _ TIJUANA, Mexico _ Tequila. Tequila.
Tequila. There are some 500 types and brands of the Mexican spirit
available here. As a result, wine-making has had a difficult time
taking off over the years. And when it did, the product was just
plain bad. But efforts to improve the quality of Mexico's wines
have begun paying off. With help from expert vintners from its
neighbor to the north _ California _ winemakers here are
experiencing a mini-boom. (Ferriss).
</P>
<P>
   With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   With locator map information.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tues., March 14, in both International/Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COMMUNISTS-$ADV19 _ TULA, Russia _ Despite the hype
surrounding Vladimir Putin, almost 50 percent of Russians are
expected to vote for other candidates in the upcoming presidential
elections. Twelve candidates are running in the race, and some of
the strongest opposition to Putin comes from the Communist Party
rank-and-file members, who disagree with Putin's views on relations
with the United States and on economic issues like land reform. In
a Communist bulwark town, regular Russians give their views about
politics and why they stand behind their man, candidate Gennady
Zyuganov. (Coker).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., March 16.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YOUNGVOTER-$ADV19 _ MOSCOW _ We talk to an 18-year-old
who will be voting for the first time in this month's presidential
election and get his/her thoughts on its importance, Vladimir Putin
and the overall state of Russia. (Coker).
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wed., March 15, in both International/Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: This story is meant to pair and run with a similar story
done by each Cox newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INDIA-$ADV19 _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will be
traveling to the volatile region of South Asia during the week of
March 20, 2000, primarily visiting India and Bangladesh. He will be
the first President to visit India since 1978 and the first ever to
visit Bangladesh. At the last minute, he has also decided to add a
stopover to the visit the new military government in neighboring
Pakistan. (Deans).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Fri., March 17, in both International/Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WOMEN _ GORE-WOMEN _ WASHINGTON _ When Tipper Gore formally
registered her husband's presidential candidacy in New Hampshire
last fall, she autographed a poster marking the state's
first-in-the-nation primary. ``The fun starts here. New Hampshire
rocks!'' she wrote. But the driving beat of the vice president's
campaign has come mostly from another brainy, beautiful blonde in
the family _ Al and Tipper's eldest daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff.
(Shepard).
</P>
<P>
   Moved Thursday in (w) Washington, (l() lifestyle and (p)
politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERCRIME _ WASHINGTON _ A new Justice Department report on
cybercrime puts Attorney General Janet Reno in the center of a
battle between cops who seek more powerful Internet policing tools
and critics who see the study as a threat to online privacy.
(Glass).
</P>
<P>
   Moved Thursday in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-FUTURE _ LOS ANGELES _ Americans participated in two great
migrations in the 20th century. First, they moved by the millions
from farms to cities, seeking jobs, and after World War II, they
moved again, this time from central cities to suburbs. In the new
century, yet another demographic pattern may emerge: immigrants and
young people will leave suburbs everywhere to find work in the
nation's booming high-tech clusters. Certain states, including
California, Texas, New York, Florida and Georgia, will get a surge
of growth from Asians, Hispanics and others seeking jobs, while the
majority will become relatively whiter, older and less prosperous.
Will we become, in essence, two countries, one old, white and
slow-growing and the other younger, multicultural and more
entrepreneurial? (Geewax).
</P>
<P>
   With TECH-FUTURE-DATA _ Chart material.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Thursday in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BOTBALL _ RESTON, Va. _ At first glance, the pre-teens and
just-teens might look like a bunch of kids playing with toy robots.
But to the high-tech firms that pick up the tab for the regional
and national ``botball'' competitions, they're something far more
valuable: potential employees. In a mix of altruism and need for an
educable work force, high tech firms are trying to influence
students' interests and choices at a younger and younger age. The
finals will be in Austin. (Mollison).
</P>
