<P>
   AFRICA-AIDSORPHANS-$ADV26 _ ZIMBABWE _ In sub-Saharan Africa,
23.3 million people _ most of them women _ are infected with
HIV/AIDS, compared to less than 1 million in North America. There
were 2.2 million deaths from AIDS in the region in 1999 _
representing 85 percent of the world's HIV-related fatalities, even
though only 10 percent of the world's population lives in the
region. Efforts to stop the disease's progress have been largely
futile and few Africans can afford treatments more readily
available in the West, such as AZT. Cultural and religious issues
also prove thorny. The disease is destroying entire villages, but
beyond that is robbing these countries of a whole generation of
potentially productive people. Perhaps the most grim by-product is
the staggering fact that the disease has created more than 10
million orphans a number that is expected to soar to 13 million
next year. The implications of this are devastating. (Roughton).
</P>
<P>
   With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   With half-page color graphics prepared by Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-CITY _ SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ The future is being carved from
a piece of Arizona desert. A new subdivision taking shape near
Phoenix is the most wired community in America. Across the country,
real-estate developers and architects are collaborating on new
neighborhoods with high-speed wiring built into the homes. The
broadband information and entertainment access is designed for
telecommuters and destined to change the way we live. At the DC
Ranch development here, the town has its own Intranet that allows
homeowners to reserve a community tennis court, set a scout meeting
on the community calendar and check their kids' grades. The
technology is intended to create a strong sense of community, not
isolate the homeowners, the developer says. (Holmes).
</P>
<P>
   With WIRED-NOT _ Not everyone is rushing to embrace the
broadband future. Some face high economic barriers, while others
say they prefer to live without the complications of computers. A
look at how hospitable the future will be for unwired Americans.
(Holmes).
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
