</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAURS0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paradigm lost
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORTADERAS CAMP, Argentina _ In science, truth is what
scientists manage to agree it is.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point, which tangentially involves Atlanta's Fernbank
Museum of Natural History: Conventional wisdom has long held that
giant meat-eating dinosaurs like Tyrannosaurus rex operated pretty
much on instinct. They fed themselves about as automatically as,
say, Venus' flytraps _ and with the same social skills.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not. Contrary evidence comes from a dig here in the
Argentine desert, sustained in part by the $1.25 million Fernbank
is paying for models of two giant fossilized dino skeletons
unearthed nearby. Paleontologists Phil Currie and Rodolfo Coria
have found new evidence that giant meat-eating dinosaurs weren't as
dumb as we've thought. They were apparently smart enough to live in
family groups, with adults nurturing their young.
</P>
<P>
   Although this finding may be of fleeting interest to non-dino
buffs, Currie and Coria's theory is a major concern within
paleontology. A scientific truth may be undone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This falls into the category of a paradigm shift,'' declares
Currie, of Canada's Royal Tyrrell Museum.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take a couple of years before we know for sure.
In the deliberate _ and sometimes petty _ scientific community,
paradigms almost never turn on a dime. Modern research is based on
the cold objectivity of the scientific method: Theories are
proposed and evidence proves them correct or not. But finding
consensus on what that research means remains a more subjective
political process, in which old truths sometimes hang on
tenaciously before giving way.
</P>
<P>
   How many findings must Currie and Coria demonstrate to prove
their theory? There is no right answer; other scientists will
decide. Before the theory is accepted, the pair must present their
research to other paleontologists at a scientific conference, where
their ideas will be analyzed and questioned. And they'll have to
publish their work in a respected journal, which will print it only
after a review panel of other prominent scientists agrees that the
research is sound.
</P>
<P>
   This system, called ``peer review,'' is designed to weed out
phony claims and misguided theorizing _ which it often does.
Remember ``cold fusion''? In March 1989, two chemists from the
University of Utah announced at a news conference what seemed like
the discovery of the century. They said they'd found an inexpensive
and clean way to produce virtually unlimited amounts of energy,
through nuclear fusion reactions. When their claims were subjected
to peer review, other scientists soon found the experiments
couldn't be replicated. Soon the term ``cold fusion'' had become a
joke.
</P>
<P>
   The system, however, can also slow recognition of good ideas,
says Lester Stephens, a science historian at the University of
Georgia. Peer panels often include scientists who've spent a
lifetime developing their own points of view, which may be
threatened by a new theory. And sometimes personality comes into
play. If a scientist is unpopular or unknown, a new theory is more
likely to be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issues like personality, envy, authority are likely to be
relevant to why scientists come to believe what they do,'' says
Steven Shapin, a science historian at the University of
California-San Diego. ``It's a very fuzzy, complicated, messy
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Some truths have been delayed for many years.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1837, Louis Agassiz concluded that there must have been an
ice age. This meant that glaciers, not the great flood of the
Bible, might have moved rocks around. Colleagues, however, were not
convinced. It took more than 30 years before Agassiz was
vindicated, his theory accepted.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the 1860s, Gregor Mendel, having discovered recessive
genes, proposed what was to become the basis for modern genetics
theory. But his writings were pooh-poohed. Only in 1900, after
Mendel's death, was the work rediscovered and given credence.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the early 20th century, Alfred Wegener theorized that all
the continents had long ago been part of a single land mass. But
conventional wisdom _ that the continents were a permanent feature
of the Earth's crust _ held until the 1960s, decades after Wegener
had died. Today, the ``continental drift'' theory is widely held.
</P>
<P>
   'ANTEDILUVIAN MONSTERS'
</P>
<P>
   New truths do tend to break through, even if old ones sometimes
get in the way. As with most branches of science, paleontology has
accepted dramatic paradigm shifts in the past 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-19th century, dinosaur fossils were thought to
have been the remains of ``antediluvian monsters,'' animals Noah
couldn't fit on his ark. Or perhaps the remains of trolls and
dragons.
</P>
<P>
   As late as the mid-1960s, conventional wisdom held that
dinosaurs were reptiles. Now it's accepted by most scientists that
dinos were direct ancestors of modern birds, and only distant
cousins of reptiles. But just last month in the journal Science,
two biologists said new findings cast doubt on the dino-bird
theory, and debate is raging anew.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of behavior of carnivorous dinosaurs, conventional
wisdom has held that only smaller dinos cooperated with each other.
Not so Tyrannosaurus rex and the even-larger Giganotosaurus (one of
the dinos whose skeletons will be permanently displayed at
Fernbank, starting this year), which have been considered too dumb
to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, Currie and his Argentine colleague Coria found the
fossils of a group of T. rexes that had died together in Canada.
They found no bones from other dinos at the site.
</P>
<P>
   If the animals had been eating when they were killed, bones of
their victims would have been found. Had the animals died
separately in a flood that washed their bones into a common grave,
the water also would have killed and buried many other creatures in
the same place. The discovery seemed to say that the T. rexes had
been a social group or family.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1998 Coria found a new species of meat-eater in the
Argentine desert. Yet to be named, the dino was even larger than
the Giganotosaurus. More important for the pack theory, it was
found in a group: six or seven of the animals, including at least
three juveniles, at the same site.
</P>
<P>
   They'd all died together. Again, there were no bones of other
creatures in the boneyard, a strong clue that the animals were
traveling in a pack or resting when they were killed suddenly,
perhaps by a muddy flash flood. The presence of young dinos
suggests the pack was a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clustered together for some reason,'' Currie says.
``Science always works on laws of probabilities. The odds of this
grouping of six dinosaurs, including two juveniles, teenagers of
sorts, and one that's even smaller, are so minuscule it's almost
impossible unless it was a family group.''
</P>
<P>
   He speculates that the giant meat-eaters, like lions, cooperated
when hunting, perhaps with the youngsters scooting along to cut a
huge plant-eater out of a galloping herd to make it easier prey for
stronger adults.
</P>
<P>
   MORE PROOF OFTEN KEY
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent paleontologists seem receptive to the new
theory.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Flessa of the University of Arizona, past president of the
Paleontological Society, says the latest find ``could be evidence
that these dinosaurs had `family values' _ that is, they cared for
their young during some part of their growth and development. This
will get people's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Holtz Jr. of the University of Maryland, one of the
world's leading specialists on giant meat-eaters, agrees. ``What's
going on in the field now looks like a paradigm shift,'' he says.
``We can conceive of smaller pack-hunters because we have them
today in lions and wolves. But the idea of carnivores bigger than
elephants living in groups seems truly bizarre and weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Currie and Coria's evidence is strong, he says, and the
implications are important.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means is that these big animals may not have been as
stupid as thought,'' Holtz says. ``Although they wouldn't have been
as smart as modern birds or mammals, dinosaurs _ and carnivores in
particular _ were probably a lot smarter than modern lizards or
crocodiles, so there could have been a certain amount of
communication between each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the paradigm hasn't fully shifted just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concentration of bones certainly suggests there was a
group behavior,'' allows Paul Sereno of the University of Chicago,
but he would like to see more similar finds before science can
``solve decisively'' the question.
</P>
<P>
   That's a common refrain in establishing scientific truths: Give
us more proof, says Robert Silliman, a science historian at Emory
University. Scientists are conservative about shifting paradigms
and ``not really on the lookout for novelty,'' Silliman says.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as with cold fusion, this caution is healthy. But
other times, Silliman says, worthy theories can be held back
because of biases in favor of accepted beliefs, some of which the
critics may have authored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a kind of pressure cooker,'' he says of the search for
scientific truth, ``with different forces pushing you to go forward
or hold back. You can get out on a limb and have it sawed off if
you're not careful.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to discover a new comet; that can be easily
verified. It's another to deduce behavior of creatures that lived
millions of years ago. So Currie and Coria will have to argue
effectively when they circulate their theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists who arrive at truths still have the job of making
the truth credible or believable to other scientists in their
field,'' says Shapin of the University of California-San Diego.
``That means no matter how certain they are, they have got to use
rhetoric, persuasion, any influence that's available to them to
persuade people that what they believe to be true is true.''
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds a lot like politics, it can be. And as with
politics, in scientific persuasion, money plays a role.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal of Medicine, for example, is one of the
most prestigious medical journals in the world. Ideas that are
published there are generally nearing the truth stage in scientific
politics.
</P>
<P>
   But the journal is not free of conflicts of interest. On Feb.
23, after being exposed by the Los Angeles Times, it admitted that
it had violated its own ethical rules by publishing articles from
authors linked financially to the drug companies whose products
they reviewed _ without acknowledging those interests.
</P>
<P>
   The journal's editors said such lapses occurred 19 times in
three years. The articles in question focused on AIDS, hair loss,
breast cancer, diabetes, alcoholism and
attention-deficit-hyperactivity disorder. The journal promises to
be more careful about disclosures of conflicts, but even so, much
of the published research will continue to be funded by
corporations that seek to profit by it.
</P>
<P>
   Money and politics intersect with science in other ways, too.
Because there's never enough funding for everything that scientists
want to study _ it's estimated, for example, that less than $1
million a year is spent worldwide on paleontological digs _ some
feel they must ``hype'' their theories to garner the attention
needed to get funds, says Ronald Numbers, a science historian at
the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more,'' Numbers says, ``scientists have shown the
importance of rhetoric, how you go about persuading people why you
should be believed over others, especially since most people aren't
going to go out and do the observation themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE WITH END IN SIGHT
</P>
<P>
   To judge by the informal comments from paleontologists, Currie
and Coria's proposal seems likely to become a truth. A theory that
big carnivorous dinos traveled in packs or families ``isn't likely
to be one of those battles that goes on forever,'' says Ed Larson,
a Pulitzer Prize-winning historian at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Currie and Coria publish their findings in a major
scientific journal, he predicts, ``pack-hunting of dinosaurs will
make news in every newspaper in the Western world.''
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance of the theory ``doesn't require that every last
scientist agrees with the new interpretation,'' says Flessa of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least it shouldn't. Considering the potential messiness of
the system, Flessa jokes, ``Cynics will tell you that a new truth
is established when the last supporter of the old interpretation
has died.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
