<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-GILMORE0320-COX     03-19 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILMORE0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zen in the wind
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Jimmie Dale Gilmore won't have many more
weekends at home this year, what with the recent release of his
``One Endless Night'' CD and the miles that must be put in to prove
its magnificence.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old singer hasn't released a new album in four years
and has never put one out on his own label, a tactic that can
either prove independence _ like John Prine _ or blur one's
visibility, as it did for the former Prince.
</P>
<P>
   So Gilmore and his wife, Janet, are making the most of this
Friday evening at their modest, porch-wrapped house on five acres
west of town. They've planned a family night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's coming over at 8,'' Gilmore tells his son, Colin,
25, who has just arrived. ``We're just having pasta, something
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so easy is trying to pin down the lineage of Gilmore's
family. The Texas music legend has three kids, including two
daughters, none of whom have the same mother and all of whom came
before Jimmie met Janet 16 years ago. Sounds like a regular country
song, don't it? But like so many other unconventionalities in
Gilmore's life, he somehow makes it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of fun,'' Gilmore says, seated at the
Spanish-tile table in his kitchen and beaming proudly, like he's
just another dad. ``Colin just graduated from Southwest Texas,'' he
says. ``He studied music, so he has a much better understanding of
the technical aspects of it than I do. He just started writing
songs, too, and I tell you, I think he's got it. I had him play
some songs for Butch and Joe, and I really think they were as
impressed as I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Butch and Joe, of course, are Butch Hancock and Joe Ely,
Gilmore's band mates in the short-lived Flatlanders, who have
performed a couple of dozen shows together over the last month and
are flirting with a reunion run. Together, they embody the holy
trinity of Texas music. Hancock was the songwriting troubadour.
Ely, the stalwart live performer. And Gilmore. ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, for one, he's often credited as the true singer of the
bunch, with his warbling, lonesome voice, an echo of the Texas
Panhandle wind of his youth. That voice is truly at its peak on
``One Endless Night,'' in near-operatic covers of Walter Hyatt's
``Georgia Rose,'' Willis Alan Ramsey's ``Goodbye Old Missoula'' and
more.
</P>
<P>
   But the quality Gilmore truly brings to the Flatlanders myth,
and that shows throughout Texas' caldron of great performers, is
his deep well of independent spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore ignores radio formats and hops from one musical style to
another like a jack rabbit finding oasis after oasis in the desert.
He makes the records he wants to make, and for that, he's a hero.
Not just in Texas, either: He earned one Grammy nomination in the
hip ``contemporary folk'' category for 1991's ``After Awhile''
album; he was voted best country artist two years running in
Rolling Stone magazine; he even fell in with the '90s college-rock
crowd, collaborating with Natalie Merchant in her 10,000 Maniacs
days and Mudhoney at the height of the Seattle grunge craze.
</P>
<P>
   As Ely recently said about Gilmore, ``You're never exactly sure
what musical can of worms Jimmie's going to bring to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmie Dale Gilmore is one of a kind, and there are all kinds of
ways he can present himself. That's never been more evident than
with the new album.
</P>
<P>
   From a straight-ahead country cover of the Grateful Dead's
``Ripple'' to a rollicking, bluesy cut of Townes Van Zandt's ``No
Lonesome Tune'' to the ethereal, haunting rendition of the
Weill/Brecht standard ``Mack the Knife'' _ the latter offering the
so-called Zen-country sound that Gilmore has refined on his own _
``One Endless Night'' is as seemingly conflicted as any of the
singer's five other solo albums.
</P>
<P>
   For Gilmore, mixing so many musical genres comes as easily as
pressing the puree button on a blender. ``I'm tagged a country
artist because of my voice, but really, I enjoy blues, folk and
rock 'n' roll just as much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was playing, like, five nights a week around Austin (in
the early '80s), my set wouldn't really change whether I was
playing emmajoe's, the Broken Spoke, the Hole in the Wall or La
Zona Rosa, all very different clubs. Sometimes I would be playing
country music to rock 'n' roll people who had never heard it, and
sometimes it was the opposite, but it never mattered to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore actually started picking his guitar in Austin on
extended stays in the late '60s, before acts like Willie Nelson,
Doug Sahm and Asleep at the Wheel landed here permanently.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of Austin's cosmic cowboy scene in the latter half
of the '70s, Gilmore was away leading a life that, to many who
heard about it, truly seemed out in the cosmos. He spent six years
in an ashram, having been introduced to Eastern religion during his
short-lived stint as a philosophy student at Texas Tech University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I really am sort of a skeptic and rationalist,
I've always had a leaning toward mysticism, and Eastern religion
really appealed to that,'' Gilmore explained.
</P>
<P>
   When he left for Colorado, his life had already had its ups and
downs. His first, brief marriage to Jo Carol Pierce _ now a
well-known songwriter and playwright in Austin _ had deteriorated.
His stint with the Flatlanders didn't fare much better. Once he
turned full time to religion, Gilmore had all but given up music as
anything but a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Gilmore found a balance between religion and music and
returned to Austin. He gigged steadily until he finally released
back-to-back albums in 1988-89 on the Hightone record label. These
discs limited him to traditional country sounds. It wasn't until
his first record through the giant Elektra Records, ``After
Awhile,'' that his records showed a blend of edgier country, folk
and blues, thus permanently tagging Gilmore a critic's darling and
giving him a cult following worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, Gilmore grew even bigger and bolder on his next two
albums with Elektra. The 1993 gem ``Spinning Around the Sun'' _
Gilmore's best seller with just under 100,000 copies sold _ was
produced by Elvis accomplice Emory Gordy Jr. and featured a finely
orchestrated, decidedly classic sound. For 1996's ``Braver, Newer
World,'' Gilmore recruited avant-garde record producer T Bone
Burnett to craft a wild mix of experimental country and even a few
all-out rock tunes. But the album wouldn't sell half of what
``Spinning'' did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned so much about the recording process with that
record,'' Gilmore said, ``and I used a lot of what I learned for
this record.''Though a return to ``After Awhile's'' rootsier sound,
``One Endless Night'' is still far from a standard Gilmore album.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, only three of its 13 songs were written by
Gilmore. Though a proven songwriter with classics including
``Dallas,'' ``Tonight I Think I'm Gonna Go Downtown'' and ``Treat
Me Like a Saturday Night,'' the singer instead turned to some of
his favorite tunesmiths, including others such as John Hiatt, Jesse
Winchester, Hal Ketchum, David Hammond and, as always, Butch
Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   Explained Gilmore, ``A lot of people think of me as a
songwriter, but I primarily think of myself as a singer. I've
always been prone to sing whatever songs I like, whether I wrote
them or not....I'm not real prolific, but I do have enough new
songs to make an album of all-new material. This time, that just
wasn't what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing Gilmore didn't want to do was make another CD for
Elektra, or any major record label. His previous three albums
produced modest profits, but not the kind that encourage big
companies to focus on the artist. Though Elektra reps wanted
Gilmore to remain with them, he turned down the option, in pursuit
of yet more individuality.
</P>
<P>
   Even the folks at Elektra admit the move might have been to
Gilmore's advantage. ``Everybody here loved him, but sometimes
artists as pure as Jimmie deserve more attention than we're able to
give them,'' said Elektra's vice-president of publicity, Joel
Amsterdam, adding a no-hard-feelings bonus that the new album ``may
be the best that he's ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore's longtime manager Mike Crowley thinks so, too. He
gambled his own money and time on co-creating the Windcharger Music
label with Gilmore, which is releasing ``One Endless Night.''
Though record companies smaller than Elektra such as Rykodisc and
Nonesuch jumped at the chance to sign Gilmore, the artist and his
manager paid for the album on their own. Eventually, a modest
distribution deal was struck with well-established Massachusetts
indie Rounder Records, but only after the album was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Though they eventually plan on a strong Internet sales base,
immediate plans to support ``One Endless Night'' call for the
typical touring jaunts to night clubs everywhere. Band members this
go-round include guitarists Rob Gjersoe and Chris Gage, backup
singer Christine Albert and bassist Brad Fordham. That's right,
there will be no drummer, and since it's Jimmie Dale Gilmore we're
talking about, there's no real point in asking why not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've always liked it when people called my music
experimental or unconventional,'' Gilmore said. ``Maybe they won't
say that so much about the music on this one, but I'll be just as
happy if they say it about my approach to the music business.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
