<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, March 20:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-RIOTS (Taipei, Taiwan) _ A day after Taiwan's Nationalist
Party was swept from power after more than 50 years, the fury of
the losers erupted, forcing President Lee Teng-hui to barricade
himself inside his party headquarters as thousands of disaffected
supporters battled for hours with police. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-LEE (Taipei, Taiwan) _ ``He betrayed Taiwan!'' ``He's a
traitor who sold out the Nationalist Party!'' The venom of the
crowds here Sunday was directed at a man who was long called ``Mr.
Democracy'' _ the man who opened up the clubby Nationalists to the
native Taiwanese majority, who engineered Taiwan's first direct
elections for president and who bravely asserted the island's
separate identity against a hostile mainland China. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-ASSESS (Taipei, Taiwan) _ Analysis of the vote in Taiwan:
How nervous is Washington? By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA (Beijing) _ As Beijing's leaders continued their
silence on Chen Shui-bian's victory in Taiwan, many Chinese people
mulled over a result they found shocking: Taiwan had chosen the
independence party, if not independence. The idea that Taiwan will
inevitably reunite with the mainland is one of the most emotional,
deeply held beliefs of ordinary Chinese. But Chen's upset victory
forced many Chinese to reflect for the first time on the depth of
their conviction, pitting their abstract belief against their
personal self-interest, since war would mean renewed hardship. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-SECURITY (Jerusalem) _ While the religious and political
dimensions of the pope's six-day trip here are large, the
logistical and security preparations by both Israel and the
Palestinian Authority are unprecedented. The visit also requires an
unparalleled cooperation between the two governments, which so far,
despite the minor sniping of Jerusalem officials on both sides, has
gone very smoothly. Both sides are united by their joint
determination to avert trouble and avoid embarrassment. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-U.S. (Dhaka, Bangladesh) _ Three decades after
Bangladesh's difficult birth after a war of independence against
Pakistan, it remains one of the world's poorest nations. A million
villagers each year lose their homes to fickle rivers that engulf
their land. Democracy suffers prolonged malfunctions, in part
because the two women who run the main political parties hate each
other down to the bone. And yet, in most ways Bangladesh now is
decidedly in less of a mess, with the poverty rate drifting down
and economic growth rates inching up. Indeed, many here fear that
President Clinton is coming not just to shake hands but to pick
pockets. It seems that Bangladesh may be sitting on a small fortune
in natural gas. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-CLINTON (New Delhi, India) _ President Clinton,
accompanied by his daughter, Chelsea, arrived to a low key welcome
here Sunday night for a state visit that the administration hopes
will set the foundation for a new relationship with India. Clinton
is the first American president to visit India in 22 years, and the
last visit by President Carter _ who made some unflattering remarks
about the government before an open microphone _ did not go so
smoothly. This time, and with those memories faded, both sides
appear determined to make a good impression on each other. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   PRAGUE-CEMETERY (Prague, Czech Republic) _ A rare archaeological
discovery has turned into a political and moral quandary for the
Czech government. What to do with the remnants of a medieval Jewish
cemetery in downtown Prague _ how to acknowledge the needs of
modernity while respecting the dead _ has become an issue the Czech
government will take up this week. What began as a construction
project for an insurance company has turned into a confusing,
hurtful and emotional battle between the Czechs and a large number
of Jews around the world. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHAS (Jerusalem) _ The furor over the Shas Party's attack
on the education minister for including a Palestinian poet in the
school curriculum has escalated into a major battle. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-POLITICS (Toronto) _ Canadian politics. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-TRAFFIC-COMPUTER (Memphis, Tenn.) _ As the FAA and the
airlines prepare, with some dread, for another busy summer, when
there are more planes in the sky and more thunderstorms to skirt
around, the Memphis airport is counting on a new computerized
system that allows a controller to study a much broader swath of
sky and test new routes with a few mouse clicks. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-REENACT (Waco, Texas) _ The government's credibility will
be put to the test this weekend when critical portions of the 1993
assault at Waco are re-enacted on Sunday at a military base with
tanks, a helicopter and camouflaged gunmen. The re-creation could
challenge the government's unequivocal assertion that federal
agents fired no shots at the Branch Davidian compound in the final
hours of the 51-day siege. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REFORMER (Austin, Texas) _ With the long march to November
under way, Gov. George W. Bush is arguing that his record in Texas
proves he is best suited to bring reform to Washington. He has even
coined a campaign slogan: ``A Reformer with Results.'' Without
question, Bush has been a popular governor, yet few Texans would
describe him as a reformer. By Richard A. Oppel Jr. and Jim Yardley
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ROTH (Wilmington, Del.) _ As chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, Bill Roth is shepherding some of the Hill's
hottest issues this year, from China trade to taxes to health care.
He's a rare Republican who's made a career of working with
Democrats to get things done. But at 79 and facing a stiff
re-election fight from Delaware's popular Democratic governor, Tom
Carper, Roth is one the GOP's most vulnerable incumbents. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-SENATE (Washington) _ John McCain returns to the Senate
on Monday facing a peculiar challenge: how to use his new
prominence to propel forward his signature issue of campaign
finance overhaul at a moment when everyone in politics is posing as
a reformer. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS-PROFILE (Washington) _ Rep. Thomas Davis of Va., the head
of fund raising for House Republicans' campaigns. By Lizette
Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   NRA-STRATEGY (Washington) _ Why is the NRA talking so tough,
when it only seems to hurt them in political circles? It may be
because it draws more and more gun owners into their ranks. By Marc
Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-RETURN (Washington) _ With more than three months to go
in its current term, the Supreme Court on Monday will enter a
concentrated period of unusual intensity and potential import. The
justices, back from a brief recess, will begin six weeks of hearing
arguments in one blockbuster case after another. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
