<P>
   TV-NOTEBOOK (New York) _ After years of whining that they have
to do something different to prevent more viewers from deserting to
cable, the networks are finally trying to figure out what. The new
gimmicks being used are sometimes stylistic and sometimes a matter
of scheduling, but all smack of the desperate need to escape a
self-defeating, business-as-usual attitude. This is the season the
old formulas finally crashed. But where is the line between a
gimmick and true innovation? By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ARTFAIR (Maastricht, Netherlands) _ When the doors to the
European Fine Art Fair opened here on Friday afternoon, the 198
exhibitors were all smiles, eager to talk about the prized
offerings they were placing before some 8,200 visitors who poured
into the convention center where the fair is held every March. But
beneath the polite banter, the atmosphere at this, the world's
largest art fair, was politically charged. Talk of the unfolding
federal antitrust investigation of auction houses in New York was
everywhere, and with it speculation about the increase the biggest
of the houses, Sotheby's and Christie's, plan to charge buyers. The
effects all this will have on dealers is uncertain. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   MOSELY-NONFICTION (Undated) _ Walter Mosely talks about his
first non-fiction book. By Felicia R. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
reviews ``Riding the Bullet'' an electronic book on the Internet by
Stephen King.
