<P>
   OSCARS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Advertising column: The 72nd
Annual Academy Awards show is looking a lot like a Super Sunday,
and not just because that's the day the ceremony is now held. The
Oscar presentation on ABC has traditionally been the second biggest
day of the year for advertising, trailing only the Super Bowl. This
year, though, that gridiron-style hoopla and hyperbole has
permeated the broadcast to the point where the network ought to
bill it as ``Oscar Bowl LXXII.''By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-NETSCAPE (Undated) _ Where does Netscape fit into the
AOL-Time Warner future? By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   PANAM-PENSIONS (Undated) _ A federal judge has sided with
employees of Pan American World Airways in a case related to their
pension plan and the way it was administered by a federal agency
after the airline went out of business. The ruling, which
eventually may lead to an increase in pension payments for some of
the 65,000 people who worked for Pan Am when it went out of
business in 1991, affects the way Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp.
administers pension plans. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-MUSIC-SOFTWARE (Undated) _ Justin Frankel, a 21-year-old
programming wizard who sold his digital music company, but perhaps
not his soul, to America Online last year, did not endear himself
to his new masters last week by publishing free software that
enables users to find and trade music files quickly over the
Internet. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
