<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WRESTLING-FILM-MEDIA-     03-19 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-FILM-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTION DISPUTE WITH WWF JEOPARDIZES FILM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The world of documentary filmmaking and the world of
professional wrestling do not often come together, but it might be
expected that if they did, there would be a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Mat,'' a documentary that tries to put a human face
on the larger-than-life characters who make their livings in the
middle and lower ranks of pro wrestling, opened on March 17 on 300
movie screens in 50 cities around the country. But prospects for
the film were greatly diminished, the film's producers say, after a
decision by the World Wrestling Federation not to allow any
television advertising for the documentary during any of the pro
wrestling group's programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince McMahon, who runs the WWF, is an amazing business guy,
and he's done a remarkable thing with his organization, but this is
kind of the way he does business,'' said Ron Howard, co-founder of
Imagine Entertainment, which produced the documentary in
conjunction with Universal Pictures. ``He wants to totally dominate
and control anything that has anything to do with wrestling.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry W. Blaustein, who made ``Beyond the Mat,'' is best known
as the screenwriter for several Eddie Murphy comedies, including
``The Nutty Professor'' and ``Coming to America.'' The wrestling
film was a five-year labor of love, Blaustein said. In the film,
such pro wrestling luminaries as Mick Foley, who wrestles under the
name Mankind, and Jake Roberts, known as Jake the Snake, talk
candidly about their love of wrestling but also about the physical
and emotional toll it takes on them and their families.
</P>
<P>
   What makes all this so surprising to the filmmakers is that
McMahon and the WWF cooperated in the filming of the documentary,
and McMahon appears prominently in it along with several wrestlers.
Lions Gate Films, which is distributing ``Beyond the Mat'' in North
America, had signed contracts with the WWF to allow ads for the
movie during WWF programs and was not told until the day the spots
were to begin running, two weeks ago, that they would not be
allowed on the air during the wrestling shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never could get a straight answer about why they were doing
this,'' said Tom Ortenberg, co-president of Lions Gate. ``The truth
is, Vince always thought he'd be able to buy the film, and I
believe, when he was ultimately rebuffed, is when he turned on the
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Byrne, senior vice president of marketing for World
Wrestling Federation Entertainment, said that, yes, the company did
refuse to broadcast the ads, but only because they violated a
long-standing WWF policy not to include any ``third-party wrestling
product'' in the WWF's shows. The ads were rejected shortly after
they were presented to the WWF, Byrne said, as is common practice
in television, even if contracts had previously been signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just recently, we bought a Super Bowl commercial, and they
rejected it _ the very same sort of thing,'' Byrne said. ``It's
very commonplace. You wouldn't put out a press release about it,
unless you were trying to promote a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortenberg said the filmmakers were puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he suspected that McMahon had two motives for
rejecting the ads. After the attempt to invest in the film was
rejected, McMahon wanted to make sure no one had a success with pro
wrestling that did not include the WWF. ``He is just trying to
prove his point, to shut down the film,'' Howard said. But also,
Howard suspects, McMahon objects to the way the wrestlers are
presented, as real people rather than as mythic cartoon characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Vince McMahon doesn't seem to understand is that the film
is a love letter to wrestling,'' Ortenberg said. ``If the film were
successful, it would do much more for the WWF than it would do for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true, Byrne said, that at one time McMahon wanted to buy
an interest in the film, but he denied that there was any
coordinated campaign of revenge against it. ``This all is just
completely a publicity stunt,'' Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this month with The Los Angeles Times, McMahon
was quoted as saying that ``we feel cheated that we have no equity
in the movie.'' But in an interview late last week, Byrne put a
different spin on it. The WWF's interest in buying part of the film
came before it was finished. After McMahon had seen the finished
film, he didn't like it and was relieved he had not invested in it,
Byrne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't find it entertaining,'' he said. ``Even though
we were denied the opportunity to participate, we probably would
have dropped the offer once we'd screened it, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Without access to the most popular pro wrestling programs on
television, Lions Gate said it would have trouble connecting the
film with its most obvious audience. Ads will be shown on other pro
wrestling shows put on by some of the WWF's competitors as well as
on some cable channels and local radio stations with demographics
that include a high concentration of wrestling fans, but it is all
very expensive, difficult and imprecise, Ortenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the pro wrestling world outside of Vince McMahon
has been hugely supportive, including many of the Internet pro
wrestling sites, so we're maximizing all of the promotional and
marketing opportunities that we can,'' he said. ``We are trying to
make lemonade out of lemons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1538EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
