<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-INDIA-0320-CO     03-19 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INDIA-0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SECURITY CONCERNS CAUSE CLINTON TO CANCEL VISIT TO BANGLADESH
VILLAGE
 &HT;    (600&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ President Bill Clinton's week-long swing through
India, Bangladesh and Pakistan got off to a sour start Sunday, when
security risks forced him to scrub a planned visit to a village in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   The stop at Joypura, where Clinton had hoped to visit with
villagers benefitting from U.S. assistance in health, education and
development programs, was to have been the centerpiece of the
president's program for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, though, two hours after Clinton arrived in New
Delhi, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in a prepared
statement that the president would not be going to Joypura, a
picturesque and impoverished hamlet 20 miles outside of the capital
city of Dhaka, ``because of concerns raised by the Secret
Service.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a rocky start for Clinton's visit, the first by a U.S.
president to the Indian subcontinent since Jimmy Carter's trip to
India in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was still planning to go to Dhaka to meet with Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina, becoming the first American president to
visit Bangladesh since the country of 128 million won its
independence from Pakistan in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials declined to elaborate on the cancellation.
Scrapping a scheduled stop, though, is unusual. As a matter of
practice, Secret Service agents preview prospective sites of
presidential visits well in advance of the actual visit.
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh, a deeply impoverished and overwhelmingly Islamic
country, is plagued with a high level of politically-motivated
violence, including bombings and assassinations. Several dozen
people were killed in politically linked violence last year,
including two ruling-party workers who were making bombs at the
residence of a member of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, army officers assassinated Prime Minister Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman and most of his family. His daughter, who happened
to be out of the country at the time, is the current prime
minister, Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, the idea of flying Clinton in the
presidential helicopter over the tropical forests and rice paddies
surrounding the village, was not on, the Secret Service concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived here Sunday night on the first leg of his tour
of the Indian subcontinent, hoping to defuse regional tensions and
tamp down a dangerous nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   With daughter Chelsea holding onto his left arm, Clinton stepped
out of Air Force One and waved, as workers scrambled to finish
painting walls, repairing pock-marked roads and otherwise sprucing
up the city in anticipation of the visit.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, engaged in a tight U.S.
Senate race in New York, is not on the trip. But her mother,
Dorothy Rodham, is.
</P>
<P>
   With no official activities on his schedule Sunday night,
Clinton told reporters he was headed to a restaurant in his
five-star hotel for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Indian food,'' he told reporters traveling with him
aboard the presidential aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   He came bearing gifts: nearly $200 million in aid meant to help
fight hunger, expand schools for children and clean up the
environment. Most of the aid will target Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance consists of:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $97 million worth of wheat and soybean oil, to be given to
Bangladesh to be used as pay to workers for such things as
repairing schools, building latrines and digging wells;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $84 million to Bangladesh, India and Nepal to promote clean
and renewable energy technologies and the use of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and $6 million to promote conservation of tropical forests in
Bangladesh, through a nature-for-debt swap.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the focus on grassroots development, Clinton is
to meet Monday with the grandfather of micro-enterprise, Muhammad
Yunus.
</P>
<P>
   Yunus is the founder of the Grameen Bank, which institutionlized
the concept of micro-credits _ small loans of $200 or so to help
poor people start small businesses _ that has since become a
mainstay of the global war on poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bangladesh clearly has been a world leader in
micro-enterprise,'' said White House spokesman Michael Hammer.
``(This) helps poor people break out of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings beginning Tuesday with Indian leaders, and later
with leaders in Pakistan, Clinton hopes to defuse tensions that
have driven India and Pakistan near the brink of war over the
disputed territory of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   He'll also be pressing for India and Pakistan to roll back their
nuclear weapons programs, a first step in knitting back together
the global non-proliferation regime put at risk by the nuclear
tests the two nations conducted two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
