<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN'S MEMOIRS SET FOR PUBLICATION IN U.S.  
 JOURNALISTS AMONG THE ONLINE CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   LOOKING AT THE CITY FROM THE WALL ST. LEVEL  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PublicAffairs, a New York company that is fast becoming the
publishing house for Kremlin politicians, is preparing to rush into
print in May with an English translation of the memoirs describing
the life, travails and Cold War spying adventures of Russia's
acting president, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The original Russian version of ``First Person'' is still
unavailable in Russia, where the country's Central Electoral
Commission has temporarily barred publication until after the March
26 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The slim volume was written by two reporters for Kommersant, a
Russian daily newspaper, who interviewed Putin for a day. The
president discussed everything from his own rigid interpretation of
freedom of speech to his boyhood dream to become a Cold War spy.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family members also were interviewed. Putin's wife,
Ludmilla, a former airline attendant, acknowledged that she burst
into tears when she heard about her husband's sudden appointment as
acting president. ``I understood that private life had finished for
at least three months, up to the presidential elections, or perhaps
for four years,'' she said, according to an outline of the book
from PublicAffairs.
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt from the Russian version appeared early this month in
Kommersant. But the book's publication was stalled; Russian law
prohibits the publication of anything that can be construed as
campaign propaganda unless it is paid for by the candidate. The
electoral commission ruled that the book could favor Putin, who
leads a field of 12 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin also is publishing his memoirs of his career as
Russian president with PublicAffairs.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, the grandson of the chef to Lenin and later Stalin,
describes his boyhood growing up in a communal flat with no hot
water or kitchen, chasing rats in a freezing stairwell. He became
entranced by films about Russian spies and at 16 volunteered for
the KGB, only to be told that he needed a university education.
Eventually, he would become a KGB agent and be sent to East
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But he clearly is a spy who has come in from the cold, ready to
shed some of his secretive ways. That means we can now be privy to
his wife's shopping habits and television preferences, and one of
the most difficult decisions of his life _ dumping his first love
shortly before a scheduled marriage.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Print Types Online
</P>
<P>
   Some say the Internet poses a threat to print journalists. But,
according to a study by Middleberg &AMP; Associates, a public relations
and marketing agency, print journalists themselves may be among
those benefiting most from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1999 survey of managing editors and business editors at
1,509 daily newspapers and 2,500 magazines, which was completed by
about 10 percent of those contacted, 73 percent said they went
online at least once a day, compared with 48 percent in 1998. The
new level was the highest percentage-point increase since the
survey was first conducted in 1994. That year, only 17 percent of
the respondents went online daily. In addition, in the latest
survey, the number of respondents who never or almost never went
online dwindled to 1 percent, from 5 percent in 1998 and 37 percent
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Don Middleberg, chairman and chief executive of Middleberg &AMP;
Associates, conducted the study with Steven S. Ross, associate
professor of professional practice at the Columbia University
Graduate School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found trends in the ways print journalists used
the Internet. In 1999, the most popular use was research,
displacing e-mail, though both were up from 1998. Ninety percent of
respondents used the Internet to research articles or as a
reference source, up from 74 percent in 1998; 83 percent used the
Internet for e-mail, up from 80 percent in 1998. In 1999, more than
half said they used e-mail at least occasionally to communicate
with readers. Half of the respondents used the Internet to search
for ideas for articles, up from 30 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Print publications are adapting to new media as well. In 1999,
67 percent of newspapers with Web sites used a common newsroom for
Web and print operations, up from 56 percent in 1998. And 40
percent of the respondents said their publications allowed their
Web sites to report information before its appearance in their
newspapers or magazines.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALLISON FASS
</P>
<P>
   Guys and the City
</P>
<P>
   You HBO viewers who have wondered what ``Sex and the City''
might be like from the male perspective: Pour yourself a
cosmopolitan and fasten your seat belts. Darren Star, the executive
producer of ``Sex and the City'' and the creator of ``Melrose
Place,'' is taping a pilot for Fox Entertainment that his staff is
already talking up as a male version of the popular HBO series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not `Sex and the City,' exactly,''' Star said. ``It's
more like `Guys and Money and the City.'''
</P>
<P>
   Star, it appears, has grown a tiny bit weary of womanly concerns
and all those pages and pages of scripts about shoe shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wanted to think about the world from the male point
of view,'' he said. ``Certainly Wall Street is a great arena in
which to explore male issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, ``The Street,'' centers on a group of aggressive
young Wall Street brokers with testosterone to burn. It stars Tom
Everett Scott, who is fresh from a role in ``Boiler Room,'' a movie
about, coincidentally, a group of aggressive young penny-stock
brokers with testosterone to burn.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Earley, vice president for entertainment at Fox
Broadcasting, a unit of News Corp., said that the pilot, if it
blossoms into a series, is scheduled to begin in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, the men, rather than sit around neurotically
dissecting their love lives and passionately debating who gets
better discounts on Jimmy Choo sandals _ as their female
counterparts might in ``Sex and the City'' _ become really excited
about the initial public stock offering of an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's also some personal turmoil in the lives of some of
these brokers,'' Star said. ``There is so much money entrusted in
the hands of these young guys, and the burnout factor is
enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. He said ``The Street'' would be suitable for broadcast
television.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
