<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PANAM-PENSIONS-NYT &LR;      03-19 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM-PENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JUDGE BACKS EX-WORKERS OF PAN AM IN PENSION CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge has sided with employees of Pan American World
Airways in a case related to their pension plan and the way it was
administered by a federal agency after the airline went out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which eventually may lead to an increase in pension
payments for some of the 65,000 people who worked for Pan Am when
it went out of business in 1991, affects the way the Pension
Benefit Guaranty Corp. administers pension plans.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ruling, the guaranty corporation must put the
interests of workers in failed pension plans ahead of its own
interests and is subject to the same rules as a pension plan in
keeping workers and pensioners informed about their pension
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was handed down last week by Judge Loretta A. Preska
of U. S. District Court in Manhattan. Preska ruled that the
guaranty corporation can be held to the standard of conduct
required of a trustee, known as a duty of loyalty or fiduciary
duty, and not just to that of a mere guarantor of payments.
</P>
<P>
   The decision may prompt new litigation from people unhappy with
how the guaranty corporation determined the amount they were due
from their employer's failed pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Association for Former Pan Am Employees contends that the
guaranty corporation did not properly determine the benefits due
65,000 workers of the airline, which filed for bankruptcy
protection in 1991 and went out of business. The association says
the guaranty corporation issued thousands of workers determinations
of the benefits due them that were improper because, among other
reasons, they failed to abide by the terms of the agreement
negotiated between Pan Am and its unions.
</P>
<P>
   The guaranty corporation, in court papers, says it is not bound
by the union contract or any Pan Am practices that went beyond the
requirements of the pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   A trial has not yet been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The association also maintains that at least 14,000 workers have
yet to be informed of the benefits due them nearly nine years after
the airline folded. Richard A. Brooks, president of the
association, said Preska's decision ``represents a substantial
victory not only for former Pan Am employees but also for all
similarly situated individuals.'' He said that the decision means
that the guaranty corporation ``will finally be forced to respect
the rights of former employees under terminated retirement plans in
the same manner as any other plan fiduciary.''
</P>
<P>
   The guaranty corporation said that it was confident it would be
found by the court to have treated all participants fairly and to
have fulfilled its obligations under federal pension law.
</P>
<P>
   The guaranty corporation characterized the decision as technical
and noted that Preska had dismissed fraud claims brought by the
former Pan Am workers against it. It said it might seek permission
from Preska to appeal her ruling prior to trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
