can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO: NATO WON THE WAR BUT, A YEAR ON, IS LOSING THE PEACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is Kosovo time again. Even if the passage of a year since
NATO's decision to bomb the Serbs out of Kosovo were not prompting
retrospection, thoughts would anyway be turning towards that
luckless corner of the Balkans. The place is a mess, and the risk
is that NATO, having won the war, is about to lose the peace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 75-word optional trim; 950 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WHAT-PEACE-KOSOVO?-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAKISTAN: THE WORLD'S MOST DANGEROUS PLACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It takes a brave man, or a foolish one, to step between mortal
enemies spoiling for a fight. Bill Clinton may be the leader of the
world's most powerful country but, if he puts a foot wrong during
his tour of India next week and his brief touchdown in Pakistan, he
could exacerbate the tensions that last year brought the two
nuclear powers to blows over Kashmir. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 100-word optional trim; 1,050 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-SCARY-PAKISTAN-ECONOMIST-925&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAS BRITISH MUSEUM LOST ITS MARBLES? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museums of the world are full of other countries' art.
Unfortunately, this happy state of affairs was not always brought
about in the proudest of circumstances. Much museum art was
acquired by dubious means, if not by outright looting. So it is
with the controversial Elgin marble sculptures in the British
Museum. Should they be returned to their original home, Greece? In
such matters, alas, the answer isn't set in stone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ELGIN-MARBLE-MESS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGNING IN THE LAND OF CAPULETS AND MONTAGUES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the main actors, the coming presidential election is no more
about ``the issues'' than ``Romeo and Juliet'' was an academic
treatise on the economy of Verona. It is about revenge. Like
Renaissance princes, the two presidential front-runners are not
just loyal to their fathers; they are fixated on them. Add clanship
loyalty to such powerful father-son bonds and you are soon in the
land of the Capulets and Montagues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 225 words; total uncut is 1,100) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-`VENDETTA'-BUSHGORE-ECONOMIST-400&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This week's droll ``Primary Color'' Column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Humor, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (375 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOEING STRIKERS: FLYING IN THE FACE OF A HARSH NEW REALITY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Grainger hardly looks like a tough union type. Yet the
aerodynamics engineer, who has spent 32 years working for Boeing,
is now more than six weeks into the longest, biggest white-collar
strike in American history. The strike has exposed the growing gap
in America's skilled classes. For many of the engineers, the bigger
change has been the way that Seattle man has given way to Redmond
man in Seattle's hierarchy. The explosive growth of Microsoft,
Amazon.com and other ``new economy'' firms has left the Boeing
engineers looking old and poor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Seattle) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story stands in 975 words; 1,200 if uncut) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-EXTINCT-BOEING-MAN-ECONOMIST-975&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FRANKLY, THEY DO GIVE A DAMN: THE SOUTH COULD DECIDE ELECTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The half-dozen Southern primary contests that took place this
week had all the tension of an election for a North Korean
communist-party second secretary. But the South will play a more
important role in the coming general election than is recognized.
And it could mean that, whatever his current problems, the race is
still George W. Bush's to lose. After years in which the South was
a GOP stronghold, the Democrats have found a way into the fortress.
Bush, like Sherman, has to sweep it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Southern-State Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 850-word optional trim; total uncut is 1,400) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-DEEPSOUTH-BUSHGORE-ECONOMIST-450&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROUTE 66: PRESERVING AMERICA'S BELOVED `MOTHER ROAD' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no other road in the United States like Route 66, none
as treasured in memory, none as much a part of American culture and
mythology, none as mourned at its death _ or as celebrated at its
resurrection. The recent enactment of a Route 66 preservation bill
is a victory not just for the road itself but for the grass roots
over bureaucracy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Route-66 States: Ill.,Mo.,Okla.,Texas,N.M.,Ariz.,Calif.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-ROUTE-66-REBIRTH-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RED, WHITE AND GREY: WHAT'S THE FUTURE FOR BOOMERS? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton, 53, is staring retirement in the face.
The good news is that he has a pension, good health and excellent
prospects for supplementary income. The bad news is that his wife
may not get the job she is angling for in the autumn, and the
family's retirement nest egg has been squandered on unexpected
legal expenses. Such are the facts the Clinton household might
provide to the Health and Retirement Study (HRS), a huge $100
million study on how Americans grow old. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Michigan _ 6th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-AGING-AMERICA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `IT'S MY TURN TO ABANDON MY SOIL, MY LIFE, MY SOUL, MY
COUNTRY' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `I am one more. Like the intellectual, the reporter, the
human-rights advocate, the displaced person. It's my turn to have
to abandon my native soil, my life, my soul, my country.'' So began
the column published last Sunday by Francisco Santos, the news
editor of El Tiempo, Colombia's main newspaper. By the time the
edition hit the streets, Santos and his family were already in the
U.S. _ before the death threats made against him could be carried
out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story stands in 775 words; 900 uncut) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-EXODUS-COLOMBIA-ECONOMIST-775&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `ASIA'S NELSON MANDELA' FACES TOUGH REELECTION APRIL 13 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What now for Kim Dae Jung, who restored South Korea's fortunes,
bolstered its democracy, tried to make friends with the communist
North _ and yet stands to be rejected by many voters when his
country goes to the polls on April 13? When he was decisively
elected South Korea's president in 1997, he was considered
something of a maverick, but nevertheless the right man for the
time and the job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Note April 13 election, South Korea) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CAN-KIM-WIN?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BANGKOK'S ELEPHANTINE PROBLEM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is a homelessness problem of massive proportions. What can
you do with squatters who eat up to 770 lbs. of food a day and
block the traffic to boot? Although elephants are not supposed to
be taken into Bangkok, the police generally have done their best to
ignore them. But on March 10 the Bangkok governor's office banned
from the capital Thailand's national symbol. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-HOMELESS-ELEPHANTS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WORLD IN INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A compilation of international financial briefs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WORLDBIZ-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEB SITE BOOKS `PRIVATE SEATS' ON EXECUTIVE JETS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a cheaper way for business travellers to fly on a
private jet. On March 9 a new Internet travel agent,
flightserv.com, launched ``Private Seats'' to allow people to buy
individual seats on chartered private jets. Starting April 17,
flights between New York and Atlanta will cost $900, only $40 more
than a business-class seat on Delta Airlines. The private jet in
America may be the last luxury toy for big boys. But in the land of
the car pool, the plane pool just might take off. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-EXEC-JETS.COM-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
