<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1666 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ELECTRONIC-BOOK-REVIE     03-19 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRONIC-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RIDING THE BULLET': CLICK IF YOU DARE _ IT'S THE CYBERCRYPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review) 
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anyone could write a book that would overcome the obstacles
of having to be read on a computer screen, Stephen King should be
the one, given his unusual gift for storytelling and his almost
universal popularity.
</P>
<P>
   So far his first attempt, a 16,000-word novella called ``Riding
the Bullet,'' appears to be succeeding spectacularly, with paid and
free downloads during the first few days of its online availability
flooding past the half-million mark. But is this the wave of the
future or just a confluence of unusual circumstances? As someone
habitually attached to the traditional form of book, I put my foot
into these new waters with the utmost hesitancy.
</P>
<P>
   I read King's book in two of the available formats: first, by
downloading it onto my laptop computer; second, on an e-book
supplied by the publisher. (Neither permits a user to print out a
copy).
</P>
<P>
   Each option had its advantages: The e-book, a book-size monitor,
proved handier and more booklike in size and shape. By contrast, my
laptop allowed me to highlight key words and sentences in highly
visible colors.
</P>
<P>
   Both allow you to turn pages, so to speak, with the touch of a
button. Both enable you to enlarge or shrink the print to a
visually comfortable size. And both permit you to go from beginning
to end of the text, or to any given page, or to any single word
even, with a couple of mouse-clicks or a few taps of a penlike
stylus.
</P>
<P>
   But with both formats I was also restlessly aware of the unusual
effort it was taking to read onscreen. As near as I can put my
finger on a reason, it is that the screen's backlighting makes the
words appear to float in the foreground and seem less solidly
present than they do on the printed page.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it is King's story itself, not one of his best, that
made reading onscreen seem insubstantial.
</P>
<P>
   True, ``Riding the Bullet'' gets off to a strong start and
builds with its author's familiar skill. Alan Parker, a student at
the University of Maine at Orono, gets a telephone call telling him
that his mother has had a stroke and has been taken to a hospital
in Lewiston. Because his car has a broken transmission he decides
to hitchhike the 120-mile trip south to Lewiston to comfort her.
</P>
<P>
   The second ride he catches is in a car that smells of urine,
driven by an old man who refuses to dim his brights for oncoming
cars and who worries out loud about catching ``that forgettin'
disease, I can't think what in the world they call it, Anderson's
or Alvarez or something like that ....''
</P>
<P>
   The moon comes up, ``a huge orange ball hoisting itself over the
horizon,'' and the man tells Alan to wish on it. He wishes that his
mother would know him when he walks into her room, and then he
regrets the wish, thinking of W.W. Jacobs' famous story, ``The
Monkey's Paw,'' in which magic wishes backfire with horrifying
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   After being dropped off by the man, Alan walks past a graveyard,
stops to read an inscription on a gravestone, ``George Staub/ Jan.
19, 1977/ Oct. 12, 1998,'' and then hitches another ride. This
driver is young and has stitch marks around his neck as if his head
had been severed and sewn back on. He wears a button on his T-shirt
that reads, ``I rode the bullet at Thrill Village, Laconia.'' After
a few exchanges he introduces himself to Alan as George Staub.
</P>
<P>
   But after getting off to such a strong start, King writes
himself into a corner that makes Alan's scary adventure seem
something of a shaggy dog story.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the most intriguing thing about ``Riding the Bullet''
is the connection that can be made between the story's implications
and the recent accident King suffered, in which he was hit by a van
while walking on a road. ``Riding the Bullet'' is reportedly the
first thing he has been able to write since his accident.
</P>
<P>
   Would reading it onscreen have been improved had the story been
more substantial? Maybe yes, maybe no. Improvements will doubtless
be made to the e-book, especially if a project to produce one with
actual pages instead of a screen ever comes to fruition at the
Media Lab at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. And
generations are growing up now entirely comfortable with reading
print on a backlighted screen.
</P>
<P>
   But reading ``Riding the Bullet,'' I sorely missed the solidity
of good old print on paper. And who knows, maybe old-fashioned
print would have made King's story seem a little more substantial.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RIDING THE BULLET'
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen King
</P>
<P>
   Scribner/Philtrum Press. $2.50 to download.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
