<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CROSS-OWNERSHIP-MEDIA     03-19 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSS-OWNERSHIP-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION COULD AFFECT TRIBUNE-TIMES MIRROR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the pending merger of Tribune Co. and Times
Mirror, the fate of three of Tribune's largest television stations
and three of Times Mirror's largest newspapers may ultimately
depend on who becomes the nation's next president.
</P>
<P>
   That is because Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive
Democratic candidate, favors keeping the current restrictions on
companies that own both television stations and newspapers. But
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the apparent Republican nominee, is
tilting against the existing rules. Under Tribune's proposed
acquisition of Times Mirror Co., announced last week, Tribune would
control newspapers and television stations in New York, Los Angeles
and Hartford, Conn., once it completed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But a 1974 federal regulation known as the cross-ownership rule
prohibits a company from owning a newspaper and a television
station in the same geographic market. Unless revised, that rule
would require the companies to either seek a rarely granted waiver
or sell the newspapers or stations when their broadcast licenses
come up for renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of lobbying by Tribune and top executives in the
newspaper and broadcast industries, neither Congress nor the
Clinton administration is expected to change the rule any time
soon. Gore and other officials in the administration say they
support the rule because it prevents too much media power from
falling into too few hands. Congressional Republicans, including
Sen. John McCain, who have tried to have it repealed, have been
blocked by top Democratic lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has not publicly articulated a position about the
rule, his top economic advisers have said it is archaic and
unnecessary. And some aides have quietly promised industry
executives and lobbyists that a Bush administration would move
swiftly to eliminate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been assured through reliable channels that the
governor would support repeal of the rule,'' said John F. Sturm,
the president and chief executive of the Newspaper Association of
America. Shaun Sheehan, Tribune's top lobbyist in Washington, said
that he, too, had heard that the governor's policy advisers had
said that Bush would repeal the rule.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the position of the broadcast industry's lobbyists,
aides to the governor's presidential campaign said they believed
that the rule was out of date, now that consumers could get
information from a wide array of sources including the Internet and
cable and satellite television.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now so many media outlets that it would make sense
to relax it,'' said Timothy J. Muris, a professor at the George
Mason University of Law, a former senior antitrust official in the
Reagan administration and one of Bush's top advisers on economic
and competition issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although support for and opposition to the rule now largely
follows partisan lines, the regulation was first adopted by a
Republican-controlled agency at a time of intense concern among
antitrust officials about the power, particularly in smaller
markets, of companies that owned both newspaper and television
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   After it was approved by the Federal Communications Commission a
quarter-century ago, television stations in a dozen cities had to
be sold. A few newspaper companies were permitted to keep their
stations in some larger cities under a grandfather clause. A
handful of other companies were treated leniently, as when Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp. was permitted to buy the New York Post even
though the company controlled a television station, on the
rationale that the newspaper might otherwise fail. Nonetheless,
regulators compelled Murdoch to sell another newspaper, The Boston
Herald, because his company owned a television station in the same
market.
</P>
<P>
   During debate over the Telecommunications Act of 1996, Gore, as
the administration's lead negotiator, managed to save the
cross-ownership rule from being repealed. As one of the final
compromises that led to passage of the legislation, the lawmakers
and the administration agreed that instead of repeal, the FCC would
conduct reviews every two years to reconsider the need for the
rule. The agency under the Clinton administration has shown no sign
of changing its stance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The different views between the Bush and Gore camps over the
cross-ownership rule illustrate one of the many ways that the
presidential race could determine enforcement of antitrust and
competition rules in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   During the Clinton administration, antitrust and competition in
telecommunications and other industries have been among the
business issues receiving the fiercest litigation and lobbying
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has revived antitrust enforcement and brought
some of the most significant cases in a generation, including
prosecution of a vitamin cartel that resulted in record-breaking
fines and, still in progress, the Microsoft case. Clinton antitrust
officials have also challenged a series of large and smaller
mergers that would have gone unchallenged in the Reagan and Bush
administrations, killing many corporate deals and ordering
extensive modifications of others.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore have provided relatively few specific details
about their views on antitrust and competition. And while whoever
is in the White House sets the overall tone and philosophy,
antitrust policies are generally set by the top officials appointed
to the Federal Trade Commission and the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the candidates and their advisers have begun to
drop broad hints that they have significantly different views of
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it yin and yang,'' said Reed Hundt, a close friend of
Gore and an antitrust expert who has discussed competition policies
with the vice president. Hundt served as chairman of the FCC from
1993 until 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Al Gore view is to side with the following constituencies:
small companies, start-ups, innovators, and attackers of
incumbents,'' Hundt said. ``The Gore view of antitrust follows in
the tradition of Teddy Roosevelt through Thurman Arnold and the
current administration. George Bush's view is much more beholden to
large companies and incumbents and sees little role for the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   In his few public remarks about antitrust, Bush has suggested
that he would return to many of the principles of the Reagan
administration and the practice of selecting antitrust enforcers
whose primary goal would be to combat price-fixing _ rather than to
use antitrust laws to protect consumers in industries, like
telecommunications, transportation and energy, that have been
significantly deregulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own personal view is the application of antitrust laws
needs to be applied where there are clear cases of price-fixing,''
the governor said in an interview with The Financial Times last
month. Asked whether the laws should be applied to situations
beyond price-fixing, he replied, ``Well, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the governor later clarified his remarks to say that he
was not ruling out other kinds of antitrust enforcement. But they
also contended that the Clinton administration had stretched some
antitrust laws beyond recognition and that a Bush administration
would pursue a more laissez-faire approach similar to that of the
Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   The differences were perhaps best summed up in a recent article
by Muris, the senior adviser to Bush, about the FTC's enforcement
of monopoly law. The article, which appears in the current issue of
the Antitrust Law Journal, criticizes the agency for an overly
aggressive interpretation of the Sherman Antitrust Act, and has
chapter titles that include ``The FTC is Wrong on the Law,'' ``The
FTC is Wrong on Policy'' and ``The FTC is Wrong on the Facts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
