<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMULA TV FADES AWAY: SUDDENLY, EVERYONE'S GOT A GIMMICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Beat,'' a swift and engrossing series about a pair of
improbably good-looking police partners, begins with the men
sitting in a bar. Mike Dorigan (Derek Cecil), the fair-haired,
clean-cut half of the team, tells the dark and impulsive Zane
Marinelli (Mark Ruffalo), ``You have this thing for psycho women.''
Just then Zane's girlfriend wanders in wearing oversized pink
flannel pajamas. ``I was sleeping, then I woke up,'' she says in a
fog. ``Suddenly I felt compelled to see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily that would be enough quirkiness for one show, but
``The Beat'' (created by Tom Fontana of ``Homicide'') soon reveals
a gimmick that makes a girlfriend in pink pj's look tame. When a
fight begins in the bar, Mike pulls out his badge and the camera
shifts from film, and the smooth glossy look of most television
dramas, to grainy video with the down-and-dirty style of cheap
reality programs like ``World's Wildest Police Chases.'' Throughout
the series, whenever the partners talk about their personal lives
we see film. When they do police work, on or off duty, the look
changes to video in a flash, often alternating within one scene.
This head-spinning approach makes ``The Beat'' feel like
``Homicide'' meets ``Cops,'' and it offers the best evidence that
even before the flood of reality programs turns up this summer, a
spring season of gimmickry has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   After years of whining that they have to do something different
to prevent more viewers from deserting to cable, the networks are
finally trying to figure out what. The stunts are sometimes
stylistic and sometimes a matter of scheduling, but all smack of
the desperate need to escape a self-defeating, business-as-usual
attitude. This is the season the old formulas finally crashed.
</P>
<P>
   But where is the line between a gimmick and true innovation? Are
these stunts, with all their accompanying hype, overshadowing the
shows' true strengths? Or is hype all there is?
</P>
<P>
   Though genuine iconoclasm is rare, the networks are brimming
with superficial changes. ``The Beat'' (beginning Tuesday night at
9 on UPN) offers the best hope of overcoming its gimmicky device.
``Titus'' (beginning Monday night at 8:30 on Fox) is less
promising. Christopher Titus, the autobiographical hero, is filmed
in black and white talking directly to the camera about his
dysfunctional family; the series blooms into color and uneven
comedy to dramatize what he is talking about. As in ``Action,'' the
failed Fox series in which words were routinely bleeped out, the
attention-getting trick can't make up for weak writing.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, stereotyped as the old-timers' network, may be shaking
things up the most. ``Falcone,'' a series about an FBI agent who
goes undercover in the mob, was delayed from a previous season
after the shootings in Littleton, Colo., and concerns about
violence on the screen. When it finally arrives on April 4, it will
play as a continuous miniseries (nine hours over eight nights)
rather than in weekly episodes. CBS is also turning to live drama,
with George Clooney producing and appearing in ``Fail Safe'' on
April 9 and Julie Andrews scheduled for a live broadcast of ``On
Golden Pond'' sometime next season.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had already created an upheaval with ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire.'' Only NBC seems dangerously content to coast along.
</P>
<P>
   The most attention-getting elements in these shows may be the
least important, though. Where does the film/video split get you in
``The Beat''? The series' true strength is its appealing, sometimes
confused characters, who are not cliches even when they sound as if
they are. The wholesome Mike is engaged to a medical student,
Elizabeth (Poppy Montgomery), and isn't picking up her hints of
reluctance about the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Zane's girlfriend, Beatrice (Heather Burns), is wonderfully
crazed; she would be a horror in life but is hilarious on
television. She reacts to a lovers' spat by pouring lighter fluid
over everything in Zane's apartment. Later she finds him in a
grocery store. ``It's not my fault that...,'' she yells and reveals
something truly shocking about his troubled family history. (It's
not child abuse; that would be the predictable shock today.) In
black-and-white flashbacks in future episodes, Zane revisits that
childhood horror. Used sparingly, the black-and-white of his past
seems deft and effective rather than gimmicky.
</P>
<P>
   Fontana, probably the best creative mind in television, knows
how to do this kind of series, and his script for the first episode
displays more humor than usual. The first episode was directed by
Barry Levinson, also an executive producer, and Zane and Mike are
as well acted as they are directed and written. A running plot
about racial tension is handled with political savvy. Two of their
white colleagues have arrested a black suspect, who dies in
custody: heart attack or choke hold?
</P>
<P>
   With all this in its favor, why does ``The Beat'' need its video
gimmick? Maybe because it's on UPN, the wrestling network. At times
``Homicide'' seemed too tony for NBC, so a downscale touch of
``Cops'' injected into a UPN show is not a stupid idea. It is also
a way of reinvigorating what is, after all, a conventional cop
show.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this particular video trick seems counterproductive, even
though those head-spinning changes become less distracting after
the first episode. The camera-swirling style of ``Homicide''
reflected its chaotic, morally ambiguous world. In ``The Beat,''
the film-video split creates a false separation. Mike and Zane are
people whose jobs constantly bleed into their private lives; that's
one of their problems. Instead of reflecting that, the
film-to-video jumpiness works against the reality of their
characters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just as the video sections of ``The Beat'' echo the reality
programming that is television's next wave, the autobiographical
genesis of ``Titus'' takes that show in a similar direction.
Performance art meets the dysfunctional family sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The show is based on the stand-up performances of Christopher
Titus. (Don't worry, no one else has ever heard of him, either,
though Fox pretends he's well known.) Here he plays a character
named Titus who makes customized cars for a living and, like the
real person, has a father who has been divorced many times and a
brother who is just as scarred by their family as he is.
</P>
<P>
   In his black-and-white addresses to the camera, interspersed
throughout the series, Titus is in a stark room with a bare light
bulb hanging from the ceiling. Despite its high concept, the show
frequently falls back on banal sitcom humor and is never as funny
as the annoying laugh track suggests. Titus and his brother think
their father must be dead because he has been in his room for four
days (cue the laugh track) without asking for a beer.
</P>
<P>
   The show's true radical element is not the cliched beer-drinking
father, but its rock-bottom assumption that dysfunction is the
all-American standard. At the start, Titus says: ``Sixty-three
percent of American families are now considered dysfunctional.
We're the majority.'' He means it. He explains that his father
``never missed a drink or a joint'' in his life but ``also never
missed a day of work or a house payment.'' This is the
dysfunctional father as heroic antihero (given perfect growling
obtuseness by Stacy Keach).
</P>
<P>
   Still, the series is better in its throwaway moments than in its
grasping, ambitious ones. Titus says that when he was a boy, if his
arm had been ripped off during a soccer game his father would have
strapped it back on and returned him to action. An irreverently
funny, colorful flashback shows a boy with a dangling, limp arm
telling Keach, ``Thank you, father, I'll be the best soccer player
ever.'' Another of the funniest lines is, similarly, a throwaway
about his girlfriend, Erin (Cynthia Watros). ``She has that Irish
temper,'' Titus says. ``Of course, she's Northern Irish so we don't
fight, she just puts a bomb in my car.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third episode, when Titus and Erin fight and say vicious
things to each other, he realizes that maybe he doesn't want to be
happy. This idea about the scars of dysfunction gives ``Titus'' a
chance to cross the line between sitcom and drama, but the episode
is psychologically astute without being funny or emotional.
</P>
<P>
   At least ``Titus'' is taking a creative chance, though, and this
season even a failed risk can be revealing. Like many other shows,
``The Beat'' has a Web site (www.thebeattv.com), a creatively
ambitious one that presents a prequel to the series, showing Mike
and Zane during their academy days. The visuals are stop-motion
jerky. Dialogue that might be amusing on screen sounds lame here.
(``What's in sauerkraut, Mike?'') The important thing about the Web
site is that it exists. And as with all these networks' gimmicks,
what looks like a stunt today may actually be pointing to a
different future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1714EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
