<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-OSCARS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-19 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MARKETERS STILL FLOCK TO ACADEMY AWARDS BROADCAST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mich.)  (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 72nd annual Academy Awards show is looking a lot like a
Super Sunday, and not just because that's the day the ceremony is
now held.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar presentation on ABC has traditionally been the second
biggest day of the year for advertising, trailing only the Super
Bowl. This year, though, that gridiron-style hoopla and hyperbole
has permeated the broadcast to the point where the network ought to
bill it as ``Oscar Bowl LXXII.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason? There is still no end in sight to the strong demand
for commercial time among marketers _ whether dot-com or not-com _
which has intensified their need to break through the clutter. One
popular tactic is to sponsor so-called marquee programming like the
Academy Awards, which draws large audiences even in an era of
fragmented viewing patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our belief is that high-visibility events, from the Oscars to
the MTV Awards to the World Series, are the best way to keep our
brand top of mind,'' said Dawn Hudson, senior vice president for
strategy and marketing at the Pepsi-Cola Co. in Purchase, N.Y., a
unit of Pepsico Inc. returning for a second straight year as the
sole beverage advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleased with the ratings and the focus and attention
our brand got'' in 1999, said Hudson, who is deciding this week
which new ``joy of cola'' spots for Pepsi-Cola by BBDO New York _
part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group _ will fill
the three minutes of time the company bought.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Oscar ratings fluctuate like the hemlines of the
dresses worn by the nominees for Best Actress. The numbers rose in
1998, when viewers tuned in to watch ``Titanic'' win 11 awards,
then fell last year for the longest show ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many years do you get a `Titanic?''' asked Marv Goldsmith,
president for sales and marketing at the ABC Television Network in
New York, part of the ABC unit of the Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even in the weak years,'' he added, ``it's still the
second-highest rated show'' behind the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That perspective was echoed by one of the longest-running Oscar
sponsors, Eastman Kodak, an advertiser from 1965 to 1969 and then
again from 1985 through this year, when the company will unspool
three 30-second commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ratings go up and ratings go down, but year in and year out
it's a terrific advertising showcase,'' said Dave Hardie, general
manager and vice president for marketing at the Kodak consumer
imaging division in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an annual decision for us to renew from year to year,''
he added, ``but we envision being part of the Oscars going
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC, in a robust market, was able to sell a 30-second spot
during the program, which begins at 8:30 p.m. EST on Sunday, for a
record average of $1.3 million. That's 30 percent higher than the
previous record of $1 million set only a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers besides Kodak and Pepsico include blue-chip names like
AT&AMP;T, American Express, Gap, General Motors, McDonald's, Merrill
Lynch, Motorola, Charles Schwab, Sony and Sun Microsystems. One
longtime sponsor, Revlon, the troubled cosmetics marketer, is
reducing its presence, to two spots from nine.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is not charging as much as it did for Super Bowl XXXIV in
January, when a 30-second spot went for an average of $2.2 million.
But with 48 30-second time slots scheduled during the show, the
total revenue is expected to top $62 million _ more than what the
Super Bowl brought in as recently as 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the entertainment Super Bowl, if you will,'' said Scott
Parks, vice president for advertising development at Blockbuster
Inc. in Dallas, a unit of Viacom Inc. that will advertise during
the program for the first time with two spots by Doner in
Southfield, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our commercials were created for the broadcast,'' he added,
``to celebrate the role that movies play in our lives.'' The spots
feature Carly Simon singing as baby pictures of stars like Lauren
Bacall, Whoopi Goldberg, Walter Matthau and Elizabeth Taylor appear
on screen.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions by Blockbuster and Pepsi-Cola to produce
commercials that will make their debuts during the show are
indicative of another way in which the Academy Awards program's
resemblance to the Super Bowl is growing. Other advertisers are
also asking their agencies to create Super Sunday-type spots
stuffed with stars, special effects and surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to kick off our new campaign with a bang,'' said
Martin Homlish, executive vice president and chief marketing
officer at SAP in New York, the software maker that is another
first-time Oscar advertiser. ``And the Academy Awards is such a
powerful venue.''
</P>
<P>
   The SAP agency, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide in New York, part of
the WPP Group, created a 90-second spot featuring the golfer Gary
Player and his careless but ingenious caddy. The commercial will
introduce the theme ``My SAP.com. You can. It does.''
</P>
<P>
   SAP is also running a 30-second spot during the ``Oscar Preview
Show,'' which begins 30 minutes before the awards presentation.
That too is like the Super Bowl in that ABC is capitalizing on the
robust demand by offering advertisers the option of buying
(cheaper) time in related programs.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities begin on Friday, with a special version of ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' with movie- and Oscar-themed questions.
The Sunday lineup is composed of the annual Barbara Walters
celebrity interview special, the preview program, then the main
event.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the Super Bowl, all that pre-game _ er, pre-show _
programming provides opportunities for advertisers that could not
or would not buy time during the primary program.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Mastercard International cannot appear during the
Academy Awards because American Express is the exclusive advertiser
in the credit card category. So Mastercard and its agency,
McCann-Erickson New York, will run a new commercial in their
``Priceless'' campaign, with a movie theme, during the Walters
program. The spot will also appear in local breaks during the Oscar
show on ABC stations in Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do the next best thing,'' said Larry Flanagan,
senior vice president for marketing at Mastercard in Purchase.
``We'll get some good exposure.'' McCann is part of McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising, a unit of the McCann-Erickson World Group,
owned by the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up and the Academy Awards and the ancillary shows
will help ABC set a record for first quarter ad revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the figures and go `Holy mackerel,''' Goldsmith
said. ``But I'm in sales. No matter how you do, they say `Can't you
do better?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
