<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EUROPE-ART-FAIR-955(2     03-19 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ART-FAIR-955(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTION HULLABALOO REVERBERATES AT ART FAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAASTRICHT, Netherlands _ When the doors to the European Fine
Art Fair opened on Friday afternoon, the 198 exhibitors were all
smiles, eager to talk about the prized offerings they were placing
before some 8,200 visitors who poured into the convention center
where the fair is held every March.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the polite banter, the atmosphere at this, the
world's largest art fair, was politically charged. Talk of the
unfolding federal antitrust investigation of auction houses in New
York was everywhere, and with it speculation about the increase
that the biggest of the houses, Sotheby's and Christie's, plan to
charge buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The effect all this will have on dealers is uncertain. The
negative publicity that Sotheby's and Christie's have been getting
is making the dealers look good, they say. Some already report that
they are being offered more goods from collectors who once relied
on auctions to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are a little uncertain about selling at auction until
things get sorted out,'' said Timothy Bathurst, a director of
Artemis Fine Arts, a London gallery that specializes in old-master
and 19th-century paintings. ``In some cases we're being offered
things for sale that Sotheby's or Christie's would have normally
gotten.''
</P>
<P>
   But the situation is double-edged. Among the many dealers who
have traditionally relied heavily on buying their stock at auction
there is concern that they will not be able to buy as much, because
the expensive commissions these auction houses are charging _ as
much as 20 percent on the first $50,000 _ will eat too deeply into
their profits.
</P>
<P>
   There is also much speculation about the effects the
investigation will have on the spring fine-art sales, which are
held in New York every May. While the dealers here are secretly
hoping to benefit, officials at Sotheby's and Christie's maintain
that the May sales this year will remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are no single big estates like a Whitney or a
Ganz, in terms of monetary value our main impressionist and
postimpressionist sale will be as big as it has been the last few
seasons,'' said Franck Giraud, head of Christie's impressionist and
postimpressionist art department worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Sotheby's estimate that their impressionist and
modern art sale this May will be impressive too, with $100 million
to $135 million worth of art for sale.
</P>
<P>
   In today's strong economy, collectors are so hungry for good
material they will buy wherever the goods are. ``No dealer is
publicly gloating about all that's going on,'' said Nicholas Hall,
who runs the New York branch of Hall &AMP; Knight. The gallery, which
also has a branch in London, specializes in old-master paintings.
``People are going to continue to buy art regardless of the
behavior of the auction houses,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the estimated 70,000 people who will have visited the
fair by the time it ends on March 26 are serious buyers. Within the
first 24 hours dealers were reporting brisk business.
</P>
<P>
   While the fair has always attracted serious collectors because
of the quality of its goods, this year's art, antiques and
antiquities are particularly impressive. There is a staggering
selection of every collecting category from old masters to
textiles, jewelry and contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Since it began 26 years ago, the fair has been known as the most
comprehensive place to see old-master paintings. It still is.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best is an early still life at Haboldt &AMP; Co., a
gallery with branches in Paris and New York. Its title is more or
less its full description: ``Figs on a Tazza With Vine Leaves, a
Basket of Grapes, Roses, Irises in a Glass Vase With Cherries,
Pears, Plums, Cob Nuts, Peaches and Other Fruit on a Draped Table
with Butterflies.'' It was done circa 1590-1600 by an artist known
only as the Master of the Hartford Still Life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the beginning of still-life painting as we know it,''
said Bob Haboldt, the gallery's owner. ``Perhaps the inspiration
came from Caravaggio, perhaps the artist had met Bruegel the Elder,
but it's a complete invention. It comes without any baggage of art
history.''
</P>
<P>
   On a table draped with a white cloth is a well-balanced
composition of fruits and flowers that are so alive on the canvas
that they almost seem to be moving. Haboldt bought the painting in
a small auction in Italy earlier this year. A slightly smaller and
later version is in the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Another rare painting that is attracting interest hangs in Jack
Kilgore's booth. The painting, ``Madonna With Child and Angels,''
circa 1607 by the Dutch master Hendrick Goltzius, features the
Virgin clad in a bright pink dress gazing down at the child, with
angels hovering in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unlined and signed on both the back and the front,'' said
Kilgore, who runs a gallery in New York. ``Goltzius was a graphic
designer who didn't start painting until 1600 and he died in 1617,
so there are only about 40 paintings by him.'' Kilgore said he
discovered the painting in a German collection.
</P>
<P>
   While the best works here tend to come from private collections,
the fair always features many paintings bought in January at the
important old-master paintings sales at Sotheby's and Christie's in
New York. Dealers buy them, have them cleaned and restored in time
for the fair and then mark them up for considerably more than they
paid for them.
</P>
<P>
   The London dealer Richard Green, for example, has a breathtaking
Canaletto from the mid-1730s, ``The Grand Canal, Venice, Looking
East From Campo di San Vio.'' He bought it at Christie's in January
for $6.6 million. He is asking $9.5 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   French &AMP; Co. also has its share of recent auction purchases. A
painting by Giovanni Segantini, ``Springtime in the Alps,'' for
which the gallery's chairman, Martin Zimet, paid $9.5 million at
Christie's in November, is now for sale at $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   Zimet is also selling Arcimboldo's ``Reversible Anthropomorphic
Portrait of a Man Composed of Fruit,'' which is considered an
ironic portrait of Emperor Rudolph II. His price is $7.5 million.
He paid just under $1.5 million for it at Sotheby's two months ago.
``Sotheby's called it an Arcimboldo but we have done extensive
research on the painting,'' Zimet said.
</P>
<P>
   Every year the fair's section of modern and contemporary art
gets stronger. Leslie Waddington, a London dealer who has been the
chairman of the event's painting's department, has been bringing in
more top dealers from Europe and New York. ``As word is getting
out, more modern collectors have started coming here,'' he said.
``They aren't people interested in icon-buying, they're educated
collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   On opening day, Waddington said, he had sold a painting by Agnes
Martin, one by Van Dongen and another by Dali.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture, decorative objects and antiquities were also getting
lavish attention at this year's fair. Among the rarest treasures is
a tapestry based on a 12th-century legend of the life of St. Anne,
dated 1527, which is being shown at the Rudigier Alte Kunst, a
gallery in Munich, Germany. ``There are only 11 tapestries of this
kind,'' said Gertrude Rudigier, who added that she found it in a
private collection in southern Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bowman, a London dealer, discovered ``Vases of the
Titans,'' a pair of terra-cotta vases by Rodin, at a chateau in
France. The vases, which are signed by A. Carrier Belleuse, the
owner of the workshop where Rodin was working around 1879, come
from the collection of Henri Ardant, who owned the Ardant porcelain
factory in France.
</P>
<P>
   Each vase is held up by four crouching and intricately carved
titans and has a Greek key pattern at the top. Similar examples are
in the collections of the Rodin Museum in Paris and the Maryhill
Museum of Fine Arts in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowds poured in and out of Bowman's booth, he said he
was having his best fair ever. ``There are several factors that are
making this a success,'' he said. ``People are thinking the stock
market could crash, and it's a good time to buy art. At the same
time, the public is beginning to realize that the auction houses
are less concerned with expertise and more with making their
commissions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
