<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1681 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DIVERSITY-ESSAY-2TAKE     03-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIVERSITY-ESSAY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL OF HUMANKIND ARE STRANGERS IN A STRANGE LAND
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I have contempt for those books,'' said a friend when I tried
to describe my mixed responses to photography books that try to
counter passive ignorance or battle active prejudice by celebrating
social diversity and emotional complexity. You know the kind I
mean. The ``those who have made significant contributions to their
people'' books. The books that focus on the rituals that make
``us'' just like everybody else. And those that glorify the
intimate, even exclusionary ties that bind a group: mothers and
daughters, say; the Jews of the Lower East Side; the Cherokee
people.
</P>
<P>
   Dances, weddings, funerals and childbirth always signal the
universal, something we can all understand. Certain kinds of work
photos signal a history of injustice and endurance that it is hoped
we all understand: a middle-aged black woman standing on a bale of
cotton looking down at her palm without expression as her white
boss counts a coin into it. Or a Mexican woman in a Texas factory,
wearing a Gap T-shirt and sewing an American flag. (Is she treated
like an American citizen when she gets off work, we wonder.)
</P>
<P>
   Certain photographs are surprising because in the social (as
opposed to the religious) realm we rarely believe or even think
about what we do not see. And because most of the American news
media have generally defined social reality (apart from ``special
interest'' stories) as WASP (in appearance at least), one is often
reduced to embarrassingly childlike exclamations like, ``Gosh!
Black, Japanese and Korean women serving in the Armed Forces during
World War II!'' Do such images matter? How can they not, given our
nation's continuing obsession with that war and the reverence for
its veterans?
</P>
<P>
   I've been studying three books in particular: ``Americanos:
Latino Life in the United States'' (Little, Brown), ``The Face of
Our Past: Images of Black Women From Colonial America to the
Present'' (Indiana University Press) and ``Shades of L.A.: Pictures
From Ethnic Family Albums'' (New Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``Americanos'' is meant to educate and disarm hostile or
suspicious Anglo readers while praising and reassuring Latino
readers. The section ``Latino Contributions'' begins, ``Far from
representing a threat to society, the Latino presence is
strengthening the basic institutions of society: the family, work
and education.'' And on the page opposite we see the photo of the
woman sewing the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction Carlos Fuentes writes: ``We descend from all
the islands naming themselves twice or thrice, Indian and Spanish
and African, in the waters of the Caribbees. We have come down from
the mountains in the great backbone of the Americas, the vast
ranges stretching from the Rockies to the Sierra Madre to the Andes
to the archipelagos, falling off like cold beautiful grapes at the
foot of the continent, Chile, Argentina ... ''
</P>
<P>
   The text is in English and Spanish, which is exactly right. The
bifurcated audience is problematic. How do you talk to people you
see as family while simultaneously explaining them to strangers?
The language moves uneasily between exhortation, uplift and
instruction, between sophistication and condescension. That is the
tone employed for a mainstream audience, to assuage their sense
that a group is alien or deviant.
</P>
<P>
   The March 20 issue of Newsweek was a perfect example, with its
special report ``Gay Today: How the battle for acceptance has moved
to schools, churches, marriages and the workplace.'' The cover
photograph featured five gay people: a man in uniform (a reservist
and state representative), a policewoman, a woman in the ministry
and two men (one black and one white) in suits, who were, it turned
out, a teacher and a physician.
</P>
<P>
   Easy to throw up one's hands and ask why the struggle for
tolerance seems always to involve reinventing the wheel. This is
the visual equivalent of those song epics that preached tolerance
and minority-group virtue in the 1940s: ``Ballad for Americans,''
performed by Paul Robeson, and ``The House I Live In,'' made famous
by Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   But when we sang and declaimed ``Ballad for Americans'' in my
grade school music class, I was moved and, yes, grateful. It
mattered that the prejudice my parents were doing their best to
shield me from could be criticized, however piously, out loud. One
can wish fervently that conversion music, speech and photography
were fresher and subtler. But they matter. Not to flaming bigots.
(It may inflame them more, as in ``How dare these people look and
act as normal as we do?'') But they matter to those whose beliefs
can shift when their collection of stereotypes is clearly out of
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Face of Our Past'' and ``Shades of L.A.'' are aimed less
at outsiders and more at the people or descendants of those
photographed. Not that one doesn't get some of the same shocks.
``What variety, what range,'' you find yourself saying when you
thought you had been educating yourself very well for some time
about your race, gender or ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But human beings are literal creatures. If society doesn't
provide visual evidence of one's existence in all its variety, or
if one doesn't work constantly to supply the lack, the mind's eye
will blur or close.
</P>
<P>
   The common stock of American imagery just doesn't include these
photographs of young black women in Gibson Girl hairdos and bathing
costumes, or of a black girl no more than 10 playing golf in a
sandlot with a club made from a stick. The year is 1905 and she
wears scuffed high-button shoes. Or young Indians dancing together
in the kinds of cowboy and cowgirl outfits that one used to see on
Roy Rogers and Dale Evans. (They were students at the Sherman
Institute in Los Angeles, a boarding school whose policy was
thorough-going assimilation). Or a room filled with elegant couples
attending the Los Angeles Chinese Tennis Club Dinner Dance of 1934.
Or a trio of pretty Korean women in 1931, posing in the sand
bathing-beauty-style, and looking as if they should be plucked from
Venice Beach and taken, along with their handsome escorts, straight
to a Hollywood studio.
</P>
<P>
   Was it George Eliot who found something melancholy about the
human gift for metaphor, since it meant we could only describe a
thing by calling it something else? There is something just as sad
about all our talk of diversity, pluralism and deconstructing
otherness. ``See the margins of the world,'' Fuentes writes in
``Americanos,'' ``where those who are different from us are waiting
to demonstrate that they are as human as we.'' His sentence is,
``Recognize yourselves in he or she who are not like you or me.''
But will we ever see the ``he or she'' he invokes as fully human
without first having to recognize ourselves in them?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1739EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0077 </DOCNO>
