<SLUG> BC-RINGLING-CIRCUS-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG MODERN MARVELS, THE CIRCUS IS STILL A GREAT ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mingling the traditional and the technological with
modern spectacle and time-tested skills at Madison Square Garden,
the Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus is marching,
dancing, swinging, soaring, pirouetting, plodding, prat-falling and
blasting off into its third century of lavish entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In a world made smaller each day by electronic miracles, the
circus remains a reminder of an era when the exotic _ people,
performers, animals _ retained the power to evoke innocent awe and
childish wonder.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, recognizing that times and tastes do not stand
rooted, this Feld Entertainment presentation, with its colorful
costumes, up-to-the-minute lighting, swirling smoke and pulsing,
upbeat music, is a fast-moving combination of generous resort-style
song and dance and old-fashioned acts in modern trappings.
</P>
<P>
   If the 130th edition of the Greatest Show on Earth boasts no
single side-splitting clown or daredevil act capable of reducing
even jaded joyseekers to bated breath, it remains a big, bright,
something-for-everyone show.
</P>
<P>
   Among this year's noteworthy attractions are Sara, the tall,
blond, 22-year-old circus veteran who cuddles and controls a
cageful of handsome tigers, and the Quiros, costumed in top hats,
white ties and tails, who evoke the lithe grace of Fred Astaire
while dancing, jumping rope, dueling with canes, riding bicycles,
forming pyramids and otherwise risking their necks on two levels of
high wire.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to risking necks, Kanat Chalabayev's Congress of
Rough Riders, an equestrian troupe assembled from components of the
former Soviet Union, perform feats of horsemanship, like hanging
upside down from fast-moving steeds; and the Flying Tabareses, a
double trapeze act with two sets of flyers, soar and somersault
across the upper reaches of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty in pink, the 18-woman Jinan Bicycle Gymnasts perform
synchronized pedaling and provide a wow finish when about a dozen
form a pyramid aboard a single bike.
</P>
<P>
   Michu the midget is back, with Jon Weiss, who not only takes a
couple of trips out of a cannon's mouth but also balances a buzzing
chain saw on his chin. And there are also trampoline artists,
capering horses and zebras, and the elephants, young and old, who
parade and perform.
</P>
<P>
   The Ringling Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus is back in
town, all dressed up and on the move into a new millennium.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   RINGLING BROTHERS AND BARNUM &AMP; BAILEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Kenneth Feld; director and staging composition, Phil
McKinley; vice president, production and talent, Tim Holst;
costumes by Scott Lane; production designer, Eduardo Sicangco;
composer, Michael Starobin; lyricist, Glenn Slater; lighting by
LeRoy Bennett; music director, David Killinger; choreographer and
assistant director, Tony Stevens; lighting director, Wally Lees;
associate production designer, Bradley Mayer; associate costume
designer, Dawna Oak; production and talent coordinator, Gueorgui
Pastujov. Presented by Feld Entertainment. At Madison Square
Garden.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Sara and the tigers; the Quiros, Anton Beliakov, Michu,
Jon Weiss; Congress of Rough Riders; the Giant Bike Troupe; Flying
Tabares; Michael James McGowan; the Ayala Sisters; Marinelli
Trampoline; Hans Ludwig; Jinan Bicycle Gymnasts; Delta Double
Swing; Yankovi Swing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
