<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1694 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GLADWELL-PROFILE-MEDI     03-19 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADWELL-PROFILE-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE NEW YORKER'S MALCOLM GLADWELL, THE WEB IS HIS PETRI DISH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Malcolm Gladwell is a 36-year-old social recluse (by
his own description) who has in the last four years written for The
New Yorker about subjects as various as how postwar American
history has been influenced by hair dye, why some people seem to
know everyone, how crime rates dropped in New York City and why the
Aaron Spelling series ``Melrose Place'' was so popular with viewers
in their 30s (they were probably in a state of arrested
adolescence).
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Gladwell published his first book, ``The
Tipping Point: How Little Things Can Make a Big Difference''
(Little, Brown), a study of how fads become fads. The 279-page book
_ for which Gladwell was paid an advance of $1.5 million, or about
$5,376 a page _ draws from Gladwell's expertise as a science
reporter, his interest in pop anthropology and his affinity for
technology.
</P>
<P>
   And true to his reputation as a technology oriented, forward
thinking kind of guy, Gladwell is the only staff writer at The New
Yorker who maintains a personal and fully stocked Web site,
complete with all his articles for The New Yorker archived and
indexed. (He owns the rights to his articles; The New Yorker does
not.) The site, Gladwell.com, has received 85,000 hits so far this
month.
</P>
<P>
   But Gladwell.com is not a promotional device, Gladwell said. The
site has excerpts from ``The Tipping Point,'' but his book is not
available through the site. Gladwell said he started Gladwell.com
more out of a sense of literary civitas than marketing opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have run into some people who think it is arrogant to have
your own Web site,'' he said. ``But it's a pain to fax people your
articles all the time, which is the main reason I have the Web
site. My view is that it is not any different from publishing a
collection of your articles in book form. Certainly charging for
stuff that's already been published seems slightly more arrogant
than making it available on the Web site for free.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest advantage of Gladwell.com, Gladwell said, is
response from visitors to the site, who e-mail their comments and
ideas to Gladwell, and also unwittingly offer themselves up as a
kind of human petri dish for Gladwell's study.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be surprised at what you learn,'' Gladwell said. ``It's
not this selfless exercise. An incredible number of my ideas come
from incredibly random conversations I have. In fact, all of them
do. So the more random conversations the better, and these are all
small, random conversations.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web site, he is able to note which articles are most
popular and which are least read _ a kind of free market survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see which pieces intrigue people's imagination and
which pieces clearly are not moving anyone's imagination,''
Gladwell said. ``The least clicked-on is some wonky, really boring
piece I once wrote about innovation,'' he said. The most clicked-on
article, he said, is ``Six Degrees of Lois Weisberg,'' a 1999
article about a Chicago woman who for no readily discernible reason
has an enormous network of interconnected friends around the world.
(She is the mother of one of Gladwell's close friends, Jacob
Weisberg, a political correspondent for the online magazine Slate.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of connectors in my life,'' Gladwell said,
referring to his term for people who appear to know a lot of
people. ``But I am not a connector. I have a relatively small
circle of friends. I'm not social at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladwell has the asocial, solitary air of an only child, but he
has two brothers: one is a music teacher and the other, he said,
``works in processed chicken.'' Born in England and raised in
Canada, he was trained as a science writer and worked as a reporter
at The Washington Post until Tina Brown hired him at The New Yorker
in 1996. His father is English, and his mother is Jamaican _ he
said that she is related to Gen. Colin Powell _ and the issue of
race has informed Gladwell's writing. In The Washington Post in
1996, for example, he reviewed an issue of The New Yorker on race,
noting that his admiration for the issue had nothing to do with his
skin color, ``which is white,'' he wrote. Three years later, in an
article in The New Yorker about athletic ability and race, Gladwell
wrote of running for his high school track team and whether his
``Africanness'' intimidated any of his track colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when his parents met in college in England in the
1950s, race was an issue; his mother even wrote a book, ``Brown
Face, Big Master,'' about her experiences as a black woman in
Jamaica and England. But race is no longer a preoccupation for the
family, Gladwell said, and he no longer considers race a strong
theme in his writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I consider myself,'' Gladwell said. ``It's
too complex. There are too many ways to define yourself, and it's
not a way I have chosen to define myself anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   On his Web site, Gladwell has chosen one defining picture of
himself. In the photograph, he is 5 years old and is wearing a
bathrobe that looks like a sort of Roman toga and carrying the lid
of a garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my shield,'' he said. ``I thought the idea of doing
battle with the world seemed appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladwell's book has not made a significant mark on best-seller
lists, a fact that Gladwell acknowledged left the door open for
irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave yourself open for an incredible amount of
criticism,'' he said, ``when you write a book called `The Tipping
Point,' and it doesn't tip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
