<P>
   This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   SEX-CRIMES (New York) _ The Port Authority bus terminal in New
York City, once a place where vulnerable children were lured into
prostitution, has seen a big drop in sex crimes, thanks to the
cleanup of the Times Square area and aggressive police enforcement.
By Andrea McDaniels. (980 words)
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIC-PETS (New York) _ Organic foods, aromatherapy,
nutritional supplements and massage. Sound good? How about for your
pet? Alternatives to pet food made with byproducts and chemicals,
as well as more holistic ways to treat the family pet, are on the
upswing. By Jean Lee Scheidnes. (1050 words)
</P>
<P>
   HIP-OPERA (New York) _ Opera is showing up in beer commercials,
in bars and even on the MTV Awards. And the hip crowd is
responding, attending more performances and embracing the music
many younger people used to think of as old-fashioned. By Abby
Tegnelia. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-CENTER (New York) _ Slam poetry, music from klezmer to
techno-rock and Yiddish classes are among the attractions at Makor,
a new Jewish cultural center in New York that aims not at the
religious, but at those who merely want a place to mingle, meet and
learn. By Nathan Hegedus. (880 words)
</P>
<P>
   HARLEM-RENAISSANCE (New York) _ Old Navy, Starbucks, even Disney
are going to Harlem, in the latest attempt to revitalize an area
with a checkered past. This time, many residents and even outsiders
are embracing the change. By Daisy Nguyen. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   POLIO-SYNDROME (New York) _ Many people who survived the polio
epidemic of the 1950s are discovering a new nightmare _ post-polio
syndrome, which can strike without warning and again interrupt or
even end the lives of those who thought that had conquered the
disease. By Alexa Jaworski. (1,000 words)
</P>
<P>
   PLANETARIUM-PLUTO (New York) _ Visitors to the new Hayden
Planetarium in New York City are surprised to find that Pluto is
not among the giant mobile depicting the planets of our solar
system. And by leaving it out, astronomers at the planetarium are
rekindling an old argument: just what makes a planet a planet,
anyway? By Dan Zehr. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   LIVE-FUNERALS (New York) _ The Internet, already swarming with
aquarium-cams, traffic-cams and this-is-my-room-cams, is starting
to attract a new kind of live event _ funerals. While the numbers
are still small, some funeral home owners say Webcasting a funeral
helps those who can't be there celebrate the life of the dearly
departed from afar. By Kate Dawson. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   STREET-NEWS (New York) _ Newspapers that benefit the homeless,
through offering them a voice as well as income from selling them
on the street, are increasing in number and reach. And the
longest-running editor of Street News in New York, which calls
itself the oldest active homeless paper in the nation, says he has
a mission _ to keep that voice alive. By William Siss. (975 words)
</P>
