<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SEX-CRIMES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX CRIMES DROP IN REVAMPED PORT AUTHORITY BUS STATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Andrea McDaniels is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By ANDREA McDANIELS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK  &UR; _ &LR;  A shabbily dressed 12-year-old boy sits on a
plastic bag for hours in the bus departure area at Port Authority
bus station, nodding off to the piped-in music. A 14-year-old girl
stands starry-eyed outside the massive building on 41st Street,
marveling at the neon lights.
</P>
<P>
   These are the types of children that social workers at the Youth
Service Unit of the station label as in ``danger of exploitation.''
In other words, easy prey for a pimp or pedophile looking for a
victim among the runaways and delinquents who end up in the bus
station, fleeing abusive parents or just skipping school.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids come here and they want to trust whoever comes
along. Some kids are easy prey,'' says Rachel Forsyth, director of
crisis services at Covenant House, a nearby shelter for homeless
teens.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the youngsters were in considerable danger. In
1995, for example, police had to deal with some 60 sex offenses
against children in the bus station, some from repeat offenders,
says Sgt. Bernard Poggioli, director of the Youth Services Unit.
</P>
<P>
   But all that has changed. Last year, the Youth Services Unit
helped 286 runaways _ and arrested just five sex offenders. ``Sex
crimes at Port Authority have gone down about 90 percent in the
past five years,'' Poggioli says. ``We're less overrun with
undesirable types. Now we can concentrate on the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Poggioli credits the drastic drop in these types of crimes to
the efforts to revamp the bus station and clean up Times Square in
general. Over the past decade, neighborhood groups such as the
Times Square Business Improvement District and the Square's new
owners, including Disney Corp., have poured millions of dollars
into changing its image so that it attracts a more wholesome crowd.
Most of the peep shows and porno houses have been closed and
replaced with superstores and new theaters to bring in sightseers
and shoppers. Local businesses convinced the city to reopen the
Midtown Community Court to deal exclusively with arrests in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention of the improvement of Times Square was to make
it safe again,'' says Brendan Sexton, president of the Times Square
Business Improvement District. ``It used to be regarded as an
entertainment district with cabaret, first-run movie houses and an
opera, but it became decrepit, abused and scary. Now we've returned
it to the people of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Port Authority increased security, improved
lighting and tightened management at the bus station, measures that
helped usher in a 36 percent drop in crime, from 2,295 incidents in
1997 to 1,475 last year, according to Port Authority Spokesman Alan
Hicks. The drop is even greater from previous years, police say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids were being pimped right out of the hotels around here,
even out of Covenant House,'' Poggioli said. (Covenant House
officials confirm that practice occurred.)
</P>
<P>
   People were using the pay phones to pimp children, telling a
child, for example, to talk to ``that man over there'' on the
phone, pointing to a client or pimp on another pay phone within
sight. It got so bad that about five years ago, Port Authority
police mounted a sting operation, equipping children with wires and
setting up video cameras to catch pimps in the act of recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic has since installed phones that do not accept
incoming calls. The station has also changed the technology on its
emergency doors so that they stay locked until an emergency arises.
Before this, homeless people and drug addicts have been living in
the stairwells and pedophiles would lure children into them for
sexual acts. ``You wouldn't believe some of the stuff that went on
here,'' Poggioli says. ``One girl told us she conceived her child
in the stairwell and gave birth to it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth Services also stepped up preventive measures. Plainclothes
police officers approach unaccompanied children and ask them for
identification and a bus ticket to show their destination. If the
child is with an adult, the adult must prove he is the parent or
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   If the officer finds the situation suspicious, he brings the
child to a social worker in the back office, who arranges for the
child to be sent home or put in a shelter. The adult may be charged
with solicitation or contributing to the delinquency of a minor.
</P>
<P>
   Certain situations set off alarm bells for officers. ``If you
saw a 12-year-old girl making out with a 38-year-old man, wouldn't
it raise your suspicions?'' asks Edwin Rodriguez, one of the three
police officers assigned to the Youth Services Unit.
</P>
<P>
   An adult who is spotted several times in the bus loading area
without a ticket is also questioned, Poggioli says. ``If the guy
shows up three, four times without getting on a bus, we know he's
probably got no legitimate reason to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   The perpetrators of sex crimes at the bus station don't fit a
narrow profile. Movie stars, priests and drug addicts are equally
represented. One man from New Jersey was paying children $40 for a
sexual act and $150 if they recruited another child, Poggioli said.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Times Square has gotten rid of most of its drug
addicts and prostitutes, it's easier to spot sexual predators among
the crowds at the bus station, police say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, there were so many undesirables in the area, one
more didn't matter,'' says Poggioli. ``But if you see a person in
here, walking around a talking to kids, they stand out like sore
thumbs. Most of our perps have either died, moved someplace else or
they're locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Poggioli cautions, such crimes haven't gone away _ just
underground.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, child molesters are soliciting underage sex
through Internet chat groups, away from the eyes of the police.
</P>
<P>
   Except when the kids arrange to meet the molester at the bus
station. In those cases, says Poggioli, ``usually, we get to them
first.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1815EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-ORGANIC-PETS &LR;      03-19 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ORGANIC-PETS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `NATURAL' MOVEMENT REACHES PET STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Jean Lee Scheidnes is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By JEAN LEE SCHEIDNES   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time, not too long ago, when you were a
fine pet owner as long as you fed your pet table scraps or chow,
took it to the vet when necessary, and maybe bought a latex toy for
it to chew on.
</P>
<P>
   Today, you would border on negligence.
</P>
<P>
   The pet owner of today, according to a growing number of
health-conscious animal lovers, should provide organic food,
nutritional supplements, interactive toys and videos, and holistic
remedies such as acupuncture, massage and aromatherapy. Over the
past 15 years or so, an entire industry has sprung up to supply
organic nutrition and holistic care to pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supermarket pet food is full of crap,'' says Norma Otero, the
manager at Whiskers Holistic Pet Care, a 13-year-old store in the
East Village. ``Would you want to eat road kill and factory
byproducts? Why would you give that to your pet? Even a human can
eat my food.'' Whiskers sells organic, all-natural pet foods. The
list of ingredients on any package of food reads like a regular
grocery list: chicken, corn, carrots ... There are no chemical
ingredients ending in ``-ide'' or ``-ate,'' which appear frequently
on most of the lists on most processed pet foods.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding a pet those processed foods all the time ``is like
giving your kid Trix versus Grape Nuts or Cheerios,'' says Amy
Shapiro, owner of two natural pet stores, the eight-year-old
Barking Zoo in Chelsea and the newly opened Another Barking Zoo in
Tribeca.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for natural pets disagree about premium brands
such as Iams and Hill's Science Diet. Barking Zoos carry them, but
Whiskers does not, because they are processed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do OK with that food,'' says Dr. Roger Valentine, a Los
Angeles veterinarian who specializes in cats. ``But when people
switch to those premium brands after having their cat on organic
food, the cats get dandruff and loose stools and hairballs and
things like that.'' But Valentine says there is not enough data to
say that cats on organic food are actually living longer.
</P>
<P>
   Lara Strazdin, manager of public relations for Iams Co., isn't
persuaded, either. ``We have not seen any studies that show organic
foods are better than non-organic,'' she says. ``If we did see
that, then honestly, we would switch.'' Iams is processed, but it
considers itself all-natural, because it has no artificial
preservatives, no color or flavor enhancers, and no salt or sugar.
Officials at Hill's Pet Nutrition, maker of Science Diet, did not
return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the conscientious pet owner has to consider much
more than food.
</P>
<P>
   Owners also have an array of pet vitamins and food supplements
to choose from, which aid digestion, improve the health of skin and
fur, repel pests and prevent urinary, kidney and liver problems.
There are special foods for pets with injuries, diabetes, allergies
or weak immune systems, and heart, kidney or gastrointestinal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been tremendous growth in the industry in the last
10-15 years,'' says Shapiro. ``So many people are inventing new
products and gadgets. More people are finding that the pet market
is a viable marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the success of this market is braced by the strong
economy. More Americans than ever can afford extras for their pets.
In addition, people have grown more knowledgeable and open to
healthy living and alternative medicine in general. But the biggest
boon to the pet industry may be the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net has done wonders,'' Shapiro says. As people have gone
online to research their own health and alternative medicines in
particular, pet owners have also educated themselves about pet-care
options on hundreds of informational Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Many pet stores now have online outlets, so for people who don't
live near a Whiskers or a Barking Zoo, natural pet supplies are
just several clicks away. But while the Internet has helped build
awareness and a customer base for natural pet supplies, some store
owners see a downside. Shapiro says she appreciates the added
business from her online customers, but worries that independent
pet stores are getting squeezed out by big online outlets such as
pets.com and petopia.com.
</P>
<P>
   The local stores have one important advantage. Pets and owners
can visit them on their walks. Inside, people can see how certain
products go over with their pets before buying. Aside from the
myriad food choices, there are organic bones and treats as an
alternative to rawhide, which Otero says is difficult to digest and
contains bleach and glue. There is a cat litter, World's Best, made
from 100 percent kernel corn, which is recommended because it is
flushable and the cat will digest it easily if it licks the litter
off its paws afterward. There are books and videos on alternative
pet therapies, such as acupuncture, Chinese and Western herbology,
massage, aromatherapy, color therapy and homeopathy.
</P>
<P>
   So how much will it cost you to become a natural pet owner? A
lot. A seven-pound bag of World's Best cat litter costs more than
twice as much as the more mainstream Fresh Step at the Barking
Zoos. A 13-ounce can of organic dog food costs up to $3.99 at
Whiskers, while a same-sized can of Friskies' Alpo costs 69 cents
at RiteAid.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, ``It may be more expensive, but your pet is
healthier and happier, and you'll spend less at the vet,'' says
Shapiro, who owns a greyhound.
</P>
<P>
   Customers agree. ``It's a big expense,'' admits Noel Canfield,
who has shopped for her seven cats at Whiskers ever since it
opened. She used to buy processed cat food, but after she lost a
cat to cancer, she started studying what was in the food and
switched to organic. ``It's been worth it because no one's been
really sick in my cat family,'' she said. ``It boosts their immune
system. I'm a nurse, and I feel like I'm being a good parent, if
you will.'' In addition, she says, organic food looks and smells
better.
</P>
<P>
   After all, money spent on pets is really spent on owners. People
see pets as benefits to their own health. Recent studies say pets
lower stress and blood pressure. Some hospitals are even using
pet-facilitated therapies.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are valuing animals more than ever, and want to take
care of them,'' says Canfield. ``I want them to be around as long
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
