<HEADLINE>
OPERA GETS HIP, APPEALS TO YOUNGER FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Abby Tegnelia is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By ABBY TEGNELIA   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On prime-time TV, beer-drinking young men sing opera
over pints of Guinness. Flip the channel, and a Perdue ad features
an opera soundtrack while a baking chicken rotates on a skewer.
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, the cast of the musical version of ``Aida''
performs song lyrics by pop icon Elton John. New York City
club-goers dance to pulsing house music in a recently opened club
named Aria, where the restrooms are labeled ``sopranos'' and
``tenors'' and the over-sized paintings and lush decor are
reminiscent of an opera house.
</P>
<P>
   The once-stodgy opera is showing up in some unusual places,
inundating audiences that are anything but the traditional
opera-going fans. And the trend is catching on. Opera ticket sales
are up, especially among young adults, and advertising firms say
their operatic commercials are selling products so successfully
that they're making more.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bowen, director of business development for Merkley,
Newman and Harty, a SoHo advertising firm, recently finished
producing a commercial for the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association. It features horses running past the finish line as an
opera soundtrack accents the cheers and heartbreak of the fans. The
campaign is geared toward men 25-55, even though the median age for
opera goers is 44, and more women than men are fans, according to
the National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising is always looking for something to cut through the
clutter in both sight and sound,'' Bowen said. ``Opera is unusual
enough and still approachable, and it makes people look up. It's
the perfect counterpoint to real world action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The opera is sheer spectacle and emotion,'' said Tom Gulick,
who in January initiated the Silicon Valley Initiative to market
opera to young professionals for the San Francisco Opera. ``It's
fascinating, entertaining, multimedia, and it gets you away from
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Opera companies across the country have groups that organize
events to draw in young professionals to the opera. The number of
18- to 24-year-olds attending opera performances in the U.S.
increased by 18 percent between 1982 and 1992, and a third of the
U.S. opera audience is under 35, according to the National
Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   At the Michigan Opera Theatre in Detroit, the Young
Professionals throw opera theme parties where members can win
``weekend fun'' prize packages that include dinner, hotel,
transportation and, of course, a performance. At the San Francisco
Opera, the Bravo Club hosts postopera parties where members dance
till dawn. Many Bravo Club members heard about the Opera via its
Web site, which has generated $1.5 million in ticket sales, more
than 50 percent from first-time ticket buyers whose average age was
35.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying very hard to make opera the hip thing to try
out,'' said Elizabeth Connell, public relations director for the
San Francisco Opera. ``We all know fads come and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's wealthy 20- and 30-somethings enjoy the feeling of
luxury that a night at the opera offers, she said. ``It's a great
date,'' Connell said. ``It's fun to get in your party dress and
have a glass of Champagne during intermission.''
</P>
<P>
   Opera attendance has been rising steadily since 1982. The three
tenors, Placido Domingo, Jose Carreras and Luciano Pavarotti, have
brought opera to hundreds of thousands of fans through TV
performances and recordings of a ``lighter'' repertoire than
classic opera. Andrea Bocelli, an Italian opera sensation who has
had some pop music crossover hits, is touring North America this
spring. On April 5, he will perform at Atlanta's new Philips Arena.
The venue, designed with input from R.E.M.'s Mike Mills, has luxury
suites in one seating area, offering a unique ``opera house'' feel.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, MTV's Music Video Awards was presented at the Met.
The opening number for the live show featured opera music, while
the event's ad campaign used pop singer Britney Spears, 17, dressed
in a traditional ``Carmen'' costume.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Farley, a consultant for Ludgate Communications, saw the
modern opera ``Squonk'' for a friend's birthday and loved it. She
said she didn't realize until halfway through the performance that
it was an opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll feel like you're in a music video through the whole
thing,'' she said. ``I've never liked the opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's audience likes highly visual events such as these, said
Eleanor Dyer, the opera specialist for the National Endowment of
the Arts. So she's not surprised that the opera is now growing in
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opera has music, design, production, a good story line and
visual effects,'' she said. ``It's a heightened emotional
awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   Opera houses have added subtitles in the last 15 years to
translate the words to the music, which are traditionally sung in
foreign languages. The words are either projected on a large screen
above the stage, or appear on individual screens on the back of
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of surtitles opened up the field of opera to a new
generation who didn't understand before,'' Dyer said. ``Even for
the people who understood the general story line but didn't speak
the language fluently, a whole new world of humor has opened up.''
</P>
<P>
   Raj Sundaram, 32, saw ``Madama Butterfly,'' his second opera
performance, at the Met while on vacation with his wife. A San
Francisco architect, Sundaram is part of the new generation opera
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opera's intellectually stimulating and a great time,'' he
said. ``It might even be better than sticking beers down my
throat.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
