<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1702 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-JEWISH-CENTER &LR;      03-19 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-JEWISH-CENTER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAMMING AND JAMMING WITH RELIGION IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Nathan Hegedus is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By NATHAN HEGEDUS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A handful of people peruse the shelves of the reading
room. Here is the gay magazine Out, featuring a beautiful man in a
tight Boy Scout uniform. Across the room is The Jewish Sentinel
with a story on the poor in Israel. The pros and cons of Jewish day
schools are fodder for the Journal of the Jewish Theological
Seminary. And Spin is highlighting the alternative rock group Rage
Against the Machine.
</P>
<P>
   This is the room that greets people entering Makor, a decidedly
different cultural center for Jewish young people. It's a place
where rabbis teach Yiddish classes on the third floor, while a
lively crowd enjoys a poetry slam over beer and wine downstairs.
From a restored townhouse on the Upper West Side, Makor offers a
blend of religion and culture with a hip twist.
</P>
<P>
   The product of focus groups and market research, Makor, which
means ``source'' in Hebrew, is designed to make Judaism more
comfortable for people who otherwise are not drawn to their
heritage. It is aimed at the estimated 100,000 New York Jews
between 22 and 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to reach people where they are culturally,'' said the
center's creative director, Rabbi David Gedzelman, a Conservative
Jew. ``We want to give opportunities for exploration, so younger
Jews can find who they are, what their talents are.''
</P>
<P>
   Gedzelman, backed by an $11 million philanthropic grant, opened
the center last September after researching the cultural likes and
dislikes of young Jews. He decided that entertainment and a social
atmosphere had to be part of any attempt to promote Jewish
education.
</P>
<P>
   For jazz fans, there are jazz nights with the hottest local
groups. If Yiddish celebratory music is more your taste, the
klezmer band shows may appeal. Weekly Sabbath dinners, with themes
like ``Judaism and Vegetarianism,'' complement Sunday guitar jams.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it is unique is an understatement,'' said Rabbi Seth
Frisch of the Conservative Fifth Avenue synagogue. ``In Jewish
history, the greatest advances came when great religions freely
shared theological and cultural insights. There is a new synthesis,
a new art. What bad could possibly come of that?''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday night, a well-dressed crowd of 200 mingled
in Makor's sleek bar, drinking and dancing to a swing band called
Jet Set Six.
</P>
<P>
   Two women with straight, shoulder-length hair sat off to the
side at a table. They said Makor presented a welcome new social
opportunity for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all places are respectable for Jewish girls to be at,''
said Stephanie Blanchard, 24, an editor at Soap Opera Weekly who
described herself as no longer an observant Jew. ``This is like a
multifaceted Y. It would be patronizing to assume that you can
gather Jews only by preaching to them. Everyone with a common
interest, to meet other young Jewish people, now has a place to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard, in a long, dark dress, fits perfectly into Makor's
target demographic _ young Jews who need a new reason to return to
Jewish circles. The center's aim is that the patrons who are drawn
by the entertainment scene will eventually become interested in the
religious side of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry slams are one of Makor's biggest attractions. Men wearing
yarmulkes join women in black tight dresses to hear poets read
about lower East Side prostitutes and life in Tel Aviv. Most work
presented at a recent slam did have a Jewish subtext. Andy Horwitz,
rotund and sporting a shaved head, read his comical ``Self-Hating
Jew'' and garnered almost perfect scores from the panel of judges
in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   David Lang, a Jewish poet competing in the slam, appreciated the
Jewishness of the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come more for the social aspects than religiosity,'' he
said. ``But I might come to the Jewish things. It is an amazing
space. I feel comfortable here.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie nights at Makor feature classics like ``Some Like It Hot''
and ``Five Easy Pieces'' and documentaries with such themes as the
origins of bebop. Gedzelman said he will include more
Jewish-oriented entertainment as time passes, following the
successful shows by Inasense, a psychedelic band of Orthodox Jews,
and the band Hasidic New Wave.
</P>
<P>
   So far, acceptance of Makor has cut across the often disparate
boundaries in Jewish culture. From modern Orthodox to Reform
practitioners, the center wins acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the secular culture being used is `kosher,' '' said
Dani Davis, the program director in the youth department of the
National Council of Young Israel, a national coordinating agency
for Orthodox congregations, ``it is absurd to say you can't use it
to educate and bring back non-observant Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone complain that the club frowns on non-Jewish patrons,
Makor staff members emphatically insist that all are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not exclude anyone,'' said Makor's musical director,
Brice Rosenbloom. ``We try to focus on Jews but a mixed crowd will
make it feel more like a club.``
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's too soon to say if the Makor bar scene is yielding
devotees of Jewish practice. Gedzelman said he plans a survey on
that point. For now, Gedzelman is pleased that attendance stands at
up to 1,000 people a week. By the fall, he hopes to double that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1818EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
