<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1703 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-HARLEM-RENAISSANC     03-19 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-HARLEM-RENAISSANCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEM'S REVIVAL IS BECKONING OUTSIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Daisy Nguyen is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By DAISY NGUYEN   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the 10 years David Taylor has been behind the
counter of Mann's Deli Restaurant in Harlem, he says he has never
been as busy as he has been lately. Ever since an Old Navy clothing
store opened in a sleek glass and steel mall near his soul-food
restaurant last month, Taylor said, business has picked up.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of a 275,000-square-foot mall and the arrival of
national chain stores such as Starbucks, Blockbuster Video and Rite
Aid on 125th Street, Harlem's main drag, are signs that the
neighborhood is on the upswing. Old Navy is the first clothing
store to open at the Harlem U.S.A. mall, but a Disney store, a
Chase Manhattan bank, an HMV Records store, a nine-screen multiplex
theater and a gym will soon follow. While some local merchants are
waiting for the entire mall to open, they say they are optimistic
about Harlem's economic future. Taylor said that he notices more
traffic on 125th Street and that the streets are safer because more
police officers are present.
</P>
<P>
   ``The construction workers come in here to dine, so do the
customers at Old Navy,'' said Taylor, 31. ``When the rest of the
mall opens, I expect our sales to increase by at least ten
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if people here can afford $3 cafe lattes, then it
couldn't be all that bad,'' said Donald Benson, 35, an assistant
manager at the Starbucks on the corner of 125th Street and Malcolm
X Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The coffee chain store is partly owned by Magic Johnson and its
interior features inspirational quotes on the wall along with a
photo of the basketball legend holding a cup of coffee. Since its
opening in Harlem last May, Benson said the response from locals
has been positive. ``We make an average of $1,700 per day and we're
thinking about expanding our store,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news for everybody,'' said Benson. ``If Starbucks
can make it in a place like Harlem, then it can make it anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon at Starbucks, several foreign tourists
stopped by to get their caffeine fix and take a break from their
neighborhood excursion. Anna Jacobson, 29, a Swedish expatriate
living in Lower Manhattan, brought her mother, Christina Ahlin, 57,
to visit Harlem. It was Ahlin's first day in town, and she wanted
to see Harlem first. Jacobson, who has lived in New York for three
years, said that she frequently shops in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stores are funky and the clothes are cheap,'' said
Jacobson. ``I get a good deal on sneakers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the streets here,'' she added. ``It's livelier and
people are more in-your-face. Down in the East Village where I
live, people like to show off too much. In Harlem, everything is
more real.''
</P>
<P>
   Melodie Brown, 32, a Harlem resident, was also in the cafe
sipping on a tall cup of coffee, a bag of clothes from Old Navy and
a cage she bought at a pet store by her side. Brown has lived in
Harlem all her life and said that she is happy to see more
businesses coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more convenient for me to walk down to 125th Street than
take the subway to downtown just to buy some clothes,'' she said.
``I also think about spending money here to support the local
businesses or big stores that employ black people. You make a
conscious decision to spend money here and keep the cash flow in
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, many stores on 125th Street were boarded up. The
mostly small businesses that were operating struggled in this
traditionally low-income neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The retail development is a result of an economic ``empowerment
zone'' created in 1994 by Rep. Charles B. Rangel, a Democrat who
represents Harlem. It offers federal dollars as well as generous
tax breaks for businesses that invest in low-income areas.
According to Terry Lane, president of the Upper Manhattan
Empowerment Zone, $300 million in cash and $250 million in tax
breaks will be invested to attract investors to the area. Harlem
U.S.A. was built on a lot that had been empty for years.
</P>
<P>
   But some small businesses resent the newcomers, as the
improvement increases property values and pushing them out. Sung Il
Oh, 61, the owner of Juno Shoe store, says he is worried he'll have
to close his shop soon because the rent has more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to pay $2,000 a month, now I'm paying $5,000 and it
could go up again next month,'' said Oh. ``This big jump doesn't
make sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh's shop is in the block between the Starbucks and Old Navy. He
has been in business for 15 years and said that since the rent
increase, business has been stagnant. ``I'm not ordering spring or
summer shoes because I might have to close next month, then what
will I do will all the unsold shoes? It'll be a loss, but now all I
have are winter boots and no one is buying them either.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Bulgar, 35, a counterman at Manna's Deli, said, ``There
are some who tremendously benefit from the new economy, and some
that lose out big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some small businesses say the change don't affect them.
Mahammad Tariq-Wasim, 27, a salesman at Jimmy Jazz, a clothing
store that sells urban street wear, says the Old Navy doesn't
threaten his business. Jimmy Jazz offers designer brands such as
Polo Ralph Lauren, FUBU and Sean John, the clothing label owned by
rapper Sean ``Puffy'' Combs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people follow trends closely and they tend to come here
to buy the hottest labels,'' Tariq-Wasim said. ``Old Navy has its
own brand, and there's a place for the store and its customers on
this street too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulgar, who has lived in Harlem all his life, says it's a good
thing some stores are closing. ``Some places should close because
they're not helping Harlem improve its image,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1819EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1704 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-POLIO-SYNDROME &LR;      03-19 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-POLIO-SYNDROME </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS BACK IN THE GRIP OF THEIR DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Alexa Jaworski is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By ALEXA JAWORSKI   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Groundbreaking vaccines of the 1950s nearly stamped
out the polio epidemic that ravaged childhoods and left many of its
victims on crutches. The names Salk and Sabin came to symbolize
triumph, the end of a national scare. Science moved on to other
deadly threats to the population.
</P>
<P>
   But to Benjamin Siragusa, his fight with polio, a disease
thought by most to be long gone, is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, more than three decades after what he thought
was his recovery, the unexpected effects of polio began taking a
toll on him. He developed what scientists and polio survivors call
post-polio syndrome, commonly known as PPS. It strikes polio
survivors anywhere from 10 to 40 years after recovery from an
initial attack of polio, according to the National Institute of
Neurological Disorders and Stroke, a division of the National
Institutes of Health. It is not a recurrence of the polio virus
itself, but a further weakening of muscles and deterioration of
nerves that were previously injured by the polio virus.
</P>
<P>
   Although hundreds of thousands of polio survivors now live with
PPS in the United States, finding a cure for PPS isn't a high
priority in the eyes of the government and the scientific
community, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more polio survivors than all Americans with
multiple sclerosis, spinal cord injuries and Parkinson's disease
combined,'' said Dr. Richard Bruno, a director of the Post-Polio
Institute at the Englewood Hospital and Medical Center in New
Jersey, who has been working with PPS patients for 17 years. ``But
Congress will not set aside one dollar.'' Over the next several
years, 100 percent of polio victims will have some symptom that is
attributable to PPS, said Bruno. Worldwide, he said, 15 to 20
million people are polio survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Siragusa, of Syracuse, N.Y., remembers his 50-year-old bout with
polio vividly. Paralyzed by the disease from the neck down at the
age of 4, Siragusa was sent from his home in Watertown, N.Y., to a
rehabilitation center in Ithaca for children with polio. There he
spent six months in a mechanical tube-like ventilator, or ``iron
lung.'' He can still hear the rushing, swooshing sound of the large
metal capsule _ like ``an eerie pulsing noise'' he said _ as it
pushed air in and out of his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though polio left him with crutches and braces, Siragusa
went on to marry, move to Arizona and open an optical business.
</P>
<P>
   He thought his battle with polio was over.
</P>
<P>
   Then 16 years ago, while standing over a display case at work,
he suddenly fell to the floor. His right leg, his ``better leg'' he
calls it because it was less affected by the virus, just gave out
from under him.
</P>
<P>
   In the following weeks, he continued to fall. Soon walking
through large parking lots exhausted him. And he was tired all the
time. Very tired. He knew there was something dreadfully wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Frightened and confused, Siragusa visited a neurologist. ``The
doctor said he had good news and bad news,'' said Siragusa, who is
now 54 and lives in Liverpool, N.Y. ``The good news was that I
didn't have something that would kill me, like Lou Gehrig's
disease. The bad news was that I had something called post-polio
syndrome.'' He had never heard of post-polio syndrome before.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 300,000 polio survivors in the U.S. may be at risk
for PPS, but doctors are unable to establish a firm incidence rate,
the Neurological Institute said. Other researchers estimate the
number to be higher. There are currently 1.63 million living polio
victims in the United States, said Bruno of the Post-Polio
Institute, and at least 75 percent have PPS.
</P>
<P>
   Once Siragusa developed PPS, he said life went downhill fast. He
had to sign over his business to his partner and retire. Now, he
must take pain and anti-inflammatory medication _ 40 to 50 pills a
day. And, according to doctors and researchers, the most he can do
for his weakening body is rest.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno emphasized that polio survivors need to know they are not
lazy or crazy, and that PPS is a progressive neuromuscular disease.
``It's a diagnosis of exclusion,'' said Bruno. When diagnosing PPS,
physicians rule out other diseases, such as anemia and amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mauro of Levittown, N.Y., first developed PPS in 1969, 16
years after recovering from polio. After recovering, Mauro rode a
two-wheeler, he said. He was also able to walk all over the campus
of Hofstra University, where he graduated in 1976 with a degree in
sociology.
</P>
<P>
   When Mauro first developed PPS in his early 20s, he initially
was told that his fatigue and shortness of breath was all in his
mind. One doctor gave him Valium. Another told him to take 20 types
of vitamins a day. ``I went through three shrinks, six doctors and
a lot of drugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now 53, he must spend most of his time in a wheelchair and on a
respirator. Because he cannot sit in front of computer for long
periods of time, he lies on a yellow mat atop a butcher block table
with shortened legs whenever he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every doctor going to medical school should be trained
in post-polio syndrome,'' said Mauro, who also began a newsletter
and Web site for disabled people who are single. Medical schools
must ``make doctors aware of the symptoms of PPS so they don't
misdiagnose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other polio survivors, he feels forgotten. He pointed
out that the March of Dimes originally began to help children with
polio. Since the end of the epidemic, the organization changed its
focus to helping babies born with birth defects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people think polio is no longer in existence.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
