<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-PLANETARIUM-PLUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUTO: ON THE FRINGE BUT IN THE FRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Dan Zehr is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School of
Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By DAN ZEHR   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In one loud chant, a sixth-grade tour group started
in on the list of planets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars ...'' Their guide at the American
Museum of Natural History's newly renovated Hayden Planetarium sang
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune ...'' The guide stopped. The
kids kept shouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pluto!''
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   The astonished youngsters craned their necks at the eight model
planets hanging from the ceiling. Pluto, what they thought was the
ninth, was not among them.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that raised more than a few astronomical eyebrows, the
planetarium has dropped Pluto from its regal planetary standing,
hewing to a debated view of the very definition of a planet. The
museum is siding with theorists who say that little Pluto is part
of the Kuiper Belt, a mass of big objects beyond Neptune, but not
one of the major planets.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials say they made the change to reflect what they
see as the mainstream of astronomy and to generate interest in the
solar system. In fact, the museum disputes the categorization of
celestial objects into a list of planets, moons, asteroids and the
like. Instead the museum has separated the heavens into zones, each
containing a mixture of those objects. The decision has fueled a
convoluted _ and not always clearly stated _ debate among
astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Trimble, a vice president of the International
Astronomical Union, takes a diplomatic stance as a representative
of an organization to which both sides subscribe. ``As far as we're
concerned it's a planet,'' Trimble said from her office at the
University of California at Irvine. ``But it's also part of the
Kuiper Belt objects.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where the quandary begins, said Michael A'Hearn, an
astronomy professor at the University of Maryland. When Clyde
Tombaugh, an Arizona astronomer, discovered Pluto in 1930, the new
object was classified as a planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called it a planet because they had nothing else to call
them,'' A'Hearn said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1992, astronomers discovered more trans-Neptunian objects _
masses beyond Neptune that orbited the sun. These chunks of rock
and ice were named the Kuiper Belt. Pluto fit into both categories.
</P>
<P>
   A'Hearn falls into the school of scientists who don't think this
debate is all that important: ``I have been amazed at how heavily
researchers have come down on one side or the other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomer Marc Buie, who has mapped Pluto, strongly believes
that being part of the Kuiper Belt does not exclude Pluto from
planethood, and the planetarium's position troubles him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing a game here,'' he said from his office at the
Lowell Observatory in Arizona. ``I can't view it any other way.
Pluto, by definition, is a planet, and to say it isn't will confuse
people in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists have used a simple definition of a planet: it is
an object that revolves around a sun, is large enough that its
gravity holds it in spherical shape, and is small enough so that
its core does not ignite a fusion reaction _ that would make it a
star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to let physics tell us what's one kind of object and
what's another,'' Astronomer Alan Stern, director of the Southwest
Research Institute, recently told a National Public Radio audience.
``We simply want to look across the solar system and say, What
burns hydrogen? That's a star. What objects are large enough to be
round and yet do not burn hydrogen? We call those planets if they
orbit the star.''
</P>
<P>
   His point is not completely lost on Charles Liu, an
astrophysicist at the Rose Center for Earth and Space, where the
Hayden Planetarium resides. Liu agrees that Pluto satisfies the
common definition of a planet. But he and his colleagues would call
it a minor planet, better classified as part of the Kuiper Belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you're going to get arguments is from those who advocate
a certain definition of planets,'' Liu said. ``For them, it's
either an issue of the definition of the word `planet' _ a word
with no universally accepted definition _ or a matter of
nostalgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Liu's problem with Buie's criteria is that they are so
inclusive. Under them, at least four asteroids, numerous moons and
the spherical Ceres, also in the Kuiper Belt, would qualify as
planets, too.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of just squeezing Pluto in, Liu said, ``we asked how the
solar system presents itself to us.'' Instead of the traditional
emphasis on the ``list'' of nine planets, he said, it's better to
talk about the solar system as a whole. ``It has some small objects
that are interesting and large objects that are interesting,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden's team emphasized five solar system zones. The first
contains the terrestrial planets _ Mercury, Venus, Earth and Mars _
that have metallic cores and a rocky crust and orbit closest to the
sun. The next orbit zone is just beyond Mars and features a belt of
asteroids. The gas giants come next: Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and
Neptune. Fourth is the Kuiper Belt, including Pluto. Last comes the
collection of comets and debris called the Ort Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   Liu says Pluto just doesn't fit with the eight major planets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under no circumstances have we demoted Pluto,'' Liu said.
``Just because we don't call it a major planet doesn't mean it's
not interesting. If we study it, it could really reveal a great
deal about how our solar system was formed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
