<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-LIVE-FUNERALS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNERALS GO LIVE ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(Kate Dawson is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By KATE DAWSON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It seems like everything these days is available
online: dating, grocery shopping. Now even the dead are going live.
Funeral home directors say more people are asking for Webcams at
services, so those who can't attend can watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people can't be there when they desperately need to
grieve,'' said Henry Rice, owner of Messinger's Mortuary in
Scottsdale, Ariz., who plugged in his funeral Webcam last October.
He said he has broadcasted at least five funerals over the Internet
so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't have family living in town or they are
older'' and have difficulty traveling, Rice said. ``It's a service
that will help get me more business. Soon, I think, Webcams will be
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is no record of how many funeral homes broadcast
services online, at least four can be found easily on the Internet.
None charge extra for the service. A family that requests it must
provide a list of mourners who want to watch the service via the
funeral home's Web site. Each person is given a special access code
so no one else but those on the list can watch the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, Straaltman, Apfel Funeral Home in Kearney, Neb., which
has been videotaping funerals for five years, began offering
broadcasts of funerals last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that the Internet is the wave of the future,''
said Stephen O'Brien, owner of the business. ``It doesn't cost us
anything and so we don't charge for it. Just in the last month
we've broadcast two or three services.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said most people who request the Web service have
relatives in other states. And while some might think there is
something peculiar about watching a funeral on a screen, he
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how many people watched Princess Diana's
funeral?'' O'Brien said. ``Do you know how many people watched John
Kennedy's funeral? Why shouldn't Joe Average have the chance to
have his funeral broadcast?''
</P>
<P>
   A funeral home in the Bronx in New York City sees its Webcam as
a way of helping the government save money. Jim Alson, the owner of
the Bronxwood Funeral Home, said some of the relatives who request
the service do so because they are in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had prisoners actually come to services in shackles and
handcuffs,'' he said. Flanked by prison guards, they have to be
kept separate from everyone else. ``With Web access,'' Alson said,
``they can avoid having their families see them in a prison uniform
and the state doesn't have to hire the guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Alson said about half of his clientele are Caribbean, so he gets
numerous requests for Web funerals from places like Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not predicting it's going to be a runaway hit, but more
places will do it if it catches on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Clark, owner of Grissom-Eastlake Funeral Home in Atlanta,
agreed. Though he does not offer the service, he said he would if
enough customers want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much of demand for that stuff because my clients
are mostly poor and can't afford computers,'' said Clark, who's
been a funeral director in Georgia for more than 20 years. ``But if
there's a demand and it impacts my business, you'd better believe
I'll do it.'' Kelly Smith of the Wisconsin-based National Funeral
Directors Association estimated that few of the 21,000 funeral
homes in the country have computers. ``The few funeral homes who
are online with Webcams have them because the owners are into
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose organization arranges seminars on e-commerce for
funeral directors, said that privacy is also an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funeral directors are extremely sensitive to the privacy of
families,'' Smith said. ``I think many will not be convinced the
Internet is a safe place to hold a private ceremony.'' Joseph
Lopez, a funeral director at Bryant Mortuary in San Francisco, said
the privacy issue is just one factor that makes him think twice
about Internet funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ridiculous,'' Lopez said. ``How can you really
mourn for someone over a television screen? What's next, a drive-up
window?''
</P>
<P>
   But funeral Webcams do not seem to be going away anytime soon.
Fred Fergerson, the owner of Fergerson Funeral Home in Syracuse,
N.Y., has a Webcam rolling around the clock pointed at the chapel's
front stoop. That means anyone surfing the Internet can watch a
coffin taken out and placed inside a hearse headed for the
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front yard of the chapel is just what you'd be seeing if
you were sitting on the curb, so it's open to the public,''
Fergerson said. He says people even come to the window where the
camera is and wave.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Fergerson has only had one family request Web access to
a funeral, but he had a problem with his computer the day of the
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try it away from the chapel,'' he said. ``A
family wants me to set up at the grave site, so we'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Four of the funeral homes that offer services via the Internet
ask family members to sign documents acknowledging that they
understand the businesses cannot guarantee success with the
broadcast. Families are also warned that the Internet is not a
secure medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``These services are not for the general public,'' Alson said.
``Our biggest fear would be if people learned how to bust through
our system and crash a funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
