<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1708 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-STREET-NEWS &LR;      03-19 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-STREET-NEWS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET PAPERS, WEB SITES AMPLIFY HOMELESS VOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(mp) 
(William Siss is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate School
of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By WILLIAM SISS   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John ``Indio'' Washington has seen it all, done it
all, and lived to tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   The former New York City case manager, job developer, social
worker, arbitrator and mediator explains: ``I have a doctorate in
theology. And I have a Ph.D. in street-ology as well as sex-ology
and hip-ology. You name it, I claim it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Indio's combination of experience and braggadocio that
makes him the longest-running editor of Street News, a tabloid that
bills itself as the ``world's oldest active homeless paper.''
</P>
<P>
   What started as an experiment in 1989 _ a newspaper about and
sold by the homeless _ has spawned a worldwide publishing
phenomenon. Bolstered by Web sites and a news service, over 100
``street newspapers'' fill a hole left by mainstream media on
homeless issues.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the Times Square Brewery on 42nd Street, Indio, 61,
smokes Newport Menthol 100s and drinks beer among the noontime
tourists. Short and thin with a devilish smile, Indio (a name that
came to him while meditating) is covered in blue Street News
clothing: baseball cap, sweatshirt and sweatpants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've helped over 10,000 people get back into the
mainstream,'' he says in a raspy voice. ``I know we have helped
people live another day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pops,'' who has been selling Street News on the subway and
around Times Square since 1989, knows very well what it's like to
live day to day. The Alabama-born vendor, homeless in the early
1990s, used to sell a hundred papers a day, but now sells between
20 and 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street News doesn't speak for the homeless,'' says the gray
bearded man with one-tooth smile, who now lives in an apartment run
by a social service agency. ``It lets the homeless speak to the
people. A lot of people don't want to hear about homeless people.
They don't want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Street News concept is simple: homeless and poor people take
10 copies of each issue to sell. They keep whatever they sell them
for. They can then buy more copies for 60 cents each, and sell them
for the $1.60 cover price. About 50 vendors sell the paper, Indio
says, including 6 women.
</P>
<P>
   The latest 48-page issue covers topics like the mayor's homeless
policy, police brutality and rent control, and lists where to find
free food and clothing. Professors, students, advocates and the
formerly homeless also write columns, profiles and poems.
</P>
<P>
   Since Street News doesn't receive public funding, advertising
pays for most of the $4,000 printing and distribution costs. Indio,
who says he doesn't receive a salary for his work, has cut down to
an 8,000-copy run, from a high of 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Harlem, Indio says he has several degrees,
including a Doctorate of Divinity from the Unity Universal Life
Church in Modesto, Calif. After serving over two years in prison
for drug possession and after a divorce in the mid-1980s, Indio
says he suffered a nervous breakdown, started smoking crack and
fell into homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Indio started selling Street News in 1989, making $150 to $300 a
week. He later edited alongside Lee Stringer, who wrote ``Grand
Central Winter'' (Seven Stories Press, 1998) about homelessness.
Indio ascended to the editor's position in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now he finds himself on a soapbox from which he doesn't plan to
step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I'm not happy with is that the majority of
the main media do not have homeless people giving their opinion,''
he says, exhaling a cloud of smoke. ``In experience, you can't
touch us. So why don't you let us participate?''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Harris, editor and founder of Real Change, a street
newspaper in Seattle, echoes Indio's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a voice of the poor that doesn't exist otherwise,''
Harris says. ``The major media largely ignores the homeless. In the
'80s, homelessness was an issue, and now it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris hopes to create the Associated Press of street
newspapers: the Street News Service. Expanding from the current
Homeless News Service, the Web-based repository should enable
papers to reprint articles for free when it launches in April on
Alternet, which distributes articles from alternative news sources
(www.alternet.org).
</P>
<P>
   As street papers blossom, the need for organization increases.
The International Network of Street Papers comprises of 21 papers
in Europe, Africa and Australia. And the North American Street News
Association (NASNA) represents over 45 street publications,
including Street News, Street Scene (Los Angeles), StreetWise
(Chicago), Hard Times (Richmond, Va.), Vox Populi (San Antonio,
Texas) and Our Voice (Edmonton, Alberta).
</P>
<P>
   NASNA's treasurer, Michael Stoops, compared street papers to
``Negro newspapers,'' which started covering black issues in 1827,
when Freedom's Journal was first published in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every minority and special interest group, like the homeless,
need their own media source,'' says Stoops, who also works for the
National Coalition for the Homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Stoops says that 25 percent of NASNA's papers have an online
presence, but doesn't believe that will hurt demand on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if all of the papers were to go online, we don't think
there would be a drop in paper revenue,'' Stoops says. ``People
would still want a copy in the subway and the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Indio believes NASNA ensures the future of street newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought tears to my eyes when I first went to a NASNA
meeting, because I saw that the idea will not be eliminated,'' he
says. ``I saw young teen-agers, all the way up to people older than
me, fighting for a just cause. So if anything happens to me or
Street News, the beat goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
