<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOSLEY-NONFICTION-ART     03-19 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSLEY-NONFICTION-ART-(1300)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRACING VIEWS FROM A MAN OF MYSTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo (NYT4) is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a scene in the novel ``Devil in a Blue Dress'' that
peeps at the place where Walter Mosley's politics and art meet.
Easy Rawlins has been pressed into detective service by DeWitt
Albright, a mysterious, sinister man who lures Easy with enough
money to make the overdue mortgage payments on his beloved home.
Easy is a Negro and DeWitt is white in the Los Angeles of 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't belong to anybody,'' Easy says to Albright's assertion
that he paid him and thus owns him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all owe out something, Easy,'' Albright replies. ``When you
owe out then you're in debt and when you're in debt then you can't
be your own man. That's capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it is that capitalism is the theme of Mosley's first book
of nonfiction, a slim, eight-chapter essay called ``Workin' on the
Chain Gang: Shaking Off the Dead Hand of History'' (Library of
Contemporary Thought). The book, published earlier this year,
explores a range of issues, including race, culture and global
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The unifying thread is the moral and economic stranglehold of
capitalism, as seen through the prism of the black American
experience. His is a progressive rather than Marxist stance and
offers different ways of looking at some old problems, rather than
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chain Gang'' begins with the idea that the millennium is an
artificial marker of human progress. Mosley looks at such defining
events as the enslavement of Africans in the New World, the
Holocaust and the detonation of the atomic bomb and contrasts
technological advances with our attitudes toward human life over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that although race is still a major problem in America
and technology has far outpaced moral growth, the greatest
malignancy is the juggernaut of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What black people have experienced as a group for centuries
many whites now experience as solitary and alienated individuals,''
Mosley writes. ``In their various groups white Americans might feel
that they belong, that there is a group spirit that looks out for
them. But individually they suffer the barbs of bureaucratic
indifference and the vicissitudes of corporate whims like everyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers Weekly called the book ``an ardent manifesto'' and a
``provocative declaration of intellectual and political
independence.'' Kirkus Reviews crowned Mosley ``a significant
African-American thinker.''
</P>
<P>
   The final chapter of ``Chain Gang'' begins with Malcolm X's
line, ``You have been bamboozled,'' from a speech about American
society that he made at a Harlem rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he was right,'' Mosley writes. ``Black people had been
fooled and lied to and broken over the promise of freedom. But the
truth is that all Americans have been fooled and broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy and capitalism make strange bedfellows,'' the essay
continues. ``In this odd brew freedom becomes a commodity. A price
is put upon our only asset, our labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, who is famous for his five Easy Rawlins mysteries, said
he wrote the book to foment and prolong a dialogue about issues
dear to his heart. He has always been political, he said, and a
nonfiction book on a serious subject was another way to resist the
artistic pigeonholing he loathes.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said that he initially chose to write about race in the
21st century but that as he chewed on his thoughts the book turned
into something more complex. That should not surprise anyone who
understands his fiction, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the only people in America writing now about black
male heroes _ that in itself is a political act, to see and cast
black men in America in a positive role,'' Mosley said over lunch
at a Greenwich Village restaurant where he frequently eats. At 48,
he is loquacious, easygoing, discernibly smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is, I write about very real social
situations,'' Mosley said. ``When I write about Easy Rawlins and he
goes out to the desert and a guy turns a gun on him, Easy doesn't
understand it isn't necessarily about race but because the guy
thinks he is going to rob him. But race informs how the guy looks
at him, too, and how Easy responds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Socrates Fortlow is completely political,'' he said of another
recurring protagonist. ``He seeks redemption. He wants to form
bonds and hope in the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Mosley said, ``I'm no more political than
Mark Twain or Charles Dickens or Herman Melville.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, a Los Angeles native who lives in Greenwich Village, is
the author of 11 books. ``Devil in a Blue Dress'' (1990), his
first, created an astonished gasp of pleasure in the literary world
and opened the door for other black mystery writers. It didn't hurt
that President Clinton called him his favorite writer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since Easy showed up, Mosley's work has been translated into 20
languages and crossed over into movies. In 1995 ``Devil in a Blue
Dress'' became a film starring Denzel Washington. In 1998 Laurence
Fishburne starred as Socrates Fortlow in ``Always Outnumbered,
Always Outgunned'' on HBO. A one-hour television series based on
the Easy Rawlins character is in the discussion stages with ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley made his debut recently in The New Yorker with a short
story about a young man on Wall Street. His first play, about three
dysfunctional relationships, will be produced in Hartford in
September. He is also working on a series of science fiction
stories set in the New York of 2040, and HBO wants another
screenplay based on the latest Socrates novel.
</P>
<P>
   Characters like Socrates Fortlow, a 60-ish convicted rapist and
murderer living a hardscrabble life in a Los Angeles slum, are
imbued with dignity and insight. They seem to reflect Mosley's
delight in subversion, in turning the expected into the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   He is, after all, the son of a Jewish mother and
African-American father who married and made their home in Los
Angles when such couples were considered eccentric at best. His
parents stayed together until his father died seven years ago. They
were crippled by the obvious inequities of being themselves in that
time and place, he said, but they loved each other and loved him
enough that he finally reached a place emotionally where he could
be himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley left behind a job as a computer programmer after the
beginnings of a novel floated into his head. It became ``Devil in a
Blue Dress.'' That was only a decade ago. Like a lot of people, he
said, he took a long time to grow up and discover his real
affinities and talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel myself as a real, everyday kind of American guy,''
Mosley said when asked whether his fiction fans might question his
moral or intellectual authority to tackle ``Chain Gang.'' ``I can't
tell you what to do. I can't answer the problem. I'm just somebody
who thinks about it, and I came to the conclusion that our moral
and technological potential is severely limited by how much we've
bought into capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens, he said, is that people do not see common
suffering brought about by economic constraints but focus on their
own victimization. And because blacks have historically been
marginalized and particularized and many social ills have been
presented as ``minority issues,'' the white skinhead and the
struggling black mother fail to realize that their HMO or their
boss is giving them both the short end of the stick.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley said he placed his hope for political and social change
on a younger generation that seems willing to make the leap to put
black Americans in the center of the American drama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
