<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PAPERS-BROADCAST-MEDI     03-19 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPERS-BROADCAST-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESENTATION OF NEWS BECOMES AN ISSUE IN NEW MEDIA PARTNERSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 6:30 p.m. on Tuesday, Ron Insana, co-anchor of CNBC's
``Business Center,'' began his broadcast with an exclusive report,
presented breathlessly: eBay and Yahoo were in discussions about a
possible merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's The Wall Street Journal's Steve Frank with what could
be a very significant development in the Internet sector,'' Insana
told his audience in at least 290,000 households as he introduced
Frank, who works as part of the cable station's news gathering
alliance with his paper.
</P>
<P>
   Frank's report made clear that no deal was imminent and that the
talks could still fall apart. But the report of a possible merger
between the two Internet behemoths sent reporters around the world
pursuing the CNBC-Wall Street Journal story _ which promptly
appeared on the CNBC Web site and the leading business news wires _
and helped send eBay shares on a short-lived $20 rally in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, essentially the same news report appeared in The
Journal, but as a small, five-paragraph article in the inside
pages. What changed in the short time between Frank's report on
CNBC and The Wall Street Journal's deadline? Several hours' more
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   After a team of Journal reporters, including Frank, made a
flurry of phone calls, the Journal editors decided that the facts
did not warrant a bigger display.
</P>
<P>
   The different treatment underscores the different demands of the
two kinds of media, and what could happen to a newspaper's
information when it is conveyed in the real-time world of
electronic journalism, especially in the environment of business
news, where minutes count and the need to highlight breaking
reports is critical. The difference is often not so much in actual
language as in the symbolic quality of the prominence of display.
</P>
<P>
   That inherent difference in approach is likely to become more
visible as newspapers, including The New York Times, increasingly
link up with television and the World Wide Web to extend their
brands. Tribune Co. made it clear last week that a cornerstone of
its strategy in buying Times Mirror Co. would be to use its print
journalists for the news reports of its television and radio
stations and its Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Times, in an experiment, is producing a 15-minute weekday
political program on the Web with ABC and a limited number of
segments for ``20/20'' and ``Good Morning America.'' The two news
organizations will not collaborate on breaking news.
</P>
<P>
   The CNBC report last Tuesday was not unusual. The competition
for business news, especially on cable television and the Web, has
put an extra premium on being fast and first.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal's managing editor, Paul E. Steiger, said
he saw nothing wrong in the different treatments of the Yahoo-eBay
talks. He said the information had been presented differently in
large part because of when the ``Business Center'' program was
broadcast in the news cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reporter who picked up the conversation between eBay and
Yahoo had a good piece of news,'' Steiger said. ``And so Steve
Frank, that reporter, mentioned it to the producers at CNBC, and in
their news environment it looked great, so they pumped it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Meantime,'' he said, ``you start reporting it for the paper's
news cycle. By the time we ran everything down, it turned out that
in terms of what was hard, it hadn't gone that much beyond''
speculation on an eBay-Yahoo deal that ran in an earlier column in
The Journal. So, Steiger said, ``this is what it was worth in the
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Steiger said he did not see any difference between the way CNBC
reported the news and the way reporters for The Journal have
traditionally written dispatches on the 103-year-old Dow Jones wire
service.
</P>
<P>
   But John V. Pavlik, executive director of Columbia University's
Center for New Media, at the Graduate School of Journalism, said
that while such a comparison was valid in some respects, there was
also an important difference: The public sees the cable channel.
The news service is used primarily by other journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, more Web sites are making wire reports quickly
available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlik said that the increasing number of business news outlets
on television and the Web were creating enormous pressure to break
news and claim it as your own.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have even an inkling of a story,'' he said, ``there
is incredible pressure to go with it because if you don't, there's
a high likelihood that somebody else will go with it and scoop
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not far from what happened at CNBC on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 2-year-old licensing agreement between The Wall Street
Journal and CNBC, CNBC pays the newspaper a licensing fee and gives
it a share of its advertising revenue in return for using its
newsroom resources. The Journal's parent company, Dow Jones, and
NBC, a unit of General Electric, are 50-50 partners in CNBC's
operations in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides benefit. For one thing, The Journal has given CNBC
additional credibility with traditional investors who were weaned
on the newspaper. Also, the network gets televised reports from
Journal staff members throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal receives not only a fee but also national
promotional exposure among people it may otherwise not reach, in a
medium in which the parent Dow Jones has struggled to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance raises the question of who is responsible for
Frank's work on television. He is one of two reporters from The
Wall Street Journal stationed permanently at CNBC's offices in Fort
Lee, N.J. Unlike other Journal reporters who show up on CNBC as
experts or with their own exclusive accounts, he takes his
direction from CNBC editors. There are two newspaper editors on
site who act as liaison between the newspaper and the cable
network, lining up print reporters for programs and keeping both
sides abreast of each other's activities. They may veto a CNBC
decision if they think their reporters are being dispatched
improperly, though Frank said this situation had not arisen.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, CNBC executives said, Frank heard rumblings about
talks between eBay and Yahoo earlier in the day. But he was not
able to confirm that until about 5 p.m. His CNBC bosses thought
that the news _ even if there was not much of it, just word that
the two sides had discussed a number of different scenarios _ was
important enough to warrant top-of-the-broadcast presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there was enormous value in two of the best-known
names on the Internet, Yahoo and eBay, getting together,'' said
Kevin Magee, executive producer of ``Business Center,'' adding,
``It's the equivalent in the 1950s of Penney talking to Sears.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank reported one person as saying that there was a 50-50
chance of some form of ``deep partnership'' and a significantly
smaller chance of an acquisition of eBay by Yahoo. Magee said this
was important enough for prominent play in a hot economy in which
investors seem to thirst for every bit of information. With
information moving faster than ever, Magee said, it is his mission
to keep his viewers ahead of the curve whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a stockholder of either eBay or Yahoo,'' he
continued, ``you wanted to know that news, which is why we wanted
to give it to you. Whether it held the same importance or not 12
hours later doesn't take away from the importance of the scoop at
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavlik said that was typical in the current news environment.
``Maybe at that moment, something might have seemed like a big
deal,'' he said. ``But in Internet time, even a few hours later it
can seem marginally interesting and not terribly important.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night. the CNBC report seemed less compelling after a
few hours. When Frank broadcast his exclusive report, The Journal's
newsroom was alerted. West Coast technology reporters were joined
by Frank in working on the story for the Wednesday paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the evening deadline rolled around,'' Steiger
said, ``it became clear the conversations were still pretty
preliminary.''
</P>
<P>
   CNBC's initial report created a ripple effect throughout
competing news media _ reaching the Reuters, Bloomberg and
Associated Press wires and financial Web sites like CBS
MarketWatch, SV.com and TheStreet.com, in which The New York Times
is an investor. The Times and The Street.com. operate a joint
newsroom that contributes both to TheStreet.com and to The Times'
Web site. Though The Times' Web site editors decided not to carry
the CNBC report, an automatic feed of breaking news from Reuters,
attributing the information to CNBC, inserted the report onto the
Times site just the same.
</P>
<P>
   In after-hours trading, eBay's stock ran up as high as $239 from
its $218.9375 close in the regular session. Yahoo rose to $171.1252
from $168.75, before returning to the lower price.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported the talks on Thursday in its Market
Place column, but called a merger or a sale unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, Frank appeared on CNBC's ``Squawkbox'' to
talk more about his report, stressing the tentative nature of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some other news organizations have perhaps been suggesting
that there is a merger closer here,'' he said. ``What we said
yesterday is there have been partnership talks between these two
companies. The likelihood on the Yahoo talks is only about 50-50
that any form of marketing alliance comes out of them, and a
significantly smaller likelihood even than that, that it would
result in an outright acquisition of eBay by Yahoo _ although that
possibility had not been ruled out. That's what we reported.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-ATHLETES-REVIEW-NY     03-19 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ATHLETES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INVESTIGATIVE REPORTS': A SNAPSHOT OF THE DOWNSIDE OF YOUTH
SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(rk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pressure on youngsters, some of them very young, to excel in
sports is a staple of journalistic exposes. And to judge by Monday
night's ``Investigative Reports,'' it is more manic than ever.
Fueled by parents, coaches, schools and the children's own visions
of glory, sports are taking up ever more time and passion,
sometimes with consequences that bode ill for health and family
relations.
</P>
<P>
   You can't tell from the examples deplored on ``Playing to
Extremes'' how widespread such cases are, and there is little
mention here of the influence of television and sponsors in keeping
enthusiasm at a high pitch. Instead, the hour goes into the impact
on a few families that seem to have been altogether carried away by
visions of glory.
</P>
<P>
   They include the family of 13-year-old Jimmy Gardner, a star
soccer player who warms up for three hours every weekday and is out
two nights a week and on weekends on what is known as ``a travel
team.'' On the weekend covered here, that means a six-hour ride to
the playing field. His father, an organizer of the travel team,
reports, ``We travel every weekend for soccer, that's our life.''
</P>
<P>
   The regimen can have unanticipated effects. A doctor who
specializes in sports injuries of very young children tells us of
an 11-year-old who complained of knee pain. It turned out that what
with soccer, hockey and tennis, he was subjecting his limbs to
heavy duty for four to five hours a day. He is a prospect for
needing a joint replacement at a very young age.
</P>
<P>
   A family's cost, in dollars and cents, can also be high, for
travel, equipment, clinics, uniforms and so forth. And Jimmy's
father tells of the emotional cost. Referring to the
parent-instigated fistfights he has seen on the sidelines, he says
that the competitive spirit ``probably transfers over to the way we
handle our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind some of the obsession with sports, the program notes, are
hopes that it may lead to a college scholarship. The family of
young Ally Absher, a potential basketball star at a North Carolina
school, is laying out thousands of dollars a year on her career.
Her coach acknowledges: ``I'm not one of these people that believes
we're just here to have fun. That's not why we're here.'' Ally
says, ``I want to go to a big college where you get seen on TV.''
Unfortunately for Absher and for the program, on the night the
camera is covering, her team loses a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Lyles, a maintenance worker at a Florida public school,
is spending much of the family savings on his two sons, talented
hockey players. His plan is for them to get into a classy prep
school that will lead to a scholarship. That means constant
attendance at competitions where they can show their stuff. ``He
forces me a lot of times when I don't want to go,'' one son says.
``He's pushing us too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The cautionary statistic cited here is that 70 percent of
youngsters ``burn out'' by the age of 13 and that fewer than 1
percent qualify for any sort of college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
