<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ONLY LOSERS ARE THE ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His team had been ousted from the National Collegiate Athletic
Association tournament. Mike Jarvis was making his way back to the
St. John's locker room.
</P>
<P>
   This was a slow, solemn walk late Saturday night _ slower, more
solemn than Jarvis probably realized. His wife, Connie, was on his
right, a university priest was on Jarvis' left. The sound of their
footsteps echoed down a vacant hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis suddenly stopped and laughed: ``I feel like I'm taking a
walk to the electric chair.'' Just as he reached the St. John's
locker room, Jarvis feigned terror and acted as if he were
resisting imaginary guards attempting to force him in the room:
``I'm not going,'' he said, his voice reverberating through the
arena. ``What did James Cagney say: `I didn't do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now laughter echoed through the hallway and softened the
disappointment of the moment. The coach had made his point:
Basketball provides a livelihood, but this was not life and death.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's enjoyed a nice, wild run. An undersized team that
passed well and overachieved met a mature, tournament-tested
Gonzaga team with a 6-foot-11-inch center who exploited St. John's
weakness in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams never get this far,'' Jarvis said. ``Still, in
order to grow, we have to have some of the same intangibles: the
feistiness the resiliency the aggressiveness,'' he said.
``Hopefully, we'll have that with more talent and a lot more depth
and size.''
</P>
<P>
   There are very few losers in the NCAA's showcase event. The
coaches are usually well compensated, the schools in the tournament
get a slice of the action. Each member school shares in the
television revenue
</P>
<P>
   There are markers everywhere of the NCAA's prosperity. Four
years ago, the Kansas City Star obtained a report showing that
Division I men's sports had ended up $156.4 million in the black
for that year. The University of Wisconsin reported $29,174,699
revenue in 1996; UCLA $13,492,587, St. John's $4,542,592 and
Gonzaga a modest $420,556. That was four years ago. The figures are
only going higher. Last year, the NCAA signed a $6 billion, 11-year
contract with CBS for television rights to the men's basketball
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The only losers are the athletes who happen to catch the eye and
wrath of NCAA investigators, tipped off to players picking up what
effectively amounts to crumbs from a bountiful table. The players,
with prodding from their coaches, are beginning to pay attention
</P>
<P>
   Matt Santangelo, who helped eliminate St. John's from the
tournament on Saturday with a 26-point performance, supported
Barkley throughout the week and became a strong advocate for
reforming a flawed system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year it seems there's been a lot more _ I don't know if
kids are being worse or if there's more attention given to it _ it
just seems like this year there's a lot of examples of NCAA
infractions,'' Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at NCAA merchandise as we went back and forth from his
hotel to practice facilities. The mugs, the jerseys with his number
on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are blessed and we are very fortunate to have our
scholarships because I wouldn't be in college if it wasn't for a
scholarship,'' said Santangelo, the youngest of nine children. His
father worked as an inventory manager at a foundry for 49 years.
``Still, it's all relative. If we were making $25,000 for the
school and they were spending $20,000 of it on tuition, where is my
place to complain? But in the scheme of things, we're making
millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what needs to change but as an intelligent,
educated person, I see my checkbook says zero, zero, zero. And
there's a lot of money going somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley was one of several players the NCAA singled out in
investigations that focused more on events that transpired prior to
their college enrollment than after it. Investigators from the
association looked into the case of Barkley's swapping cars with a
family friend, questions about the source of Barkley's tuition for
prep school, asked about the administration of his SAT test and
whether there had been improper contact with agents or with
representatives of agents.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the Red Storm season completed, the university will
stop and confront the hounds that have been on the trail for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley is expected to announce any day now that he is putting
his name into the National Basketball Association draft.
</P>
<P>
   He repeatedly has said how much he loves college life, college
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play another year, I love college basketball; it's much
different from the NBA,'' he said. ``There's more competition, guys
aren't worried about the paycheck at whatever time of the month.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean he's leaning toward staying? Barkley smiled,
sheepishly, sighed and shook his head as if to say he didn't want
to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer that,'' he said. ``That's a whole different
topic. That's a whole different story, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley told a post-game news conference: ``Life goes on. Right
now I'm just looking forward to doing my schoolwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night, Jarvis stood in the nearly empty St. John's
locker room, still stinging from the loss and thinking about the
future. Last month he said he would wait until the season ended to
renew his battle with the NCAA. For the moment, though, his
priority is Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want for him to go home, I want him to mean it when he says
he's going to be a student,'' Jarvis said. ``I want him to spend
some quality time with his mother and with whomever his spiritual
adviser is, and really go deep and deep and deep into his soul and
try to find out what is the best thing that he should do for the
right reasons and then do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1828EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0112 </DOCNO>
