u e BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      03-19 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-LINE LAW FIRM LINKS UP TO THE NEW ECONOMY  
 SPORTS ILLUSTRATED SWIMSUIT STILL A LIMITED EDITION  
 A PRODUCT GOOD ENOUGH FOR GOVERNMENT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD-LINE LAW FIRM LINKS UP TO THE NEW ECONOMY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone doubting the increasingly mainstream status of Internet
start-ups need hear only two words: Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The former senator and 1996 Republican presidential nominee
offered the opening remarks last Thursday evening at the coming-out
party in Washington for EqualFooting.com, a dot-com that plans to
create an online marketplace where small businesses would buy
industrial supplies, like plumbing equipment and hydraulic systems,
from national distributors.
</P>
<P>
   What has any of this to do with Dole?
</P>
<P>
   He holds the title of special counsel at the powerhouse
Washington law firm of Verner, Liipfert, Bernhard, McPherson &AMP;
Hand. The firm represents EqualFooting.com and is making e-commerce
a new focus. Last Thursday's party followed the firm's announcement
earlier in the day that it was starting an Internet ventures group.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 minutes or so that he spoke, Dole praised EqualFooting
and promoted the law firm's efforts to be part of the digital
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the law firm's courtship of dot-coms demonstrates how
little distance is left between the high-tech world, once staunchly
unwilling to cozy up to Capitol Hill, and the inside-the-beltway
elite, formerly dismissive of the Internet's role in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Marla P. Grossman, former minority counsel to the Senate
Judiciary Committee and now director of Verner Liipfert's Internet
group, contends that her firm can wield its influence in Washington
to help Internet interests ``use the resources of Capitol Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies ``are realizing increasingly that
Washington, D.C.'s influence really extends across the nation and
its influence has a direct and significant impact on their bottom
line,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the old-style, old-economy law firm may know Capitol
Hill, it may have to come up to speed itself to be a player in the
Internet world.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman cited as one of the firm's dot-com accomplishments the
fact that it helped Angie Kim, the president of EqualFooting.com,
land a speaking engagement at an e-commerce conference at Saginaw
Valley State University in Michigan. But just how much influence
the law firm can exert may depend on whether it can reach beyond
the heartland in Saginaw Valley to the heart of Silicon Valley.
--MATT RICHTEL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS ILLUSTRATED SWIMSUIT STILL A LIMITED EDITION
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those serendipitous meetings that most
entrepreneurs only dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibiting his wares at the International Fashion Boutique Show
in Manhattan last May, Keith Merl, an importer of hand-woven
Guatemalan cotton and other Central and South American textiles,
received a visit from an editor for Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   She was particularly interested in one of his hats, and
commissioned Merl to make a bathing suit from the same fabric. Thus
did Merl's swimsuit come to adorn a model featured in the
magazine's 2000 swimsuit edition, which hit newsracks last month.
</P>
<P>
   Merl's business may never be the same. (Or maybe it will; more
on that in a moment.) In the last month, his Web site,
www.artesaniainc.com, has received nearly 12,000 hits; most of
these were from people interested in the bathing suit, many of whom
reached his site through a link on www.sportsillustrated.com. So
far, though, Merl hasn't found a manufacturer or online retailer to
produce and sell the suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what volume to expect,'' Merl said. ``Anyway,
the rest of the business was going so well, I said I wasn't going
to get into the bathing suit business.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his business involves selling South American
textiles wholesale to Japanese companies; owning a retail store
called Artesania, in the Willowbrook Mall in Wayne, N.J.; and
selling clothing through the Sundance Catalog. The mall store is
doing particularly well, he said, and he is considering licensing
the Artesania brand.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Merl will ever get into the swimsuit business is still
up in the air. Eventually, he said, he does hope to have the
wherewithal to manufacture and sell the suits. But he does not seem
to have the 24/7/365 urgency that marks the budding e-commerce
executive. Last week, clicking the ``Swimsuit'' link on his Web
site produced the message ``HTTP/1.1 404 Object Not Found.'' Merl,
meanwhile, was off to Europe on vacation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --LAURIE J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A PRODUCT GOOD ENOUGH FOR GOVERNMENT WORK
</P>
<P>
   It is not often that a business will promote its products'
performance as being on a par with an activity of the federal
government. But Royal Consumer Business Products is betting that
such a connection will strike a chord with security-conscious
consumers. The company is promoting its new line of low-cost paper
shredders as enabling consumers to ``Shred Like the Feds.''
</P>
<P>
   The lower priced of the two new lines is called the FBI series.
The four FBI. models, ranging from $29.99 to $99.99, offer
consumers a relatively high level of security, a determination
based on the smallness of the shreds. By such reckoning, the CIA
line _ three models ranging from $49.99 to $200 _ is more secure,
mincing paper into morsels as small as confetti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to project that our product was a security
product,'' said Todd Althoff, head of marketing for Royal, which is
based in Bridgewater, N.J., and is a direct descendant of the
original Royal typewriter company founded in 1904. He said a
trademark search turned up a lot of products named after the FBI
and CIA, but no shredders.
</P>
<P>
   Both product lines are aimed primarily at families looking to
shred household documents, such as bills and financial records.
</P>
<P>
   In the 14 years since Royal was acquired by Olivetti SpA, the
company has gone through a significant transformation, as has the
typewriter industry itself. Today, in addition to home shredders,
Royal sells electronic organizers and a low-cost personal digital
assistant called the Royal da Vinci that competes with the Palm
Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   But for Royal, the biggest opportunity may be in home shredders.
Last year alone, the company sold more than two million shredders
to households, and the pace is continuing this year, Althoff said.
Consumers are realizing how vulnerable they are to invasions of
privacy, he said, particularly since passage of legislation a few
years ago that makes one's trash public property once it leaves the
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any garbage you put on your curb is in the free domain,
legally,'' he said. ``That includes your financial records, tax
returns, even pre-approved credit cards applications.'' --LAURIE J.
FLYNN &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
