(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windswept heavy snow will spread Monday from the mountains of
southern Wyoming and eastern Utah into northern Arizona and
Colorado as a storm center strengthens over the Southwest. Snow
accumulations over a foot will be common by early Tuesday including
some areas near metropolitan Denver. Additional snow will fall in
the central Rockies Tuesday as the storm stalls. Farther west,
strong winds with frequent gusts over 35 mph near mountain passes
will buffet much of Nevada and California.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will be locally heavy ahead of a front from the eastern
Ohio Valley to the interior Carolinas. Lighter showers will occur
in the Great Lakes states. The damp weather will move a little to
the east Monday as high pressure remains steadfast over the
Northeast. New England will be mainly sunny but onshore winds will
cause patchy clouds from the central Appalachians to the Middle
Atlantic Coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SLOW STORMS
</P>
<P>
   The season of slow storms has begun. For the next two months,
the jet stream will vacillate, retreating north as warmer air
arrives from the tropics, or surging south as the last chilly air
masses empty from the Arctic. Like a flooded river leaves behind
pools of standing water as it recedes into its banks, the jet
stream often leaves behind stagnant pools of cold air when it
retreats north. These high-level cold pools favor the development
of storms. During the next few days, a sluggish storm will bring
heavy snow to the Rockies. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
