<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOORE-COLUMN0319-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech coaching search could turn to Tubby
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville, TN _ The plot thickens in the search for Bobby
Cremins' successor at Georgia Tech, and the final chapter is
evolving into a doozy. Maybe, just maybe, the Yellow Jackets will
make the cow jump over the moon by hiring a former Bulldog who is a
current Wildcat.
</P>
<P>
   Tubby Smith to Tech?
</P>
<P>
   Oooooh.
</P>
<P>
   Could happen. In fact, if you believe the inside buzz (not to be
confused with Tech mascot Buzz) around the South Regional, the
Jackets already have asked Smith to become their new basketball
coach, with a wink and a nod from the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   This is for sure: If the buzz involving Smith and Tech isn't
true, Tech athletics director Dave Braine should change that in a
hurry. Like now. Smith has plenty of time to talk to Braine, since
Syracuse eliminated Kentucky on Saturday in the second round of the
Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of Cremins' 19 seasons at Tech ranged from the
start to the middle. Since then, the Jackets have missed the NCAA
Tournament six of the last seven years, which means just an average
Smith year at Tech would be huge. That's because an average Smith
year is great.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're wondering, it would make sense for Smith to skip
a fourth year inside the pressure cooker that is coaching Kentucky
basketball to enjoy the friendly confines of Alexander Memorial
Coliseum. In fact, if you're Smith, and you hear from Braine about
returning to the Peach State for the first time since your two
impressive seasons at Georgia during the mid-1990s, you flee.
</P>
<P>
   You sprint. You realize that Delta is ready when you are on the
way out of Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   Smith shouldn't have left the state of Georgia in the first
place. Along the way to becoming at least the Vince Dooley of
Bulldog hoops, he spent the first of his two seasons going to the
Sweet 16. That was in addition to Smith's two trips to the Sweet 16
with Tulsa. After Smith won 24 games in his second year at Georgia
along the way to the NCAA Tournament, it was off to Kentucky. He
spent his debut with the Wildcats doing the worst thing possible.
He won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Smith's Kentucky teams have been super, but not
superb, and that stinks for the demanding Wildcat fans.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Smith created an ongoing furor in the commonwealth when
he decided to use his son, Saul, as Kentucky's point guard. And you
just know the whining among Wildcat fans is heading for even higher
decibels after a near loss to St. Bonaventure on Thursday at the
Midwest Regional before that definite loss to Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   What all of this means is that you can ignore the smoke screen
around here that is filling the Gaylord Entertainment Center,
before Miami dribbles today against Ohio State. Miami athletics
director Paul Dee said Friday night that he gave permission three
weeks ago to his pal Braine to interview Miami coach Leonard
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hamilton is a wonderful coach, taking the Hurricanes to
three consecutive trips to the NCAA Tournament for the first time
in their history, he is no Smith. Neither is Seton Hall's Tommy
Amaker or Dayton's Oliver Purnell, nor any of the others falsely
rumored to be on Tech's short list.
</P>
<P>
   That's why those at Tech have to get Tubby if they can get
Tubby. And, according to the buzz, they can get Tubby.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
