<HEADER>
A1726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PRAGUE-CEMETERY-ART-2     03-19 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAGUE-CEMETERY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MODERN CITY DISTURBED BY ITS MEDIEVAL DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The discovery in downtown Prague of the
remnants of a medieval Jewish cemetery has turned into a political
and moral quandary for the Czech government and an embarrassment
for the small Czech Jewish minority.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Czech government will decide how best to
acknowledge the needs of modernity while respecting the dead, and
thus how to dampen the furor that has turned what began as a
construction project for an insurance company into a confusing,
hurtful and emotional battle between the Czechs and a large number
of Jews around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has come down to a question of economics versus
reconciliation,'' said Rabbi Marc Schneier, president of the North
American Boards of Rabbis, who has tried, along with the U.S.
Embassy here, to mediate the dispute. ``But I think reconciliation
will win out.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, he warned sadly, ``the situation could become
explosive,'' with worldwide demonstrations by Jews against the
Czech government. That would be a pity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Czechs are willing partners, they're not the enemy,''
Schneier went on. ``The problem is that there has been a lot of
misinformation, and the Prague Jewish community and some elements
of the international Jewish community are not on the same page
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Abraham Ginsberg, the London-based director of the
Committee for the Preservation of Jewish Cemeteries in Europe, is
more suspicious of the Czechs and of the insurance company. Still,
he says, ``I really don't know how it got so messy. We're pretty
confused, too. In 12 years, we've never had such a case.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Czech insurance company, Ceska Pojistovna, started work
on a new building on Vladislavova Street downtown, its biggest
concern was preserving the 19th-century facade of its old
headquarters and digging the underground parking garage for its
employees that the city of Prague mandated for new construction.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, as digging proceeded, some bones were discovered,
the first indication that a medieval Jewish cemetery, one of the
oldest found in Europe, still existed under the site. The cemetery
is believed to have been started in the 13th century, outside the
city's ancient walls, and probably served as the central burial
site for all Bohemia's Jews.
</P>
<P>
   As Prague expanded in the 15th century, King Vladislav Jagiello,
who had no great love for the Jews and for whom Vladislavova Street
is named, ordered the cemetery removed in 1478, and tombstones were
used for the construction of new houses. The first layer of the
cemetery, an area believed now to cover 8.4 acres (3.4 hectares),
or two city blocks, was thus desecrated. But archaeologists say
that at least another two levels of graves remain.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance company site covers only about 5 percent of the
ancient cemetery. A fence encircles the muddy area where bones were
found, a few yards below the current street.
</P>
<P>
   The company feels trapped, says Ludek Kozusko, head of the
company's construction department, which stopped work voluntarily
10 months ago, when the Ministry of Culture became involved.
``We've been waiting for 10 months,'' he said. ``So now we are
stuck just because we behaved decently.''
</P>
<P>
   After discussions with the chief rabbi of Prague, Karol Sidon,
and the government, the company worked out a deal last November _
or so it thought. By Jewish law and tradition, remains should not
be disturbed. So the idea _ similar to the treatment of an ancient
cemetery discovered in Hamburg, Ginsberg said _ was to slice out
the earth containing the remains, lower the entire section further
into the earth, seal it with concrete, then build over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't crazy about the solution,'' said Sidon, a former
dissident who is close to President Vaclav Havel. And Sidon soon
came under pressure from rabbis abroad, who believe that the graves
should not be disturbed at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Jewish community, with only some 1,500 active members
now, was isolated from foreign organizations until 1989 and the
fall of Communism, the rabbi said. ``I don't want to get us in that
position again,'' he said. At the same time, he said, without
foreign pressure even the more sensitive post-Communist state might
not have acted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So he got in touch with the chief Ashkenazic rabbi of Israel,
Yisrael Meir Lau, who sent his own expert, Rabbi Mendel Eckstein.
The result was a ruling that the graves already uncovered should be
left undisturbed in perpetuity, causing Sidon to pull out of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The company was inundated with angry letters and e-mails _
Schneier calls it ``a smear campaign'' _ accusing it of
anti-Semitism. Most of the angry letters presume, wrongly, that the
cemetery in question is the famous 15th-century Old Jewish Cemetery
in the former Jewish quarter, a haunting graveyard that has become
one of Prague's tourist landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Then another delicate issue erupted. Archaeologists called in
after the original digging had removed some 130 remains in 1997 and
1998 for testing. Placed in coffins, they had been put in an
existing Jewish cemetery, but Lau and other foreign rabbis insisted
that they be reburied in their original spot.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy helped to arrange a reburial ceremony on Feb.
24, and at least 100 people showed up. The company said there was a
safety risk and refused entry to the site. ``It turned into a
demonstration,'' said Ginsberg, who was there. ``We sat on the
ground and said prayers and lamentations and people started to
cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidon, uncomfortable, said: ``It's important to rebury the
bones. But it should have been done with the agreement of the
company. I mean, we don't really need people jumping in the air and
throwing themselves on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But the event underlined the increasing stakes. With a noted
liberal as its president, the Czech government _ a member of NATO,
in line to join the European Union and mindful of the isolation of
neighboring Austria since the right-wing party of Joerg Haider
entered government there last month _ is not eager to have the
confrontation worsen.
</P>
<P>
   The 130 remains have been put in a mausoleum, but Ginsberg said
that new demonstrations would be planned if the remains were not
reburied immediately at their original site.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered culture minister, Pavel Dostal, has finally come
up with proposals to be made at a Cabinet meeting this week. All
would declare the entire cemetery a cultural monument and ban new
construction, officials say. As for the company's site, the first
proposal would accept Lau's proscription, halting any further
building there and compensating the company for costs that could,
Kozusko says, reach $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   The second proposal would be the November compromise, involving
the sinking of the cemetery and its sealing. The third, which no
one takes seriously, would remove the remains and rebury them
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth idea, officials say, is to leave the area of the graves
undisturbed, but to build over it, possibly creating an enclosed
memorial space. It is also possible that the city will simply let
the company have an exception and build without a garage.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, however, Schneier fears it is too late for a
cultural compromise. He believes the government, to end the issue,
will choose the first option and compensate the company, perhaps
with contributions from Jews abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Sidon thinks there is plenty of blame to go around, and that
both his government and foreign Jews should be more sensitive to
each other's past.
</P>
<P>
   As for the insurance company, Vaclav Balek, a spokesman, says:
``We just want a decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
