<SLUG> BC-CANADA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRETIEN DISMISSES FEARS OF RIGHTWARD TREND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ When reporters needled Prime Minister Jean Chretien a
few days ago about unfavorable poll results, suggesting that he
should step aside, Canada's leader turned on them like a
lumberjack, saying: ``Listen to me _ I am the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Chretien opened the convention of his Liberal Party in Ottawa
this weekend declaring his rock solid intentions to run for a third
term in elections expected for May 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But some Liberals fear that Canada is tiring of Chretien, 66, a
populist who entered politics in 1963 just before John F. Kennedy
was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   While Chretien has led Canada since 1993, the Liberals only won
38 percent of the popular vote in the last election, in 1997. The
party won a narrow majority of the seats in the Parliament, largely
because the right split, delivering almost all of Ontario's 103
seats to the Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   But now many Liberals fear that Canada is shifting rightward,
joining a trend that has marked American and British politics in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Liberals, the center-right trend is lead by Paul
Martin, the country's 61-year-old finance minister, an advocate of
tax cuts. Polls published last week in Toronto newspapers, The Star
and The Globe and Mail, indicated that most Canadians would like
the prime minister to step aside in favor of his younger,
pro-business finance minister, who has a more modern image.
</P>
<P>
   With the Martin faction increasingly restless in Ontario, the
nation's economic and electoral powerhouse, a dozen Liberal members
of Parliament loyal to the finance minister secretly met with his
advisers recently in a Toronto airport hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting the challenge from the younger politician, Chretien was
recently photographed skiing in Quebec. Going into his party
convention, the last before next year's elections, he told
reporters: ``I am in good health and I will continue. I will see
you in the buses and the aircraft during the electoral campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   At a party caucus, which Martin chose to skip, Chretien warned
Liberal members of Parliament Wednesday night: ``I will not be
pushed through the door.''
</P>
<P>
   At the party conference, as Young Liberals supporting Chretien
chanted ``Four more years, four more years,'' he did not mention
tax cuts. Instead, he positioned his party as champions of the
poor, saying that ``the press, which is controlled by the big
financial interests,'' criticizes Liberals ``because we have
programs to help the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Canadian Liberals often run from the left and then
govern from the right, some analysts predict that if Chretien runs
next year, a new conservative coalition would make inroads into
Ontario, home province for one-third of the members of the House of
Commons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Paul Martin could become the leader any time soon, all
kinds of Ontario right-wing voters would stay with the Liberals,''
said Desmond Morton, a historian who directs McGill University's
Institute for the Study of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   To overcome a regional split among conservatives, the Reform
Party, based in the West, is trying to reinvent itself as a
national party, the Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance. In a
party convention next June, conservatives are expected to choose
between Preston Manning, 57, the the party's leader, and Stockwell
Day, 49, the treasurer of Alberta, an advocate of a flat income
tax.
</P>
<P>
   In his keynote speech Sunday night, Chretien directed much of
his fire at Day, lampooning a provincial flat tax that is to go
into effect next January in Alberta as ``the dream of millionaires
and the nightmare of average Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not let them erode medicare through creeping
privatization,'' Chretien said, in reference to Alberta's proposal
to allow overnight stays in private clinics. Referring to
conservatives' opposition to a federal revenue sharing system
designed to provide roughly equal services across Canada, he said:
``We will not let them scale down support for poorer regions of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Chretien urged Canadians to look at the conservative religious
belief that he contends is hidden behind Day's public image. ''We
don't want a party that is very much in the hands of the religious
right,'' Chretien told 2,500 Liberals Sunday night. Referring to
Day's opposition to abortion, he added: ``We do not want a party
that threatens a woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberal strategists believe that when the campaign begins they
will be aided by opinion polls that routinely give the Chretien
government approval ratings around 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What is in their favor, they say, is the best economic
performance since the 1960s. Canada's unemployment rate has dropped
to 7.6 percent, its growth rate has increased to about 4 percent,
inflation is around 2 percent, and a deep budget deficit has been
turned into a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   On the national unity front, the issue of Quebec separatism is
in hibernation. Last week, the House of Commons passed a ``Clarity
Bill'' designed to set clear rules for any future referendum on
secession.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Marzolini, whose firm conducts polls for the Liberals,
struck an upbeat note, telling convention delegates, ``Our
opponents are currently at their weakest point in history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
