<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SOUTH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCH MADNESS ON AUSTIN'S MUSIC FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEVA CHONIN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas &LR;   &LR; _ Austin was hit by two storms this weekend: One
involved high winds, spectacular flashes of lightning and rivers of
rain; the other offered high spending, occasional spectacular
flashes of talent and torrents of beer and tequila. Both have left
this cool little college town rumpled and nursing a happy hangover.
</P>
<P>
   Most will agree, though, that the latter outburst was more fun.
The 14th annual South by Southwest Music and Media Conference (SXSW
for short) swamped Austin with 7,000 schmoozing industry insiders
and music fans who watched some 900 bands, ranging from hometown
hero Rob Schneider to Japanese pop sensation Puffy, go wild on
stages throughout the city from Wednesday through Saturday nights.
It was a street party and club extravaganza par excellence _ but
then, it always is.
</P>
<P>
   What made this year's SXSW different from its earlier years was
a lack of industry hype: There was no trend du jour, no ``it'' band
claiming to embody the sound of the times.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of trending can be read several ways. On the optimistic
side, it's an encouraging statement on the survival of independent
music in a time when the word ``indie'' has been reduced to a
historical footnote. The effect of being unfashionable was mostly
positive. Freed from the pressure that comes with trying to be an
overnight success _ the hope still persists, but hope is not
expectation _ bands were free to enjoy themselves, play to fans and
future fans, and rib the chattering journalists, A&AMP;R reps and
publicists invariably clustered to the rear of the club.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, this could signal a return to the festival's heyday as
an extended meet-and-greet for industry outsiders. Some of the
weekend's best showcases were presented by smaller labels such as
the Bay Area's Man's Ruin and Lookout! Records, which hosted packed
lineups at the gritty but cool Emo's.
</P>
<P>
   More realistically, the lack of a defining sound or group could
be symptomatic of a calcified music industry's lack of direction;
for the first time in decades, no one is hazarding any guesses on
where music is headed in a post-everything age.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a buzz at SXSW, it was a philosophical one: Yes, it
is possible to survive and even flourish in the midst of a musical
depression. Patti Smith's Thursday performance at Waterloo Park _
her first Austin show in 20 years _ proved that she hasn't lost her
inspired edge after decades in the business. Steve Earle overcame
terrible sound and chilly temperatures to turn in a fine
performance at the outdoor Stubbs, and Cypress Hill, cashing in on
the rap-rock sound it probably helped inspire, debuted its new rock
incarnation to enthusiastic response.
</P>
<P>
   The Meat Puppets re-emerged for two shows with founder Curt
Kirkwood fronting a new lineup sans his legally and chemically
troubled brother, Cris. The veteran Mekons and their various
offshoots _ the Waco Brothers, Sally Timms' solo gigs _ gave fun,
fascinating testament to creative endurance, and the
indie-turned-major-turned-indie-again Guided by Voices attracted an
overflow crowd to a party thrown by Revolver Magazine, a new
publication bravely venturing into a shaky print market.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of newer talent to choose from, too. Texas' own
at the drive in sent MC5 and garage rock fans into a tailspin with
its frenetic live show, which featured group members literally
bouncing off the walls; Creeper Lagoon and Elliott Smith (playing
with a full band that included Quasi's Sam Coomes) were templates
of melodic grit. Songwriter Neko Case was moody and enchanting,
whether commanding her own stage or guesting with the Mekons on
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   If any act drew consensus raves it was Shelby Lynne, who was as
stunning in concert as she is on her gorgeous debut CD. Her two
Saturday performances _ one at an evening showcase, the other at an
afternoon party hosted by Interview magazine _ gave full play to
her elastic phrasing and pitch-perfect merger of blues-diva vocals
with country twang.
</P>
<P>
   There were the usual number of celebrity sightings over the
weekend, including Metallica's Lars Ulrich, who registered at the
Four Seasons under the name Sam Spade, and Neil Young, who turned
up in the audience at Jimmy Dale Gilmore's performance at the
Broken Spoke. Janeane Garofalo was spotted getting down to
Nashville Pussy at the Revolver party.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to say whether this year's hype-free SXSW was an
anomaly, a musical pit stop, the beginning of an end or the end to
a beginning. Considering the chaotic state of the music industry,
it could well be an amalgam of all four. One thing's for sure, and
this is really all the justification the festival needs: It was
about 900 bands more inspirational than the new 'N Sync album.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
