<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1732 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-LEE-NYT &LR;      03-19 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-LEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 MANY BLAME LONGTIME PARTY LEADER FOR NATIONALIST DEFEAT IN TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (With TAIWAN-CHINA, TAIWAN-ASSESS, TAIWAN-RIOTS) 
 (rk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ ``He betrayed Taiwan!'' ``He's a traitor who
sold out the Nationalist Party! ``He's a monster, lower than a
dog!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Step Down Lee! Step Down Lee!''
</P>
<P>
   The venom of the crowds here Sunday was directed at a man who
was long called ``Mr. Democracy'' _ the man who opened the clubby,
all-powerful Nationalist Party to the native Taiwanese majority,
the man who engineered Taiwan's first direct elections for
president and who bravely asserted the island's separate identity
against a hostile Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   That man, Lee Teng-hui, Taiwan's first elected president and the
chairman for the last dozen years of the Nationalists, who arrived
in the 1940s from mainland China, has been obsessed with his own
mission, once even comparing himself to Moses.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's achievements cannot be erased and are acknowledged by most
Taiwanese. Yet Sunday he had to be escorted from his party
headquarters under the cover of water cannons and riot police and
his political base appeared to be eroding fast, creating dangerous
political uncertainty for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   And if the thousands who openly vented their rage in the last
day were only a tiny share of the people, many of their criticisms
_ that he had become autocratic, ever more mired in political
corruption and reckless to the point of incompetence _ seemed to be
widely shared.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the complaints were rooted in recent events, especially
the Nationalists' election disaster on Saturday, while others
reflect festering ethnic and political resentments going back to
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now disliked by all kinds of people for different
reasons,'' said Lu Ya-li, a political scientist at National Taiwan
University.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the people blowing air horns and screaming
epithets outside Lee's residence and party offices, or milling
edgily at the headquarters of their new hero, James Soong, the
Nationalist who has now turned independent, were lifelong
Nationalists themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate cause of their emotional eruption was the
devastating defeat of Lien Chan, the Nationalists' own candidate
for president in Saturday's elections, alongside the near-victory
by Soong _ a former Nationalist icon elbowed aside by Lee, who thus
sowed the seeds for Saturday's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Many Nationalist supporters distrust the opposition leader Chen
Shui-bian, who won on Saturday with 39 percent of the vote. But it
was Lee's responsibility for the bitter split among the
Nationalists that was the main complaint Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To some outraged rank-and-file party members, the defeat
reflected inexcusable and selfish blunders by Lee and his failure
to democratize the party's own methods of candidate selection. With
a primary or other open process, many say, Soong would have been
the sole party candidate, and would have won handily.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the protesters in the streets said they believed much
worse: that Lee had intentionally schemed to get the
independence-leaning Chen elected, even if it meant the
near-destruction of their cherished Nationalist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Soong was once Lee's right-hand man at the party helm. He also
had helped Lee consolidate his power in the late 1980s: a
``mainlander'' himself, he helped persuade fellow skeptics among
those who fled China in 1949, when Chiang Kai-shek abandoned
Communist-dominated China for Taiwan, that they could accept Lee, a
Taiwan native with the island's distinctive rustic accent, as the
new national leader.
</P>
<P>
   Soong enjoyed strong support from the mainlanders, who with
their offspring make up less than 15 percent of Taiwan's population
of 22 million. Many of Sunday's demonstrators were mainlanders.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them, it was clear from their remarks, have long
resented what they considered Lee's takeover of the Nationalists.
What many saw as his increasingly dictatorial and unstable behavior
over the last four years, exemplified by his surprise announcement
of a ``state-to-state relationship'' with the mainland that caused
a crisis in relations with China last summer, only fed their
rancor.
</P>
<P>
   And now what many see _ with no real proof _ as his machinations
to further a secret pro-independence agenda is the last straw, an
unforgivable act of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   A more tangible and serious charge against Lee is that after
helping to bring free elections to Taiwan he failed to confront the
next hurdle to democracy, the island's notoriously sleazy politics.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say that while open vote-buying by the Nationalists
may be declining, improper links between politics and business and
even organized crime have if anything grown more prevalent as Lee
sought to preserve the Nationalist Party's power in local and
national elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a short-term view, always doing what was needed to win
the next election,'' said Shelley Rigger, the author of ``Politics
in Taiwan'' (Routledge, 1999) and a political scientist at Davidson
College in North Carolina, in an interview. ``The price is that the
party has gotten deeper and deeper into the world of dirty money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the downside to the Lee legacy,'' Rigger said. ``He
chose to go for the lazy win instead of the bold reforms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
