<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1733 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-TITUS-REVIEW-SFCHR     03-19 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TITUS-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDIAN AIRS HIS OWN FAMILY'S DIRTY LAUNDRY ON `TITUS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One casting note. Margot Kidder has signed to play an
eco-terrorist cannibal queen in the syndicated series ``Amazon.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark your calendars, and I mean now. It's a three-episode story
arc beginning April 22. Wonder if they know that's Earth Day?
</P>
<P>
   To business. This is the TV season of the chatterbox, and
stand-up comic Christopher Titus comes out with some heavy gab at
the top of his new, autobiographical Fox show, ``Titus,'' which
premieres Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Back to Kidder. I'm just thinking, is there any chance she'll
talk while she eats?)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Titus, a lanky man with choppy blond hair, comes into a
sparsely furnished room and clicks on a bare lightbulb overhead.
The camera pulls in tight. He begins talking to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Los Angeles Times states 63 percent of American families
are now considered dysfunctional,'' he says. ``That means we're the
majority. We're normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people that had the mom, dad, sister, little white
picket fence _ those people are the freaks. Normal people'' _ seems
he forgot what he said just a moment ago _ ''terrify me, because
they haven't had enough problems in their lives to know how to
handle problems when they come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the gist of the story that follows, and all the
stories in the three episodes Fox sent for preview, involve Titus'
not knowing how to handle problems when they come up.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the possibility that his father (played by Stacy Keach)
might be dead behind his bedroom door. See, it's been several days
since Dad emerged for a beer. Christopher, his dimwit brother Dave
(Zack Ward) and Christopher's girlfriend Erin (Cynthia Watros)
assume that he's dead.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has the nerve to open the door and check.
</P>
<P>
   So the dysfunctional part is genuine. Titus, in a recent
interview, said his real father has been married half a dozen
times.
</P>
<P>
   And, as in the show, his mother was institutionalized in a
mental asylum. Or, as Keach breaks the news to a much younger
Christopher in the show, ``Son, your mom is shacked up in the wacko
basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The show hops around. It's Titus addressing the audience. It's
Titus as a kid, enduring a beer-swilling father with a penchant for
macho carelessness. And it's Titus' present-day predicaments, many
revolving around Erin. She's based on Titus' real-life wife, Erin.
</P>
<P>
   If you can get past being chatted up by Titus, and the studio
audience laughter that seems to have been cranked up without mercy,
``Titus'' has its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   It's a brisk show with a young sensibility. Titus himself wears
surprisingly well once you get into the show, Keach is gruffly
imposing with a deft comic edge, and Watros unfailingly lights up
the place.
</P>
<P>
   The show is also, surely, about as far as network TV can stray
from the old ``Father Knows Best'' conventions without groans and
winces where there are supposed to be laughs.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sort of signal scene in which the childhood Titus is
beginning to extend a finger toward an electrical socket. His
mother, or possibly stepmom _ apparently we'll never see a full
facial shot of any of the elder Titus' wives _ moves to help. Dad
calls her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, go on,'' he says to the boy.
</P>
<P>
   There's a crackling sound. The light in the room flickers.
</P>
<P>
   Dad: ``Bet you're not going to do that again, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   I can't say for sure where Titus' real-life experiences merge
into fiction on the show. But when he was asked in January about
his mother and stepmothers, he said this: ``My brother's mom, I
still talk to her. I talk to my second one. My third one, I haven't
heard from in a while. My sixth one, we talk on and off. But there
are times we have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his real father, Titus said he demanded and got a new car
in exchange for being ridiculed on the show. A customized Ford
Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
