<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-NYT &LR;      03-19 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEEP FEELING THAT TAIWAN IS CHINA'S IS PUT TO TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Mulling over the shocking fact that Taiwan had chosen
the independence party, if not independence, in Saturday's
presidential election, a common response of many Chinese in Beijing
on Sunday was the nervous question: Do you think there will be war?
</P>
<P>
   Many shook their heads at the possibility. Although Beijing's
leaders have been silent about the victory of Chen Shui-bian, every
educated Beijinger now seems to know the details from satellite TV
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that Taiwan will inevitably reunite with the mainland
is probably the most emotional, deeply held belief of ordinary
Chinese, from college students to retired factory workers. Last
week, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji said 1.25 billion Chinese would be
willing to ``spill blood'' to prevent its independence.
</P>
<P>
   But Chen's upset victory forced many Chinese to reflect for the
first time on the depth of their conviction, pitting their abstract
belief that the return of Taiwan is manifest destiny, against their
personal self-interest, since war would mean renewed hardship in a
country that has only recently improved its living standards.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday night the Chinese government issued its only
reaction to the victory, a brief, moderate statement, which said in
part, ``We will listen to the words and observe the actions of
Taiwan's new leader, and wait and see in which direction he takes
cross-strait relations.''
</P>
<P>
   A government poll released last week showed that 95 percent of
Chinese approved using military force if Taiwan sought
independence. But Sunday, the emotions behind that figure were
complex and contradictory. Although most Chinese will say they care
deeply about Taiwan, many are personally ambivalent about fighting
for the cause, even if they think a fight is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly believe that Taiwan should return to the
motherland; after Hong Kong and Macao, it is the only one left,''
said a 20-year-old English major at People's University, who gave
her name as Xuan. ``But we don't support the use of force. That
wouldn't be good for anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Xuan, like many other young Chinese, has seen living standards
rise significantly in the last decade and has seen society change,
as China has opened its doors to Western culture and business. The
growing young elite watch NBA games, invest in stocks, travel
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   And the young elite know that a war with Taiwan, which would
almost certainly draw in the United States, would mean a return to
a more austere and isolationist life.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for non-Chinese to understand the depths of the
Chinese devotion to Taiwan, which is born partly of decades of
Communist Party propaganda and partly of the humiliations of
China's history, when Westerners carved up China for their economic
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``China was divided when it was weak, and now that it is getting
strong again, people's nationalist feeling rises and they feel
strongly it is time to reunite the country,'' said Zhang Yunling,
the head of South Asian Studies at the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there is a strong conviction here that countries
naturally strive to keep every inch of land, no matter how remote
or at what cost. Chinese officials are wont to ask American
reporters how Americans would respond if Alaska or Hawaii tried to
secede. They seem disbelieving when the question is answered with
an indifferent shrug.
</P>
<P>
   And for many Chinese today, that deep emotional attachment still
governs their views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinary people just want to get on with their lives, and
whether Taiwan becomes independent has no effect on them,'' said
Wang Wei, a store manager, who said he watched Taiwan's election
returns on a Hong Kong television station with some army friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``if Taiwan does take steps toward
independence, we'll surely just have to give them a beating.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were less quick to the draw and hoped that their
government _ most known for its unyielding behavior _ would make
compromises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both sides will have to make adjustments to their
policies,'' said a 22-year-old physics major at Beijing University,
who refused to give his name. ``After all, Taiwan is democratic
now, and the people have exercised their own right to choose a
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he too ``accepted that war was inevitable'' if Taiwan
declared independence, saying he personally could not bear the
thought of China's being divided forever. He added:
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of unity is very important to the Chinese people, and
we treasure the idea. These ideas have sunken deeply into people's
minds, and we just accept them and wouldn't think of changing
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
