<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-THEATER-MOON-REVIEW-S     03-19 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-MOON-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MESMERIZING `MOON' 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK &LR;   &LR; _ Everyone who loves great acting here had the
Broadway revival of ``A Moon for the Misbegotten'' penciled in to
their spring calendars long before it opened Sunday at the Walter
Kerr Theatre. The chief lure was Cherry Jones, the sublime star of
``The Heiress'' a few seasons back, who is playing the sensual and
beneficent Josie Hogan in Eugene O'Neill's late comic tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Jones gives a carefully crafted and admirable performance as a
big-boned country girl in love with an alcoholic Broadway actor.
But the great acting in the show _ the heart-shattering,
spontaneous glory of this ``Moon'' _ comes from the two male leads,
Roy Dotrice and especially Gabriel Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Plunging through the bourbon fumes and flirtatious charms of
James Tyrone Jr., Byrne reveals the acrid self-loathing and raw,
unreachable pain of the character closely based on the playwright's
doomed older brother. The climax comes in a mighty third-act
monologue of guilt and glimmering redemption that could stand alone
like a great aria.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne, the noted Irish film actor (``Miller's Crossing,'' ``End
of Days''), has a droll sense of playfulness in his early scenes
with Josie and her father, Phil.
</P>
<P>
   Dotrice is a perfect scoundrel as this tenant pig farmer, a
conniving scamp with an opportunist's flinty eye and a clockwork
sense of comic timing. He's as eager to dismiss his own son as ``a
pious lump'' as he is to taunt a snooty oil man neighbor (Tuck
Milligan) who makes the mistake of appearing at the Hogan shack
with a riding crop to register a complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moon'' turns on a series of tricks and ill-conceived schemes.
Phil has designs on the Tyrone family money, and he'd like to get
his daughter in bed with his landlord James to blackmail him out of
some. Josie, who dodges and weaves around her own romantic resume,
is willing to see what happens when she gets James alone in the
moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   James gets into the spirit with his own gambit, pretending that
he's agreed to sell the Hogan farm to the oil man Harder. Further
feints and double-crosses complicate matters and, when the air
clears, finally convince Josie of James' goodness.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Moon,'' written as a kind of spiritual epilogue to the
Tyrone family chronicle of ``Long Day's Journey Into Night,''
doesn't rise or fall on plot. Like a lot of O'Neill's work, it
drifts toward deep, endlessly rolling waters that seem to set the
characters afloat in a vast darkness of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when James staggers back to the Hogan farm,
2 1/2 hours late and already well lubricated for his moonlit
rendezvous with Josie. Maddened by more bourbon to the point of
nearly raping her, he's driven at last to tell the story of his
mother's death. It all spills out of him like water freed from a
damn: her deathbed disappointment in his drinking, the awful train
trip home from California with her corpse and the whore he
entertained in another car.
</P>
<P>
   Cradled in Josie's arms, his body pooled there in exhaustion and
relief as he confesses his sins to her, Byrne carries the audience
along with James to the bottom. It's an astonishing, soul-scouring
feat.
</P>
<P>
   When he blinks his eyes open after a dreamless sleep, he seems
lighter, almost buoyant. Even his hangover is a blessing _ the
``heebie-jeebies'' are gone. But Byrne makes us see that this new,
unburdened James is also mortally fragile. Picking his way offstage
at the end, it's clear, he will never find his way back again.
</P>
<P>
   Josie is the agent and witness of it all. Jones plays her with a
blend of blunt physicality and soft-spoken tact. She swaggers
around in ungainly boots, thumping her body against the beaten
clapboard of Eugene Lee's set, hands on hips, her much-admired
breasts thrust out.
</P>
<P>
   Jones does a lot with her legs, which fall wide open when she
sits, shins bared. She's her father's trailer-trash equal when it
comes to tormenting Harder. Her voice, meanwhile, is touched with
wistful sweetness. Her neatly trimmed hair shines.
</P>
<P>
   Director Daniel Sullivan treats her like an improbable thing of
beauty. He blocks some key scenes with Josie's backside to the
audience and frames parts of her body now and then in the shack's
windows.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very skillfully worked out, but Jones' Josie never
comes together as a rounded character. The component parts shift in
and out of view _ the vigor and vulnerability, the surges of love
and wary misgivings _ without creating a bigger picture.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, the veteran Broadway director of Wendy Wasserstein,
Herb Gardner and others, is more at home with the play's comic
scenes. Dotrice's devilish glitter fades to pale self-negation. The
fourth act stutters.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne's performance gives this ``Moon'' its glowing center.
Audiences may come to see Jones. They'll come away with Byrne's
James Tyrone Jr. burned into their memories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
