<SLUG> BC-POPE-MIDEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE'S VISIT TO MIDEAST SEEN AS SPIRITUAL, POLITICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ When Pope John Paul II arrives here Monday he
begins what the Vatican insists is a deeply personal and spiritual
pilgrimage, and not a political journey.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the Middle East, and he is the pope.
</P>
<P>
   So nearly everything about the 79-year-old pontiff's visit to
Israel and the Palestinian territories _ a path strewn with
land-mine issues such as the future of Jerusalem, Palestinian
independence, and the haunting history of the Holocaust _ is seen
here as political.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six days, John Paul will follow in the footsteps
of Jesus and revisit the roots of his faith _ a trip that took five
years of intense diplomatic and logistical preparations and which
celebrates this Jubilee Year dedicated to the 2,000th anniversary
of the birth of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time a pope has visited Israel since Pope
Paul VI in 1964. In the interim, two Arab-Israeli wars were fought,
the Palestinian uprising exploded, the Persian Gulf War engulfed
the region and then cleared the way for a peace process that has
become tortuously bogged down.
</P>
<P>
   And in all that time, John Paul becomes the first pope ever to
visit Israel since the Holy See recognized the state of Israel in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul has said he sees the journey as the crowning of a
21-year reign that has taken him to more than 90 countries. His has
been a papacy of breathtaking change, from his role in the
political demise of the Soviet Union beginning in his native Poland
in the early 1980s; to this month's sweeping apology for sins of
Catholics from the brutality of the Crusades to the injustice of
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   The pope is scheduled to ascend Mount Nebo, where Moses died
after leading the Israelites out of Egyptian captivity before they
crossed over the Jordan and into the Promised Land. It is one more
step in what he calls the path of Abraham, the patriarch that binds
together Jews, Christians, and Muslims in their belief in one God.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the pope plans to celebrate Mass in an Amman stadium for
the small minority of Roman Catholics in this overwhelmingly Muslim
kingdom. Then he will go to the banks of the River Jordan, where
Jesus was baptized by John.
</P>
<P>
   From Jordan, the pontiff will travel to Bethlehem, where Jesus
was born, to Nazareth, where he grew up, to the Galilee, where he
centered his ministry, and to Jerusalem, where he was crucified.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's very presence in Jerusalem is seen as politically
charged, since both Israelis and Palestinians claim the Holy City
as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Israel says that Jerusalem is its eternal and indivisible
capital. The Palestinians say that East Jerusalem and the Old City,
which were captured by Israel in the 1967 Six Day War from Jordan,
should be the capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican _ and most of the governments of the world including
the United States _ say that the future of Jerusalem should be
determined at the final peace talks between Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides seem to be angling to use the pope's visit to
legitimize their claims as he arrives at a critical time just
months before the final peace talks are set to begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael McGarry, rector of Tantour, a theological
institute established by the Vatican in Jerusalem, said: ``One way
to think of this trip is visually. What will be the defining image?
The pope holding a Palestinian child at a refugee camp? The pope
praying at the Western Wall? The pope visiting Yad Vashem?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the end it will be all of these images, and the
political sides will choose whichever image they want to focus
on,'' McGarry said. ``But I think for the pope, this trip is a
spiritual pilgrimage. That is the image he comes here with.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, John Paul will visit Yad Vashem, the Israeli
Holocaust memorial, and Deheishe Refugee Camp, one of the many
where the estimated 3.5 million Palestinian refugees ended up after
being displaced by the Arab-Israeli wars of 1948 and 1967. He will
meet Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime minister, and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian Authority president.
</P>
<P>
   But even this carefully balanced itinerary could touch off
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Rosen, a key figure in the dialogue between the
Vatican and Israel who has met with the pontiff on a dozen
occassions in recent years, has praised his relentless effort to
bridge the gulf between Catholics and Jews. But he said the Vatican
must be careful not to make it appear that the Yad Vashem visit is
being balanced against the Palestinian refugee camp visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does this he will stumble into one of the most
dangerously emotional pitfalls in the Middle East. The two historic
occurrences are simply not comparable,'' said Rosen, who is the
director of the Anti-Defamation League in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``To even set up an itinerary that suggests that the loss of 6
million Jews in the Holocaust could be compared to the Palestinian
refugee problem, as serious and real an issue as that is, is
something that would strike a very sensitive nerve in Israel,''
Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul visits one week after a historic act of contrition by
the church. The pope issued a sweeping apology for sins of
Catholics, from atrocities of the Crusades and the Inquisition, to
brutal acts against Jews in which Catholics participated.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israelis and Jews worldwide have welcomed this, but many
also took notice that the Pope did not specifically mention the
Holocaust in his March 12 ``Day of Pardon'' Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Some extremists in Israel are vowing to protest the pope's
visit, and Sunday, swastikas were painted on the helipad where the
pope is to arrive in Tel Aviv and fake blood was spattered on
welcome signs.
</P>
<P>
   David Kimche, president of the Israel Council on Foreign
Relations and a former ambassador-at-large for Israel, said: ``What
was not said in Rome left a bitter aftertaste . . . I hope that
what was not said in Rome will be said in Jerusalem. If not, the
bitter aftertaste will remain.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Israelis are not the only ones waiting for words of
repentence.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Naim Ateek, an Anglican priest and Palestinian
theologian, said Palestinians are hoping that the pope will use his
moral authority to encourage Israel ``to apologize for the
oppression of Palestinians.'' He hopes that the visit to the
refugee camp will enlighten the world to the right of return of
Palestinian refugees, another particularly thorny issue to be
resolved at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope will come here for a short time, but we are going to
live here for a long time,'' said Ateek, a powerful voice in the
Christian minority of the predominantly Muslim Palestinian
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a strong statement from the pope that will make it
clear that the people who are oppressed and who live under
occupation are the Palestinians,'' Ateek said. ``If the pope does
not do it, some of us are going to be embarassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Christians _ half of them Eastern Orthodox, a third Roman
Catholic, and the rest various denominations of Orthodoxy and
Protestantism _ are less than 2 percent of the total population in
Israel, the West Bank, and Gaza. In Jordan, the Christians
represent about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Arab Christians' diminishing presence in the Middle East is
another sensitive issue that the pope will face in his trip, and
many Christian leaders are hoping that he will address their plight
as a minority caught between a powerful Jewish state that sees them
as Palestinian and a surging Palestinian Muslim population that
often overlooks their concerns as a Christian minority. The result
is that Christians are emigrating at a high rate to the United
States, Canada, Australia, and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Sabella, a professor at Bethlehem University and
director of the International Christian Committee, who has
documented the diminishing Christian presence in the Holy Land,
said, ``The pope's presence is very important to Christians
regardless of denomination. He doesn't need to say anything
directly to us, or anything directly political. All he needs to do
is show how important the Christian presence is in the Holy Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcel DuBois, professor at Hebrew University and the winner of
the Israel Prize for decades of scholarship to promote
understanding between Jews and Christians, said, ``The Pope is
coming back to the sources of his faith, and he does this as a
prilgrim. I think all of the attention on the political issues
misses the point, the personal holiness of John Paul II. This is
genuine. And this is the reason he is here despite the way everyone
will interpret it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
