<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1748 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-BLACKMAN-BOS     03-19 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BLACKMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT L. ``BOB'' BLACKMAN, 81; LONGTIME DARTMOUTH COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert L. ``Bob'' Blackman, who coached Dartmouth College to
undefeated seasons in 1962 and 1965 and devised innovative plays _
including one that helped put the Tennessee Titans into the Super
Bowl this year _ died Friday. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Blackman died after contracting an unknown disease while
touring Singapore and Malaysia, his wife, Kay, said. He was deemed
well enough to return to his home in Hilton Head, S.C., but he fell
ill again during the flight, she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the plane made an emergency landing in San Francisco, Mr.
Blackman was taken to Peninsula Medical Center in Burlingame,
Calif., where he died of complications.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Blackman also coached at the University of Illinois and
Cornell University, but he made his mark at Dartmouth and was
inducted into the College Football Hall of Fame in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He began his coaching career as a student at the University of
Southern California after his own promising career was derailed
when he contracted polio during his freshman year. Unable to
abandon the sport, Mr. Blackman became a student assistant to the
coaching staff at USC.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, he coached several naval base teams during
World War II. He coached Monrovia High School in California after
the war before taking a position at Pasadena City College, where
his 1951 team won the National Junior College championship.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after two years at Denver University, Mr. Blackman
succeeded Tuss McLaughry at Dartmouth in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a revelation to me,'' retired Boston Globe columnist
and former Darmouth sports information director Ernie Roberts said
Saturday from his home in Hobe Sound, Fla. ``He was an innovator in
what seemed to be mundane things, such as the way the team came out
of the dressing room and broke up into groups, with every group at
a particular part of the field, like The Rockettes. Everything was
organized. He didn't leave anything to chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Blackman was remembered as an imaginative coach, with many
people pointing to the final play in this season's NFL playoff
match between the Buffalo Bills and the Titans: a kickoff return
that ended with a cross-field lateral that led to the winning
touchdown. Mr. Blackman has been credited as the originator of the
play, which he once used to beat Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   In 16 seasons, Dartmouth garnered seven Ivy League titles and
tied for three more. Mr. Blackman's 1970 team, his last at
Dartmouth, is considered among the best in school history,
compiling a 9-0 record while outscoring opponents by a 311-42
margin. That season also included six shutouts. The team received
the Lambert Trophy as the best college football team in the East
that year, beating out Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   When he retired from Dartmouth, Mr. Blackman left as the
winningest coach in school history with a record of 104-37-3. Years
later, he was made an honorary member of Dartmouth's Class of 1941,
the year Mr. Blackman graduated from USC.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, Mr. Blackman was affiliated with the East-West
Shrine Game.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Mr. Blackman leaves his daughter,
Julie, of Hilton Head, S.C. Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
