<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Siemens and Mannesmann to Form Car-Parts Venture
</P>
<P>
   Siemens of Germany said that its car-parts unit was planning a
partnership with Mannesmann's VDO auto-parts business in the face
of mounting competition in the car industry.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens and Mannesmann's Atecs, which intends to sell shares in
an initial public offering, will hold equal stakes in VDO,
according to published reports in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Method Behind Gladwell.com
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker writer Malcolm Gladwell operates his own Web
site, which offers all his articles online and excerpts from his
new book, ``The Tipping Point.'' But Gladwell.com is not a
promotional device. Gladwell said he started the site in part to
interact with visitors who e-mail their comments and ideas, and who
also unwittingly offer themselves up as a kind of human petri dish
for Gladwell's interests in science, pop anthropology and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Pan Am Workers Win Pension Ruling
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has sided with employees of Pan American World
Airways in a case related to their pension plan and the way it was
administered by a federal agency after the airline went out of
business. The ruling may lead to an increase in pension payments
for some of the 65,000 people who worked for Pan Am when it went
out of business in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Grappling Over a Documentary
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond the Mat,'' a documentary on the characters who make
their livings in the middle and lower ranks of pro wrestling,
opened on Friday in 50 cities. But prospects for the film were
greatly diminished, the film's producers say, after a decision by
the World Wrestling Federation not to allow television advertising
for the documentary during any of the pro wrestling group's
programs.
</P>
<P>
   A Putin Biography Made in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   PublicAffairs, a New York company that is fast becoming the
publishing house for Kremlin politicians, is preparing to rush into
print in May with an English translation of the memoirs describing
the life of Russia's acting president, Vladimir V. Putin. The
original Russian version of ``First Person'' is still unavailable
in Russia, where the country's Central Electoral Commission has
barred publication until after the March 26 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers Tread Carefully With Web
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies have acknowledged the Internet's potential
for simplifying the byzantine process of finding insurance quotes
and applying for coverage, but they also note the downsides:
Consumers, they say, cannot use the Web to speak with real people
in real time about the complexities of coverage; and by selling
directly to consumers through their own Web sites, the companies
risk an insurrection among the insurance agents who have been their
bedrock source of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's High Tech Courtship
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole _ the former senator and presidential nominee as well
as a ``special counsel'' at a powerhouse Washington law firm _
helped host an event last week that introduced EqualFooting.com, a
dot-com that plans to create an online marketplace where small
businesses would buy industrial supplies. The law firm's courtship
of dot-coms demonstrates how little distance is left between the
high-tech world, once staunchly unwilling to cozy up to Capitol
Hill, and the inside-the-beltway elite, formerly dismissive of the
Internet's role in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising's Other Super Bowl
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar presentation on ABC has traditionally been the
second-biggest day of the year for advertising, trailing only the
Super Bowl. That demand continues this year because there is still
no end in sight to the strong demand for commercial time among
marketers _ whether dot-com or not-com _ which has intensified
their need to break through the clutter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
