<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1751 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-RIOTS-2TAKES(T     03-19 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-RIOTS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOTS ROCK TAIPEI DAY AFTER NATIONALISTS ARE OUSTED FROM POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ A day after Taiwan's Nationalist Party was
swept from power after more than 50 years, the fury of the losers
erupted Sunday night, forcing President Lee Teng-hui to barricade
himself inside his party headquarters as thousands of disaffected
supporters battled with the police for hours.
</P>
<P>
   While the worst riots in a decade raged outside the building _
sealed like a fortress with cordons of riot policemen and powerful
water cannons _ Lee bowed somewhat to the intense anger, and agreed
to step down as party chairman in September, a year earlier than
planned. Three senior party leaders submitted their resignations,
but in the turmoil, Lee refused to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling of the Nationalist Party after its candidate
finished last in a bitter three-way presidential race poses huge
potential dangers for Taiwan at a time of delicate transition.
</P>
<P>
   The country's newly elected president, the opposition leader
Chen Shui-bian, is viewed with deep suspicion by China for his past
advocacy of Taiwanese independence. So far, Beijing has had no
official reaction to his election, but Washington is so concerned
that senior administration men have been dispatched to China to
keep tensions from escalating.
</P>
<P>
   After a half-century of iron rule, the Nationalists are being
replaced by Chen and his Democratic Progressive Party, which with
the legislature still under Nationalist control, will preside over
a divided government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, James Soong, the former Nationalist who ran as an
independent and finished a close second in Saturday's election,
announced the formation of a new party, in effective splitting the
Nationalist movement.
</P>
<P>
   If Lee is forced out as the Nationalists' chairman, it is
unclear how effectively he could govern Taiwan until May 20, when
Chen is inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
   Chen sought to cool tempers, saying: ``With the end of the
election, fervor should also become a thing of the past. We hope
everyone will calm down so things can slowly return to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the magnitude of their defeat became clear to the
Nationalists, the tensions long simmering in their ranks exploded
into the streets of this normally tranquil capital.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters, the vast majority of them supporters of Soong, cried
``Lee Teng-hui is a traitor!'' and pelted the Nationalists'
headquarters with eggs and stones. They set upon the arriving cars
of Nationalist officials, smashing windshields. One adviser to Lee
was dragged out of his car and beaten; another fled in a panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KMT is very weak now,'' said Lee Ching-ping, who attended
Sunday's emergency meeting of the Kuomintang, as the Nationalists
are known in Taiwan. ``The question is: Who will be the next leader
of the party?''
</P>
<P>
   For the party, Lee's departure would leave a major vacuum. The
charismatic, 79-year-old president has utterly dominated the
Nationalists for more than decade, since he succeeded Chiang
Ching-kuo in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee's leadership has been more divisive than is commonly
thought in the outside world, where he is viewed as the man who
brought democracy to Taiwan. In recent years, the party has become
split between native-born Taiwanese _ like Lee _ who favor taking a
strong line toward China, and mainland-born people _ like Soong _
who favor a more conciliatory approach.
</P>
<P>
   Lee ignited a firestorm in July when he announced that Taiwan
and China could negotiate reunification only on a ``special
state-to-state'' basis. China, which views Taiwan as a renegade
province, denounced Lee for taking the first steps toward Taiwan
independence.
</P>
<P>
   The party split was aggravated when Lee clashed with Soong, a
Nationalist heavyweight who had become one of the country's most
popular politicians as the provincial governor of Taiwan. After Lee
picked the more reserved Lien Chan instead of Soong to be his
designated successor, Soong declared that he would run as an
independent and was expelled from the party.
</P>
<P>
   The feud between Lee and Soong was so bitter that supporters of
Soong believe that the president would have done anything to defeat
his candidacy _ even if it meant throwing the election to the
opposition's candidate, Chen. Although Lee campaigned on behalf of
the Nationalist candidate, Lien, his support was perceived as less
than passionate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Chen's past support for Taiwan independence is seen by
many as closer to Lee's position than either Soong's or Lien's.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Chen drew 39 percent of the vote, while Soong won 36
percent and Lien 23 percent. Some political analysts said Lien's
weakness played to Chen's advantage. And that, to the protesters,
was proof that Lee had orchestrated his own party's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This party has a 100-year history, and he sold it out in a
single election,'' said Jerry Ho, 31, a businessman. ``His strategy
was to pull down Lien's vote, so Chen would win the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho said he believed that 95 percent of the protesters accepted
the result of the election and the legitimacy of the new president.
But he said the demonstrators wanted to hold Lee accountable for
his role.
</P>
<P>
   Another demonstrator who gave his name as Chen said Lee was ``a
traitor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough for him to step down in a few months,'' said
Chen, as he clutched one of the hundreds of air horns that were
being sounded in a deafening cacophony of rage. ``We want him to
resign immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Soong sought to channel the anger of his
supporters. He announced that he would create a new political party
to challenge the primacy of the Nationalists. The party, which does
not yet have a name, would be similar to the Nationalists in
ideology, he said, but would be cleaner, breaking with the
corruption that long characterized Nationalist rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KMT has gone against the wishes of the people and against
the democratic process,'' Soong said, as hundreds of cheering
supporters mobbed the streets outside his campaign headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the mayhem across town, Soong urged his supporters to
be ``calm and rational'' and avoid ``bloodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Soong left the door open to a possible reconciliation with the
Nationalists, saying he would pursue talks with other parties. It
was not clear whether he could bridge the gap with his former
colleagues, though some officials of the Nationalist Party are
reportedly eager to see Soong return.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was clear Sunday that Lee was losing support, even among
Nationalist officials who had not defected to Soong's camp. Sunday
night, Ma Ying-jeou, the popular mayor of Taipei, tried to calm the
demonstrators by telling them that he would pass on to Lee their
demand for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Ma, who is one of Nationalists' rising stars, earlier faxed in
his resignation from the party's standing committee. Lien, humbled
by his poor showing in the election, also submitted his resignation
as deputy chairman of the party. But neither Lien and Ma were able
to attend the emergency party meeting because the building's
entrance was blocked by dozens of howling protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Those people who got close wound up being attacked. Witnesses
said Hsu Li-teh, a top adviser to Lee, was pulled out of his car
and beaten. Wang Jyng-ping, the speaker of the legislature, fled
from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Lee managed to get into the building. But after the meeting,
protesters trapped him inside for several hours by crowding around
the exits. He finally escaped after 5:30 p.m. when a phalanx of
riot policemen and a water-cannon truck cleared a path for his
motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   Lee did not issue a statement. And political analysts cautioned
that the president was not likely to give up his position without a
fight. But on the day that Taiwan opened a new chapter in its
political history, he increasingly seemed like a relic _ and the
party he heads bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think of the Kuomintang as this huge, powerful
party,'' said James D. Seymour, a senior research scholar at the
East Asian Institute of Columbia University. ``But we found out
this weekend that the emperor has no clothes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
