<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TY SHINE'S GAME EXCEEDS HIS DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Caught between the past and the future, Ty Shine
will always have Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   He will always have the game in which he came off the bench
shooting because ``that's who I am, I'm a firing kind of player.''
</P>
<P>
   For two years he has been the backup at Seton Hall, starting
mainly when Shaheen Holloway was injured. Next year the school is
bringing in Andre Barrett from Rice High in New York, perhaps the
top point-guard prospect in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In these post-Marbury-Iverson days, point guards do not enroll
in college for the luxury of being apprentices. There were even
rumors that Shine had mused about transferring, something he denied
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't think too much about that,'' Shine said. ``Coach is
trying to build something here. You need kids like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was being the good soldier in a moment when he could have
gloated or bargained or whined. Perhaps he is destined to always be
an interim point guard, but Sunday Ty Shine produced one of the
epic victories of the new Tommy Amaker regime, or any other epoch
at the New Jersey school.
</P>
<P>
   In the time it took for Holloway to fall awkwardly and sprain
his left ankle eight minutes into the game, Ty Shine went from
backup to the only recourse. He pumped in 26 points in 37 minutes,
including the consummate 3-pointer that put Seton Hall ahead to
stay in a 67-65 overtime victory over Temple in the second round of
the national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that good things come to people who wait,'' he said.
``Today is a perfect example.''
</P>
<P>
   Shine said he kept his spirits up through constant telephone
contact with his grandmother, Julia Shine, and his mother, Barbara
Shine, back home in Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother tells me to be patient,'' he said Sunday.
``She's old. She knows a lot. People say I'm a mama's boy because I
call my mother every day, sometimes two or three times at night,
when she comes home from work. Telephone cards. Lots of telephone
cards.''
</P>
<P>
   In a gloomy winter of a fatal dormitory fire on the campus in
South Orange, N.J., Shine tried to stay positive. He had played 521
minutes in 30 games, had a decent 7.1 scoring average, but he had
never started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Shine admitted. ``I wait my turn. I had to deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is grateful because there were players at the local
park in Augusta ``who never got their chance for whatever reason.''
Instead, he played a senior season in Cincinnati, put in another
year in prep school and came to Seton Hall because ``I wanted to go
to a school that was down, that was trying to get back to where it
used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He started eight times last season, a bit longer than Holloway
might have liked, but eventually Holloway was back handling the
ball, and Shine was spending more than half the game on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an outstanding player,'' said Amaker, the suave Dukie who
seems a trifle out of place in his current ex-urban New Jersey
milieu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who has seen him knows that,'' Amaker said about
Shine. ``They go against each other in practice, and competition
makes people better.''
</P>
<P>
   In his state of magnanimity, Shine agreed with that Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk trash,'' Shine said. ``I have confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Shine was on the bench when Holloway was carried toward
the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting ready to come in,'' Shine said. ``I'm used to
it. I gave a boost last year and I tried to give a lift today. We
were kind of down, and firing was the best thing I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his first three shots from 3-point range, and brought
Seton Hall back into the game. Then, when the adrenaline might have
been expected to wear off, he kept firing. He started to look a
little rubbery in overtime, but when Greg Morton set a perfect pick
he popped in a 3-pointer that put Seton Hall ahead, 66-65. And when
it was over, Shine did not have much reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying when I went over to talk on television,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a big Kenny Anderson fan when I was a kid,'' he said,
referring to the pro star who passed through Georgia Tech in a
hurry. ``I couldn't picture myself in these kinds of games. I've
never had a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   His raw delight was in contrast to Holloway's sense of
entitlement when he ran from coast to coast for the winning drive
against Oregon Friday afternoon. Holloway has reason to think he
should be performing derring-do every game. Shine just wanted more
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With Holloway leaving here in a wheelchair, his playing career
at Seton Hall may be over. Next season the rookie will arrive with
high expectations. Ty Shine had no way of telling what will happen
this week in Syracuse, or next season, but he will always have
Buffalo, and the day he came out firing.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
