<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE LAKER SHOW AND ITS SURREAL IMAGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Salley lent his wit and wile to one of Phil
Jackson's championship Chicago teams four years ago. The veteran
center was around for the basketball, but Salley most remembers the
spectacle, the feeling that wherever Michael and the Bulls went,
the world stopped and pointed its Nikon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just from a circus-atmosphere standpoint, you can already see
that with these guys,'' he said Sunday as Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe
Bryant laced up their hightops in a room adjacent to the visitor's
locker room at Madison Square Garden. ``In one sense, we're the
Lakers. In another sense, we're the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Salley spoke several minutes before he went out to be
interviewed by Roshumba, the model who works for VH1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if Phil plays me one minute,'' Salley said with
his arm around Roshumba and a big smile on his face. ``The coach
can bench me, send me home, cut me. It doesn't matter. I'm a happy
man right now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Laker Show indeed came to the Garden Sunday, its eclectic
media and fan base trailing a few steps behind, taking in the most
surreal atmosphere surrounding an NBA game in New York this season.
</P>
<P>
   Snoop Doggy Dog in purple and gold. Willie Nelson and Penny
Marshall courtside. Rap, country or Laverne, the Lakers somehow
appease everyone across the kitsch landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In related news, poor-shooting Patrick Ewing and the Knicks fell
to a Western Conference juggernaut, 92-85. But Sunday had less to
do with hoops than it did with the arrival of America's post-Jordan
team, Shaq and the popular collection of entertainers increasingly
followed around the country as if they were rock stars, Jordan, or
both.
</P>
<P>
   There was basketball at the Garden. O'Neal pulverized the
Knicks. He left the backboard support shaking for nearly 20 seconds
after he threw down an alley-oop pass from Brian Shaw with less
than a minute left.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three points. Ten rebounds. Two pretty assists to Bryant
along the baseline for reverse layups, over-the-shoulder flips like
Kareem used to throw to Magic when he was double-teamed.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's play was erratic and uneven, but at times he was as
frighteningly good as O'Neal. He treated the Knicks like traffic
cones at the end of the third quarter, zigzagging through the lane
until he hit a hanging layup from the right side at the buzzer _ a
demoralizing shot that pushed LA's lead to 11.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear why O'Neal recently began calling himself and
Bryant, ``The Combo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I jab them and he drops them,'' Bryant said. ``It's a nice
little nickname he came up with on the back of the bus. I like it.
It fits.''
</P>
<P>
   You look at the Lakers and then you look around the NBA, and
it's almost unfair. Glen Rice, a player who could average 25 points
for half the league's teams, took only 10 shots and made three.
Derek Fisher could start at point guard in more than 20 NBA cities.
Rick Fox and Robert Horry, two of the game's better role players,
also come off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes when they find their rhythm, Shaq, Kobe and friends
remind you of the crew that shows up late to the YMCA, determined
not to wait for another game. They erase your five from the sign-up
sheet and replace it with talent so superior, you end up playing
with a bunch of dentists in dingy headbands, watching a playground
dream team hold court all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant even acknowledged that invincible feeling, that on some
nights no one can stay with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game becomes very easy, very simple _ especially when
we're hitting our shots and we know that we're on,'' he said.
``Once we get a rhythm, you can kind of see them adjust to it.
That's when you know you've got them on a string. You can play them
all game long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks tried their hand as antagonists, but weren't very
successful. Before the game, Jeff Van Gundy was asked about
Jackson's penchant for giving players on his teams books as
personalized gifts.
</P>
<P>
   He took a few less-than-subtle shots at Jackson, the all-knowing
one, whom Dave Checketts met with last season when the Knicks
appeared lottery-bound.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever given a player a book, Van Gundy said: ``I
may have, but I haven't publicized it. To get to this level, every
coach is intelligent. Some choose not to let you know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He later added: ``Like with Phil, he got his start with the best
player in Chicago. He went from maverick to genius. If you start
with the Clippers or something like that, suddenly it's `You can't
coach.'''
</P>
<P>
   Their running feud is amusing, but you wonder if it's not time
for Van Gundy to devote less time to his outward disdain for
Jackson. He's got other pressing concerns to worry about, like how
the Knicks became a warm-up act for Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, nothing changes. Nearly two years after he stepped
away from the game, Jackson comes to the Garden with the best team
and the best player in the NBA. And wins. Van Gundy and the Knicks
are vanquished. Again.
</P>
<P>
   And John Salley, smiling with his arm around Roshumba, is still
enjoying the spectacle. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
