<HEADLINE>
J. RUSSELL KING, TIMES EDITOR, DIES AT 45 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Fla., N.Y., Pa., Mo.)  (jw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ J. Russell King, a deputy news editor of The New York
Times who sharpened the prose of reporters, the precision of
headlines and the meaning of news for readers with a learned,
subtle and anonymous hand, died on Saturday night at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center. He was 45 and lived in Manhattan
and Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was AIDS-related pneumonia, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   A lanky, wry, restless Oklahoma redhead called Rusty, a graduate
of Haverford College who tried law school and taught high school
for a year before becoming a journalist, King worked briefly at The
Wichita Eagle and The Miami Herald before joining The Times in 1982
as a copy editor.
</P>
<P>
   But his talents for language, broad knowledge of politics and
world and national affairs, and other journalistic skills soon
carried him onto the news desk, a small team of editors who oversee
the preparation of the newspaper's front page and serve as a final
quality checkpoint between the newsroom departments and the reader.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, King and his group, working behind the
scenes, helped backstop the work of reporters and editors by
refining the content and style of the day's major articles and
headlines. His mission was to detect and correct inaccuracies,
redundancies, slips in fairness and imprecise, inelegant or
offensive language.
</P>
<P>
   One example of his measured editorial judgment was his memo from
1992 on whether offensive names for minority groups should be
printed. It read in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the targets of prejudice were using the taboo term
themselves, where was the harm?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the harm is that frequent use of offensive words, no
matter who is saying the words or where, cannot help suggesting
that the offense is slight. Every time we print such a word,
particularly in a lighthearted or humorous context, we risk letting
people think that it is acceptable to use it ourselves. And of
course we are further concerned with littering the paper with what
amounts to obscenity _ it simply lowers the tone of The Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, especially on weekends, it was King who laid out Page 1
in consultation with the paper's top editors.
</P>
<P>
   James Russell King was born in Tulsa, Okla., on Nov. 3, 1954. He
grew up in Ardmore, Okla., and was valedictorian of his high school
class in 1972. He earned a bachelor's degree in American studies
from Haverford College in Pennsylvania in 1976 and spent the next
few years in search of a profession.
</P>
<P>
   He taught writing for a year at Ardmore High, attended Columbia
University Law School for a year, and, from 1978 to 1980, studied
at the University of Missouri School of Journalism while working as
a faculty instructor and as an editor and reporter for The Columbia
Missourian.
</P>
<P>
   After a summer with The Wichita Eagle in Kansas and two years
with The Miami Herald, King joined The Times in 1982 as a copy
editor on the national desk. Seven years later, he moved to the
news desk as an assistant editor. He was named a deputy news editor
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He was an active member of the National Lesbian and Gay
Journalists Association, was a mentor for many new Times staff
members and _ among the small crew who worked into the early hours
_ began an annual tradition of wearing formal dress to work on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   King is survived by his mother, Mary Ann Jones King of Ardmore,
and two sisters, Melinda Ann ``Kit'' King of Dallas and Leslie
High-Smith of San Marcos, Texas. A brother, Philip, died last
September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1772 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-19 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ISLANDS OR MAINLAND, KAMEHAMEHA PORK IS FIT FOR A HAWAIIAN
KING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Are we there yet?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Capt. George Vancouver never uttered those exact words
while cruising the waters now known as Puget Sound. But he was not
the kind of passenger you would want sitting in the back seat on a
long trip.
</P>
<P>
   You might say Vancouver groused his way through the Northwest
waters. In the ship logs he complained about the unending forests.
He was bored by the majestic peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Where did he think he'd been sent by the British navy, to
inspect the topless wahines along Sugar Beach on the coast of Maui?
</P>
<P>
   That was the root of Vancouver's despair. He had visited the
Hawaiian Islands. And after that happy trip, Puget Sound just
didn't measure up.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't looking for the Emerald City. George was ready to buy
a time-share condo in Kihei.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1791, Vancouver made his second visit to Hawaii and
moored off Sugar Beach, where a totem pole now marks the site of
his landing.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting on Maui was his old buddy from a previous voyage, King
Kamehameha.
</P>
<P>
   If George Vancouver was a party animal, that aspect of his
personality escaped most historians. He seemed to charge his
batteries watching Kamehameha have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   At the welcome feast, the Hawaiian king reportedly ate two large
fish, an extra large bowl of poi, a small pig and an entire baked
dog. He consumed this meal unaided, and despite the fact he was
missing most of his front teeth.
</P>
<P>
   A meal like that today _ sans pooch _ could cost a visitor from
Seattle as much as $90. So it pays to bring your teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Each winter more and more rain-streaked Puget Sounders
rediscover Maui, where topless and bottomless wahines from Akron
now cavort about eight miles south of Sugar Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers are apparently welcome at the nude beach. But out of
deference to the memory of George Vancouver, it might be nice if
you kept on your royal navy officer's hat. If you are a real sport,
you might also volunteer to organize the welcoming feast with an
entree like:
</P>
<P>
   Kamehameha Pork
</P>
<P>
   1 3-pound pork loin roast
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, cut in slivers
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dried thyme, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons soft bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   With a thin-bladed kitchen knife or pirate's dirk, make several
deep insertions in the roast. Shove a slice of garlic in each.
Plunk the roast in a baking pan and rub with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the thyme with the wine, pour over the roast and let it sit
for 1 to 2 hours at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Tent a sheet of aluminum foil over
the roast and shove the pan (including the marinade liquid) into
the oven. Let roast for 50 minutes. While it is cooking, mix
together the bread crumbs, mustard and chopped parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Remove roast from oven. Discard the foil. Baste with the pan
juices, adding more red wine to the pan if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the mustard mixture over the top and sides of the roast
and return to oven for 40 minutes or until the thermometer reads
170 to 180 degrees. Let meat rest out of the oven a couple of
minutes, then carve into thick slices.
</P>
<P>
   Don't have a cow if the roast is pink inside. Pork is safe to
eat once it exceeds the temperature of 137 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   This roast should serve six or more along with this side dish
from a wahine named Winnifred.
</P>
<P>
   Win's Green Rice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rice
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup melted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped American cheese
</P>
<P>
   4 beaten eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, ground or shredded
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Dash of pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, mashed
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups minced fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Mix everything together in a casserole and bake in a 350-degree
oven for 1 hour. This serves four but is easily doubled or tripled.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make the rice your main dish, it's great with
creamed shrimp spooned over the top.
</P>
<P>
   After his feast with Vancouver, Kamehameha entertained the crowd
by staging a mock battle. He rolled and tumbled to avoid weapons
thrown at him and caught the spears in his bare hands.
</P>
<P>
   After your feast on Maui's notorious beach, a game of intramural
volleyball might be in order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2000EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
