<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1774 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-SECURITY-ART-NYT     03-19 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-SECURITY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLY LAND JITTERS HEIGHTEN SECURITY FOR PAPAL VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 13, 14 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A recent newspaper cartoon illustrated the anxiety
here that something will befall Pope John Paul II on his six-day
pilgrimage to the Holy Land, which begins on Tuesday. The cartoon
shows Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel encouraging the pope to
step out onto a bridge that extends into the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we cross, let us pray,'' the pope says, hesitant.
</P>
<P>
   The image recalls a disaster that Israelis cannot forget _ when
a temporary bridge built for athletes in an international meet in
1997 collapsed, leaving four dead and scores injured. And last
week, when a stiff wind caused structural damage on the stage where
the pope will preside over a huge outdoor Mass, it sent a shudder
through many Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collapse of a pillar even before anyone has stepped foot
on the stage is a sign from heaven that your appeal to the Jewish
people for forgiveness may have been premature,'' Yoel Marcus wrote
to the pope in a tongue-in-cheek column on Friday in the newspaper
Haaretz.
</P>
<P>
   While the religious and political dimensions of the pope's
six-day trip here are large, the logistical and security
preparations by both Israel and the Palestinian Authority are
unprecedented. The visit also requires an unparalleled cooperation
between the two governments, which so far, despite the minor
sniping of Jerusalem officials on both sides, has gone very
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   A key concern of security officials was allayed last week when
the Palestinian police, acting on a tip from the Israelis, captured
two Islamic fundamentalist terror suspects with 88 pounds of
explosives. Having fled an Israeli raid on their hideout, during
which several of their colleagues were killed, they were considered
an at-large risk for an imminent attack.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials have not received specific threats against
the pope himself, although a tiny group of Jewish extremists is
aggressively antagonistic to his visit, the first state visit here
by a pope.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime late Saturday night, Jewish extremists vandalized the
helipad that has been specially built for the pope on Mount Scopus.
They ruined welcome signs, spray-painted ``Pope Out'' in English on
the pavement, and sketched a graphic equation between the Christian
cross and a swastika. ``Where were you during the Holocaust?'' they
wrote in Hebrew. Israeli police suspect the extreme right-wing Kach
group.
</P>
<P>
   The general potential for violence in the area is what concerns
security officials, who note that the pope's trip touches on all
the most sensitive issues here, from the Holocaust to the
sovereignty of Jerusalem to the right of return of Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real threat because of the security situation in
Israel,'' a senior security officer said. ``And the basic
assumption is that the pope is a target.''
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, 18,000 police officers, 4,000 soldiers and 250 Shin
Bet agents will be engaged in the security and logistical operation
during the visit. ``It is probably the largest, most complicated
and most sophisticated operation of VIP protection we've ever
done,'' said Brig. Gen. David Tsur of the Israeli police.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli security officials will turn over the pope to
Palestinian security when he lands at the heliport in Bethlehem on
Wednesday for his day in the Palestinian Authority's territory.
``We have very good cooperation with the PA, and they will take
full responsibility there,'' Tsur said. ``We have trained with them
for this. We did it with Yeltsin. It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowds themselves will also be a phenomenon. Some 60,000
pilgrims from 71 countries are flying into Tel Aviv, 45,000 of them
on special charters, making it the single biggest week in Israeli
tourism history.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism authorities are projecting revenues of $50 million,
much of it benefiting El Al, the airline, and two charter airlines.
About 300 extra flights will land in Israel during a five-day
period that began Saturday, and 800 buses have been chartered.
</P>
<P>
   El Al is offering items duty-free to pilgrims, including
telephone calling cards containing a bubble of water from the
Jordan River, olive-wood miniatures and ``Biblical perfumes.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 2,000 foreign journalists are expected this week,
including the television anchors for CBS, NBC and ABC. As a media
event, it is likely to outstrip the groundbreaking visit of
President Anwar el-Sadat of Egypt to the Israeli Parliament in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   The pope will stay at the papal ambassador's residence near
Mount Scopus in East Jerusalem and travel around the country in an
Israeli army Blackhawk helicopter. His ``popemobile'' arrived last
week, but an army dune buggy was customized as a substitute for his
trip into the Old City, whose alleylike streets are too narrow for
the pope's usual vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   In the Old City, the Via Dolorosa got a million-dollar,
privately financed facelift for the occasion, and newly arrived
pilgrims are already crowding the winding cobblestone path that
tradition says Jesus took to his crucifixion. Juan Romero, 26, of
Salamanca, Spain, took the uphill trek Sunday, bearing a rented
cross. He stopped at every station of the cross and then emerged
from the Church of the Holy Sepulcher to treat himself to a falafel
in pita with extra tahina sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only go so far in replicating Jesus' experience,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The densely packed, often garbage-strewn Old City is looking
almost spiffy as Jerusalem prepares for the pope.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bethlehem area, the Dehaisheh refugee camp is strung with
welcome banners. But the refugees decided not to freshen up the
dingy place, which would alter its depressing reality. One sign
apologizes to the pope that no street will be named after him in
the camp. ``We do not intend to stay here,'' said the residents of
52 years.
</P>
<P>
   Various officials offered various explanations of what took
place at the stage last weekend, from the loosening of a few cables
to the collapse of a canopy to the cracking of a critical beam that
crashed down on the stage several feet from where the pope is
supposed to stand.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli newspaper editorialists were quick to cringe. ``All
we ask is that there not be a disaster,'' one wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2003EST &QL; 
