u i BC-TAIWAN-U.S.-565&AMP;ADD-N     03-19 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-U.S.-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SCRAMBLES TO RESCUE ITS CHINA POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For more than a decade, Washington has urged Taiwan
to let true democracy flower, knowing that it could eventually lead
to the defeat of the Nationalist Party by pro-independence forces
and put the island, and even perhaps the United States, on a
collision course with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   But when the moment arrived at the weekend, administration
officials conceded, the timing was singularly inopportune.
</P>
<P>
   The victory of Chen Shui-bian, the opposition leader who until
recently was an open advocate of Taiwan's independence from China,
sent White House and State Department officials scrambling Sunday
to prevent an escalation of tensions.
</P>
<P>
   And it may well change the calculus for the administration's
biggest foreign policy push in Congress this year, getting China
into the World Trade Organization, a deal that is ultimately more
about security and China's role in the world than about regulating
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks ago we were focused on the domestic debate here,
over the WTO and arms sales to Taiwan,'' a senior administration
official said. ``But the landscape has completely changed. And now
our primary focus is to manage the cross-strait relations _ and to
keep everyone from doing something stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's top official for Asia, Stanley Roth, and
the U.S. delegate to the United Nations, Richard Holbrooke, are in
Beijing now. Their plan, administration officials said Sunday, is
to urge President Jiang Zemin to say little in public and reach out
to Chen, rather than give in to hard-liners pressing to make good
on China's recent threats.
</P>
<P>
   Their visit will be immediately followed by the arrival of
President Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, on
completion of Clinton's trip to India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the White House searched on Sunday for someone
to send to Taiwan with a similar message to Chen about the need to
steer clear of statements likely to incite Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely choice, officials said, is former Rep. Lee
Hamilton, a longtime China hand who now runs the Woodrow Wilson
International Center for Scholars. Under the bizarre diplomatic
rules of Washington's ``one China'' policy, no senior U.S. official
can officially visit or consult with the island's leaders _ even as
the United States gives Taiwan defensive weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Even if an immediate crisis is averted, the ouster of the
Nationalists greatly complicates Clinton's effort to give order to
a messy relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With only 10 months left in office, he wants to persuade
Congress to give China permanent trading rights and a voice in the
World Trade Organization. Earlier this month, Clinton argued
passionately that the vote marks the United States' best chance to
change China _ through the Internet and the opening of its market _
and to loosen communist control.
</P>
<P>
   But if Jiang and his prime minister, Zhu Rongji, decide in
coming weeks that Taiwan's new challenge mandates a response,
administration officials say, the economic opening to Beijing may
be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that Beijing will maintain the stance that it took
immediately after the election on Saturday, a moderate tone,'' said
Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative, who is at the
center of the WTO debate. But if that tone changes, she said,
``there's no telling where this could go.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The administration is already under pressure from conservatives
to sell far more arms to Taiwan, to counter Beijing's growing
missile threat to the island. Last month, the House voted
overwhelmingly to approve the Taiwan Security Enhancement Act,
which would establish direct military communications between
Washington and Taipei and expand U.S. training of Taiwan's military
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration considers the legislation so provocative to
Beijing that Berger referred to it recently as ``the Taiwan
Insecurity Act'' and has recommended that it be vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, led by Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip,
chose it as the first major bill for the year precisely because it
would challenge China. And if tensions escalate in coming weeks, it
may be appended to the World Trade Organization legislation _
leaving Clinton with the agonizing choice of letting his major
overture to China die, or outraging Beijing by linking its economic
role in the world with support for an island that it considers, now
more than ever, a renegade province.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term U.S. concern is that the suddenly chaotic
political landscape in Taipei could put the United States into the
middle of a dangerous crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has been committed to Taiwan's defense since the Cold
War. In 1996, Clinton sent two carrier groups to the end of the
strait in response to China's firing several missiles into waters
near Taiwan before elections that year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Zhu warned that any move toward independence _ or
even foot-dragging in talks about unification _ could prompt China
to ``spill blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The American response is to leave China with the impression that
the United States would intervene if China made a military move.
But that threat is of diminishing value. The Chinese know the U.S.
political landscape well _ and Clinton's aides, in private moments,
wonder aloud whether Americans would risk war with the world's most
populous nation over the fate of Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
