u l BC-KARAOKE-NIGHTS-1STLDW     03-19 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KARAOKE-NIGHTS-1STLDWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY KARAOKE WON'T DIE 
 
AMATEUR SINGERS LIVE FOR THEIR FEW MOMENTS ONSTAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos are not available) 
 
By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Most Saturday nights, Marge Vinzant and her sister,
Mitriel, don't care about going to a movie, dining at a fancy
restaurant or checking out the singles scene.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they can be found at a front-row table at a southwest
Houston karaoke bar, where they patiently wait their turn to stand
in front of an audience and sing for applause.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally men on the prowl stop by their table and try their
best come-on lines. The women slough them off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been there, done that,'' says Marge.
</P>
<P>
   They direct their attention to the stage and applaud
enthusiastically when any singer hits a high note. When their
moment arrives _ it happens only a couple of times on a busy night
_ they work hard to pick a song that will move the crowd to get up
and dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel good. It calms me down,'' says Marge, a
banker by day. ``I like to sing in front of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Amateur singers live for the few moments when they get to belt
out a favorite tune onstage. Their devotion is a primary reason why
karaoke _ like cockroaches and ozone _ just won't die.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after this singing art form swept through the
United States, karaoke is the subject of a new Gwyneth Paltrow
movie, ``Duets,'' and remains a staple in most cities.
</P>
<P>
   Even pop superstars are taking part.
</P>
<P>
   People magazine reports that Whitney Houston and Bobby Brown
recently stopped by a West Hollywood, Calif., karaoke bar. When
Houston belted out her monster hit ``I Will Always Love You,''
patrons called friends on their cell phones to let them listen in.
</P>
<P>
   Not only adults get into it. A popular show on MTV, ``Say What
Karaoke?,'' is a raucous karaoke competition in which contestants
sing the latest songs in flamboyant costumes selected from a nearby
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a communal fun vibe,'' says Tony DiSanto, MTV
vice president of production, who helped create the show. ``There's
a little bit of rock star in all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter the venue, karaoke works this way: A would-be singer
sifts through a thick book of song titles, chooses the one to sing,
writes it down on a piece of paper and gives it to the host, better
known as the KJ.
</P>
<P>
   When his name or table number is called, he goes onstage, grabs
a microphone and sings, accompanied by background music and aided
by lyrics flashed on a video monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The craze began nearly 20 years ago in Japan _ ``karaoke'' is a
Japanese word that translates loosely as ``empty orchestra'' _ when
a pub owner improvised with recordings because a popular
entertainer was unable to perform. Customers sang along, and soon
karaoke was spreading around the world.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, karaoke was ``huge'' in Houston clubs, says
Oskar Torre, owner of Overtime Productions and the Karaoke Host,
which provides DJs for parties and rents out equipment. In the
mid-1990s, however, many clubs began dropping the entertainment
because it seemed out of date.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened, Torre says: Karaoke went from
``commercial to consumers.'' Torre began to get calls from people
wanting to rent equipment for weddings, bar mitzvahs and other
family functions.
</P>
<P>
   Now karaoke has become so popular again that Torre is opening a
recording studio in his Houston-area offices next month so fans who
are looking to improve their singing can bring in a song and record
it digitally on a CD with karaoke-style background music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine out of 10 people dream about a singing career,'' he says.
``This gives them a perfect opportunity to unleash those
inhibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for karaoke's renewed popularity is simple, Torre
says: We all like to sing. We've sung in the school choir. Or at
church. While driving in our cars. Or, if we're really shy, in the
shower.
</P>
<P>
   At a karaoke bar, ``these people can go from being nobodies to
Thursday-night somebodies,'' he says, pointing out that many bars
have karaoke sing-alongs on Thursdays to get an early start on the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The ``heart of karaoke'' is on display, Torre says, when novices
summon the courage to sing for the first time. ``Two or three
idiots get up, and they can't carry a tune, but they're having a
great time,'' he says. ``That is the chemistry you look for.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynda Escalante remembers the first time she got up to sing
karaoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got applause, and that was a real rush,'' she says. ``A lot
of people secretly want to be a star without the pressure and just
have fun. Singing is good for the soul. If you're having a lousy
day, it just makes it better.''
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, she started Laser Karaoke by Lynda after
renting a karaoke machine and buying it ``as a toy for the house''
because she liked it so much. Now she rents out equipment and hosts
karaoke nights.
</P>
<P>
   When she's not working, she and her husband like to hang out
with friends at a sports bar in the north Houston, which has
karaoke sing-alongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people make the circuit; they try to see who else is out
there,'' she says. ``Others like a little bit of singles action.
But most people have a favorite spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Morales, a gymnastics teacher, got interested in karaoke
about five years ago because it helped relieve his depression after
a divorce. He met his fiancee, Tina Allen, at a karaoke bar. Both
sing regularly in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it `hooked on phonics,''' says Allen, a nurse who's
hoping for a singing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I opened my mouth (to sing), I had friends,''
Morales says. ``It's a nice, friendly way to meet people. It's like
one big melting pot. It brings together everyone with music.''
</P>
<P>
   Another regular, Pam Holter, got interested in karaoke after she
split up with her husband and went to a nearby bar to get away from
her troubles. It offered karaoke, and although it took her nine
months to get up in front of an audience, she was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a microphone in your hand, it's a natural high,''
says Holter, who's an accountant. ``You don't need drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she has a circle of karaoke friends who care about her, and
she's having the time of her life, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Morales differentiates several levels of karaoke singers:
serious singers who care more about a good selection of songs and a
high-quality sound system than about a bar's location; party groups
that drink a lot and sing to have a good time; and ``event'' crowds
that participate on special occasions at a hotel or auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   When Jessica Pizzitola turned 30 recently, she reserved a
private room at Spotlight Karaoke _ one of the few Houston spots
that offer nonstop karoke every night _ for a party with her
friends. But before the evening was over, she came out to the main
stage. With a cigarette in one hand and a microphone in the other,
a tiara on her head and a pink boa over her shoulders, she gave a
soulful rendition of the Gloria Gaynor classic ``I Will Survive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so many people have this little desire to be a star,''
says Pizzitola, a Houston native who now lives in Austin, where she
is a personal assistant to a film director. ``Even though some
people think it's cheesy, it gives you that moment where you can be
a star _ even if it's only for a second.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Trostle, a research chemist who had a good time with the
Rolling Stones song ``Satisfaction,'' says the hardest part about
singing karaoke is working up the courage to go onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You confront your fears singing in front of strangers,'' he
says. ``But once you do it, you're so relieved. You think, `I made
it, and the gong didn't ring.'''
</P>
<P>
   The allure can become addictive.
</P>
<P>
   When Casey Dippel was 18, he stood up in a now-defunct club and
sang the UB40 song ``Kingston Town.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly nine years later, Dippel is a regular on the karaoke
scene. Besides singing at Houston clubs several times a week, he
checks out karaoke bars when he goes on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   He has sung in such places as Atlanta, San Francisco, Phoenix
and Orlando, Fla. He says people have asked him whether he's a
professional singer. Some have followed him to his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go in any karaoke bar in the world and get respect,''
says Dippel, a 26-year-old assistant superintendent for a gas and
air compressor company who models his singing style on Ricky Martin
and George Michael. ``That's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
