<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-DAVIS-PROFILE-ART-NYT     03-19 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS RELY ON A WALKING POLITICAL ALMANAC
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ga., Mo., N.D., Neb.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Thomas M. Davis III does not want an asterisk
next to his name in some political almanac with a footnote reading,
``Bungled Republican control of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a tough job he has, chairman of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, especially with all those House Democrats
dreaming up decorating schemes for the suites they hope to fill in
the next Congress, and going on about gun control and health care
all the time. The last man who held the job, Rep. John Linder of
Georgia, was replaced after Republicans lost five seats in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one advantage I would give them right now, it isn't
financial because we've outraised them and we will continue to
outraise them,'' Davis, who represents suburban northern Virginia
and is in charge of the Republicans' election strategy, said about
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that under Gephardt they have the eye of the tiger,'' he
said, referring to the minority leader, Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri. ``They have shown amazing discipline, and they are very
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   So Davis has made it his mission to badger his Republican
colleagues to raise more money, bushels of it, and to force them to
visualize life in a House controlled by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are sitting there measuring drapes to your office,''
Davis tells his Republican friends, some of whom have reacted less
than graciously to his pestering. ``And that bill you got through
this year, next year you will be lucky to be a co-sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes a similarly menacing approach with business leaders.
Many of them have been donating to Democrats as well as
Republicans. ``They may not get everything they want out of this
Congress,'' Davis said, ``but I tell you what, they are on defense
the next Congress if Democrats take control.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a tough one for Davis and House Republicans. They
were way down in the polls, carrying $3 million of campaign debt
and spending money like it was there to burn.
</P>
<P>
   There was one big payoff, though, and it came in Davis' home
state. Virginia Republicans captured the statehouse, which meant
they would control the redistricting process in 2002. Soon after,
one Democrat incumbent in the House decided to defect. Another
decided to retire. This gave Republicans a slight chance to regain
seats in November, and a much-needed psychological boost.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 51, is a Republican who is hard to pin down. A lawyer and
a former board chairman of Fairfax County, an area of prosperous
suburbs near Washington, he is a moderate who supports gun control
and free trade, and who takes a middle stance on the abortion
issue. (The government should not intrude, nor should it pay for
the procedure, Davis believes.) He meets with gay groups and labor
officials. He is a Christian Scientist among Baptists and
Methodists. He is also a lawmaker who actually embraces the term
``politician,'' a word that causes most Republicans to recoil.
</P>
<P>
   His moderation did not sit well with conservative Republicans
who sought to block his selection as campaign chairman. ``I got
some pretty vicious faxes and e-mails about me, about `Don't let
this guy get the keys,''' Davis said. ``But I won pretty
comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because Davis has spent his lifetime preparing for the
job, or so it seems. ``He takes it seriously,'' said Rep. James P.
Moran, a Virginia Democrat and a friend. ``Michael Jordan used to
say of Charles Barkley, `He will never be as great as I am because
he doesn't live basketball.' Tom Davis lives politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing everyone who knows Davis immediately says about
him is that he is a walking political almanac.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him who won some obscure House race in some little-known
patch of Kansas or Maine or Florida, way back in 1982, and he will
recite the name, then drop in the margin of victory, just to show
off. It is a parlor trick he is hoping will pay off when he
formulates the strategy for keeping control of the House. A net
gain of only six seats for the Democrats would tip the balance away
from the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas M. Davis III was born in Minot, N.D., to Nebraska-bred
parents in 1949. The family moved to Arlington, Va., when he was a
boy, and it was there, hollering distance from the nation's
capital, that Davis became obsessed with politics.
</P>
<P>
   By seventh grade, Davis could name all of the nation's 400-plus
House members and the 100 senators. A year later, a neighbor told
him about the Capitol Page School, where students attend morning
classes, then spend their afternoons working as pages in the
Capitol. He lobbied for admission and persuaded the two Nebraska
senators to sponsor him. He became the president of his class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wanted to be something ambitious,'' he said, from
his home in a relatively modest section of Fairfax County. ``I just
like politics.''
</P>
<P>
   No ambition? In politics? ``Not anymore,'' he said. ``There's no
money in it.'' But isn't there money in it after you leave
politics? ``I guess, if you don't embarrass yourself,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   At Amherst College in the late 1960s, the hippie heyday, Davis
was an oddity: a teetotaler (his father was an alcoholic) and the
chairman of the Young Republicans. It was at Amherst that he struck
up a lifelong friendship with David Eisenhower, the former
president's grandson and Richard Nixon's son-in-law. When
Eisenhower was living at the White House, after his marriage to
Julie Nixon, he would set up whiffleball games on the White House
tennis court. Davis' first date with his wife, Peggy, an
obstetrician, was during a whiffleball game. They now have three
children.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his own political lineage, Eisenhower said he found
himself relying on Davis to make sense of the politics swirling
around him. ``I would shuttle between the White House and Davis
back at Amherst,'' Eisenhower said, ``and he was in their league,
at that age.''
</P>
<P>
   Of today's politics, Davis said that it did not take an Einstein
to decipher the Democratic strategy for winning back the House.
``They are all about trying to blow up the Congress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they are very disciplined over there. I just think our
guys have to understand that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
