</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE MUSCLES THE JAZZ PAST THE NETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The man who is arguably the best power
forward in basketball history wheeled in the paint and began
throwing around his muscle. His immense shoulders were smashing
Keith Van Horn in the chest. His thigh-sized biceps were smacking
him in the ribs. And 16,103 fans and a team of defenders were
hoping against the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But Karl Malone has been at this for 15 years, crushing the
dreams of opponents with his strength, skill and experience. So
naturally his move, which was culminated with a half-hook layup
that fell softly through the net, was good, breaking a tie score
with 1 minute 49 seconds to play and drawing a foul on the helpless
Van Horn as well.
</P>
<P>
   Malone made the ensuing free throw for the last of his game-high
32 points, and the wise, old Utah Jazz, with some timely shooting
from the reserve point guard Howard Eisley, held on to hand the
Nets their first loss in five games, 92-88, before a deflated crowd
at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game a veteran team guts out because you
don't allow yourself to think tired,'' Malone said. ``There's no
panic in this team. We finish with a flurry. This was a big game
for us. The Nets are still playing for the playoffs. So it's not
like the Nets early in the season, where it didn't mean anything to
them. Every game means something to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who were led by Stephon Marbury's 23 points and 12
assists, treated the game appropriately and played solidly enough
to beat a lesser team with perhaps a lesser star. But the
6-foot-9-inch, 259-pound Malone, his bodybuilder's physique defying
his 36 years, gripped the game and would not let go, scoring 24
points in the second half, including 11 in the fourth quarter,
before fouling out for the first time since Nov. 5, 1995, with 48.3
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl is probably one of the best power forwards to play the
game and he really took the team on his shoulders,'' Nets coach Don
Casey said. ``I don't know how you stop Malone. We've been studying
tapes for the last 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   There certainly is no shame in losing to the Jazz, who finished
a five-game trip with four victories to improve to 44-21. If it
were not for the indomitable Los Angeles Lakers, the Jazz would be
the league's hottest team, having won 10 of its last 11 games and
17 of its last 20.
</P>
<P>
   But each defeat cuts deeply into the Nets' postseason hopes, and
Sunday's kicked off a week in which the Nets (28-37) face four
playoff teams. They visit Toronto on Tuesday and Charlotte on
Wednesday before hosting Minnesota on Friday. Like Sunday, they
could play well each time out and lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who fell in similar fashion to the Jazz, 106-101, on
Feb. 28, were teased by victory throughout Sunday's contest. After
falling behind by 22-11, late in the first quarter, they put
together a terrific 21-2 run to move ahead by 32-24 five minutes
into the second.
</P>
<P>
   John Stockton, Utah's future Hall of Fame point guard, was on
the bench for most of the Nets' spurt due to foul trouble, and
Eisley did not appear to be headed for the co-starring role with
Malone. But with Stockton (5 points, 10 assists, 1-for-7 shooting)
and Jeff Hornacek (4 points, 1-for-6) struggling
uncharacteristically, Eisley and Bryon Russell filled the void,
scoring 15 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Eisley scored 9 in the second quarter to help the Jazz fight
back for a 45-45 tie at halftime, and behind Malone's dominance,
Utah entered the fourth with a 69-66 lead. With two of their
recently ballyhooed reserves, Johnny Newman and Lucious Harris,
draining 3-pointers, the Nets moved ahead by 78-74 with 6:59
remaining, but an offensive funk followed, giving the Jazz the
sliver of opportunity it needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets failed to score on seven straight possessions, missing
six shots and committing one turnover, to fall behind by 82-78 with
less than 3 minutes left. Van Horn, who missed seven of his first
eight shots and had just 4 points entering the final period,
finally asserted himself, scoring 6 straight points to pull them
within 85-84.
</P>
<P>
   But Eisley sank a 15-footer with 57 seconds on the clock to
increase the cushion to 3 points. Twenty-nine seconds later, after
Van Horn (14 points, 9 rebounds) had drawn the sixth foul on Malone
and hit two free throws, Eisley again foiled the Nets, throwing in
a 19-footer over Marbury. With just 28 seconds left, the Nets began
sending Utah to the foul line, where the Jazz made 3-of-4 shots to
keep the hosts at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have guys on that team that are not just role players,''
said Kerry Kittles, who finished with 14 points. ``They have guys
who can actually do great things. When you're shutting down guys
like Hornacek and you're making it hard for them, and a guy like
Eisley comes off the bench with a solid 15 points, that's tough to
overcome. A lot of times, that's the biggest difference in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   That, and arguably the greatest power forward ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
