<HEADER>
A1794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-CAROLINA-STANFORD     03-19 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CAROLINA-STANFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA SHOWS IT BELONGS BY UPSETTING STANFORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Stanford chose to toss 22 of its 58 shots
from behind the 3-point arc. North Carolina decided to fly at the
Cardinal on nearly every one of those shots, to clip the Cardinal's
wings and roll forward to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth-seeded North Carolina mesmerized the South Region's
top-seeded team, beating the Cardinal by 60-53 on Sunday in a game
of persistent Carolina defense, opportunistic Carolina offense and
a blueprint Carolina finish. North Carolina (19-13) will play
fourth-seeded Tennessee next in Austin, Texas. The crowd in the
Birmingham-Jefferson Civic Center watched the Tar Heels earn their
17th Sweet 16 appearance in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not your average school and this is not your average
team, regardless of what happened in the regular season,'' said
Carolina forward Jason Capel, who scored 8 points, but, more
importantly, limited Stanford's leading scorer, Casey Jacobsen, to
5 points on horrible 2-of-12 floor shooting. ``Our coach has taken
a beating, more than the players, and that's a shame because he can
only do so much. Our team was figured dead in the first round
against Missouri. Well, I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Guthridge, the Tar Heels' coach, beamed with pride over
this bunch. It followed last year's group that was booted from the
first round of the tournament by Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard against Stanford, we deserved it,'' Guthridge
said. ``Our defense of their 3s was very good.''
</P>
<P>
   It was better than that.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford made only 6 of its 22 3-point shots (27.3 percent). Its
starters converted only 14 of 50 overall shots. Jumper, jumper,
jumper, jumper. Few Stanford drives to the basket resulted in eight
free-throw attempts for the game. Carolina won the battle in the
paint by 26-20 and 7-foot center Brendan Haywood led the way with
12 points and 8 rebounds. Stanford had not scored fewer than 64
points in any game this season and in 14 games had scored at least
80.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted us to make a statement,'' Haywood said. ``We wanted
to show people, the ones who counted us out a long time ago, that
they don't know basketball as well as they think. This is big for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford made 10 of 29 shots in each half and shot 34.5 percent
for the game. It won in rebounds, 38-32, but did little converting
on second chances with its 14 offensive rebounds. The Cardinal
looked dizzy. It led by 27-20 with 2:17 left before halftime and
then allowed eight straight Tar Heels points. That gave North
Carolina a 28-27 halftime lead. And then North Carolina scored the
first 6 points of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal guard David Mosely (17 points) kept his team alive with
early sharp shooting, but as the game progressed, he faded. Forward
Ryan Mendez entered off the bench to proved a lift on 4 of 4
shooting (including two 3-pointers) for 12 points. But without
Jacobsen scoring and with forward Mark Madsen (2 of 7 for 5 points)
and center Jarron Collins (3 of 10 for 8 points) struggling in
general, Stanford was doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some looks but didn't make them,'' said Mike
Montgomery, Stanford's coach. ``They gave us some problems. They
forced us to do some things we don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Capel on Jacobsen was the genesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a lot of film on him and saw he liked to come off
screens and shoot,'' Capel said. ``I wanted to be physical, make
him go to one side and force him to put the ball on the floor. He
doesn't like to do that and he wasn't as effective because of it.
You know, it only takes one shot to get a shooter going. He made
one on me when I slacked off but I wasn't going to let that happen
again. Wherever he was at, I was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why Stanford was seeded No. 1. Despite
its awful shooting, its complex struggles, it fought back to lead
47-45 with 8:03 to play. Three minutes passed before either team
scored another basket.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Carolina freshman guard Joseph Forte who finished
the Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   Forte made a layup and then sank consecutive 3-point shots to
give Carolina a lead it would not relinquish. Forte scored 11
points in the final five minutes, showing the flash and dazzle that
made him the Atlantic Coast Conference rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told me to stop shooting like I was scared,'' said
Forte, who finished with 17 points. ``He said let it go and I
started to do that. At this stage, you can't be nervous or you go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   That is where Stanford (27-4) is headed.
</P>
<P>
   But Carolina rolls forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I don't know what happened to make
people on our team come to their senses,'' said Ed Cota, the senior
Carolina guard who led all players with 10 assists. ``We had a
rough year, especially early, but that's over now. We're playing
more team basketball. We get to play for another day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
