<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BOSOX-SNAFU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX UPSET BY A 5-HOUR ROUNDTRIP FOR A LATE POSTPONEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ The game, as exhibitions go, could have
been the highlight of the spring: Pedro Martinez pitching for
Boston, Mike Mussina for Baltimore, sellout crowd, Orioles fans
watching on television back home. The game, however, was not
played. It fell victim to a fiasco that had the Orioles angry with
the Fort Lauderdale Stadium grounds crew and the Red Sox furious,
albeit quietly, with the Orioles. An unnecessary five-hour
round-trip bus ride can produce that kind of reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the problem and reason for the lost pitching
matchup and lucrative gate was the grounds crew's failure to cover
the infield with the tarpaulin on Saturday after the Orioles had
played the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told they didn't put it on because we took batting
practice after the game,'' Orioles Manager Mike Hargrove said. ``I
said that has nothing to do with it. Then they said, well, they
didn't call for rain. I said you have to think of a better one than
that because I watched the weather report.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove made a few other comments, he said, but added: ``I
don't know how, in a printable way, to tell you what I said. I
reverted to a very short vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   A chance of rain, indeed, was in the weather forecast Saturday,
and with the field left uncovered, rain fell through much of the
night. If that precipitation was not enough, rain fell torrentially
after 8 a.m. Sunday, adding to the lake in right field and the
quagmire that was formerly the infield.
</P>
<P>
   With more rain in the forecast, which the grounds crew by now
had apparently heard, the workers belatedly put the tarp on the
infield, completing that chore just before 10 o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had planned to leave their spring training complex
across the state in Fort Myers at 8. They delayed their departure,
though, until getting a go-ahead from the Orioles. An Orioles
official called them at 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called and told us to come,'' Red Sox Manager Jimy
Williams said. ``They didn't tell us the tarp wasn't on all
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The grounds crew had told the Orioles that once the weather
permitted and the tarp was removed from the field, it could get the
field ready for a game in an hour and a half or two hours. The
Orioles presumably told the Red Sox to come because they believed
they would be able to play, however late they would have to begin.
Teams do not easily forgo sellout crowds and television revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who studiously avoids controversy or inflammatory
comment, declined to say what he really thought of riding a bus two
and a half hours each way for nothing. The game was called off five
minutes before the Red Sox reached the stadium. But Williams left
little question about how he felt about the Orioles at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' Williams said, sitting for a few minutes in the
visiting clubhouse, ``the Orioles went to Cuba for a game. We had a
game scheduled with them that day. They never even sent a team. We
had to get another game. This year we had games scheduled for last
weekend in St. Petersburg and Fort Myers, and then we added games
in the Dominican Republic. But we still played the other games,
too. We honored our contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the uncertainty of the weather, the Red Sox did not
bring Martinez. He stayed in Fort Myers to pitch in a minor league
game instead. The players who did make the trip got back on the bus
for the return two-and-a-half-hour trip across Alligator Alley.
After they left, more rain fell. This time the tarp covered the
infield, protecting it for the Orioles' scheduled day off Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
