<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT TERM'S CLOSING PHASE TO BE INTENSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Calif., Ariz., Texas, Va., N.J., Neb.)   (jw) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With more than three months to go in its term, the
Supreme Court on Monday will enter a concentrated period of unusual
intensity and potential import. The justices, back from a brief
recess, will begin six weeks of hearing arguments in one
blockbuster case after another, a series of high-profile appeals
that appear drawn from today's headlines and that have already
marked the term as a likely landmark.
</P>
<P>
   These questions suggest the scope of what awaits the justices
among the two dozen cases they will hear between now and the last
week in April, the final building blocks of the 1999-2000 term:
</P>
<P>
   Does public prayer before a high school football game violate
the separation of church and state?
</P>
<P>
   Are the Miranda warnings still required before the police can
interrogate a suspect in custody, or has Congress effectively
overruled the 34-year-old Miranda decision?
</P>
<P>
   Can states put into effect their own views of foreign policy by
withholding state business from companies that trade with
disfavored regimes.
</P>
<P>
   Can states, and by extension Congress, criminalize the surgical
procedure that abortion opponents call ``partial-birth abortion''?
</P>
<P>
   Do the Boy Scouts have a constitutional right to exclude gay
youths and men from leadership roles?
</P>
<P>
   These cases and more _ on the legal threshold for winning an
employment discrimination case, on constitutional standards for
enhanced sentencing under hate crime laws, on congressional
authority to make arson a federal crime, on whether political
parties can be required to open their primaries to voting by
nonmembers _ are all due for decision by the end of June, the
court's goal for resolving all argued cases and finishing its term.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an amazing term, with no major area of
constitutional law that doesn't have the potential for major
change,'' Erwin Chemerinsky, a law professor at the University of
Southern California, said in an interview. Noting the high-profile
nature of the court's docket, he continued: ``I wonder whether the
magnitude of this term, the prominence of these cases, will have
the effect of making the court more salient as an election issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that some major cases that were argued three, four or even
five months ago remain undecided as this new round of arguments
begins, the prospect of an orderly, on-time conclusion to the term
strikes many people who follow the court as wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Among the earlier cases that are still undecided are those on
the Food and Drug Administration's authority to regulate tobacco
products and on the constitutionality of the Violence Against Women
Act, as well as a major church-state conflict over federal
financing for computer equipment in religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   The justices have all but complete control over which cases to
accept but relatively little control over the timing, generally
considering new appeals in the order in which they were filed. So
the unusual concentration of high-profile cases for the March and
April arguments simply reflects the fact that most of them reached
the justices' desks during the fall.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a detailed look at some of the cases the
justices will hear in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESSIONAL AUTHORITY
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing its inquiry into the limits of congressional law-making
authority _ thought to be virtually limitless before the court
reversed course five years ago _ the court will hear a challenge on
Tuesday to a federal prosecution for burning down a private
residence. The question in Jones vs. U.S., No. 99-5739, is whether
Congress intended the federal arson law to apply to a private home
and, if so, whether Congress had authority to do so under its power
to regulate interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN POLICY
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Massachusetts will defend its so-called Burma law,
which in effect prohibits state agencies from doing business with
companies that do business in Myanmar, formerly Burma. Dozens of
state and local governments once aimed similar economic weapons
against South Africa's apartheid regime. Those went unchallenged,
but the federal appeals court in Boston, ruling in Natsios vs.
National Foreign Trade Council, No. 99-474, found the Burma law to
be an impermissible state intrusion into the federal government's
foreign affairs power.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL TEAM PRAYER
</P>
<P>
   The court will hear a Texas school district's appeal of a ruling
that barred the practice, highly popular in the state, of
student-led prayers at public high school football games. The March
29 argument in the case, Santa Fe Independent School District vs.
Doe, No. 99-62, is likely to focus on whether the students' prayer
is truly private speech, and therefore presumably constitutional,
as the district and state maintain, or whether the circumstances of
the student's selection and performance make the event a form of
public worship that the Supreme Court's precedents forbid.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MIRANDA
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, two years after the court's ruling in Miranda vs.
Arizona, Congress tried to blunt the decision by reverting to the
``voluntariness'' test for the admissibility of confessions in
federal prosecutions, with the court-specified warnings
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Republican and Democratic administrations refused to apply
the law, known as Section 3501, while conservative law enforcement
groups tried to bring it to the lower courts' attention. Finally
last year, the federal appeals court in Richmond, Va., ruled that
Congress was free to overturn Miranda and that it had, in effect,
done so. The Supreme Court's conservative bloc has been notably
lacking in deference to Congress, so one interesting question for
the April 19 argument in Dickerson vs. U.S., No. 99-5525, is what
stance the conservative justices who have criticized Miranda will
now take.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court ruled last year that the phrase
``partial-birth abortion'' as used in a 1997 Nebraska law
criminalizing the procedure ``has no fixed medical or legal
content'' and was so ill-defined as to be potentially applicable to
common techniques used for abortions early in pregnancy. That
placed an ``undue burden'' on a woman's exercise of her
constitutional right to abortion, the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals held.
</P>
<P>
   As the Supreme Court's first abortion case since 1992, Stenberg
vs. Carhart, No. 99-830, carries obvious political and emotional
freight. One question for the April 25 argument is whether the
justices will confine themselves to examining the deficiency the
appeals court identified, or whether they want to make a broader
statement about the constitutional status of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   BOY SCOUTS
</P>
<P>
   Although the effort of a gay Eagle Scout, James Dale, to regain
his place in a New Jersey troop has positioned Boy Scouts of
America vs. Dale, No. 99-699, as a gay rights case, the court may
well not see it that way. The question for the April 26 argument is
whether the Boy Scouts have a right, under the First Amendment's
protection for freedom of association, to define its own
``expressive character'' by excluding gay members.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent relevant precedent, the court ruled
unanimously that the Boston St. Patrick's Day parade could not be
required to include a group marching under a gay-rights banner. But
in ruling for Dale, the New Jersey Supreme Court noted that he was
not carrying a banner but simply wanted to remain a member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
