<HEADLINE>
SPRING TRAINING A CULTURE SHOCK FOR LAMB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ Mike Lamb has been playing baseball almost
all his life and what happens on the field hasn't changed all that
much in his first major-league camp.
</P>
<P>
   It's what happens off the field that he has found overwhelming
as he tries to win a job as the Rangers' third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' Lamb said yesterday before the Rangers' 5-4
loss to the Philadelphia Phillies. ``It's something new. In spring
training, I've never had to fight for a position in the minor
leagues. That's something new for me. But it's not like I've been
overmatched and it's not like I don't think I can hit, even though
my average is not what I wanted it to be. I'm not discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it; it's just different than anything I've
ever done. A ton of people asking you for your autograph, wanting
to take your picture. Reporters asking you questions, radio, TV .
.. people saying one day, `you're going to be there,' the next week
saying, `what's happening, what's going on?' For someone going
through it the first time, it's a cultural shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb was the Rangers' Minor League Player of the Year last
season, hitting .324 with 21 home runs and 100 runs batted in. When
the Rangers failed to re-sign Todd Zeile in the off-season, it
appeared Lamb would be the Rangers' starting third baseman on
Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   But then Triple-A third baseman Tom Evans showed up in Port
Charlotte doing his best Mike Schmidt impersonation, hitting four
home runs in the first eight games. Suddenly Lamb no longer was a
sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even older players can get overwhelmed by it,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``It's all part of the learning process.
It's different here than Double-A and Triple-A. But Mike Lamb is
going to be fine. He's going to hit and he's going to find a place
to play in the big leagues real soon.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that it's hard to tell when.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb walked in his one pinch-hit appearance yesterday and is
batting .242. Evans, who has cooled off, went 0-for-3 but is still
hitting .400. There are two weeks left in camp and the Rangers'
intense third base competition continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know more in two weeks,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb understands that. He said he never came to spring training
with the belief that he would automatically be the Rangers'
starting third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to have to earn it,'' Lamb said. ``It's not
a given just because Tommy isn't on the 40-man roster. If he needs
to be in Arlington on Opening Day, he'll be there. They'll make the
move. I saw him down in Triple-A and I respect the fact that he's
been around. He's a good ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Rangers said was we're going to give you the
opportunity, that's all I can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb admitted it's hard not to think ahead or keep from
wondering what's going to happen at the end of spring training. He
also admitted he was pressing a little bit at the start of spring
after Evans got off to a great start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you see Tommy doing well and you're trying to
match it,'' Lamb said. ``You can sit there and say, I'm not going
to hit a million home runs, so I just have to stay within myself.
But it's harder to do it than to just say it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not scared of not winning the job. If I have to go to
Triple-A, it doesn't mean life is over. It just gives me more time
to be better prepared if I get called up or for next year. It's
still an opportunity to play baseball at a high level. Triple-A is
quality baseball, it's not a slam in the face if I've got to go
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lamb made one thing clear, ``I'm not saying I want to go to
Triple-A. I'm going to do everything I can to make this team.'' /
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
