<HEADLINE>
SEGUI HAPPY WHEREEVER HE PLAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEARWATER, Fla. _ David Segui made one thing perfectly clear
upon joining the Rangers yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   He has no problem being the Rangers' designated hitter even if
he would rather be playing first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally I'd rather play first base,'' Segui said. ``But I'm
not the manager; I don't make out the lineup. I've never once
complained about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui was acquired from the Toronto Blue Jays on Thursday in a
three-way trade that sent Lee Stevens to the Montreal Expos. He is
expected to be the Rangers' designated hitter while Rafael Palmeiro
returns to first base.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Johnny Oates continues to insist both will play in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much, I don't know,'' Oates said. ``I can't be wrong with
either one of them at first base. As we go along in the season,
we'll see what develops. We'll figure out each day what's best for
the team ... and that's what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Segui, ``Johnny doesn't have to explain anything to me.
Whatever he wants, I'll do. I'm not going to complain that I need
to play first base more or DH less. I'm here to win, not to
complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui has been a first baseman for most of his career but the
Toronto Blue Jays used him as a designated hitter last year after
acquiring him on July 28 from the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's boring as hell when you're used to playing in the
field,'' Segui said. ``It's an adjustment at first. It's a totally
different mindset. I'm a little high-strung and I had to control
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui played for Oates for three years while they were with the
Baltimore Orioles. Third base coach Jerry Narron and general
manager Doug Melvin were also there and Segui said, ``They're all
people I respect. It's nice to be in a situation where you're
comfortable.''
Oates on realignment
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates has seen newspaper reports suggesting Major League
Baseball's next realignment will put the Rangers in a six-team
Central Division. But his preference would be for baseball to have
six five-team divisions, even if it means an inter-league game
every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like symmetry,'' Oates said. ``At least you get the same
number of teams to beat out as everybody else.''
Injury report
</P>
<P>
   The latest on the Rangers' injured pitchers:
</P>
<P>
   Justin Thompson (left shoulder surgery) threw batting practice
for 10 minutes yesterday without problems. He limited his
repertoire to fastballs and changeups and did not throw a curve.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland (strained groin) came through Friday's throwing
session without any day-after soreness. He is expected to throw off
a mound again today and batting practice tomorrow. Manager Johnny
Oates said he'll sit down with Wetteland after that and formulate a
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Venafro (strained ligament in left middle finger) threw
yesterday for 10 minutes without tape on the finger. Venafro
reported some initial pain but said it went away after two or three
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Loaiza, scratched from his previous start because of
tightness in his elbow, threw for 12 minutes in the bullpen and
said he felt normal. He'll start tomorrow against the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Bill Haselman was hit in the right knee with a pitch in
the second inning and had to leave the game. He is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Helling allowed three runs in five innings against the
Phillies yesterday, leaving Rangers starters with a 3.19 earned-run
average in spring training. The Rangers staff has a 4.89 ERA.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
