<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-SETONHALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETON HALL'S BACKUP POINT GUARD UPSETS TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ During the palpitating pressure of overtime,
Shaheen Holloway's face was temporarily clear of tears. He rose
from his wheelchair, balanced his weight on his one healthy foot
and stood to cheer his Seton Hall teammates who were trying to beat
Temple without him Sunday in their second-round game of East
Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates were the underdogs even when they had their
co-captain and star guard, and they played most of day without him
because he left early with a badly sprained left ankle. They
trailed twice in overtime. But they got what they needed when Ty
Shine _ Holloway's replacement _ hit yet another 3-point field goal
from the top of the key to bring his game total to 26. That gave
Seton Hall a 1-point lead with 18.9 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a Temple turnover, a Temple foul and two free throws
by the freshman Greg Morton, who had missed two others in the
previous minute. Holloway, his chair parked at the end of the
bench, caught Morton's eye and encouraged him by demonstrating the
shooting motion. Morton made one of two. The lead was 2 points.
With the final seconds ticking away and the screams of the fans
filling the air, Temple's Lynn Greer launched a desperate long shot
that banked off the back of the rim and triggered two celebrations
of a 67-65 Seton Hall victory.
</P>
<P>
   While Pirates players rushed together on the floor, Holloway
raised his arms in exultation before being engulfed by team
personnel, including the Rev. Frank McNulty, one of the team
chaplains. ``He was crying,'' McNulty said. Holloway had his
reasons. ``I was afraid this was going to be my last college
game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It still could be for him, but not for his team. The Pirates
will meet Oklahoma State Friday in the regional semifinals in
Syracuse, the Cowboys having defeated Pepperdine, 75-67, in
Sunday's first game.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, who was hurt when he stepped on a Temple player's
sneaker while making a layup on a fast break with about 12 minutes
left in the first half, has no broken bone but a severe sprain, the
team announced. After returning from the X-ray room of a nearby
hospital, he was wheeled to the bench, his ankle wrapped, raised
and covered by ice, with 12:40 left in the game. He wiped tears
from his cheeks and fans tried to console him by chanting his name.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway's status for next weekend is, at best, questionable. In
the previous game, a 72-71 victory over Oregon, Holloway had scored
the winning basket on a floor-length drive in overtime. Of the 48
games so far in this tournament, Seton Hall has played two of the
most exciting.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the hero was Shine, the sophomore not content with
his backup, who played 37 minutes and made 9 of 15 field-goal
attempts, including 7 of 11 from 3-point range over the matchup
zone defense of the Owls. Shine brought the ball upcourt, ordered
teammates into position and fulfilled the mission of a morning
prayer session. During that pre-breakfast meeting, McNulty spoke to
some of the players about courage. After the game, Shine approached
the priest and said: ``That thing on courage helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   They needed that and much more and they got it from several
sources. Rimas Kaukenas, gritty as usual, scored 18 points and
crashed to the floor several times. Darius Lane scored 16 points
and grabbed 14 rebounds. Lane had four assists and Shine had five.
Although Temple got 27 points from Mark Archer, the Owls got only 6
assists from Pepe Sanchez, their star guard, who fouled out in the
final minute of regulation time. The Owls, seeded No. 2 in this
region, ended their season at 27-6 while the 10th seeded Pirates
rose to 22-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very empty,'' Sanchez said. ``We weren't ready enough
to handle all the pressure. We're not a great team. We're a good
team. We have what we deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seton Hall people feel the same way. The players and coaches
are cautious about trivializing tragedy, but all are aware of the
mood lingering on campus from the dormitory fire that killed three
freshmen in January. Tommy Amaker, the coach, said ``Our whole
school drew closer'' after the fire and that the basketball team is
helping to raise spirits even as mourning continues.
</P>
<P>
   The exhilaration of this weekend is being felt in groups and by
individuals. Kaukenas, one of the more eloquent of the Pirates,
said: ``At the end of the game, we had a timeout and I told
everyone that we had to win because we owe it to Shaheen. He really
helped us get into this position. For us to come out of this with a
win, it is very exciting, probably the most exciting thing to
happen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Many moments suggested a different result. The Owls led by 14-3
in the fifth minute and the Pirates were turning over the ball.
Samuel Dalembert, their big freshman center, triggered a brief
surge when two blocked shots led to 5 quick points on fast breaks.
But the last two also brought Holloway's injury. ``I didn't want it
to end like this,'' said Holloway, a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Shine making shots, Dalembert took his fourth foul in
the second minute of the second half. He went to the bench and this
weakened Seton Hall's defensive presence. But Shine, Lane and
Kaukenas combined to make 15 of 30 attempts from 3-point range. The
Temple lead never exceeded 5 points. Dalembert returned and made a
layup a minute later to give the Pirates the lead. At the
regulation buzzer, Kevin Wilkins missed a jumper that would have
won the game for Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   They would have to wait another five minutes, but victory would
be theirs. Shine, who wears the numeral ``0'' on his shirt _ the
one that looks like a basketball hoop _ had bided his time as
Holloway's understudy. After he had career bests in minutes played
and points scored Sunday, he still had enough energy to rush to the
sideline after the final buzzer to answer the cheers of the fans by
placing his right hand to his forehead and giving them a snappy
salute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things come to those who wait,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
