<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA STANDS BY CRITICISM OF PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MARC LACEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the face of criticism from political friends and
foes alike, the National Rifle Association refused on Sunday to
back off the supercharged rhetoric of the group's executive vice
president, Wayne R. LaPierre Jr., who last week labeled President
Clinton as an accessory to murder for not enforcing the nation's
gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre did decline to repeat the inflammatory line that the
president has blood on his hands, but he nonetheless stood by his
remarks in a series of television appearances on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I used some strong language,'' LaPierre said on NBC's
``Meet the Press.'' ``But I did it to center the issue on the fact
that this administration, over the last seven years, has dropped
federal enforcement of existing federal gun laws against the bad
guys by 50 percent. And that's why I used the language, to center
the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the NRA itself, LaPierre's tough talk won accolades from
some hardliners who have regarded him as too moderate in his
defense of gun owners' rights. Turning up the heat on Clinton, NRA
officials say, has also resulted in an increase in the
organization's membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he said what he did I thought, `It's about time someone
says it like it is,''' said David Edgar, who builds swimming pools
in Houston and keeps guns for self-defense. Edgar logged onto his
computer and joined the NRA last week after hearing LaPierre
lambaste the president for allowing a certain level of violence in
the country for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of people beating around the bush,'' said Edgar, who
described himself as a vehement gun proponent. ``There are so many
gun laws and every time the president opens up his mouth about
another one, people like me go out and stock up on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the political world, NRA allies were clearly
uncomfortable with LaPierre's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wouldn't have said that,'' said Rep. Tom DeLay of
Texas, the House majority whip and an NRA ally.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican presidential
candidate, also has urged the NRA to engage in more civil
discourse. Five years ago, Bush's father, former President Bush,
resigned from the gun organization after LaPierre signed a
fund-raising letter that referred to federal agents as ``jackbooted
government thugs,'' a comment for which he later apologized.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA suffered a setback on Friday when Smith &AMP; Wesson, the
nation's largest handgun manufacturer, broke ranks with the other
companies and struck a deal to end government lawsuits. The
organization is also battling the White House over gun control
legislation caught in a logjam on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance Sunday on ABC's ``This Week,'' Charlton Heston,
the president of the NRA, called LaPierre's language ``extreme
rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heston stuck by LaPierre's intent. And the two NRA leaders
blamed the administration on Sunday for the shooting death of a
sheriff's deputy, Ricky Kinchen, in Atlanta last week. Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin, a leader of the Black Panthers in the 1960s who
was known then as H. Rap Brown, is wanted in connection with the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this administration had done their job properly, that Rap
would still be in prison and Deputy Kinchen would be alive,''
Heston said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, who was with the
president in New Delhi, said on ``Meet the Press'' that such talk
was ``really sick rhetoric, and it should be repudiated by anyone
who hears it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it appeals to some activists within the NRA who want no part
of even the compromise legislation that the gun lobby has supported
on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a gun law that reduces crime,'' said Neal Fox,
an NRA board member who considers LaPierre too moderate. ``There
are a lot of unconstitutional laws out there that don't have any
reason to be enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said the NRA has been accused of far more deaths than
LaPierre is putting on the White House. ``We're baby killers, and
we're responsible for Columbine and even the Oklahoma City
bombing,'' said Fox. ``To hear our critics, all evil can be traced
to the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre joined the NRA in 1977 after working as a legislative
aide to a Democratic assemblyman in Virginia. He has risen through
the ranks, survived criticism about his management style and
financial stewardship, and seen the organization through many
crises.
</P>
<P>
   But within the NRA, he must always watch his back. Some members
complain that he is not a real gun lover and that he is more
comfortable in a suit and tie than in camouflage. Others say he is
overly concerned with courting politicians.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre's anti-Clinton remarks illustrate the delicate line he
must walk. He alienated some political supporters and aggravated
the White House but may have helped the organization boost its
hard-core base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money doesn't come in when you don't talk tough,'' said
Dudley Brown, executive director of Rocky Mountain Gun Owners,
which considers the NRA too moderate. ``Also, you can't raise money
if members are mad at you. You get them on your side by talking
tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
