<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN RETURNS TO AN UNEASY SENATE  
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John McCain returns to the Senate on Monday with a
national following but facing a peculiar challenge: how to use his
new prominence to propel forward his signature issue of campaign
finance overhaul at a moment when everyone in politics is posing as
a reformer.
</P>
<P>
   The question will be placed front and center barely hours after
Senate Republicans face the ticklish etiquette of how to welcome
back a colleague who often ran against them and forced their chosen
candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, to eat up the $70 million
that was supposed to go a long way to ensuring his ultimate
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, the Kentucky Republican who has been
McCain's chief antagonist on changing the campaign finance law, is
opening hearings on the issue on Wednesday. And Sen. Chuck Hagel,
the Nebraska Republican who is one of McCain's closest friends in
the Senate, has entered the debate with his own rival measure,
which McCain's allies call deeply flawed.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed interest in campaign finance might look like good
news for the advocates of change. ``If anyone had said a year ago
that campaign finance reform would be a central theme of the
primaries and the general election, I don't think anybody would
have believed that person,'' said Sen. Russell D. Feingold, the
Wisconsin Democrat who co-sponsors McCain's bill to ban large
unregulated contributions to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   But McConnell insists that McCain's defeat showed that
Republicans, at least, widely oppose his efforts to cut down on
money in politics. And Bush, for all of his criticism of Vice
President Al Gore's fund-raising efforts, shows no signs of
embracing a bill that he criticized sharply in his debates with
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   So the seeming proliferation of reformers could serve less to
propel forward legislation than to take the edge off the issue by
providing election-year cover for candidates who want some of
McCain's sheen. ``I've never seen so many reformers in my life,''
said Fred Wertheimer, the president of Democracy 21, a group
advocating tighter campaign finance laws. ``The danger here is
clear _ people trying to co-op the campaign finance reform issue
and pass off fake reforms as real.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is how McCain will respond. The senator's aides
have made clear that McCain will maintain a national presence to
promote his ideas, establishing a political action committee to pay
his expenses for a national speaking tour and to stump for
like-minded Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Whether McCain will ever endorse Bush is still an open question.
The senator is planning to confer with his former campaign staff on
an array of topics in meetings on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But almost immediately he must decide on legislative tactics _
whether and how much to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Originally McCain and Feingold had proposed legislation that
banned the donations to political parties known as soft money and
reined in the ability of outside groups to run issue advocacy
advertisements, which are really thinly disguised efforts designed
to promote or attack a candidate. The bill won a majority of the
Senate but not the 60 votes needed to overcome a Republican
filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   With many Republicans and conservative groups calling the
provisions on issue advertisements an assault on constitutional
guarantees of free speech, the two men last fall stripped their
bill down to just the banning of soft money in hopes of picking up
more votes. They planned to then try to win the necessary 60 votes
on the floor by accepting amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The House last year passed the companion bill for
McCain-Feingold, sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and
Martin T. Meehan, D-Mass. But in the Senate, McCain and Feingold
made no headway when Democrats forced votes on the more
comprehensive original bill and the Republican leadership then took
the issue from the floor as deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Now Republicans look as if they may be prepared to coalesce
around Hagel's bill, which has several Democratic sponsors. ``From
my point of view it has big deficiencies,'' McConnell said but
added, ``at least it's a different kind of bipartisan vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would limit soft money donations to national political
parties, allowing individuals, unions and corporations to
contribute a maximum of $120,000 per election cycle. At the same
time it would triple the current $1,000 limit on individual
contributions to federal candidates, which has not changed in the
quarter century since it was enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The proponents of the McCain-Feingold legislation argue that
rather than limiting money in politics, Hagel's approach would
actually allow more money to pour into politics because the limits
on soft money are so porous. Hagel would not stop federal
candidates or officials from raising soft money for state political
parties, so his cap on such donations could well prove meaningless
beyond shifting where the fund-raising takes place.
</P>
<P>
   While Hagel says that many states have strict limits on
fund-raising, Feingold says, ``It's not real reform.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Mark Buse, a senior aide to McCain, said he ``genuinely
appreciates the effort that Senator Hagel is making'' but that he
``cannot support the Hagel bill as currently written.''
</P>
<P>
   As McCain sorts out how to move forward on campaign finance
legislation, his Senate colleagues have been wondering how to
handle him. Just a month ago, several Republicans say, Sen. Trent
Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, was wondering whether a
long primary fight meant that McCain should be replaced as chairman
of the Senate Commerce Committee to keep the committee moving.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, Lott's spokesman, adamantly denied that such an
idea was ever considered. Another senior Republican official who
declined to be identified said Lott's second in command, Sen. Don
Nickles of Oklahoma, calmed the waters by suggesting that Senate
Republicans just wait and let the presidential race play out
further.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, however, eager to patch up rifts in their
party and keep in their fold the legions of independents McCain
attracted, his colleagues debated ways to celebrate McCain, perhaps
with a cocktail reception, or a cake or a standing ovation. No
matter that on the campaign trail McCain often held up projects for
Lott's state as examples of pork or that he proclaimed his victory
in New Hampshire as a triumph over the ``machine'' of Sen. Judd
Gregg, R-N.H. Or that he used similar language against Sen. John W.
Warner of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican celebrations were vetoed by McCain's aides
and supporters, and he is now expected to get a more sedate welcome
back at the Republicans' weekly lunchtime caucus on Tuesday. ``The
last thing any of us want is some kind of hypocritical and
duplicitous kind of activity,'' said Hagel, who was one of McCain's
national campaign chairmen. ``John has differences with some of our
colleagues and they have differences with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
