<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE E-MAIL FEUD GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., said Sunday that he would
subpoena President Clinton's chief counsel to appear before a
congressional committee this week to explain a computer glitch that
might have kept e-mail messages received by hundreds of White House
officials out of the hands of congressional and other
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the White House counsel, Beth Nolan, acknowledged in
a letter to Burton, the chairman of the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee, that a series of problems prevented some of
the e-mail messages received by administration officials from being
searched in 1998 when the White House was responding to various
subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   But Nolan said it would cost as much as $3 million and take as
long as two years to fix the problem, which she said was caused by
unintentional human error. She added that she did not know the
number of unrecorded e-mail messages sent from outside the White
House or the relevance of their contents.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan also disclosed a previously unknown glitch on the computer
server in the office of Vice President Al Gore. ``We are still in
the process of determining the scope and time period involved,''
she said. Burton said he would pursue that matter at a hearing on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Computer specialists who helped set up the White House computer
system have said that administration officials were slow to fix the
problem. Several contractors employed at the White House also said
that a White House supervisor threatened them with the prospect of
criminal prosecution if they disclosed the problem to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest glitch was caused, officials say, when a technician
mistakenly labeled an e-mail server as ``MAIL2'' instead of
``Mail2,'' causing the computer to misread the label. A
typographical error in another line of computer code also prevented
certain e-mail messages from being recorded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
