<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY 
Ready to choke on another expose on Bobby ``Hoosier Daddy'' Knight?
Capitalizing on the latest allegations made by a former Indiana
player to CNN/SI, this branch of the Time/Warner media
conglomeration has its own take on the General, sending Frank
Deford out for an up-close-and-personal that had to be updated
right up to air time. There are three other pretty compelling
stories in this show, too, if you're wondering, including one on
ESPN billiards maven ``The Black Widow.'' That'll be our cue to
watch. ``Real Sports,'' HBO, 10 p.m. (replays this week Tuesday at
5:30 p.m., Wednesday at 2 p.m. and Friday at 10 a.m.) 
TUESDAY 
Their second meeting in five days (after an inconclusive 2-2 tie
last week) also marks their last encounter of the season. FYI: The
Ducks (9-8-3) actually have a far better record within the division
than the Kings (5-11-2). NHL: Ducks at Kings, ESPN2, Fox Sports
Net, 7:30 p.m. 
WEDNESDAY 
The NBA playoffs begin in one month from here, in case you were
wondering. NBA: Golden State at Lakers, Fox Sports Net, 7:30 p.m. 
THURSDAY 
With 76 percent of the tournament complete, the Daily News is
projecting a UCLA-Duke final. Or Wisconsin-Tulsa. Or ... NCAA men's
basketball tournament: Midwest and West Regional semifinals, 4:30
p.m., Channel 2, including UCLA vs. Iowa State. (Those regional
finals are a doubleheader Saturday starting at 1:30 p.m.; the East
and South Regional semifinals are Friday at 4:30 p.m. with those
two finals' doubleheader Sunday starting at 11:30 a.m.) 
FRIDAY 
If Jose Canseco coulda only stayed healthy his entire career ... so
here's his chance to show up his former ``Bash Brother'' in a
long-ball contest. ``Big League Challenge'' home run tournament:
Mark McGwire vs. Jose Canseco, ESPN2, 2:30 p.m. (Series runs each
weekday this week on ESPN2 at 2:30 p.m.) 
SATURDAY 
Disney is gonna preempt Cartoon Saturday for this? MLS: Galaxy at
D.C. United, Channel 7, 11 a.m. 
SUNDAY 
We've conceded that Denzel ``Hurricane'' Washington doesn't have
enough juice to KO Kevin Spacey in the Oscar battle for best actor.
Given that there are any Oscars to give out. So we're more
interested to see how many times Jack Nicholson's limo will circle
the Shrine Auditorium as he tries to watch the end of the Lakers
game on the back-seat TV. McMurphy should be going nuts right
around the start of Billy Crystal's opening number. NBA: Lakers at
Sacramento, Channel 4, 3:30 p.m.; Academy Awards, Channel 7, 5:30
p.m. 

