<HEADER>
A1845 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH20-PERSONALS-SFCH     03-19 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH20-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' category)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; REAL-LIFE TRYOUT FOR PLAYING A MOVIE ROLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
In his forthcoming memoir, ``The Measure of a Man''
(HarperSanFrancisco; $26),  &UR; Sidney Poitier &LR;  describes
meeting &UR; Spencer Tracy &LR;  and  &UR; Katharine Hepburn &LR;  just before the
making of ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner?''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie (set in San Francisco), Poitier plays the African
American fiance of Tracy and Hepburn's daughter; in 1968, it was
considered daring social commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taken to Miss Hepburn's house so she could check me
out,'' writes Poitier. ``When I arrived at her door and that door
opened, she looked at me and didn't say a word and didn't crack a
smile. But that was her M.O. ... I could tell that I was being
sized up every time I spoke, every response I made. I could imagine
a plus and a minus column, notations in her mind. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is that the formation of this business
relationship was almost a literal `pre-enactment' of the situation
in the film we were about to make. The black man was coming for
dinner, and we didn't usually do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Poitier knew that both Hepburn and Tracy were ``ordinary, decent
folks. And in fact they turned out to be that _ and a hell of a lot
more. But they were anxious early on, for good reason, and they
simply had to find out about me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hedy Lamarr &LR; , who died on January 19, left $83,000 in stock to
Lt.  &UR; Chuck Stansel &LR; , a police officer in the Orlando, Fla., suburb
of Casselberry. Stansel, who had been asked to relay a message to
her in 1991, says she befriended him and his family. He was in the
habit of stopping by her house about twice a week to run errands
for her. ``She asked me to buy her some cranberry juice one day,''
he told APBnews.com
</P>
<P>
   - Wireless Flash reports that the El San Juan Hotel in Puerto
Rico is placing a plaque on the spot where  &UR; Barbara Walters &LR; 
interviewed  &UR; Ricky Martin &LR;  for a future TV special.
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Jeffrey Wigand &LR; , whose whistle-blowing is the subject of ``The
Insider,'' will attend the Oscar ceremonies, his invitation having
been obtained for him by  &UR; Michael Mann &LR; , director and producer of
the movie. Wigand did not call the academy himself; inquiries were
made in his behalf by Canadian lawyer and fellow anti-smoking
crusader  &UR; Doug Lennox &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; CHEZ MICKEY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Architectural Digest's special Hollywood at Home issue features the
New York apartment of  &UR; Mickey Rourke &LR; , which is _ considering
Rourke's tough-guy image _ surprisingly formal and opulent. ``He
loves talking about design, and he's good at it,'' said Rourke's
decorator,  &UR; David Purdie &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Rourke said he met with Purdie many times to discuss the
project. ``My ideas came from some of the hotels where I stay in
Europe _ the Raphael in Paris, the Negresco in Nice and Blakes in
London, especially the  &UR; Claudia Cardinale &LR;  Room. I wanted the
apartment to be impersonal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want any pictures of me or any books on shelves. I
wanted it to look like a place where I would come as a visitor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Work gets me money, recognition and pleasure. It gives you,
everyone, friendship and self-esteem. When people are raving about
you, that is what is rewarding. And work continues to buy me
recognition and popularity. Your work makes you viable. If you are
as old as I am, who would invite you to a party?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Helen Gurley Brown, 78, to the Telegraph of London. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
