<SLUG> BC-POPE-SECURITY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLY LAND JITTERS HEIGHTEN SECURITY FOR PAPAL VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 13, 14 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A recent newspaper cartoon illustrates the anxiety
here that something will befall Pope John Paul II on his six-day
pilgrimage to the Holy Land, which begins on Tuesday. The cartoon
shows Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel encouraging the pope to
step out onto a bridge that extends into the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we cross, let us pray,'' the pope says, hesitant.
</P>
<P>
   The image recalls a disaster that Israelis cannot forget _ when
a temporary bridge built for athletes in an international meet in
1997 collapsed, leaving four dead and scores injured. And last
week, when a stiff wind caused structural damage on the stage where
the pope will preside over a huge outdoor Mass, it sent a shudder
through many Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collapse of a pillar even before anyone has stepped foot
on the stage is a sign from heaven that your appeal to the Jewish
people for forgiveness may have been premature,'' Yoel Marcus wrote
to the pope in a tongue-in-cheek column on Friday in the newspaper
Haaretz.
</P>
<P>
   While the religious and political dimensions of the pope's
six-day trip here are large, the logistical and security
preparations by both Israel and the Palestinian Authority are
unprecedented. The visit also requires an unparalleled cooperation
between the two governments, which so far, despite the minor
sniping of Jerusalem officials on both sides, has gone smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   A key concern of security officials was allayed last week when
the Palestinian police, acting on a tip from the Israelis, captured
two Islamic fundamentalist terror suspects with 88 pounds of
explosives. Having fled an Israeli raid on their hideout, during
which several of their colleagues were killed, they were considered
an at-large risk for an imminent attack.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials have not received specific threats against
the pope himself, although a tiny group of Jewish extremists is
aggressively antagonistic to his visit, the first state visit here
by a pope.
</P>
<P>
   The general potential for violence in the area is what concerns
security officials, who note that the pope's trip touches on all
the most sensitive issues here, from the Holocaust to the
sovereignty of Jerusalem to the right of return of Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real threat because of the security situation in
Israel,'' a senior security officer said. ``And the basic
assumption is that the pope is a target.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
