<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAYHILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS ADDS TO HIS MOMENTUM AND CONFIDENCE, AND EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The story line was familiar, and so was the
outcome. Tiger Woods protects Sunday leads like a miser protecting
his money. Davis Love III must have felt like a rock climber,
trying to scale a mountain that kept getting steeper and steeper.
Love never made it to the top, falling once again to Woods, who has
dominated Love and dominated golf for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Add the Bay Hill Invitational to Woods' growing list of
victories. And with next month's Masters fast approaching, Woods is
marching toward Augusta with more momentum and confidence than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Winning for the third time this year, and for the seventh time
on tour in his last 10 starts, Woods cruised to a four-stroke
victory over Love to win at Bay Hill, the tournament hosted by
another golf great, Arnold Palmer. Woods shot 70 Sunday to finish
18 under par for the tournament (269), comfortably ahead of Love
(14 under par), who shot 72, and Skip Kendall (13 under par), who
had an impressive final-round 67 to finish third.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods begins Sunday holding a lead, he almost always ends
his day holding a trophy. Sunday was the 13th consecutive time that
Woods has won a tour event when he has either held or shared the
lead after 54 holes. Woods does not just close tournaments, he
slams the door. And Sunday, the door slammed in Love's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it that much more special to beat one of the top
players in the world,'' said Woods, who has won 18 times in 76
career starts on tour, almost once ever four times he has played.
</P>
<P>
   The $540,000 first-place check increased Woods' 2000 earnings to
more than $2.58 million. Starting the day with a two-stroke lead
over Love, Woods led the final round from start to finish,
dictating the day with his potent driving ability. Woods hit tee
shot after tee shot onto the fairway, keeping constant pressure on
Love to make birdies because Woods refused to make mistakes. Woods
only made two birdies, but he did not make any bogeys, taking the
conservative approach on a windy, overcast day when scoring was
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Woods did miss a green, his brilliant short game took
over. Woods missed a combined 13 greens in regulation during
Saturday and Sunday, yet he never made a bogey. If he needed to
make a long putt for par, he made it. If he needed to get up and
down from a bunker, he did.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Woods' game appears to be in prime condition _
his driving, his distance control, his short game and his putting.
In six starts this year, Woods has three victories and two seconds,
with his only non top-10 finish coming at the Nissan Open, when he
tied for 18th place. When Woods arrives at a tournament, opponents
no longer wonder if he will contend. They expect him to. And Love,
one of the game's longest hitters, had the humbling experience of
being easily out-driven by Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's playing everybody's A game every week,'' said
Love, who lost to Woods at the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship last month. ``Mentally now, he's got the advantage. On
No. 4, he hit it 50 yards by me. It was just astounding. There's
very few guys that I get out there with and say I cannot keep up. I
don't ever expect to hit one by Tiger unless he pops it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Love ran into trouble early, when he bogeyed No. 2 and No. 3 to
fall four strokes behind. At No. 3, Love pulled his second shot
into the water, the kind of blunder he could not afford to make.
</P>
<P>
   Woods increased his lead to five strokes when he birdied No. 5,
and from there the outcome looked almost certain. Love did close to
within two strokes with birdies on No. 5, No. 10, and No. 11, but
Woods responded with a birdie at the par 5 No. 12, then Love
bogeyed No. 14 with a three-putt to fall four strokes behind with
five holes to play. Woods simply does not lose leads like that
often.
</P>
<P>
   One of the only things that went wrong for Woods Sunday is that
university he attended, Stanford, lost to Love's school, North
Carolina, in the National Collegiate Athletic Association men's
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I can enjoy that,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for Woods is The Players Championship, which begins
Thursday in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla. Woods will then take a week off
to prepare for the Masters (April 6-9), where he will obviously be
the favorite. Everything Woods has done this year has been directed
toward preparing for the Masters, the first of the year's four
majors. And at this point, Woods looks more than ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm heading in the right direction for Augusta,'' Woods said.
``Hopefully next week I'll have some signs that I'm actually
playing a little bit better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
