<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1858 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-LAKERS-NYT     03-19 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS' TURNAROUND BECOMES A TALL TALE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One at a time, the Knicks' big men would duck around
the back of Shaquille O'Neal only to disappear behind the Lakers'
perfect hide-and-seek prop. One at a time, they would plant a
forearm in O'Neal's waist and stick a body on his frame only to be
brushed off like lint from his lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Here was O'Neal, as ominous as a funnel cloud, and the Knicks
were trying to stop his force with a screen door. Here was Coach
Jeff Van Gundy's plan: He would send help once O'Neal began his
fe-fi-fo-fum moves through the paint, but he would not waste his
manpower, at the risk of leaving the other stars from Hollywood
open.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the execution of this strategy had the Knicks giddy
with confidence. For a while, the celebrity-spiked crowd at Madison
Square Garden could imagine a bicoastal finals without shuddering.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Kobe Bryant snapped his fingers on their daydream. As he
started to zip around Latrell Sprewell on his way to
flashbulb-drenched dunks, after Bryant blew the tip of his index
finger like a gunslinger at one point, Phil Jackson could find more
comfort than ever over his career choice.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Jackson's tandem topped whatever his coaching foil
from New York could come up with as a response. Sunday, Jackson's
new version of Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen (O'Neal and
Bryant) took over the game in the second half and delivered a 92-85
puncture wound to the Knicks' egos. Next to O'Neal's 43 points,
Bryant added 17 of his 24 in the second half to take control of a
game the Knicks lost once the third quarter began.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an opportunity for us to make a statement and we fell
short,'' said Sprewell, who was helpless to defend against Bryant's
playground moves. ``Kobe made the big shots, got some big rebounds.
He came through for them. It was a frustrating day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks could not unearth one of their big stars to counter.
With O'Neal running out to alter the high-arching shot of his
counterpart, Patrick Ewing finished 6 for 20 with 12 points. With
Bryant irritating Sprewell's rhythm, the Knicks high-energy forward
mustered only 13 points on a 5 for 13 day. With a listless second
half, Allan Houston managed only 20 points after scoring 13 in a
riveting first half.
</P>
<P>
   That is when the Knicks had a 44-43 lead. That is when they were
shutting down everyone but O'Neal. He had 24 points but the rest of
the Lakers were 7 for 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made everyone who guarded him look 6-feet tall,'' Sprewell
said. ``He is just a huge and dominant player to defend against.
But the thing about him is, he has a surprisingly soft touch. He
was hitting that jump hook, and made most of his free throws. With
the way he has been playing this year _ and he's probably the
m.v.p. right now _ we knew we had to stop everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the third quarter began, the Knicks' euphoria over that
potential was replaced by dismay. The Lakers went on a 13-5 run to
take a 7-point lead on the strength of free throws by Bryant and
O'Neal. By the end of the third quarter, the Lakers had a 69-58
lead after taking 13 fouls shots to the Knicks' 3 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the game,'' said Ewing, who did not go to the foul
line once on the day. ``They got the calls. We didn't. That's the
way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the third quarter ended was an omen. As Bryant spun
through the lane, he flipped up a wild driving layup from the seat
of his pants. And it fell right into the net as the third-quarter
buzzer went off.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of digging deep into their assertiveness training guide,
the Knicks continued to counter with jump shots even after O'Neal
picked up his fourth foul a minute into the fourth quarter. When
they did drive to the basket, it was not emphatic. Several times
during the day, Marcus Camby missed layups when a sure dunk seemed
like an option if not for his sore right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make any excuses,'' said Camby, who had eight
rebounds but was just 1 for 8 from the field. ``I know I'm not 100
percent but I should hit those shots. We just didn't play as well
as we're capable of this time. I know we can play better against
them than that. We had our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Each one was botched, though. After the Knicks cut the Lakers'
13-point fourth-quarter lead to 8 with 4 minutes 39 seconds left,
Bryant made an awful pass that hit Sprewell right in the chest. He
fumbled the ball, let it slide off his hip and Bryant gobbled it
up. In one motion, Bryant slipped behind the 3-point arc and
unleashed a shot that fell perfectly at the shot-clock buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was typical of our day,'' Sprewell said. ``The ball was
right there for me and I should have had it. He turns around and
hits a 3-pointer. Just typical of the kind of day it was.''
</P>
<P>
   It was deflating. After winning four in a row, after putting
their season of lulls behind them, this was a chance to gain some
confidence. The Knicks played defense, holding the Lakers to 42.5
percent from the field, and grabbed the rebounding edge, 48-46, but
they could only afford to let O'Neal dominate his one-on-ones with
the helpless Kurt Thomas and slow-moving Ewing. Once Bryant shook
loose from Sprewell, the strategy collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What O'Neal did was fine,'' Van Gundy said of O'Neal's 43
points. ``It was Bryant's 17 in the second half that hurt us. You
hold a team like that to 42 percent shooting and out-rebound them,
you did a good job defensively. Bryant allowed them to get
separation from us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
