<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODEN CALLS WATSON'S PERFORMANCE `REMARKABLE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There is a new contender for the greatest
postseason performance in UCLA history. Earl Watson, meet Gail
Goodrich and Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   Just how does Watson's game against Maryland (17 points, a
school-record 16 assists, no turnovers) compare to the best the
Bruins have to offer?
</P>
<P>
   Was Watson as good as Gail Goodrich, who scored 42 points in the
1965 championship game victory over Michigan?
</P>
<P>
   Was he as good as Bill Walton, who made 21 of 22 shots and
scored 44 points in the 1973 championship game victory over Memphis
State?
</P>
<P>
   And what about Ed O'Bannon, who had 30 points and 17 rebounds in
the 1995 championship victory over Arkansas?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Watson's scoring can't compare. But it could be decades
before someone duplicates a 16-assists, no-turnover game.
</P>
<P>
   The man who knows best, former coach John Wooden, declined to
pick a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a remarkable performance (by Watson),'' Wooden said.
``Itcompares to any of the fine individual performances in
tournament play.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich, Walton and O'Bannon won championships with their play.
Watson won a second-round game. That's not to diminish his
brilliance, but the stakes simply are not comparable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, try telling the Bruins that. They were in awe of
Watson afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like what Earl did,'' forward Rico
Hines said. ``Baron (Davis) has done some amazing things, but Earl
was in a zone. He was in total command. He could do anything he
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   More Watson: He doesn't have to look far for advice. Assistant
coach Michael Holton was the starting point guard on UCLA's 1980
team that lost to Louisville in the NCAA finals. Holton has
counseled Watson all season on making the transition from off-guard
- his position in 1998 and '99 - to point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Holton also made some points about playing the point in March
Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to play differently in the tournament, but you
have to recognize the transition opportunities - when they're there
and when they aren't there,'' Holton said. ``In the tournament,
because of its single-elimination format, turnovers have much
greater significance. One swing of the momentum can put you behind.
I think Earl understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   If his day job doesn't work out: No doubt, the highlight of
UCLA's postseason banquet last week was a short speech from guard
Ray Young, who has shot poorly all season but won the best
defensive player award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just spoke the truth,'' Young said, smiling. ``I told
everybody that the coaches fooled me into playing defense by
telling me it would help my offense. Well, next year, when I get my
offense on track, they can kiss this award goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally: Amazing how similar UCLA's season has been to North
Carolina's. They are two of the most successful programs in college
history. Both are talented teams that underachieved during the
regular season. Both head coaches were severely criticized. Both
teams found new life in the tournament. Both stunned higher-seeded
teams in the second round (UNC beat Stanford on Sunday). Both have
morphed into Final Four contenders.
</P>
<P>
   And finally II: Three weeks ago, who figured UCLA would be the
last Pacific-10 team standing?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
