<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   This is a tale of two cities.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 3, I made my entry into Manhattan when my mother
moved back from California. I spent the next 15 years living in
poverty in a rooming house. This gave me the opportunity, as a
young impressionable lad, to explore Gotham on foot.
</P>
<P>
   One day en route to Central Park, when I was 10 years old, I saw
a large black limousine pulling up in front of a Park Avenue hotel.
The uniformed doorman threw open the door, saluted and welcomed a
distinguished-looking man in a dark suit carrying a briefcase. When
the door of the hotel closed, I was left marveling at what wonders
awaited this person who disappeared under a sparkling crystal
chandelier.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, I was in Paris on a business trip, and my
large black limousine pulled up in front of the Hotel Ritz. A
uniformed doorman saluted as he opened the car door.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching my briefcase, I noticed out of the corner of my eye a
small boy staring at me in much the same way I, as a young boy, had
stared outside the Manhattan hotel. I wanted to tell him that if he
wished to trade places, he should study hard, get degrees in
engineering, learn a foreign language and get involved in
international sales. But I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   _ HJALMAR JOHANSSON
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Kolinsky was walking through a toy store with her
4-year-old granddaughter, Arielle Gordon, when they spotted a Woody
doll from ``Toy Story.'' According to the instructions, the doll
was supposed to talk or sing if his belt buckle was pushed. Arielle
pushed, to no avail. ``Maybe Woody is tired today,'' Kolinsky said.
Arielle flicked her eyelashes to indicate her scorn: ``Or maybe
batteries are sold separately,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor's name and specialty _ obstetrics and gynecology _ were
on a sign at the bottom of a street-level office window in Astoria.
Murray Hausknecht spotted another sign in the left corner of the
window: ``No deliveries in a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Kamisher, a volunteer in art therapy, entered the
hospital room of an elderly woman in a wheelchair who was reading a
John Updike novel. The two discussed the author, and the woman then
confided that she would turn 94 the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the best thing about being 94 years young?'' Kamisher
asked.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't hesitate a moment. ``No peer pressure,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   STATIONS IN LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Backward in time my memory races
</P>
<P>
   To when subway stations stood for places _
</P>
<P>
   When the stairs at Prospect Park revealed
</P>
<P>
   The panorama of Ebbets Field,
</P>
<P>
   And one could become a most happy fella
</P>
<P>
   Watching Robinson, Reese and Campanella.
</P>
<P>
   And then at night, we would make a beeline
</P>
<P>
   For 50th Street on the C or E line,
</P>
<P>
   Where the old Madison Square Garden proudly stood,
</P>
<P>
   And ``Allagaroo'' meant we could and would.
</P>
<P>
   While those of us of stouter faith
</P>
<P>
   Hied to 155th and Eighth _
</P>
<P>
   Cheers and boos in equal parts resounded,
</P>
<P>
   As the Giants' hopes were Polo Grounded.
</P>
<P>
   And who can forget our own Palladium _
</P>
<P>
   The station that emptied on Yankee Stadium _
</P>
<P>
   In the days before it was renovated,
</P>
<P>
   When its Mantle-piece was consecrated?
</P>
<P>
   And if none of these choices suited us well,
</P>
<P>
   Why, then we all could go to ``El.''
</P>
<P>
   _ HENRY FONER
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Sharing has long been an acceptable solution for two people
coming upon a cab from different directions.
</P>
<P>
   On a cold day earlier this year, the other party was Jerry
Stiller, the comedian who had an ongoing role on ``Seinfeld.'' He
gallantly offered to give up the cab. I discovered that we were
going in the same direction and suggested that he join me. But
because this is a time of star-crazed stalkers, I was suddenly
being scrutinized and he initially demurred.
</P>
<P>
   I quickly told him that some years ago I had interviewed Anne
Meara, his wife, for an article and promised not to lay a finger on
him. He got in.
</P>
<P>
   We were soon chatting like old friends about his wife's new
play, his son Ben Stiller's new movie and his own latest role on
the television program ``The King of Queens.'' We arrived at my
destination all too soon.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't have a big punch line. It's just a magical New York
moment, one that could only happen in a city with charming
celebrities and a permanent shortage of cabs.
</P>
<P>
   _ JULIE DAVIS
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My friend Bobbie Kramer was working with a recent college
graduate. The young woman asked Kramer if she knew how to address
an e-mail message and was instructed on the proper procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you want to cc it to someone, you put their address
here,'' my friend said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's cc?'' the young woman asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carbon copy,'' my friend said.
</P>
<P>
   She was unprepared for the query that came next.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that?'' the young woman asked.
</P>
<P>
   _ DON DUNN
</P>
<P>
   REDECORATING
</P>
<P>
   April has ordered green carpeting,
</P>
<P>
   Laid wall-to-wall on her floor,
</P>
<P>
   And fitted slipcovers in floral design
</P>
<P>
   To accent her new spring decor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, her supplier has warned her
</P>
<P>
   That March presents problems of freight,
</P>
<P>
   Clogging the lanes with his blizzards
</P>
<P>
   And making delivery late.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALMA DENNY
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Dim was in line outside the Cobble Hill Cinema in
Brooklyn waiting to see ``American Beauty.'' As they waited, a man
in a car pulled up to the curb and asked what the movie was about.
Dim replied that it was about a dysfunctional family. ``I can go
home for that,'' said the man in the car before he sped off.
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Continuing-education legal seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Observer: Nathaniel B. Taft
</P>
<P>
   Participants: Elderly man helping young attractive woman slide
her arms into the sleeves of her coat.
</P>
<P>
   Young woman: ``Thank you, I thought chivalry was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Elderly man: ``Not dead but in intensive care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2126EST &QL; 
