u p BC-NJ-SENATE-RACE-NYT &LR;      03-19 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN SENATE RIVALS DRAW BATTLE LINES, QUIETLY, IN NEW JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ While the Democratic race for the Senate
narrowed months ago to a showdown between the comeback-craving
former governor, Jim Florio, and the multimillionaire Jon Corzine,
the Republican contest still looks more like a schoolyard scrum.
</P>
<P>
   No less than four candidates are aggressively seeking their
party's nomination in the June 6 primary. Not one of them is a
household name. And not one of them is doing much yet to change
that.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, as Corzine's television advertisements saturate the
airwaves and Florio's broadsides fill the newspapers, the jostling
among the Republicans for now is largely out of public view.
</P>
<P>
   William Gormley, a veteran lawmaker from the Atlantic City area,
is quietly wielding the accumulated leverage of two decades in the
state Senate to reap endorsements from influential leaders in North
Jersey, outside his base.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Franks, a four-term U.S. congressman from Union County
and two-time state Republican chairman, is trying to convert his
relationships with hundreds of low-level party officials into a
groundswell of support in a series of county conventions over the
next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   James Treffinger, the Essex County executive, is hoping his
record of fiscal reform and of winning re-election in a
predominantly Democratic county will persuade party workers to give
him a chance.
</P>
<P>
   And Murray Sabrin, a onetime Libertarian whose positions on
social issues are far to the right of any of his opponents, is
spreading the word to the conservative faithful, hoping opponents
of abortion rights and gun control will turn out in June in record
numbers, giving him a plurality as the three moderates split the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   For all but Sabrin, who is running outside the party
establishment, the next few weeks will be critical in gaining
organizational support, as county Republican leaders and committees
decide upon their endorsements in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's 21 county committees give a preferential
ballot position to the Senate candidate they endorse, whether by
voting in a county convention or by fiat of the county chairman.
The party line plays an inestimable role in influencing the
Republican loyalists who vote in primaries, especially if turnout
is light, which appears likely since the Republican presidential
nomination is no longer in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Who gets the line must be decided by April 13. Between now and
then, seven counties will hold conventions to decide their
endorsements, culminating on April 8 in Bergen, the most populous
county and home to about 10 percent of New Jersey's Republican
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate is pursuing a geographic strategy. Gormley and
Franks, who are considered the two leading contenders, are trying
to solidify their own home territories while cutting away at one
another's. Gormley, for example, already has the party line in
Atlantic and Cape May counties, and is all but assured of it in
Ocean, giving him a solid base from the Jersey Shore to the
Delaware Bay. He is also the favorite to get the line here in
Mercer County, where the county executive has endorsed him, and in
heavily Republican but sparsely populated Hunterdon County, just to
the north.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, whose congressional district spans parts of Union,
Essex, Middlesex and Somerset counties in the heart of the state,
has also made important inroads to the south: he has won the party
line in Burlington County, near Camden, and is a strong contender
in Cumberland, which borders Cape May, because of the support of
Rep. Frank LoBiondo, a longtime rival of Gormley's.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger is assured of the party line only in Essex and
Passaic, and is a favorite to win it in Hudson County. But he is
hoping to carry Monmouth and Morris Counties, two heavily
Republican areas where no one will receive the party line.
</P>
<P>
   The three rivals have been making similar pitches. Each has
sought to depict himself as the most conservative on fiscal
matters. For example: Gormley boasts of voting to cut state taxes
37 times since 1990, Franks of helping to write the first balanced
federal budget in decades, and Treffinger of having never supported
a single county tax increase despite inheriting a $100 million
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   But they are also making personal appeals, and increasingly
attacking their opponents. Treffinger, who has made an early effort
to compensate for his poor name recognition by running radio
advertisements throughout the state, is promoting his biography as
an adopted child who was the first in his family to graduate from
high school. He is also criticizing Gormley for accepting casino
money, which is prohibited in state races.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley is recalling his vote to ban assault weapons, which
prompted the National Rifle Association to mount what he calls a
``vicious soft-money campaign'' to defeat him in his 1991
re-election effort. In doing so, Gormley, who portrays himself as
unwavering on matters of principle, is drawing a stark contrast to
Franks, who first voted against the weapons ban and later did not
vote either way on a bill to repeal it.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, for his part, is reminding loyal Republicans of his
streak of 11 electoral victories, and of his efforts to take
control of the Statehouse from the Democratic Party while he was
state Republican chairman. Between the lines in that outwardly
wholesome message are digs at both his rivals. Treffinger, for
example, is no lifelong Republican; he worked for Gary Hart's 1980
presidential campaign and left the Democratic Party only in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, meanwhile, is vulnerable to attacks on his electoral
record and even his loyalty to the Republican Party. He finished
fourth in a gubernatorial run in 1989, nearly lost a primary for
his own seat in 1991, and was trounced by LoBiondo in a
congressional primary in 1994. In addition, Gormley was widely
criticized for having been cozy with Florio's Democratic
administration; Florio carried Gormley's home county in his losing
re-election campaign against Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
