r s BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX     03-19 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON SUSPENSION POSSIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN AND JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars might be without winger Scott Thornton when
their four-day layoff ends.
</P>
<P>
   Referees assessed Stars winger Scott Thornton with a five-minute
match penalty for his forearm to Sharks winger Marco Sturm's face
with 45.1 seconds remaining in yesterday's game. The NHL
automatically reviews all match penalties, and a suspension is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton said there was no intent to injure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know what kind of penalty I got until they
announced it, so we'll see,'' Thornton said. ``I just tried to hit
him, that's all. I didn't hit him with my stick or anything. I've
seen a lot more severe and taken a lot worse in games.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem began when Sturm first wrestled Thornton to the ice
and tossed him against the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can go after me, but to get his stick up? That's a
different story,'' Sturm said. _ Jennifer Floyd
Sydor, Nolan clash
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor left the game with 13:13 remaining
after being checked from behind by Sharks captain Owen Nolan. Sydor
didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said Sydor had a hip pointer but would be fine in
a day or two. Sydor said he was hurt more on the slash before the
hit but still wasn't amused by Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done it before,'' Sydor said. ``If I would've known it
was him, I would've gotten my elbows up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, meanwhile, didn't seem too concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it every game, so this was no different,'' Nolan said.
_ Jeff Caplan
Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Two of Dallas' injured players skated yesterday, but only one is
likely to return in time for Friday's game against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Guy Carbonneau (wrist) felt fine with his playing
cast, and Ken Hitchcock said he expects Carbonneau to practice with
the team tomorrow. Stars winger Blake Sloan, meanwhile, wasn't as
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sloan is not ready yet,'' Hitchcock said. ``His ankle is still
bothersome.'' _ Jennifer Floyd
Lukowich the winger scores
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman-turned-forward Brad Lukowich scored his third goal of
the season and first as a forward. Joe Nieuwendyk set up the goal,
Lukowich's first since Dec. 27. It snapped a 27-game scoreless
streak.
</P>
<P>
   When the red light when on, Lukowich raised him arms, looked up
and said, ``Thank you.'' He later said he was thanking his
teammates and Ken Hitchcock for putting him in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should be on that line,'' Lukowich mused. ``Me, Hully
\RBrett Hull\S and Nieuwy really snap it around well out there.'' _
Jeff Caplan
Dominating penalty kill
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' league-leading penalty kill suffocated the Sharks on
all seven San Jose power plays, and Jaime Langenbrunner, who has
become an integral member of the penalty kill while filling in for
Blake Sloan and Guy Carbonneau, scored a short-handed goal to tie
the game 1-1 at the 11:26 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killing with Mo \RMike Modano\S makes it a little easier. He's
a pretty good penalty killer,'' Langenbrunner said. _ Jeff Caplan
Pushor back in mix
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jaime Pushor returned to the lineup for the first
time in five games. He replaced Dave Manson, who was a healthy
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Pushor played 10:27 on 13 shifts with one shot and one hit,
playing alongside defensive partner Sylvain Cote. Pushor has played
in only four of the past 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt Push was getting too far away from the group
emotionally,'' Hitchcock said. ``We have to keep him close.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he hopes to soon work in Joel Bouchard, the
defenseman the Stars claimed off waivers from Nashville before the
trading deadline. _ Jeff Caplan / nn
</P>
