<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR'S BACK, AND ALL IS WELL WITH STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In his first game on home ice after nine days of _ how
shall we put this? _ league-suggested ``quiet time,'' goaltender
and noted headlock-artist Eddie Belfour was greeted warmly
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Was there ever any doubt he would be?
</P>
<P>
   After all, this was Reunion Arena, located as always on the
corner of Wrist-Slap Boulevard and Absolution Lane, where even Roy
Tarpley could count on receiving a clean slate.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's ``incident'' on March 8 and subsequent charges of
misdemeanor assault and resisting arrest were viewed by most Stars
fans as:
</P>
<P>
   A. trumped-up charges;
</P>
<P>
   B. a much-needed, preplayoff rest for the Eagle;
</P>
<P>
   C. just another pothole on the road to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't their necks that Eddie put in that alleged headlock.
So when the 17,001 at Reunion started chanting ``Ed-die! Ed-die!''
during yesterday's 5-3 victory against San Jose, the Stars' planets
all seemed back in harmony again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've overcome adversity all year,'' defenseman Darryl Sydor
said. ``We're behind Eddie 100 percent, and he's on the road up,
which is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I think the break was kind of good for Eddie, you
know?''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour had returned to the net on Saturday afternoon in
Chicago, stopping 26 of 28 shots and later complaining of rink
rust. He had missed five games.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear that he wanted to get back between the pipes as
soon as possible, and coach Ken Hitchcock granted his wish, sending
Belfour out on back-to-back days for only the fourth time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think today I felt 100 percent better than I did
yesterday,'' Belfour reported. ``The idea now is to just take it
one game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but Hitchcock had used the same expression _ one day at a
time _ in describing what a sobering episode Belfour and the team
had just gone through. They were lucky. Phone calls at 5:30 in the
morning usually echo with some sort of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to trivialize what the police claim was outrageous
behavior by Belfour on that morning two weeks ago. But as the warm
welcome yesterday at Reunion seemed to say, no one was hurt, let's
get on with this thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a guy who, to me, shows a singular focus back there,''
Hitchcock said of his veteran goaltender. ``He's taking things one
day at a time now. What I see is a guy who's taking a methodical,
very mature approach to things.''
</P>
<P>
   Mature? Well, let's not be hasty. This is a guy, after all, who
had to be placed in leg irons in his cell two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make any comments on that,'' Belfour announced,
``because of legal issues that are pending.''
</P>
<P>
   To judge Belfour in the meantime, Hitchcock said, you need to go
back to the beginning of this NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a different Eddie all year,'' Hitch said. ``He's
been a looser guy, who's shown a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran afoul _ and he's paid the price.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hitchcock has said since the March 8 incident, Belfour was
never going to have a problem blending back in with his teammates.
While the Stars were fighting through a plague of injuries _ among
others, losing Joe Nieuwendyk for 34 games, Jere Lehtinen for 56,
Derian Hatcher for 25 _ Belfour manned his position like a rock.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't just the Stars' most valuable player. Belfour had been
playing like the league's MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, he can forget the latter now. Even the NHL has a
conscience. Sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   But the prize is still very much again within reach, as
yesterday reminded. Two goals within 98 seconds in the first period
turned a usually stressful division contest into a yawner.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour himself was solid without being sharp. He allowed Owen
Nolan's shot from an oblique goal-line angle to slip between his
knee and the goal post for one San Jose score. A bad turnover by
Hatcher led to another. The third Sharks goal came during garbage
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little concerned about going back-to-back,'' Belfour
said. ``But I felt a little stronger today, better than I expected.
I guess all that hard work in the gym is paying off.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere out there, Belfour suggested, is the golden groove
that he lost when things turned ugly that morning and he was
suddenly serving a nine-day penance. But it'll come soon, he seemed
to say.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour himself had as good an epitaph as any of the whole
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have some great leadership in this room,'' he said,
motioning to his teammates, who seem poised for another Stanley Cup
run.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Belfour is not an issue with this Stars team. Don't let
some out-of-town TV guy tell you otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The break might even have done him good, you know?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
