<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-DUKE-KANSAS-NYT &LR;      03-19 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-KANSAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNABLE TO PULL AWAY, TOP-SEEDED DUKE HOLDS ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BARRY JACOBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _ Sometimes the seeding does not matter.
</P>
<P>
   When Duke and Kansas, two of the most successful programs in the
modern game, met Sunday in the second round of the East Regional,
the action was fierce, no quarter given. Defense dominated. Every
shot, every movement was contested. Even the head coaches got into
a brief confrontation on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Not until Kansas guard Kirk Hinrich missed a 3-point attempt
with 7 seconds left, and Duke's Chris Carrawell corraled the
rebound, did the top-seeded Blue Devils secure a 69-64 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The victory allowed the 29-4 Blue Devils _ with Michigan State
in the Midwest the only No. 1 seeds remaining _ to advance to the
regional semifinals on Friday at Syracuse. Duke will face
fifth-seeded Florida, a 93-76 winner over Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a high-caliber game from the get-go,'' said Mike
Krzyzewski, the Duke coach, seeking his ninth Final Four berth
since 1986. ``I've been in over 60 of them in the NCAA, and that
was a big-time game.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke scrambled to get back in the game after falling behind
early, and the score was 35-35 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils threatened to pull away several times in the
second half, and built a 59-50 lead with 6 minutes 14 seconds to go
on a pair of free throws by Shane Battier.
</P>
<P>
   Battier, a forward who played all 40 minutes, led both teams
with 21 points, 8 rebounds and 8 blocked shots, and drew praise
from Kansas coach Roy Williams as ``the most alert, the most aware
defensive player I can remember in college basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite shooting only 36.2 percent, getting beaten on the
boards, 44-41, and committing 17 turnovers, eighth-seeded Kansas
responded to Duke's largest lead with 9 unanswered points. A
3-pointer by Jeff Boschee, a sophomore guard, tied the score at
59-59 with 3:31 left.
</P>
<P>
   Duke pushed its edge back to 4, only to see the Jayhawks score 5
straight, taking their last lead, 64-63, on a 3-point play by Nick
Bradford with 1:18 left.
</P>
<P>
   But Carlos Boozer, a freshman center who had 15 points, got the
last of his 13 rebounds on a follow shot to put Duke back in the
lead, 65-64, with 53.5 seconds remaining. Then, following a Kansas
timeout, he stole a Bradford pass, Carrawell was fouled and made a
pair of free throws to push the advantage to 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Hinrich's miss and two more free throws as Duke made
87.1 percent of its 31 attempts, and a narrow escape for the
nation's top-ranked team on a night it committed 23 turnovers and
made 37 percent of its shots.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's habit this season has been to jump on an opponent at the
outset of a game, then extend its control with the nation's most
prolific offense and a hard-nosed man-to-man defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Kansas swiped the script.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks scored the game's first two baskets, then staggered
Duke with three consecutive 3-pointers by Hinrich, to build a 13-4
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the flustered Blue Devils missed eight of their first
10 shots and committed four turnovers. After Hinrich hit his third
bomb, Krzyzewski called timeout to calm his team.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's defensive intensity immediately picked up, resulting in a
dozen first-half turnovers by Kansas and four blocked shots for
Battier.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blue Devils could not convert another shot until Nate
James, the junior guard, hit a 3-pointer with 10 minutes 49 seconds
left in the half, cutting the deficit to 13-7.
</P>
<P>
   Duke pulled to 15-14 at the 8:36 mark on a 3-point play by
Carrawell, the senior forward who had 15 points. Kansas answered
with a basket by Ashante Johnson, and following one of Duke's 10
first-half turnovers a television timeout was called.
</P>
<P>
   Irked by an earlier call, Krzyzewski, already animatedly trying
to inspire his team, began arguing with official Terry Christman.
That spurred Williams to come to the Duke bench to join the
discussion. The Kansas coach's arrival precipitated a brief
exchange before the coaches were separated by officials.
</P>
<P>
   Duke took its first lead, 25-24, on an inside basket by Boozer
with 4:16 left in the half. But Kansas maintained narrow leads by
converting shots, collecting 13 of its 25 rebounds in the period on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, in his 12th year at Kansas, entered the game with the
best winning percentage among active coaches (80.2). But despite
visits to the Final Four in 1991 and 1993, he is often remembered
for twice being upset in the second round while holding a No. 1
seed _ in 1992 by nine seed Texas-El Paso and in 1998 by eight seed
Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he came within a play or two of turning the tables as
Kansas ended its season 24-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down here, this team came through, this team grew up,''
Williams said, his voice breaking. ``I just wish we had more games
to play.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the opener Sunday, Florida employed a style that stressed
full-court pressure defense, open-court opportunities, and taking
the first available shot. That pace was not unfamiliar to Illinois,
an at-large entrant from the Big 10. But it proved fatal as Florida
controlled the action for the entire second half and easily won,
93-76.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought our style of play was very, very effective,'' said
Billy Donovan, the Florida coach. ``The game really started getting
going up and down the floor in the second half, and that's
certainly to our liking.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the second straight year Florida (26-7) advanced to the
Sweet 16. The fifth seed survived overtime to defeat No. 12 Butler,
69-68, in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Young, deep and talented, the Gators sometimes play with
abandon. But they are also capable of playing with intelligence and
precision, as they proved by closing the first half with a 19-6
rush, then holding Illinois at arm's length the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   During one stretch late in the game, Florida converted 18 of 19
free throws en route to 78 percent accuracy at the line.
</P>
<P>
   When they had an open look from the perimeter, the Gators made 9
of 18 3-pointers. Once the Southeastern Conference club established
that threat, and grew accustomed to the physical interior play of
Illinois' front court, it was equally effective inside.
</P>
<P>
   Four Gators, two guards and two frontcourt players, finished in
double figures. Mike Miller, a sophomore forward, paced his team
with 19 points and 9 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
