<SLUG> BC-BKC-SWEET16-0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seeds get swallowed
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. _The wildest 24 hours in the history of the
NCAA Tournament almost turned totally crazy Sunday afternoon when
Duke, the No. 1 seed in the East Regional, needed four free throws
in the final 29 seconds to beat eighth-seeded Kansas 69-64.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, which advances to Friday's East Regional semifinals to
play Florida, was one of the few highly-seeded teams to survive an
upset-filled second round on Saturday and Sunday. Two No. 1 seeds
(Arizona, Stanford), three No. 2s (Cincinnati, Temple St. John's),
and three No. 3s (Ohio State, Oklahoma, and Maryland) all failed to
advance to the Sweet 16. That tied an NCAA record for the fewest
top 16 seeds to advance to the regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time since the NCAA Tournament field went to 64
teams in 1985 that only two No. 1 seeds advanced to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest shocker of the day was 10th-seeded Seton Hall, which
upset second-seeded Temple 67-65 in overtime in the East Regional
in Buffalo, N.Y. Close behind on the upset meter was North
Carolina, the No. 8 seed in the South, which knocked off top-seeded
Stanford 60-53 in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, Big Ten, and Big East each placed three teams in the
Sweet 16. Here is a breakdown of this week's regional semifinals:
</P>
<P>
   East: The last time Duke met Florida in the NCAA Tournament was
at the 1994 Final Four in Charlotte. Duke won that game but lost to
Arkansas for the national championship. Florida beat Illinois 93-76
on Sunday in Winston-Salem to advance to the Sweet 16 for the
second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's other game in Syracuse, Seton Hall will take on
third-seeded Oklahoma State, which knocked off Pepperdine 76-67 in
Buffalo, N.Y. If Seton Hall and Duke both win, Seton Hall coach
Tommy Amaker would meet his mentor, Mike Krzyzewski, for the
regional championship and a spot in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   South: After a disappointing season by North Carolina standards,
the Tar Heels were given no shot of getting to the Sweet 16. The
win by North Carolina (20-13) over Stanford not only kept the Tar
Heels alive in the tournament, but extended their streak of 20-win
season to 30. North Carolina will meet Tennessee (26-6), which
knocked off defending national champion Connecticut 65-51 on Sunday
in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's other game in Austin, Tex., surprising Miami
(23-10), a 75-62 winner over Ohio State on Sunday in Nashville,
will take on Tulsa (31-4), which beat second-seeded Cincinnati
69-61.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest: Michigan State (28-7) joined Duke as the only other No.
1 seed to advance when the Spartans knocked off Utah 73-61 on
Saturday in Cleveland. The Spartans, who reached the Final Four
last season, must now take on fourth-seeded Syracuse (26-5) on
Thursday in Auburn Hills, Mich., about an 80-mile drive from the
Michigan State campus. At one point this season Syracuse was 19-0.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's other game at the Palace of Auburn Hills, UCLA
(21-11), the No. 6 seed, will take on second-seeded Iowa State
(31-4). UCLA put together the most impressive performance of the
tournament Saturday night when the Bruins destroyed third-seeded
Maryland 105-70 in Minneapolis. Iowa State, the Big 12 champion,
advanced by beating Auburn 79-60 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   West: The West is by far the whackiest regional as the Nos. 4,
6, 8 and 10 seeds advanced to Thursday's semifinals in Albuquerque,
N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Gonazaga (26-8), the Cinderella team from 1999, found that the
slipper fits two years in a row. The champions of the West Coast
Conference knocked off second-seeded St. John's 82-76 on Saturday
to advance to its West semifinal game with Purdue (23-9). The
Boilermakers pulled off a mild upset on Saturday in Tuscon by
beating third-seeded Oklahoma 66-62.
</P>
<P>
   LSU (28-5) advanced to the Sweet 16 for the first time since
1987 by beating Texas 72-67 on Saturday in Salt Lake City. The
Tigers, the No. 4 seed, will take on eighth-seeded Wisconsin on
Friday. Wisconsin (20-13) shocked top-seeded Arizona 66-59 on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
