<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.Y.-POLICE-SHOOTING-     03-19 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-POLICE-SHOOTING-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI STEPS UP HIS DEFENSE OF POLICE IN FATAL SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pressed to respond to charges that he is demonizing
the victim, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani on Sunday intensified his
criticism of Patrick Dorismond, the unarmed man killed on Thursday
by an undercover police officer, suggesting that his ``pattern of
behavior'' and his actions the night of the shooting had
contributed to his death.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also confirmed that he had authorized the release of
Dorismond's arrest record immediately after the shooting, citing
the public's ``right to know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People do act in conformity very often with their prior
behavior,'' Giuliani said Sunday during a television interview on
``Fox News Sunday.'' The news media ``would not want a picture
presented of an altar boy, when in fact, maybe it isn't an altar
boy, it's some other situation that may justify, more closely, what
the police officer did.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made the comments during the second day of a sprint
through five upstate New York cities, the most extensive weekend of
campaigning so far by Giuliani, the Republican candidate for the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign calendar had called for a weekend filled with
genial, vote-gathering events, from a volunteer fire department
supper in Waterville to baby cuddling and handshaking at St.
Patrick's Day parades in Syracuse and Buffalo. But in the Fox
interview, conducted while Giuliani was at a veterans breakfast in
Elmira Heights, and encounters with the news media on Saturday and
Sunday, the mayor was repeatedly drawn back to Thursday's shooting
of Dorismond, a 26-year-old security guard, after a brief struggle
outside the Wakamba Cocktail Lounge, on Eighth Avenue near 37th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   And at home in New York City, Giuliani's remarks about the case
drew immediate condemnations from some of his traditional critics,
like the Manhattan Borough President, C. Virginia Fields, and the
Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's comments on ``Fox News Sunday'' were his most
extensive to date about the shooting. The mayor said that he had
authorized Commissioner Howard Safir on Thursday to disclose
Dorismond's criminal record, which consisted of arrests, in 1987,
1993 and 1996, on charges of robbery, assault, attempted robbery
and criminal possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you read the man's background _ arrested for robbery,
arrested for attempted robbery, arrested for assaulting someone in
a driving dispute, arrested for assaulting someone in a marijuana
dispute, with calls to his home for other disputes _ it is a pretty
bad record,'' Giuliani said Sunday in a news conference that
followed his appearance at the St. Patrick's Day Parade in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said it was not that relevant that Dorismond's only
convictions in the public record are for two disorderly conduct
charges, given that ``usually it is a plea down from a more serious
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also defended the police department and the officers
involved, largely adopting the version of events offered by the
police and a lawyer for Detective Anthony Vasquez, the 29-year-old
officer who fired the fatal shot. According to this version, as
Giuliani told it Sunday, Dorismond began attacking an undercover
officer who was trying to engage him in a drug sting as he was
standing outside the Wakamba bar about 12:30 a.m. Thursday waiting
for a cab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officer Vasquez came to the aid of the police officer
who was being beaten up,'' Giuliani said in the Fox interview.
Dorismond and Kevin Kaiser, who was with him, then ``rushed for his
weapon,'' Giuliani said, referring to Vasquez, ``and that's how the
shooting took place.'' Kaiser has said that it was the undercover
officer, Anderson Moran, who threw the first punch.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, before leaving for his upstate trip, Giuliani
commended Detective Vasquez, who he said ``put his life on the line
in the middle of the night to protect the safety and security of
this city,'' but he did not mention the detective's disciplinary
history, which includes drawing his weapon during a bar fight that
he was reportedly involved in while off-duty in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's remarks this weekend stood in contrast to his initial
approach to the case, the third fatal police shooting of an unarmed
man in 13 months, calling on Thursday for the public to try to not
let ``their bias, their prejudices, their emotions, their
stereotypes,'' lead them to any quick and possibly unjustified
conclusions about the case.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Walcott, president of New York Urban League and a mayoral
appointee to the Police Department's Courtesy, Professional and
Respect Committee, said Sunday that if the mayor wanted the respect
of blacks and others concerned about allegations of police
misconduct, he should have stuck to his original position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't get it,'' Walcott said. ``The mayor at one point
calls for people to suspend judgment and wait for all the facts are
in and then at the same time the mayor and police commissioner
begin the process of demonizing an innocent man killed by a police
officer. He is just creating a bigger wedge between the police and
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields, the Manhattan borough president, said Dorismond's
criminal record was not relevant to the case, because the officers
did not know anything about his past when they approached him
outside the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is totally ridiculous and absurd for him in some way to
attempt to justify the killing of this young man by saying he had a
record,'' Fields said of the mayor. ``When you shoot a person they
are obviously not wearing a badge that shows their past criminal
record.'' She addded, ``It shows a lack of sensitivity and
caring.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Adams, co-founder of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who
Care, said he was particularly outraged that Giuliani and Safir
released details from Dorismond's criminal record from 1987, when
he was a juvenile and the case file was sealed by the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to look at criminal records, at 15 I was
arrested,'' Adams said during a rally Sunday outside of One Police
Plaza, the department's headquarters. ``Does that make me a person
who shouldn't be allowed to walk the city? When did it become that
because of an activity at 13, 14, or 15 years old this should cause
you to be shot? For a man to justify that, that is sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said all he was trying to do was ensure that both sides
of the story were told.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are things that unless this is a game of let's blame the
police for everything, the public has a right to know,'' the mayor
said in his Fox interview.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond's mother, Marie Dorismond, a Haitian immigrant, did
not speak with reporters Sunday. A makeshift shrine to Dorismond,
with 20 sprays of flowers and 16 votive candles, had been set up
outside her home on Parkside Avenue in the Flatbush section of
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Marie Dorismond condemned the portrayal of her
son as a repeat offender. ``My son is not a criminal. He has two
children,'' she said on Friday, adding, ``What is this lie?'' in
response to the criminal arrest record released by Safir and
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Family members on Sunday said they would address the public at a
news conference Monday afternoon, with other Haitians living in
Brooklyn and the family's lawyer, Johnnie L. Cochran Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stream of visitors Sunday was Abner Louima, whose
assault by police officers in a Brooklyn station house three years
ago caused a sensation. Two officers were convicted in the assault
last year, and three were found guilty this month of covering up
the attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
