<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CONTRASTING ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first great test of a new democracy is not only
in the way its government tolerates opposition, but whether it is
willing to transfer power to that opposition after a fair election.
</P>
<P>
   The new United States faced that test in 1801, after the ruling
party of John Adams and Alexander Hamilton had been beaten in the
popular vote by Thomas Jefferson's Anti-Federalists. It was touch
and go for weeks, as the stunned Federalists tried to make a deal
with Aaron Burr to block Jefferson's presidency. Only secret
patronage concessions, hotly denied, and Hamilton's personal hatred
of Burr caused the party in power to turn over the keys to the
Executive Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan passed the same test last weekend. The party in power
ever since Chiang Kai-shek fled China was split by an insurgency.
The opposition party, favoring independence, contended vigorously.
China warned the free Taiwanese of ``blood'' in their future if
they dared vote for the dissident Chen Shui-bian.
</P>
<P>
   That attempted intimidation put Chen over the top. The old
guard, to its credit, will transfer power peacefully. Taiwan thus
proves its democratic strength.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is proving the opposite. Late last year, the kakistocracy
propping up Boris Yeltsin decided not to risk giving up power. To
avert election defeat by the Primakov-Luzhkov party, the ruling
Kremlin crew upset the constitutional schedule. Yeltsin suddenly
stepped down and named Vladimir Putin, a KGB apparatchik, to be
acting president.
</P>
<P>
   By staging this coup, the ruling party was able to have its
candidate in office, with all its powers of patronage and media
control, at election time. Its anointed new leader received a
prestige boost from Britain's Tony Blair and America's Bill
Clinton. A level playing field was averted.
</P>
<P>
   To distract the Russian people from high-level corruption, war
hysteria was whipped up. Chechens aching for self-rule were
designated as threats to Russians in their homes. Power-starved
Russian generals were encouraged to pillage at will.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, the ruling clique not only changed its image from
puffy Yeltsin to hard-eyed Putin, but changed the subject from
venality and economic stagnation to a cost-free victory over the
despised rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Needed was only a symbolic bridge connecting fear of the
Chechens to anger at truth-tellers in the Russian media. The ruling
clique found that in Andrei Babitsky, a Russian Radio Liberty
reporter who filed embarrassing facts from behind battle lines.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky was arrested and ``exchanged'' by Chechen quislings;
when Western interest made his disappearance awkward, the reporter
was brought to Moscow on trumped-up charges. Putin, as Election Day
neared, then made the connection between the hated Chechens and the
beleaguered Russian press by loudly branding the reporter a
``traitor.'' This plainly implied that any pursuit of truth in a
war zone is treason.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin plan was to call a snap election to exploit war
fever. That's how it could renew its power before the extent of
Russian casualties became known and the surge of support for the
militarist Putin ebbed. But Chechen guerrillas in the mountains
have not cooperated; ambushes abound. Polls show Putin popularity
beginning to erode, and a quick vote is in the power clique's
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Kremlin's choice remains far ahead of his main
opponents, the Communist Gennadi Zyuganov and the lonely democratic
reformer Grigory Yavlinsky, Putin hopes to avoid a two-man runoff
by winning over 50 percent of the votes on March 26. Even if he
does, there's this wrinkle in the law: Unless 50 percent of
eligible voters show up on the first round to vote for all
candidates, the election must be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin clique will inflate next week's count by stuffing
ballot boxes. But Harvard's Graham Allison reports from Moscow that
apathy is rampant; even the Communists had trouble rounding up 150
bodies for a Red Square rally. Apparently many Russians are
disgusted at the way they've been had.
</P>
<P>
   We see what comes when rulers don democratic trappings but use
every trick to avoid relinquishing power. As Taiwan's party of
power bows to the will of a victorious plurality, Russia's party of
power perpetuates a fraud on the Russian people. That's the
difference between a successful and a failing democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
