<SLUG> BC-TECHBUILDSID-COSTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HIGH-TECH BUILDERS, INTANGIBLES OUTWEIGH BAY AREA'S
HIGH  COSTS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Solectron and Flextronics International, the two local leaders in
contract manufacturing for the high-tech industry, both have
growing networks of production facilities across the country and
around the world. But executives of both companies expect the Bay
Area to continue playing a major role in their operations, despite
the area's high costs.
<P>
   Solectron, far and away the largest company in the category, has
about 30 factories around the world, including major facilities in
Guadalajara, Mexico, and Sao Jose dos Campos, Brazil, as well as in
Ireland, Scotland, France, Germany, Romania, China and Malaysia.
Flextronics operates ``industrial parks'' _ combining its own
production facilities with space for its major suppliers _ in
China, Hungary and Guadalajara, with additional major sites in
Scotland, Sweden, Austria and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both companies say their foreign facilities,
including those in developing countries, are just as advanced as
their Bay Area facilities. ``We build buildings that look just like
our factory in San Jose, we train people just as we do in San Jose,
we build canteens and provide food just like we do in San Jose,''
said Flextronics CEO Michael Marks. ``And,'' he said, ``we return
the water we use cleaner than we got it, even though the norm in
some of these places is just to dump wastewater into the sewers.''
</P>
<P>
   But for both companies, and for most of their top-tier
competitors, the Bay Area remains a uniquely important location.
Solectron's Milpitas facility is still by far its largest, and
according to Chief Financial Officer Susan Wang, shipments from the
Bay Area still account for 45 percent of the company's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and executives cite several reasons for this region's
continued importance for electronics manufacturing, despite its
high costs. One factor, Wang said, is that the Bay Area offers an
``unparalleled concentration of talent,'' even though the companies
recruit engineers as well as laborers in every country where it
operates.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important advantage of this area, most observers
agree, is that so many high-tech companies, wherever their
headquarters are, develop their products here. Traditionally, most
companies like to keep at least initial production close to their
design centers, so their engineers can quickly diagnose and correct
any problems that surface as production gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   Once product designs and manufacturing processes have been
stabilized, production is often moved to foreign factories to take
advantage of lower costs and proximity to foreign customers.
Nowadays, that dynamic doesn't apply just to simple and technically
unsophisticated products: Flextronics' Marks said his company is
starting to move production of routers to its Guadalajara campus,
and eventually it may even do the same with the servers it builds
for Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   But with new high-tech products continuing to flood into the
market, there should still be plenty of work for Bay Area
facilities. Flextronics' Marks noted that his company has, on
average, rolled out one new Cisco Systems product every three days
for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Wang noted, moving production of some products offshore
may never be worthwhile, especially as product life cycles grow
ever shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In volume production, we and our customers both know the
benefits of moving offshore, but we also know the risks,'' said
Solectron's Wang. ``For one thing, it disrupts your supply chain _
even if you can convert to local suppliers, you still have a
complicated transition to manage. Sometimes it's just not worth
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jabil Circuit of St. Petersburg, Fla., one of Solectron and
Flextronics' top competitors, set up shop in San Jose back in 1984,
according to Beth Walters, vice president of corporate
communications. But until recently, Jabil had only a relatively
modest, 30,000-square-foot facility there. Because of this area's
costs, Walters said, Jabil hesitated to expand it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, it finally decided to do so, adding additional 170,000
square feet to its plant and boosting total employment there to
700. While acknowledging that ``customers kind of enjoy having you
close by,'' especially at the beginning of a relationship, Walters
downplayed the long-term importance of proximity. ``Once they know
you,'' she said, ``they'd usually rather have you do the project in
the lowest-cost facility, or the one closest to their markets.''
</P>
<P>
   What finally persuaded Jabil to increase its investment in this
area, she said, was the steady stream of high-tech startups here.
``If you're not here, you don't find out about them and they don't
find out about you,'' she said. ``That's why we finally decided we
had to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
