<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHBUILDSB2-PROSPER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 `RAW RECRUITS' ARE PROSPERING IN CONTRACT MANUFACTURING  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Contract manufacturing is often associated with low wages and even
sweatshop conditions, but executives at the industry's top-tier,
tech-oriented companies say these stereotypes have little relevance
to them.
<P>
   Solectron's philosophy, according to the company's chief
financial officer, Susan Wang, is to look for ``raw recruits'' it
can hire at just above minimum wage; in general, she said, the
company aims to keep its base salaries at about the 25th percentile
in each labor market where it operates.
</P>
<P>
   But once hired, she said, Solectron's workers _ or
``associates,'' as the company calls them _ enjoy a variety of
opportunities not available to most low-wage workers. For starters,
they're eligible for bonuses, with no cap, based on their business
unit's success in meeting its targets. Wang called the program ``a
form of profit sharing.'' (Stock options, however, are limited to
engineers and managers.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, ``we provide a tremendous amount of
training,'' largely through a program called ``Solectron
University,'' which offers courses in everything from soldering to
supervision. Wang noted that the company's chief operating officer
and the vice president in charge of Western U.S. operations
(including California and Washington) both got their start on the
shop floor.
</P>
<P>
   Flextronics CEO Michael Marks tells a similar story. New
recruits at his company's San Jose facility usually start at $6.50
to $7.00 per hour, but move up quickly, and average wages are
between $10 and $11. (In Mexico and Hungary, he said, the company
pays about $1.75 an hour, and slightly more than that in China and
Malaysia.)
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, Marks said, Flextronics' workforce is made up
largely of women, many of them Latino and Vietnamese immigrants.
``That's always been true of manufacturing in this country,'' he
said. ``It's the newcomers who fill the ranks, but then they move
up the ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   Flextronics doesn't have a formal ``university'' like
Solectron's, but it, too, puts a high priority on upgrading a
worker's skills, he said. In China, it offers its workers free
English lessons on Sundays, and at its Guadalajara industrial park
it runs a fully accredited high school.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Bay Area's major contract electronics manufacturers
is unionized, and Amy Dean, executive director of the South Bay
AFL-CIO Labor Council, declined to comment specifically on working
conditions at them, except to note anecdotal reports of health and
safety issues and workers' compensation complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really part of a broader issue,'' she said. ``Outsourcing
is increasingly common throughout the economy. We need to figure
out new ways to represent people in industries like this, benefits
need to be portable, and the government needs to update
unemployment insurance and workers' compensation to reflect this
phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
