<SLUG> BC-CONCERTS-WEBCAST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LORNE MICHAELS BACKS WEBCAST CONCERT SERIES  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Call it MTV for MP3.
<P>
   Riffage.com, a Palo Alto firm that uses the popular MP3 online
music format to promote undiscovered musical talent, is teaming
with a college cable network controlled by TV producer Lorne
Michaels to create a series of half-hour TV concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Riffage.com today will announce a deal to co-produce ``Riffage
Live from the Great American Music Hall'' for the Burly Bear
Network, which beams programs by cable to students at schools like
Stanford University and San Francisco State University.
</P>
<P>
   The first show will be Webcast March 28 and repeated on the
Burly Bear Network in mid-April, with the full 13-week series
debuting this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, colleges have been the breeding ground
for the MP3 movement, using the format for compressing audio files
to transmit music on the Internet. The MP3 phenomenon has also
provided unknown garage bands and independent artists access to a
global stage previously unattainable unless they caught the ear of
a big record label.
</P>
<P>
   Riffage.com, which has attracted investments from America Online
and BMG Entertainment, is one of several Bay Area startups trying
to stake out a piece of the emerging online music industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Riffage is the first to try using the more traditional
channel of television to showcase artists who are gaining fame
among MP3 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's converging entertainment,'' said Jason Rubenstein,
Riffage's vice president for live programming. ``As an aggressive
young Internet company, we're going to try to change the rules of
the ecosystem for music.''
</P>
<P>
   Burly Bear, launched in 1994, produces about 12 hours a week of
programming watched by about 500,000 viewers, said Brian Nurenberg,
the network's senior vice president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Broadway Video, a New York production company owned by
Lorne Michaels, creator of NBC's long-running variety show
``Saturday Night Live,'' bought a 75 percent stake in Burly Bear
for about $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The network is available on cable systems reaching about 5
million students at 450 schools from Boston College to UCLA. It
also runs a Web site, at www.burlybear.com.
</P>
<P>
   The company produces offbeat shows, such as ``Half-Baked,'' a
cooking show for dorm-room denizens. And there's the animated
``Kevin Spencer,'' described on Burly Bear's Web site as ``the
8-year-old, chain smoking, alcoholic, sociopath you'll grow to
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein believes college students are the perfect audience
for ``Riffage Live.'' Downloading online music has become so
popular an activity among college students that more than 100
universities combatting clogged Internet lines have blocked or
restricted access to Napster, a popular software program that
allows easy sharing of MP3-formatted songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to hit the audience right between the eyes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Riffage will split advertising revenues and co-produce ``Riffage
Live'' with Broadway Video, which also produces ``Saturday Night
Live.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
