<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHBUILD-CONTRACTORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH BUILDERS FOR HIRE  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Manufacturing _ to many the essence of the old economy _ turns out
to be one of the fastest-growing and most lucrative segments of the
new one.
<P>
   At least that's the case for a small group of companies that
specialize in cranking out circuit boards, cell phones and other
high-tech items on contract to the companies who design and market
such products.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade the major players in this build-for-hire
business have recorded dizzying rates of growth.
</P>
<P>
   The largest and best known of them, Solectron of Milpitas, has
racked up a compound annual growth rate of more than 53 percent
since 1992, according to Chief Financial Officer Susan Wang. For
fourth-ranked Flextronics International, which is incorporated in
Singapore but has its headquarters in San Jose, the comparable
figures are about 70 percent growth annually over the past seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has rewarded these companies and their top
competitors by bidding up their stock prices at a rate even most
dot-coms have to envy. And they've been spared _ even during last
week's sharp Nasdaq sell-off _ the extreme volatility that marks
most new-economy investments.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to see why, said J. Keith Dunne, managing director
at Robertson Stephens in San Francisco and a longtime bull on the
contract-manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only sector that's growing as fast as the Internet,''
he said, ``plus it has proven profit potential.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, electronics manufacturing contractors were
perceived mainly as sources of low-wage manual labor _ usually by
immigrant women _ that the likes of Cisco Systems and
Hewlett-Packard considered too unrewarding and even undignified to
bother with.
</P>
<P>
   For smaller contractors there's still some truth to that image,
industry observers say. But over the past decade, Solectron,
Flextronics and a half-dozen or so major competitors have emerged
from the pack to become global giants and technological powerhouses
in their own right.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to expanding U.S. operations, even in high-cost
Silicon Valley, they've built or bought state-of-the-art production
facilities in Mexico, Malaysia, China, Hungary and elsewhere around
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   And they've moved beyond manufacturing into areas like product
design, component qualification, testing and supply-chain
management. In some cases, they have even taken on order
fulfillment and post-sale support: Flextronics, for example, not
only builds Cisco routers, but ships them directly to end users
whose orders Cisco forwards; Cisco never has physical possession of
the products that carry its name.
</P>
<P>
   With their new scope and sophistication, the top tech
manufacturing specialists have taken on a new name: Instead of
contract manufacturers, they now call themselves ``electronics
manufacturing service,'' or EMS, providers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they call themselves, they've become key partners for
high-tech companies increasingly determined to focus on their core
competencies, technological innovation and brand building, rather
than physical production. While the outsourcing model first took
hold in the computer and data-networking categories, in recent
years telecommunications companies have also boarded the bandwagon,
especially as they struggle to keep up with skyrocketing demand for
cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   So reliable and efficient have the EMS leaders proven themselves
that many of their customers have lately decided to turn over
management and even ownership of important production facilities to
them. And the companies involved aren't just cyberstartups with no
experience in the real world of production; they're
electronics-industry leaders that have been building their own
products for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Just in the past few months, for example, Solectron _ the only
two-time winner of the U.S. government's prestigious Baldridge
Award for manufacturing excellence _ has acquired facilities from
IBM, Alcatel and Ericsson, among others. For its part, Flextronics
has announced similar arrangements with Ericsson, Cabletron and
Fujitsu Siemens.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the local companies, as well as their fellow EMS giants,
have also been gobbling up smaller contract manufacturers,
component suppliers and design specialists at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   Flextronics, for example, merged in November with the Dii Group,
a Colorado contractor. In January, it bought out Palo Alto Products
International, the company that designed the original PalmPilot and
the newer Palm III and VII models. And this month, it added four
companies with facilities in North Carolina's Research Triangle
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Solectron, meanwhile, acquired Smart Modular Technologies, a
leading maker of memory modules, and Americom Wireless Services, a
Los Angeles specialist in mobile-phone repair.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, contract manufacturers by most estimates now produce
nearly 20 percent of the worldwide electronics industry's
trillion-dollar total output, and their share is growing by the
month. Flextronics CEO Michael Marks recalls that in 1994, when his
company went public, he predicted that contractors' share could
eventually reach 30 percent, and most observers thought he was
dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   Now he predicts that his industry will soon account for 60 to 80
percent of worldwide electronics production, and this time no one's
laughing. Indeed, Robertson Stephens' Dunne said the consensus
among industry watchers is that 65 or 70 percent is a realistic
target.
</P>
<P>
   Given the size of the electronics market, those projections
translate into opportunities fo staggering dimensions: In today's
market, Dunne notes, an additional 10-percent share means $100
billion in incremental business. And that's not even counting the
likely growth in the electronics pie.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Dunne said, the biggest challenge facing the EMS
industry may be that ``there's more business coming their way than
they can absorb in the near term.''
</P>
<P>
   Flextronics' Marks agrees, focusing particularly on the problem
of finding the talent needed to sustain his company's dizzying
growth. ``Direct labor'' _ blue-collar production workers _ ``is
still somewhat available,'' he said. ``The problem is finding the
engineers and supervisors and procurement people we need, not just
here in the Bay Area but all over the country. It's always been
difficult, but lately it's been damn near impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's not worried about growth slowing. ``I just don't see
any plateau, at least in the next three or five years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, who received bachelor's and master's degrees in
psychology before picking up an MBA at Harvard (where, he says, he
didn't do very well in the one manufacturing course he took),
assumed leadership of Flextronics in 1993. Just last week, Fortune
magazine named him one of six ``Heroes of Manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been breathtaking, to tell you the truth,'' he said. ``I
never would have imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at &LR;  hnorr &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
