<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-TENNESSEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE KNOCKS THE CROWN OFF TEETERING CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Out of sync, weaving and bobbing on the
brink, Connecticut could not gain its balance here Sunday. Finally,
it fell flat. Hard. With injured point guard Khalid El-Amin missing
nearly 27 minutes, Connecticut felt its crown slipping throughout
its 40-minute waltz with Tennessee. It was reminded of the
difference a year can make.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Connecticut won it all.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the crown fell off.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Tennessee kicked it off.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Volunteers found a wounded team and licked its
lips. It threw all of its darts on the bulls-eye, shot all of the
marbles out of the ring, played aroused and intense and beat ailing
Connecticut, 65-51, before 16,108 fans in the Birmingham-Jefferson
Civic Center. Tennessee (26-6) advances to the Round of 16, to
Austin, Texas, where it will play North Carolina, an earlier 60-53
winner here over Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to call it like it is,'' Tennessee Coach Jerry
Green said. ``They aren't the same team without El-Amin. It's
unfortunate for them he wasn't 100 percent. Couple that with the
fact that we played probably our best game of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   For Connecticut, it was an ugly combination.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin had suffered a high right ankle sprain here Friday in
Connecticut's first-round victory over Utah State. He had undergone
treatment for the last 48 hours attempting to recover, but it was
not to be. In the 13 minutes 17 seconds that he played (6:20 of it
in the first half), he limped noticeably. He grimaced. His game was
gone and he was unable to push off the ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee attacked him. And Connecticut was unable to attack
without him.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin had been their playmaker, their general for 34 games
this season. Sunday he took two shots, scored two points and had
one assist. Suddenly, in the Huskies' 35th game, they had to find a
way to operate without him.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a car without a steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult to take some one who is not just your
point guard but also the focal point of your team in so many ways,
someone you depend on running the offense, and trying to overcome
that,'' Connecticut's warrior center Jake Voskuhl said. ``It was an
adjustment we couldn't make.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman point guard Tony Robertson tried: He was 1-of-7
shooting with two assists and three turnovers in 33 minutes played.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman point guard Marcus Cox tried: He was 0 for 3 with no
assists in six minutes played.
</P>
<P>
   For Connecticut, with El-Amin unable to go, the head was cut
off.
</P>
<P>
   The body quickly followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times it was very evident that they were a team out of
whack,'' said Tennessee center C.J. Black. ``But I don't know too
many teams who can play without their point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee forward Vincent Yarbrough said: ``Definitely, they
were kind of lost. It wasn't just that they lost Khalid, but it was
also that they were playing against good competition.''
</P>
<P>
   A team that played 40 minutes of flourishing basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee shot 44.7 percent. It made 16 of 23 free throws. It
made only eight turnovers and created seven steals. Yarbrough
scored 14 points, Black 13 and guard Tony Harris 18 though he shot
only four of 11 from the field. Tennessee led, 32-22, at halftime
and never looked back. It built its lead to as many as 19 points in
the second half. Only a 3-point shot made by Connecticut's Albert
Mouring (17 points) as the final buzzer sounded prevented
Connecticut from finishing with fewer than 50 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started the game inside, and then did a nice job of
kicking it outside,'' Jim Calhoun, the Connecticut coach, said of
Tennessee. ``They played a terrific game. Our defense was fine
without Khalid, but our offense struggled tremendously. We depend
on Khalid's energy so much. Khalid is the head of the dragon.''
</P>
<P>
   How much did the Huskies miss him?
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than his penetration all season, his ability to
draw fouls and shoot free throws and create similar opportunities
for others. Minus El-Amin, Connecticut for the entire game shot
four free throws and made four assists. Its points, assists and
steals (one) were season-low totals for Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with Tennessee dishing and daring, with its
acrobatic play Sunday _ it sank 16 of 23 free throws and created 15
assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a tough game,'' Connecticut senior forward Kevin
Freeman said. He fought valiantly and scored 14 points and grabbed
7 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's string of seven tournament victories was snapped.
This was its worst post-season loss since 1992. It finished with a
25-10 record.
</P>
<P>
   The crown will not be Connecticut's this time.
</P>
<P>
   But Calhoun was proud, anyway, especially of Voskuhl and
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake and Kevin are special and they have been a pleasure to
``In four years they had 109 wins, three Big East championships and
a national championship. All they ever wanted to do was win and
help the team. We may have had bigger personalities and brighter
lights, but none more special. I miss them already.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
