<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1890 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHR     03-19 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOSCOPE COLUMN: GENE-PATENT OPPONENTS NOT LICKED YET  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
San Francisco artist Marilyn Donahue has proposed a simple way for
people to protest the patenting of human genes.
<P>
   She suggests people copyright their own DNA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably won't have much legal effect,'' admitted the
former biology researcher turned artist. ``For me, this is really
about making people take an interest in where biotechnology is
going.''
</P>
<P>
   If only President Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair
had consulted Donahue last week, before they tried to call
attention to issue of patents and the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders issued a statement promising that public labs
would continue to make gene maps freely available, while agreeing
that private firms can continue to patent genes.
</P>
<P>
   Their pronouncement spooked Wall Street into thinking the
government might ban gene patents, sparked a run on biotech stocks
and wiped out billions of dollars of paper wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue's copyright, in contrast, offers considerable symbolic
bang for less than a buck. She demonstrated her technique Thursday
night before the Coalition of Artists and Life Forms, a San
Francisco group organized by artist Dale Hoyt.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the copyright works.
</P>
<P>
   Have someone take a snapshot of you licking a first-class stamp.
Enclose the snapshot in a self-addressed envelope, using the stamp
as postage. When the letter arrives, drop it in a file drawer. The
canceled stamp proves when you ``authored'' the saliva sample.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Kretsinger, assistant general counsel for the U.S.
Copyright Office, chuckled upon hearing Donahue's idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting protest,'' Kretsinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Her office has never considered whether DNA could be
copyrighted, though Kretsinger doubts licking a stamp meets the
legal test for a copyright, which is meant to protect original,
creative works.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have any creative control over your DNA,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue isn't the first artist to challenge gene patents. Last
month, British poet Donna MacLean asked her government for a patent
on herself, claiming she is an original invention 30 years in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists have also challenged gene patents. Jonathan
King, a molecular biologist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, is circulating a petition ( &LR; www.gene-watch.org &LR; ) asking
Congress to ban the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patenting of genes is a new and profound theft of the
human commons,'' King said. ``Genes evolved over time. We inherited
them from our parents, they weren't invented by corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   King said that when U.S. patent laws took effect in 1793, they
embodied the principle that living things could not be patented.
For 140 years, plant breeders tried to get around this ban and get
protection for hybridized plants. In the 1930s, they persuaded
Congress to bestow limited commercial protection on plant hybrids.
The tags hanging from ``patented'' roses in nurseries trace their
origin to those laws.
</P>
<P>
   But King said the plant protections were weak compared with
patents that confer on their holder a 20-year monopoly on the
invention.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1980, a U.S. Supreme Court decision lifted the ban on
patenting living things. The case revolved around Ananda
Chakrabarty, a General Electric scientist in the 1970s, who
genetically altered a bacteria so that it could digest petroleum _
a potentially useful tool for cleaning up oil spills.
</P>
<P>
   When Chakrabarty sought to patent his oil-eating microbe, patent
officers, following 180 years of precedent, rejected his
application. Donald Chisum, a law professor at Santa Clara
University, said the case went to the Supreme Court, which voted 5
to 4 that a patent could be granted on ``anything under the sun
that is made by man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In its natural state it (the bacterium) did not eat oil, he
(Chakrabarty) gave it the appetite,'' said John Doll, chief of the
biotech division at the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The patent office interpreted the Chakrabarty decision as
permitting gene patents. ``The logic was that if living organisms
could be patented, small pieces of chemicals isolated and purified
from them should be patentable,'' Doll said.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated and purified are the key words. As Doll explained, the
100,000 or so genes in the human body are clumped inside the
nucleus of every cell. Envision a piece of steel wool, made up of
filaments wound round and round. The entire steel wool would be the
human genome. A gene would be a single tiny snippet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the gene) is not just floating around,'' Doll said. ``Man
went in, clipped it out of the genome, isolated it, gave it to us
and said this is what it does.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Chakrabarty decision, biotech firms raced to isolate,
purify _ and patent _ the genes that produced insulin, growth
hormones and blood production factors. These patents allowed firms
like Genentech Inc. in South San Francisco and Amgen Inc. in
Thousand Oaks to create businesses around the drugs that these
patents controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Today, hundreds of genes have been patented, and not just by
private firms. The University of California has 265 gene-related
patents.
</P>
<P>
   Despite opponents like King who want to restore the ban on
living patents, most observers think the gene patents awarded so
far provide a necessary incentive so companies will invest in
developing biotech drugs.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Paul Billings, a geneticist who serves with King
on the Council for Responsible Genetics, a public interest group in
Cambridge, Mass., supports gene patents that lead to drugs or
diagnostic tests.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, a growing concern has arisen that
private firms are employing machines that make it so easy to
isolate and purify genes that only a handful of companies might end
up unraveling the steel wool and patenting large chunks of the
human genome.
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton and Blair hoped to do last week was cheer on the
handful of public labs that have equipped themselves with the same
automated gene-reading machines. These public labs are racing to
discover genes _ and make them public _ before private gene-mappers
can monopolize the genome.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody knows what will happen if the private firms win.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a mess so complicated that it almost takes a
science degree to understand, Donahue, the born-again artist who
spent 18 years doing lab research, wants to prod people into
thinking about where all this gene mapping will lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art makes you stop, look and contemplate,'' Donahue said over
a lunch plate of pommes frites. Legally speaking, she knows her
copyright stunt isn't worth the warm spit on the stamp. But as a
form of participatory art, she thinks it has power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be amazing,'' she asked, leaning across the table,
``if 10,000 of us came forward? A judge would have to listen to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   (For more on DNA copyrights visit  &LR; www.mudhaus.com/marilyn &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
