<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1893 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DSL-SELFSERVE-SFCHRON     03-19 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DSL-SELFSERVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PAC BELL TO OFFER DSL YOU CAN INSTALL  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
It took Pacific Bell six technicians and more than nine hours on
four different days to install Joe Ramos' high-speed Internet line
in Half Moon Bay. On another date, workers simply didn't show up at
all.
<P>
   The installation process didn't go any more smoothly for San
Francisco filmmaker Ronald Levaco, who also ordered a digital
subscriber line, which offers superfast Internet access over
conventional copper phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell workers initially spent six hours struggling to get his
DSL working in his Haight Victorian. After they left, Levaco said
another program wiped out his settings. Levaco hasn't been able to
use his DSL since.
</P>
<P>
   But SBC Communications of Texas, which owns Pac Bell, says it is
on the verge of making DSL installation so simple that most
customers can install the line themselves in 30 minutes to an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few weeks, the phone company plans to update its
software, revamp its &LR;   &LR; manuals and use other technology to
eliminate the need to send technicians to ``the vast majority'' of
customer homes, said Lee Culver, SBC's director of broadband
development.
</P>
<P>
   Customers in the Bay Area will be able to install DSL themselves
starting late this month or early next. To encourage
self-installation, the company plans to eventually charge customers
roughly $100 to $120 if they still want a technician to handle the
task.
</P>
<P>
   Other phone companies, including US West and Bell Atlantic,
already encourage customers to install DSL themselves with similar
financial incentives. (US West says more than 6 out of 7 customers
handle the task themselves.) And AT&AMP;T recently started
test-marketing home installation kits for its high-speed Net
service over cable television lines south of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the move could be a boon to Pac Bell and consumers
alike.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell customers often gripe about taking time off work to
wait for technicians, who sometimes show up late or miss
appointments altogether.
</P>
<P>
   And eliminating visits could save SBC tens of millions of
dollars a year. SBC says it is typically costs $100 or more to
dispatch a DSL technician to a customer's home, which adds up.
Since SBC plans to sign up 831,000 DSL customers this year and each
customer typically needs two visits, the total cost for
installation visits could exceed $166 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Pac Bell customers who've had trouble with DSL installations
doubted the phone company could make the process smooth enough for
the average customer to handle alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just bailing on their responsibility,'' Levaco said.
``That's like when you're having trouble with your health service,
so they tell you to do your own colonoscopy.''
</P>
<P>
   Levaco also complained that Pac Bell's current manual is simply
``a thrown-together series of stapled pages.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ramos, of Half Moon Bay, said he didn't receive any manual
at all. Although his DSL works fine, Ramos said he still doesn't
know how to access his Pac Bell e-mail account. And since the
installation, he said he's had trouble shutting down his computer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Culver insisted the new self-installation manual and
software is better than anything technicians are using today. ``SBC
has gone through extensive ... testing with very real customers in
our labs in Texas and California,'' Culver said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Pac Bell customers already say their installation is a
breeze. Art Allen in Saratoga said the technicians did the job in
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Pac Bell says customers will simply need to
insert a new, thicker phone cord (called a filter) into their phone
jacks, plug in a DSL modem, slide a networking card into their
computer slot, start the Pac Bell software and follow the prompts.
</P>
<P>
   The company also plans to set up a special tech support line to
guide customers through the installation process. The support desk
is scheduled to be open seven days a week and remain open as late
as 11 p.m. weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, SBC will offer the kits on its Web site and through
its customer service phone numbers. But ultimately, SBC hopes to
market the kits through electronics stores as well.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Pac Bell has installed boxes that split customer
phone lines in two, one part to handle voice calls and a second to
handle the Internet connection. But Pac Bell says it can now do
that electronically from its main offices.
</P>
<P>
   The company will still have to dispatch technicians to do
``inside wiring'' if a customer's computer isn't close to a phone
jack. But generally that isn't a problem, because customers usually
already log on to the Net through their phone before ordering DSL.
</P>
<P>
   SBC says it will launch the self-installation kits in the Bay
Area in the next few weeks, then roll the service out to other
areas. But some phone companies are further ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic first started letting customers install the lines
themselves in New York last summer, and expanded it to the rest of
its territory along the Eastern seaboard late last year. Nearly 4
in 5 Bell Atlantic consumers now handle DSL on their own, though
some run into problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say that it goes smoothly for everyone,
because it doesn't,'' said spokeswoman Joan Rasmussen. But she said
customers appreciate the convenience of handling the installation
whenever they want.
</P>
<P>
   US West, which started offering self-installation kits in
October, estimates 86 to 88 percent of customers completed the
task. Another 2 percent of customers order the kits, but wind up
calling in a technician for help.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the glitches, a US West executive said phone companies
couldn't handle the growing wave of DSL orders if they had to
complete every installation themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot afford the physical resources required,'' said Matt
Rotter, who oversees US West's DSL service. ``It's not
sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   Both US West and Bell Atlantic also waive the extra installation
fees if a customer tries to install DSL but runs into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Cable operators, of course, also hope to save money by letting
customers handle the task themselves. Dispatching a cable
technician typically costs between $70 and $140 per visit, said
Richard Holden, an executive at Redwood City's ExciteAtHome, the
nation's largest provider of cable modem service. Cablevision, for
instance, has been aggressively promoting self-installation in New
York City, he said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, the dominant cable operator in the Bay Area, also began
test marketing self-installation kits in two Circuit City stores in
Mountain View and Redwood City in November.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can install the service themselves if they live in one
of 13 communities south of San Francisco, though AT&AMP;T hopes to
offer it more widely in the Bay Area this year.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
