<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1894 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-NBA-SINKING-RATINGS-1     03-19 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-SINKING-RATINGS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1,050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC LOOKS FOR ANSWERS AS NBA RATINGS SINK  
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS ratings comparison to last year in 3rd graf; SUBS 5th graf to
add fan alienation after last season's lockout to list of reasons;
ADDS cable ratings also falling in last graf of first take; ADDS
amount of games telecast nationally in 7th graf of 2nd take.) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``f'')  
(ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just two years ago, the NBA was a very hot sports attraction on
network television, the ratings for its playoff finals at times
eclipsing those for baseball's World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the last season for Michael Jordan, the
transcendent sports star of the 1990s, and two years after his last
game the NBA has seen its popularity on network television plummet,
to the despair of its network partner, NBC.
</P>
<P>
   After spending $1.75 billion on rights for four NBA seasons
starting last season _ more than double the previous amount _ NBC
is now suffering through a terrible NBA year, particularly in prime
time, with audiences down by 20 percent. That has been enough to
send NBC's weekly prime-time ratings into a tailspin and its
overall basketball ratings down from 4.3 to 3.6 in a year. That
means the games are seen in approximately 700,000 fewer homes this
season. One week ago, on a Sunday night when the network showed a
game in prime time, NBC recorded the lowest rating for any night in
a season in the network's history.
</P>
<P>
   Now both the league and the network are talking about sharply
cutting back the number of prime-time games next season.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's exit from the court is generally the main reason cited,
since ratings had generally held steady through the end of his
career. But NBA and NBC executives and advertisers mentioned an
array of factors, including the overexposure of NBA games on cable
and local stations, particularly this season; the emergence of
Tiger Woods as the sports star most like Jordan in appealing to
casual sports fans; viewer alienation after the player lockout last
season; and, more fundamentally, the growing tendency of young
players to curtail, or even forgo, college basketball careers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed the quick movement of college players _ making it
difficult to build widely popular stars for a national audience _
is a marketing problem being blamed for what seems to be the
decline in interest. The regular-season ratings for college
basketball on CBS, the network most associated with the collegiate
sport, hit an all-time low this season, 1.9 (about 2 million
homes), although the NCAA tournament, now in progress, has been
generating ratings about on par with last season.
</P>
<P>
   But with the college game not able to establish stars through
four years of steady television appearances, both levels of the
sport have been affected, said David Stern, the NBA commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question at all that this is a factor,'' he said.
``There's a building process to exposure for these star players.''
</P>
<P>
   For years the NBA thrived on the regular arrival of pre-marketed
players, said Dick Ebersol, the president of NBC Sports. Jordan,
Magic Johnson and Larry Bird all catapulted to stardom in exciting
final games in the heavily viewed NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in Jordan's wake, the NBA is increasingly faced with the
task of marketing new stars, many of whom either attended only a
year or two of college, like Allen Iverson of the Philadelphia
76ers and Vince Carter of the Toronto Raptors, or did not go to
college at all, like Kobe Bryant of the Los Angeles Lakers and
Kevin Garnett of the Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   Both Stern and Ebersol repeatedly called the current season a
``transition year,'' meant to build up the host of new NBA stars
they believe are about to emerge from under Jordan's long shadow.
But the declaration reflects at least as much a hope as a
prediction. Stern said the league recognized that ``We have to get
people exposed to this next generation of stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strong preference would be to have a Tim Duncan and a
Grant Hill come into our league after four years in college,''
Stern said, citing two stars who finished their four years of
eligibility in college. ``But that isn't going to be the case as a
matter of law.'' Young players have established through legal
precedent that they have the right to seek a pro career without
regard to their college status.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has not even approached the popularity of the collegiate
tournament for its feature games on NBC Sunday nights this season.
The games hit a low a week ago when a total of only about 4.5
million people tuned in from 7 to 9 p.m. on Sunday March 12 to see
games between the Knicks and San Antonio, the teams that squared
off in last year's playoff finals, and _ in other parts of the
country _ Seattle against Toronto, the latter featuring Carter, who
has become the league's latest hope to replace Jordan as a
high-flying scoring talent.
</P>
<P>
   For the season, NBC is averaging only about 5.9 million fans for
its regular season prime-time games, down from 7.4 million last
season. The contrast that may be most jarring to the league is what
is happening to viewing for wrestling, which, on the UPN network,
is averaging more than 7 million viewers in prime time this season.
Even on cable, on the USA Network, wrestling is averaging about 7
million viewers every Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern said it was not fair to use wrestling as a comparison.
``It's just an entertainment phenomenon,'' he said. ``It's like
`Dawson's Creek' or ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings falloff has serious economic implications for NBC
because the audiences are clearly not approaching the expectations
of its advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Normally advertisers buy time on network programs with a
guarantee of certain audience figures. NBC does not give a formal
guarantee to its NBA advertisers, but there is an understanding
that if the network falls short of expectations it will offer what
are known as ``make good'' advertisements _ free commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol expressed confidence that enough time can be found in
the normal breaks of games to accommodate the make goods. But
whatever ad time the network gives away free is at least a missed
opportunity. The advertising marketplace is so strong right now
that NBC could sell that time at high prices to new advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Igiel, president of broadcast for Media Edge, a division of
the Young &AMP; Rubicam advertising agency, among several other
executives, pointed to the sheer number of NBA games that an
average television viewer can see every week as one reason the
weekend games have little special appeal. Turner Broadcasting's
cable channels have as many as four games a week, and local
channels like MSG in New York carry a home team's other games, and
cable stations' ratings are down as well. ``There are so many games
and so many teams,'' Igiel said. ``The NBA is all over the place.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The sheer number of teams also means that the star players do
not play as often in every city. The most widely cited geographical
problem facing the league involves the newly designated heir to
Jordan, Vince Carter. NBC has been realigning its schedule to
include his games. He paid off that endorsement by scoring 51
points in his first nationally televised game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his next game was included in the pair that set a new low
for NBC in prime time (even though he scored 34 points in that
one). One problem cited is the team Carter plays for, the Toronto
Raptors, a team many casual sports fans probably still do not know
is in the NBA. It is also in a city whose local ratings do not even
count. Canadian cities do not factor in U.S. ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Stern needs to make some move to get Carter to Chicago
or New York,'' said Donnie Deutsch, chairman of Deutsch Inc., which
represents such clients as Foot Locker. ``The rest of the league
needs him in a big media market.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern scoffed at that suggestion, saying a city's size is no
impediment to a star emerging. ``A few years ago, Orlando became a
huge team for us,'' he said. ``I just don't buy for a minute that
Vince Carter has to be in a major market.''
</P>
<P>
   What the league needs, both he and Ebersol argued, is simply
more time to get fans entranced with talents like Carter and
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol argued that in a world where every sport now competes
not only with other sports but also with the Internet and endless
other diversions, ``it is more important than ever to have stars.''
He compared it to a production job from early in his career, NBC's
``Saturday Night Live,'' which has risen and waned on the strength
of the stars in its cast. But television, in general, is producing
few big stars, because of the fragmentation of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   From a practical point of view, Ebersol said, the 17 games NBC
has in prime time this year, up from seven last year, are simply
too many. But that is partly a result of the huge 133 percent
increase NBC paid for the rights two years ago. It was forced to
put on more games to try to generate additional advertising
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said that with all the games that are being aired, the NBA
``is actually being seen by more eyeballs.'' But he said, ``Every
time we do a new television deal we take a look at it. It may be an
interesting time now to take a look at this one.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in the long term, the NBA will maintain its value
because in a world of so many options for consumers, big sports
events will still be must-see choices that audiences will plan
ahead for. ``We are live, so we are among the last appointment
viewing on television.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the short term, NBC has few answers for its problems
Sunday nights. As one longtime NBC executive put it, ``Right now,
Sunday night is a train wreck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
