<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-ST.JOSEPHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS GAINS FINAL 16 AS DEFENSE NEVER RESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RON DICKER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J._ Rutgers has prided itself on its defense all
season. But Sunday night against the St. Joseph's Hawks in the
second round of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
women's tournament, the Scarlet Knights outdid themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Scarlet Knights bullied the Hawks, they
outhustled the Hawks, and finally, they beat the Hawks, 59-39, in a
West Regional game to advance to the Round of 16 for the third
straight season.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers (24-7) will play in Saturday's regional semifinal in
Portland, Ore., where it will face the winner of the game between
third-seeded Mississippi State and 11th-seeded Alabama-Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Tasha Pointer scored 16 points for Rutgers and Usha Gilmore
turned in another inspirational performance off the bench, adding
12. Gilmore received a standing ovation from the partisan crowd at
the Louis Brown Athletic Center when she left with the Knights
leading by 57-37 with 1 minute 15 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, fans began to chant, ``Sweet 16, Sweet 16, Sweet
16.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers turned a disciplined St. Joseph's team into a wilted
mess in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph's (25-6), seeded 10th, kept within 4 points in the
first 20 minutes, but a 13-2 run by Rutgers put the already
cold-shooting visitors in a hole from which they could not dig out.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Zampella had 12 points for St. Joseph's and Jana
Lichnerova had 9 points.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph's has said it plays in a lot of physical games in the
Atlantic 10 Conference. But by early in the second half the Hawks
began showing the effects of playing against the Knights' bumping,
shadow-like defense.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Sutton-Brown and Davalyn Cunningham muscled in for
putbacks in a 7-0 surge to extend the Knights' 4-point lead at
halftime into a 30-22 cushion with 15 minutes 35 seconds left in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers Coach C. Vivian Stringer kept substituting to help keep
the Knights' energy level up on defense.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, in which Rutgers scrapped to a 23-19 lead,
nobody was making shots _ inside or outside.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, shoulders were crunching, elbows were
flailing and fingers were poking. Ninety seconds into the game,
Jana Lichnerova of St. Joseph's took a finger in the eye while
fighting for a rebound. She began bleeding and left the game for a
few minutes before returning with a black eye.
</P>
<P>
   Each team seemed to test the limits of the referees with each
possession, and each team's shooting percentage suffered for it.
St. Joseph's shot 26 percent and Rutgers 30 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-REFORM-1STLD-WRI     03-19 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REFORM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH NOT WIDELY KNOWN AS A REFORMER TEXAS  
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS title in 13th graf; CORRECTS ``described'' to ``privately
called'' in 3rd graf of 2nd take) 
 (rk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr. and JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; AUSTIN, Texas _ With the long march to November under way,
Gov. George W. Bush is arguing that his record in Texas proves he
is best suited to bring reform to Washington. He has even coined a
campaign slogan: ``A Reformer With Results.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Bush has been a popular governor, yet he is
not widely viewed in Texas as a reformer. Unlike Sen. John McCain
of Arizona, who bucked his own party on issues like campaign
finance and tobacco legislation, Bush is not as confrontational,
nor is he usually identified with sweeping change. His record is
largely built on compromise and his ability to build coalitions
with conservative Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's boldest effort at reform _ his 1997 plan to overhaul the
state's outdated tax code _ failed badly. The governor won plaudits
for his courage but ultimately could not leverage the ``political
capital'' he has promised to use if elected president: He could not
win the support of enough lawmakers in his own party.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues, consumer advocates complain that he often
describes as ``reforms'' actions benefiting the powerful Texas
business interests that have supported him, rather than consumers.
On the campaign trail, for example, he has portrayed himself as a
leader in reforming health maintenance organizations, yet he
resisted two important pieces of patients' rights legislation. And
his claims about the consumer benefits of tort reform _ a package
of bills that sought to curb large jury awards in civil cases _ are
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an incremental-change specialist,'' said Bruce Buchanan,
a political scientist at the University of Texas, ``sometimes in a
partisan way, like tort reform, which is a big business issue,
sometimes in a bipartisan way, such as small changes in
education.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Bush has found success, particularly during his
first legislative session, on initiatives he describes as reforms,
like changes in tort laws, stricter welfare rules, a crackdown on
juvenile crime, and giving more local control to public school
districts. Those efforts won Bush praise from lawmakers in both
parties, but all were popular issues before he took office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tort reform and all those things, we were already working on
them. It was smart politically for him to take advantage of that,''
said Pete Laney, the Democratic Texas House speaker and one of the
key legislative leaders who forged a bond with Bush early on. ``He
had all those things going on during his campaign, and that was
great politics for him to use those.''
</P>
<P>
   Laney added that `reform' means very different things to
different people. Some of the 1995 tort reforms, for example,
reversed changes made during the `reform' legislative sessions of
the early 1970s, he said. `Reform is pillage and plunder if you're
against it, and it's good government if you're for it,' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a Bush spokesman, said the governor played crucial
roles in the passage of reforms he campaigned on in 1994, as well
as later reform initiatives. Some, like tort reform, might have
died had Gov. Ann Richards, a Democrat, been re-elected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is able to reach across party lines to bring people
together,'' Bartlett said, adding that reforms ``are the main
reason he almost got 70 percent of the vote for his re-election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush declared tort reform an ``emergency'' when he took office
in 1995. Business groups had laid the groundwork for the
legislation but Bush's strong support was essential. And many of
these groups were among the governor's biggest campaign
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers passed seven bills, including a centerpiece measure
that reduced the punitive damages for which businesses and other
defendants might be liable if a jury determined they had committed
wrongdoing. At the same time, the bill raised the level of proof
plaintiffs must show to win such damages.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the laws helped rid Texas of ``junk and frivolous''
lawsuits, but others say the changes shifted the judicial balance.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie James, director of the &UR;  &LR; Austin office of Consumers Union
said, ``While it was portrayed as a fight between honest businesses
and greedy trial lawyers, the fight was really about businesses not
wanting to be held accountable when they harm consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has credited tort reform with saving consumers and
businesses nearly $3 billion in insurance premiums, with the
biggest part coming from auto liability rates. But the mechanism
for those savings has come not from Bush's proposals but from a
provision introduced in 1995 by a Democratic legislator requiring
state officials to adjust rates ahead of time to account for the
effects of tort reform, like lower settlements for injury claims.
</P>
<P>
   And some former senior Texas insurance officials contend that
the $3 billion claim is false anyway, and that the biggest
beneficiaries of the new laws are insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How they can continue to claim $3 billion in tort reform
savings is baffling to me,'' said Birny Birnbaum, an Austin
consumer advocate who served as the Texas Department of Insurance's
chief economist during the administrations of both Richards and
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Data from the state show that overall statewide premiums for
auto liability insurance stayed flat following tort reform, before
a slight dip in 1998. But insurers' profits soared because their
annual incurred losses were, on average, lowered by more than $600
million through 1998, the most recent year for which figures were
available. Five years ago, insurers incurred 70.1 cents in losses
for every dollar in premiums; in 1998, losses were 58.2 cents for
every dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Montemayor, the current insurance commissioner and a Bush
appointee, said better driving habits and safer cars had played a
larger role than tort reform in raising insurance company profits.
But he acknowledged that insurers probably had received some
benefits from tort reform in 1996 and 1997, until rates were rolled
back more the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little timid on the front end of this in terms of
the rate rollback because we really did not have a good feel for
the effects of tort reform,'' Montemayor said. But he added that
later ``we corrected that, and more than made up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Two years after tort reform, Bush, arguing that the state taxing
system was unfair and outdated, brushed away concerns that he could
hurt himself politically and proposed the biggest restructuring in
more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has property and sales taxes but no broad-based income
tax, and while corporations pay a form of business income tax,
partnerships do not. Bush contended that the state's booming
service-based economy was not paying its fair share, while
homeowners and industries with heavy capital spending paid too
much. He also wanted a more stable and reliable source of school
financing.
</P>
<P>
   His plan was to reduce property taxes, and pay for it mostly by
raising sales taxes and establishing a 1.25 percent tax on a
business' net income, depreciation and labor costs, minus its
capital expenditures, with the first $500,000 exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The plan drew fire from professional groups, including doctors
and lawyers, as well as retailers and other businesses with high
labor costs and low profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the expected winners were petrochemical companies, oil
refiners and other capital-intensive industries _ not a surprise,
perhaps, since Bush's new business tax tracked closely a proposal
offered to the governor by Charls Walker, a former Washington
lobbyist who ran a tax-advocacy organization financed mostly by
capital-intensive industries that favored the Bush plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was essentially a hidden sales tax,'' said Dick Lavine, a
senior analyst with the Center for Public Policy Priorities, a
nonprofit research group in Austin representing low-income
taxpayers. Overall, he said, the plan would take ``an already
regressive system and compound it.''
</P>
<P>
   And other, more powerful people were skeptical. The late
Democratic lieutenant governor, Bob Bullock, privately called the
plan as ``dead on arrival.''
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers junked the Bush proposal and assembled an
alternative the governor endorsed, but Bush was later unable to
persuade enough Senate Republicans to vote his way as legislators
tried to reconcile differences between the House and Senate
versions. Late in the session, Bush salvaged a $1 billion property
tax cut financed by the state's budget surplus. In 1999, Bush made
no effort to resurrect tax reform, instead seeking _ and getting _
more tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush could have put his political capital on the line'' to get
the tax plan passed, said Bill White, the former chairman of the
Texas Democratic Party, noting that another governor might have
threatened to campaign against dissenting legislators or made a
broader appeal to the public. But he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, the Bush spokesman, said: ``When times are relatively
calm, it's difficult to persuade people to change. He understood
that going in, and he was ultimately proud of what we did
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the tax cuts, not his failure at tax reform, that Bush
mentions on the campaign trail. He has also taken to boasting about
his role in reforming health care in Texas, a role that many in
Austin say is greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   One commercial for Bush says that while Congress deadlocked over
health care legislation, ``he passed a patients' bill of rights.''
But people involved in the process note that in 1995 Bush vetoed
the first Texas patient protection bill, and two years later he
considered vetoing the most groundbreaking HMO bill that Texas
lawmakers had debated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to say, `I reformed the tort system,' then that's
fair game,'' said James, the consumer advocate, ``but if he wants
to say he reformed health care, that's a different animal. The
reforms happened despite him, not because of him.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The 1995 patient protection bill included provisions requiring
annual report cards for health maintenance organizations and forced
HMOs to provide necessary emergency-room care. Today, Bush says he
vetoed the bill because of unfair exemptions it gave certain HMOs.
But in his veto proclamation he also mentioned other concerns:
``numerous new regulations on managed care organizations,''
including HMOs, and higher costs for employers.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the governor instructed the insurance commissioner to
draft rules that covered much of what the bill did. Consumer groups
objected strongly to the veto, but they praised the commissioner's
rules. The issue resurfaced in 1997, when the legislature codified
those rules and passed an expanded patient-protection package.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest battle, though, was over a bill to make Texas the
first state to allow patients to sue for malpractice HMOs that deny
necessary medical care. Bush warned of a veto, and his resistance
brought his staff into conflict with one of his staunchest
Republican allies, Sen. David Sibley, the bill's sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor, Sibley complained about the governor's
staff, saying, I can't make them happy no matter what I do, unless
I completely gut the bill.'' Sibley did not back away from that
comment in an interview, but he described Bush as a leader on
health care issues, saying he was supportive of the other
patient-protection measures passed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some other legislators involved have different recollections.
Patricia Gray, a Democratic House member who sponsored a bill
requiring HMOs to allow women direct access to their
obstetrician-gynecologist without having to first see a
gatekeeper'' physician _ a measure Bush has touted as a key HMO
reform _does not recall the governor, or his staff, providing any
help on the bill. I have no recollection of him being involved
whatsoever,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   That bill's senate sponsor, Florence Shapiro, a Republican, said
Bush's office did weigh in while the bill was in a senate
committee, and that he was supportive.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, lawmakers overwhelmingly approved the right-to-sue
bill, and Bush, who might have faced an embarrassing override vote
had he vetoed the bill, allowed it to become law without his
signature. His spokesman, Bartlett, said Bush became more
comfortable with the bill after provisions were added reducing the
likelihood of a flood of new lawsuits, including a requirement that
disputes first be reviewed by an independent panel.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Ross, chief lobbyist for the Texas Medical Association,
described Bush's evolution on health care issues as a ``baptism by
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on a steep learning curve,'' Ross said. ``You have to
give him credit for traveling a pretty far philosophical distance
in such a short period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
