<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LAVIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN'S POSITIVE ATTITUDE INSPIRES BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA basketball coach Steve Lavin has made all the
right moves in recent weeks. He tweaked the offense to improve
rhythm and flow. He put the defense in attack mode, and he injected
practice with heavy doses of efficiency and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing Lavin has done tactically can match what he did
psychologically - or didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't lose faith.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't dwell on defeat.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't let the Bruins give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where coach Lavin is really gifted is that when the team was
down after the Arizona trip, he made sure to be up,'' said UCLA
assistant Michael Holton. ``That level of leadership guided us
through the toughest time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were swept by the Arizona schools in mid-February and
dropped to 13-11 overall and 4-8 in the Pacific-10. They had lost
six of seven games. Their NCAA Tournament chances were fading. The
players were confused. The fans were angry. The season was in the
balance.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the Bruins are preparing for Thursday's showdown
against Iowa State - their third Sweet 16 appearance in four years.
They have won eight straight, they pounded Maryland in the second
round,and they are one of the hottest teams in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, it's been a remarkable turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Lavin just stayed positive with us, because that's his
personality,'' freshman Jason Kapono said. ``He could be faced with
(hate mail), and he'd find something positive in it. He stayed
confident in us. His message was: `Times are bad and people are
counting us out. But we're a pretty good team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Lavin's message made no sense: the Bruins had
just lost two games by 44 points. Their ballhandling was atrocious.
Their shot selection was awful. They appeared to quit against
Arizona State. They played scared at Arizona. They were alternating
between two offensive philosophies (motion and structure) and two
defenses (zone and man-to-man). They certainly didn't look like ``a
pretty good team.''
</P>
<P>
   But the players had three reasons to believe:
</P>
<P>
   --Lavin had evidence. He gathered the Bruins in their locker
room in Pauley Pavilion and rolled videotape of their victories
over NCAA Tournament-bound teams DePaul, Pepperdine, Purdue and
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't had those reference points, it would have been
difficult to keep the guys up,'' assistant coach Jim Saia said.
``But we were able to go to the film and show them.''
</P>
<P>
   --The problems were obvious. UCLA committed 45 turnovers in the
two games and took a slew of bad shots; both flaws led to easy
baskets for the opponents. Correct the mistakes, Lavin implored,
and the outcome would be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so bad, they were laughing at themselves,'' Saia said.
``We were literally handing the other team the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   --The coaches saw what the players (and fans and media) did not
- that the Bruins were improving. They were recognizing defenses
quicker and executing the complicated offense more efficiently.
They were reacting more and thinking less, a sign of evolving
comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Lavin said, `You can't see it, but the staff sees it,'
'' Holton said. ``We were finding ways to counter what the defenses
were doing. We saw their poise and their resiliency improving over
the course of weeks. Coach Lavin told them, `You're right there.
Don't take a step back. Don't leave your game in the desert.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He reduced their focus from the big picture to the small
picture so they had something to feel good about.''
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged, the Bruins jumped on every morsel of optimism
available. Lavin is optimism incarnate.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the down times, coach Lavin was always positive with
us,'' guard Ryan Bailey said. ``He told us there would be brighter
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Those brighter days have arrived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
