<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLOTTA SORENSTAM HALTS STREAK AND SISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TOM SPOUSTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Charlotta Sorenstam emerged from two shadows Sunday,
stopping Karrie Webb's streak of three straight LPGA tour victories
and beating her older sister, Annika Sorenstam, with a final-round
68 to win the first tour event of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotta Sorenstam outplayed Webb, the world's top-ranked
player, down the stretch of the Standard Register Ping tournament
at the Legacy Golf Resort, saving par several times to retain a
one-stroke lead until the last hole, where she sank a short birdie
putt and shared an emotional moment with family members. She saved
the longest embrace for Annika, the winner of 19 tour events, who
has already qualified for the LPGA Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tears of joy,'' Charlotta Sorenstam said.
</P>
<P>
   She finished at 12-under-par 276 to win by two shots over Webb
(70) and by five over her sister, who finished with a 73. Leta
Lindley shot 70 and Carin Koch carded 72 to tie for fourth place at
282.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice for Karrie to win and match Tiger, but
I still wanted to stop her,'' Charlotta Sorenstam said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it my best shot,'' said Webb, who fell short of tying
Nancy Lopez's record of five consecutive victories in 1978. ``I
still finished second and still had a chance to win. I had good
chances all the way through _ birdie chances on just about every
hole. I didn't make the putts down the stretch. I've made my fair
share of putts, but one day they weren't going to drop, and this
was the week it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sorenstam threw down par-saving putts. At No. 13, she
sank a 10-footer after blowing a wedge over the green. At No. 15,
with Webb's ball resting 2 feet from a birdie, Sorenstam salvaged
par with a brilliant sand shot that stopped a foot from the hole
and prevented a two-stroke swing.
</P>
<P>
   Now tied at 11 under par, she made par again with an 8-foot putt
at No. 16 after Webb hit the shot that arguably cost her the
tournament. Webb put her approach shot in a bunker and faced a
tricky lie in the sand. But she bladed her next effort past the
flag stick to the back fringe, chipped 20 feet past the hole and
missed the putt coming back. ``I just hit a shank,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   The bogey left her one stroke behind with two holes left. Both
players made par at No. 17, before Webb hit into a bunker at No. 18
and watched as Sorenstam clinched her victory with a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a chance, but she played awesome,'' a tearful
Annika Sorenstam said of her sister. ``I'm so proud of her. She's
always been in my shadow, and now she's broken through. I'm more
happy for her because I know what she has gone through, with
everyone comparing her to me. I just wanted her to play her own
game because I knew she was good enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunes changed quickly as Webb and the Sorenstam sisters
approached the turn.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotta Sorenstam seemed unflappable as she reached 11 under
par and took a brief four-stroke lead with a birdie at the par-5
eighth hole. Webb answered immediately, rolling in a 6-foot putt
and dropping to eight under. At the par-4 ninth, Charlotta
Sorenstam hit her tee shot into a bunker and took bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Webb made an easy par on that hole, then sank a 6-footer for
birdie at No. 10 to cut the lead to one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   They matched birdies again at the par-5 12th, before Webb tied
her with a short birdie putt at No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam, bidding for her second straight victory, never
recovered from consecutive bogeys at Nos. 9 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   She made one birdie and one bogey coming home, but missed
several other opportunities. It was a surprising slide for her
considering she has won 14 of 23 tournaments in which she has had
the final-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlotta just made some great shots,'' Webb said. ``She was
solid as a rock. Her putts, they didn't hit the lip and go in. They
were dead center all day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
