<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WACO-REENACT0320-COX     03-19 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-REENACT0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. district judge bars release of Waco re-enactment video
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT HOOD, Texas _ Once again Sunday, at about 11 a.m., tanks
rolled not far from Waco while overhead aircraft recorded their
actions.
</P>
<P>
   In about three hours, the court-ordered test at Fort Hood to
determine whether flashes on an infrared video taken at Mount
Carmel on April 19, 1993, were caused by gunshots or glint was
over.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco, however, barred
release of the video. The court-appointed expert, Vector Data
Systems Ltd., will release its report on the test video in about a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Houston attorney Mike Caddell had promised to release the tape
to the media today. Caddell is the lead attorney in a
wrongful-death lawsuit filed against the government by surviving
Branch Davidians and relatives of those who died at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk about it,'' Caddell said at a press conference
outside Fort Hood's main gate. ``We'll still give you our analysis.
We just won't be able to show you the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Caddell nor Michael Bradford, U.S. attorney for the
Eastern District of Texas, said they had any inside knowledge of
what the test will show.
</P>
<P>
   However, both men expressed confidence it will support their
view of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the tape comes out I'm confident it will be so different
from the tape of the 19th that it will put this issue to rest,''
Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only explanation they've offered for the flashes is glint
from debris,'' Caddell said. ``I know we're not going to get
flashes from debris that looks like the flashes from the 19th.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bradford and Caddell were supposed to receive digital
copies of the video for study late Sunday. They will release their
analysis of the test video and how it compares with the
Forward-Looking infrared (FLIR) video from Mount Carmel sometime
Monday .
</P>
<P>
   Buses took observers, but no media, to a remote site at Fort
Hood about 15 miles from the front gate, according to a Fort Hood
public information officer. Smith, Special Counsel John Danforth,
congressional investigators and members of the Texas Rangers were
among those in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a part of the base that was lonely, desolate and took
us about an hour to get to,'' Caddell said. ``We had to go through
three checkpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said he was concentrating too intently on the test
protocol to sum up the atmosphere at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were all trying to see if the test was carried out
in accordance with the protocol,'' Bradford said. ``Those were the
issues I was thinking about rather than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The test was scheduled to start at 10:30 a.m. Sunday. But it
took until after 11 a.m. for the temperature to warm up over 65
degrees, one of the test protocols. After lying on the ground for
20 minutes, eight shooters arose and went to a spot where there was
an M-16 rifle, a CAR-15 rifle, two 9 mm MP-5 submachine guns (one
suppressed), a Remington automatic shotgun, a Browning 88 9 mm
pistol, a M60 machine gun and an MK-19 automatic grenade launcher.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell said the last two weapons, which were supposed to be
used at the conclusion of the test, were late additions to the
start of the test.
</P>
<P>
   The shooters fired single shots first at a target 10 yards away.
Later, they also fired at a 30-yard target. When the shooters
finished, the protocol called for them to place their weapons down
and go to the rear of a Bradley fighting vehicle and a combat
engineering vehicle. From inside the Bradley, a shooter armed with
an M-79 grenade launcher was to appear, stand next to the vehicle
and fire two ferret rounds of tear gas, two M-651 rounds and two
flashbang rounds at the farthest target.
</P>
<P>
   Both the beginning and end of the test were developed to
determine whether people can appear invisible to the FLIR camera.
Plaintiffs had argued that the reason no people are seen in the
Mount Carmel FLIR is that they may have worn FLIR-resistant
clothing or they may have been on the ground and their body
temperature reflected that of the soil. The shooters Sunday wore a
variety of camouflage outfits, including a sniper outfit with
vegetation adornment and a Noxex flight suit, which was won by
members of the FBI's hostage rescue team.
</P>
<P>
   However, Caddell said Sunday that government agents can be seen
in the original FLIR. He promised to release photographs today
Monday proving his claim.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides tried to frame what they see as the key question to
be answered by the analysis of the test video.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first issue is can we see people in the tape,'' Bradford
said. ``As you know, the people firing weapons were wearing the
clothing that it's been alleged will make you invisible on the FLIR
tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Caddell saw it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the comparative analysis that will be the most
meaningful is whether the flashes were generated by gunfire or
trash,'' he said. ``Which one most looks like the flashes from the
FLIR of April 19th. Don't let this be about people. That's not the
real debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The press conference Sunday had a subplot. Davidian Clive Doyle,
who was injured in the fire, vented anger at Caddell, whom he
claimed had written letters to Davidians asking them to drop out of
the case. Doyle is represented in the lawsuit by Ramsey Clark, a
former U.S. attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell denied the charge, although he told Doyle that he
wouldn't divulge his correspondence with clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to comment on confidential attorney-client
communications,'' Caddell said. ``That's not appropriate and you
know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle also was frustrated that Caddell wanted to stage a
re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a lot of confidence in the re-enactment,'' Doyle
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Branch Davidians and their lawyers exposed to the public
... that the initial FLIR shows gunfire. They're out here to prove
it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a long drawn-out day, Caddell said there was one
bit of humor. The FBI's so-called Nightstalker plane, which carried
the FLIR camera and was called top secret by the government in
fighting the re-enactment, buzzed the test site after it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``So all that hurrah about classified information and we
couldn't see the Nightstalker apparently went out the window,''
Caddell said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
