<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-WELD-GOVERNOR-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-GOVERNOR OF MASSACHUSETTS CASTS EYES ON ALBANY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass., Tenn., N.C.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It might seem hard to imagine what significance the
life of Sam Houston, the legendary 19th-century Southern statesman,
might have for a blue-blood Yankee like William F. Weld, the former
Massachusetts governor who is now a lawyer and venture capitalist
living on Manhattan's Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   But with Weld, who was born on Long Island, back in New York and
talking about running for governor here in 2006, the comparison
made perfect sense to his friend Lamar Alexander, the former
governor of Tennessee, who immediately promised to send him a Sam
Houston biography.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to run and win, Weld would become the only American
to serve as governor of two different states other than Sam
Houston, who was governor of Tennessee from 1827 to 1829 and
governor of Texas from 1859 to 1861. And the similarities would not
end there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only was he governor of two states, but he resigned from
both of them on principle,'' Weld said, smiling as he recounted a
recent telephone conversation with Alexander. ``I said, `Oh,
really; he was a quitter like me.' And Lamar said, `Yes, but a
quitter on principle.' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Weld did not exactly quit the Massachusetts State House on
principle, but rather out of restlessness. After a failed bid to
unseat Sen. John F. Kerry in 1996, he resigned to pursue a curious,
ill-fated quest to become ambassador to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   When that collapsed _ his nomination quashed by a fellow
Republican, Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, who opposed Weld's
liberal views on social issues _ he joined a Boston law firm,
McDermott, Will &AMP; Emery. Late last year, he was asked to head the
firm's New York office.
</P>
<P>
   It is a job in which Weld professes to be content, even as he
talks openly about the possibility of a return to public service in
time for the 2006 governor's race _ the first one he would be
eligible to enter after meeting the state's five-year residency
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very comfortable niche right here,'' he said in an
interview in his small corner office overlooking Rockefeller
Center. But he has never had much patience for comfort. He quit his
first law firm, for example, dropping off partner track to join the
staff of the House Judiciary Committee during the Watergate
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Already, he has begun to surface in Republican circles at the
highest levels, most recently last month at a fund-raising strategy
session at the ``21'' Club in Manhattan with supporters of Gov.
George W. Bush, including Gov. George E. Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   But while he did register to vote in New York in time for the
presidential primary on March 7, he has not yet taken an active
role in local politics and did not join state Republicans for a
rally after the Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in airplanes for the last week,'' he said a few
days after the primary, recounting recent business trips: ``Palm
Beach, Nashville, Chicago, New York, Boston, New York, Boston, New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Weld said he expected his role to be limited to fund-raising for
the near future. He is a Bush campaign ``Pioneer,'' the campaign's
designation for those who have helped raised more than $100,000 for
the Texas governor. He said he had also offered to make telephone
calls on behalf of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   From his days in Massachusetts, Weld is well armed to help his
friends, with a ready list of about 30,000 dependable campaign
contributors who supported him in the past.
</P>
<P>
   He is also planning to lend a hand to the bid of Mayor Rudolph
W. Giuliani o f New York for U.S. Senate. ``There are not too many
people who can go on TV and say, `You know, I am a friend of
Hillary Rodham's for 25 years standing but I am telling you we have
got to have Giuliani in there,' '' he said. He is planning to
organize a fund-raising dinner for Giuliani in Boston, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weld and the mayor have been friends since the mid-1980s, when
Giuliani was associate attorney general at the Justice Department
and helped Weld be appointed as U.S. attorney in Massachusetts.
They campaigned with each other in their previous races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly love the idea of Rudy getting down there in the
Senate and chewing on everybody's leg,'' Weld said. ``He would not
let people get away with the palaver and chaff that passes for
political speeches in Washington these days.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush went on to win the White House, Weld said he would be
unlikely to accept a post in the administration. ``It's too soon,''
he said. Even if he were eligible to run for governor in 2002, Weld
said he might not be ready.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, William Floyd Weld spends his days exploring
venture capital investments and contemplating leveraged buyouts of
education companies. While he is a trained lawyer _ Harvard Law
School, Class of 1970 _ and a former federal prosecutor, his role
now is as a power broker and rainmaker.
</P>
<P>
   He is also at work on his third political mystery novel. ``I
like to range from side to side, law, business, writing, and I
don't have to travel to avoid being bored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If and when he decided to return to government, he said he would
set his sights on Albany and a job that would fit his background
and interests. ``It would be a kind of a waste to run for an office
where the upstate and suburban experience would not be all that
relevant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, New York is a far more natural place for Weld than
Boston or Cambridge, where he still owns a home. He is a namesake
of William Floyd, one of four signers of the Declaration of
Independence from New York, and he grew up on his family's 600-acre
farm in Smithtown, on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   His great-grandfather, Francis Minot Weld, founded the
white-shoe Manhattan investment bank of White, Weld &AMP; Co., which
was bought by Merrill Lynch in 1978. His wife, Susan Roosevelt
Weld, also a native New Yorker, is a great-granddaughter of
Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that Weld, by the end of his career, will have
held as many public offices as his new hero, Sam Houston, who, in
addition to being governor twice, was attorney general in
Tennessee, president of the Texas Republic, a congressman and
three-term U.S. senator. All this, as well as having been an Army
officer, diplomatic attache to several Indian nations and the
runner-up for the presidential nomination of the National Union
Party in 1860. But it would be out of character for Weld not to try
to come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Houston got bored just like you,'' Lamar Alexander told
him in their phone conversation. ``He went to live with the Indians
and he hunted game and chased Indian princesses.'' To which Weld
replied, ``Maybe the Oneontas or the Oneidas would take me in
upstate. They have some pretty good revenues from gaming and I'm
pro-gaming, and this business of 100 percent hunting game and
Indian princesses doesn't sound all bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
