<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTRAND FOX, 92, AN ECONOMIST AND SECURITIES EXPERT AT HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bertrand Fox, an economist and expert on the securities industry
who taught for more than 20 years at the Harvard Business School,
died March 14 at his home in Lexington, Mass. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who lived in Lexington for 45 years, was the business
school's director of research from 1953 to 1968.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, he redirected the school's research, which had
relied almost exclusively on case studies, toward more systematic
analysis, said J. Keith Butters, who was a close friend and fellow
member of the school's faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very ticklish assignment because it involved
challenging a lot of vested practices,'' Butters said. Fox managed
it by ``being tactful and absolutely fair and careful in everything
that he did,'' Butters said.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on expertise he developed as an adviser to a group of
investment banks that the federal government sued unsuccessfully on
antitrust grounds, Fox later reintroduced investment banking to the
Harvard curriculum. In 1967, he became the first person to hold the
Jacob H. Schiff Chair of Investment Banking; 12 year earlier, he
had been the first to hold the Edsel B. Ford Chair of Business
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, 10 years after he retired from its faculty, Harvard
Business School gave Fox its Distinguished Service Award. After
leaving Harvard, Fox worked as a consultant with the Cambridge
Research Institute until he retired in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who was born in Wisconsin, studied mathematics and
astronomy at Northwestern University, where he was a quarterback on
the football team and a member of the track team. He went on to
earn a doctorate in economics at Harvard, then taught economics at
Williams College.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Fox was director of the Military
Requirements Division of the War Production Board. In that role, he
helped the United States government decide how to allocate
resources between the war effort and the domestic economy. From
1958 to 1962, he was director of research for the United States
Commission on Money and Credit.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Patricia; a sister, Gertrude Tuttle,
of Tacoma, Wash.; four sons, Philip of Grosse Pointe, Mich., Thomas
of Washington, Kenneth of Englewood, Colo., and Peter of Palo Alto,
Calif.; two daughters, Ann Gulbransen of Sharon Center, Ohio, and
Joan Fox-Bow of Yorktown Heights, N.Y.; and eight grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
