<SLUG> BC-GEN-CYBER-LADN </SLUG>
 
SO IT'S BEST TO AVOID CYBERSTICK OF McSORLEY, TOO? 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As sports video games strive to become more and
more realistic, the players who they aim to duplicate on the screen
can't help but be a bit more frightened at the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Will they someday be replaced altogether?
</P>
<P>
   Calm down.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Laperrier, the Kings' resident video-game expert, tried out
the new Sega game ``NHL 2K'' for Sega Dreamcast in the players'
lounge at the team's practice facility in El Segundo recently and
was left almost speechless.
</P>
<P>
   Which in itself is a pretty frightening thing to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first started coming out with these games, everyone
skated the same, looked the same ... but now it's getting scary,''
Laperrier said. ``I recognize myself on the game, all the little
details like how I skate. I'm not like Luc Robitaille - I'm not the
fastest guy - and that's how I am on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Laperrier then shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they going to do to improve these games in five
years?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all that's left is to tweak the goalie moves, suggests
another Kings gamer, Jamie Storr, who has the game as well and
squared off against Laperrier the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get all the goalie moves to look real
</P>
<P>
   the equipment never looks right,'' said Storr, the team's No. 2
goalkeeper. ``It's almost too hard to get that. But this game seems
to get the closest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also find it pretty difficult to play. At least, it's very
hard to score.''
</P>
<P>
   A goalie should appreciate that. But the fact is, in the
evolution of NHL video games, ``NHL 2K'' probably has come closest
to matching a real game - meaning scoring isn't supposed to be
easy.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 motion capture images are what make the realism
burst out on the screen (100 alone for the goalies), along with the
high resolution that the Dreamcast system already brings. All 27
arenas are available to play on.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of the game include the option of putting teams
in one of several game jerseys - the Kings can even suit up in
their 1967 bright yellow pajamas. And the advanced offensive
settings allow for three styles of play: passive (positional),
normal and aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up fighting. The controllers allows for ducking,
grabbing, jabbing and a hard punch during a scrap, but you can
avoid a fight by pressing the A button three times at the start, so
if the other players drop their gloves, they get the penalty and
you don't.
</P>
<P>
   But the game directions also warn you that if you hang onto the
puck too long, you'll get flattened by a defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best description is from a review that appears in the
April issue of Playboy magazine: ``(This game) is so good, it
hurts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
