<HEADER>
A1924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-DNA-NYT &LR;      03-19 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-DNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEADLINES, DATABASES AND DNA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, March 19:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki wants to tap the potential of DNA evidence to
help solve crimes, and his instinct is surely right. The power of
the technology was illustrated when biological evidence found at a
crime scene 20 years ago was shown to match a DNA sample taken
recently from a jailed robber for inclusion in New York's newly
expanded DNA database. But Pataki's two new legislative proposals
are so broad as to warrant concern. The Legislature needs to
proceed with caution.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's first bill would eliminate the statute of limitations
for 16 felonies, including rape, manslaughter, aggravated sexual
assault, robbery, burglary, second-degree arson, illegal firearm
sales, gang assault and aggravated assault on a police officer.
Murder is already exempt. The idea is to keep cases open so
prosecutions are not foreclosed if evidence from unsolved crimes
turns out to match DNA profiles in the state's expanding database.
</P>
<P>
   There is a strong case for abolishing deadlines in cases of rape
and other violent sexual assaults where semen tests can now
identify the assailant with reasonable certainty by his DNA code.
Indeed, a suspect's DNA profile in this narrow band of cases should
be a sufficient identifier for a prosecutor to obtain a ``John
Doe'' warrant _ the novel approach taken by a Milwaukee prosecutor
last fall and by Manhattan prosecutors last week to prevent the
prosecution deadline in rape cases from expiring. A change in the
law to lift time limits on prosecutions based on matching existing
rape evidence with developing DNA databases makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   But the case for completely lifting the present five-year
statute of limitations for a long list of other felonies, where the
biological evidence found at the crime scene typically is not
definitive, is not persuasive. DNA evidence is an important law
enforcement tool. But it is not a magic bullet that overrides
traditional concerns about fairness, and the ability of defendants
to muster evidence in their defense, that were behind time limits
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the five-year limit does not appear as inflexible as
the governor makes out. In an important decision last year, the
state's highest court, the Court of Appeals, held that the time
limit in a serious felony case can be extended up to another five
years when the police are diligent yet cannot discover a suspect's
whereabouts because his identity remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's second bill would require every person convicted
of a state crime to provide a biological sample for a state
database. At some point, it may make sense to broaden sampling. But
Albany approved a law vastly expanding its DNA databank just last
August to include about 30,000 people convicted of the most common
and violent felonies. Their testing is not yet completed, and the
state crime lab already has a backlog of DNA samples. If the
governor is truly serious about maximizing the crime-solving value
of DNA, his first priority is to shore up existing lab capacity to
solve the present backlog problem, and to educate police detectives
in how to identify and properly handle DNA samples at crime scenes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
