<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EVERHART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REX EVERHARD, WHO ACTED IN 26 BROADWAY SHOWS, DIES AT 79 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rex Everhart, a character actor who appeared in 26 Broadway
productions including ``1776,'' in which he played Ben Franklin,
and ``Working,'' for which he received a Tony Award nomination,
died on March 13 at a hospice in Branford, Conn. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was lung cancer, said his wife, Claire Richard
Everhart.
</P>
<P>
   Everhart, who started his theater career in 1939, worked in
regional and repertory theaters including the Phoenix Theater, Yale
Repertory Theater and seven seasons at the American Shakespeare
Festival in Stratford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the Shakespeare Theater's production of ``The Comedy
of Errors'' in The New York Times in 1963, Howard Taubman wrote,
``Rex Everhart handles the two Dromios with unfailing comic
gusto.'' And in 1964, reviewing ``Much Ado About Nothing,'' Taubman
said that as the constable Everhart ``somehow pries a grin out of
us even when we know every simple-minded joke that is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor's television career, which started back in days of
live broadcasting, included series, plays, films, soap operas and
commercials. Appearing in 16 feature films, Everhart was most
recently the voice of Maurice in the Disney movie ``Beauty and the
Beast.'' Having made his 1955 Broadway debut in ``No Time for
Sergeants,'' Everhart's other Broadway shows included ``Anything
Goes,'' ``Rags'' and ``Woman of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Everhart was born in Wateska, Ill., and received a degree in
theater at the Pasadena Playhouse and bachelor's and master's
degrees at New York University. He lived for 37 years in Westport,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Everhart and his wife, also an actress, met in 1960 when they
were in the Broadway musical ``Tenderloin.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Everhart is survived by his daughter,
Degan, of Baltimore, and a granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
