<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-OKLAHOMASTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE FALLS TO OKLAHOMA STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ It was a crazy dream to begin with. The fact
that it lingered ever so tantalizingly never changed that.
</P>
<P>
   A colorful, headband-wearing, retro-Afro-looking basketball team
from a small, strict college in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   A new coach with a reputation to mend.
</P>
<P>
   Both in need of the other. Their paths crossing, improbably.
Together they travel further then any team in school history,
shocking the nation and capturing its heart all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, it was crazy all right.
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA Tournament is safe haven for such audacity,
practically daring teams to dream so wishfully.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a catch. It can end at any time.
</P>
<P>
   For Pepperdine, that moment came Sunday. Oklahoma State was
responsible, halting the Waves' record-breaking season in a 75-67
second-round East Regional victory before 19,351 at HSBC Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It ends the Waves (25-9) hopes of reaching the Sweet 16 for the
first time in school history. As far-fetched as that appeared a few
weeks ago, it actually seemed possible after they beat Indiana on
Friday in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   There was disappointment afterward, but also a sense of
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew who we were when we came out here, but we found
out who we were,'' Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff said. ``Now
it's up to the younger guys to build on the tradition we started.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was quite a contrast from Friday, when Pepperdine blazed
to a 77-57 win over Indiana. The Waves could only flicker against
Oklahoma State, its offensive rhythm choked off by the Cowboys'
quick, rugged defense.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (25-6) now moves on to the Sweet 16. The Cowboys
play Seton Hall on Friday in Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves return home to Malibu, frustrated with the result but
much more popular then when they left. Their win over Indiana was
an awakening. All of a sudden people were interested in the players
with the crazy hairdos, eclectic personalities and free-spirited
brand of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   There was intrigue about van Breda Kolff, exiled after six years
at Vanderbilt, reborn in Southern California. Van Breda Kolff is
responsible for the Waves' contagious, uptempo style after shelving
former coach Lorenzo Romar's grind-it-out offense. The Waves took
to it immediately. The fans at the East Regional embraced it, too.
</P>
<P>
   When Pepperdine walked off the floor Sunday, many in the arena
stood and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach mentioned in the locker room that when we first got here
(there were only) two Pepperdine fans, our (athletic director) and
his wife,'' Tezale Archie said. ``Three days later half the
building is chanting for us. So definitely, we made a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves had loftier goals then introducing the country to
their fun-loving style, though. They felt all along they could beat
Indiana and whoever else stood between them and the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   There were opportunities to do that against Oklahoma State, but
inconsistent shooting (42 percent) ruined the chance for a decisive
run to take control.
</P>
<P>
   The effect was two-fold. The Waves never got on a roll, and
their full-court press, which is triggered by made baskets, was
rarely a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt if we could keep the press on, it would wear them
down,'' van Breda Kolff said. ``Unfortunately, we just couldn't
make a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Armstrong had 19 points but was only 3 of 10 from the
field. Kelvin Gibbs made just 2 of 10 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine was 27 of 64 overall, offsetting Nick Sheppard's 13
points on 5-o-6 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got all the looks we wanted, we just didn't knock them
down,'' said Archie, who had a career-high 14 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys broke it open with a 14-4 run to make it 65-50 with
3:59 left. Joe Adkins did most of the damage, connecting on two
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Joe. He's done it four years here,'' Cowboys point
guard Doug Gottlieb said. ``When we need a bucket and he's open,
it's going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkins' offense was crucial. Pepperdine surrounded Desmond
Mason, the Cowboys' leading scorer, forcing him to surrender
possession most of the time. Mason finished with just 13 points,
five off his usual pace.
</P>
<P>
   It was a calculated risk by the Waves. By swarming Mason, it
allowed Adkins (18 points) and Fredrik Jonzen (21 points) more room
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Jonzen, a 6-10 center, made 7 of 13 shots, many on layups when
Oklahoma State found open seams in Pepperdine's pressure defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody is going to spread their defense you can't be
content just to get the ball across the midcourt line,'' said
Cowboys coach Eddie Sutton. ``You've got to attack the basket and
take it through the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine made one last push over the final minute, getting two
steals, a 3-pointer from Armstrong and two from Archie to make it
72-67 with 45.9 left.
</P>
<P>
   But Pepperdine never scored another point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed we didn't win this last game because our
goal was to make it to the second round,'' forward Tommie Prince
said. ``But we were happy that we were here and that we made a
little noise.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of noise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
