<DOCNO> NYT20000319.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1931 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      03-19 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECIDEDLY DIFFERENT `TITUS' TAPS COMIC'S TROUBLED LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Titus, a new comedy from Fox, is clever, funny and troubling.
</P>
<P>
   Not your normal combo. And not your normal sitcom. Even while
you're laughing at former stand-up comic Christopher Titus and his
twisted relationship with his father, you can't escape the
question: When does the comedy end and the therapy begin?
</P>
<P>
   ``This show is my real life,'' Titus said back in January.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe not exactly. Titus' real father has been married six
times; his TV father, hilariously played by Stacey Keach, only
five. His real-life mom, who was insane, is dead. His TV one _ also
insane _ is alive.
</P>
<P>
   The pain of growing up in this emotional whirlwind is what Titus
mines _ successfully _ for com edy in the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from a dysfunctional family means nothing rattles me,''
Titus says in one episode. ``Hey, once you've driven a drunk father
to Mom's parole hearing, what else is there?''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that makes you laugh instead of wince is the
remarkably blame-free way Titus _ the real and the TV versions _
presents all of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``To write the show,'' Titus said, ``you had to have gone past
it and seen the positive aspects of what ever your life was. . . .
You're never going to see us go to a real sappy place of `look what
happened to me.' It's great to laugh about it because then it blows
it away. It turns it into a joke instead of what life was.''
</P>
<P>
   See what I mean? You don't know whether to hug the guy or charge
him $125 an hour for listening.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, jokes about alcohol, corporal punishment, mental
illness and the like won't go over big with everyone. Titus and
Jack Kenny, one of the show's executive producers, sounded
prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you have to laugh at something,'' Kenny said. ``If
you're not laughing . . . then you may as well just do a drama, and
we're not doing drama. We'll try to be democratic in our political
incor rectness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not poking fun at'' sensi tive subjects, Titus said.
``It's my life, so we're not poking fun at it. And you know what
else? If it's picketed, I'll join the picket. It is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is, over the course of an entire episode, a little tiring.
The downbeat sarcasm, however clever, makes a half-hour seem twice
as long.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Titus is different from traditional comedies, and that
counts for a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Next patient! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
