<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Monday, March 20, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Larry Johnson on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8035.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-STRIKE (Undated) _ The Boeing strike vote. Expect voting
to end around 4 p.m.; they'll begin counting immediately. Union
says to expect results as early as 7 p.m. PST.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE-CAPITAL-SEATTLE (Undated) _ When George Clute founded
Olympic Venture Partners in 1982, the banker turned venture
capitalist had to travel out of state to find promising new
start-up companies to fund. ``There just weren't enough quality
deals in Seattle,'' said Clute, whose Kirkland firm invested about
60 percent of its first $25 million fund in California companies.
Things have certainly changed. Partners at Olympic now spend more
time crossing the 520 bridge than buzzing down to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   By John Cook. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   KINGDOME-MEMORIES (Seattle) _ In a brick building near Pioneer
Square, Elizabeth Furlow hunts for ghosts of the Kingdome. She
slips inside a dimly lit storage room and locks eyes with Jack
Lelivelt, the late baseball manager for the Seattle Rainiers, a
minor league team. It's love at first sight. ``I'd like to have
him,'' she says, studying the bronze plaque honoring the man who
led the Rainiers to two championships six decades ago. Furlow is
part of a cadre of local curators on a mission to save Kingdome
memorabilia and souvenirs. Their pursuit has taken on greater
importance given the imminent demise of the Kingdome on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert L. Jamieson Jr. (Story will move in the ``a''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Column on the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN (Undated) _ ``Are we there yet?'' Actually,
Capt. George Vancouver never uttered those exact words while
cruising the waters now known as Puget Sound. But he was not the
kind of passenger you would want sitting in the back seat on a long
trip.
</P>
<P>
   By John Owen. (Story has moved in the ``d'' category.)
</P>
