Netcenter, a division of America Online's Netscape. The Netcenter
portal turns a small profit, in large part because it can use the
huge technical and sales infrastructure of AOL. Even before the big
increase in traffic that AOL hopes for from Netscape 6.0, Netcenter
has more than held its own against the competing portal sites.
(Marty Katz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 19, 2000 -- GLADWELL-PROFILE-MEDIA --
Malcolm Gladwell, a writer at the New Yorker magazine in the new
Conde Nast building in Times Square. Gladewell's current web site
contains his articles from the New Yorker, along with information
on his new book, ``The Tipping Point''. Gladwell is the only staff
writer at The New Yorker who maintains a personal and fully stocked
web site, complete with all of his articles for The New Yorker
archived and indexed. Gladwell owns the rights to all of his
articles. Gladwell.com, has received 85,000 hits so far this month.
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 19, 2000 -- IBM-LINUX -- Left, Sam
Palmisano, 47, senior vice president and executive of IBM's
Enterprise Systems Group with Dr. Irving Wladawsky-Berger, 52, vice
president of the Technology and Strategy Enterprise Systems group
at IBM. Wladawsky-Berger was the one who convinced Sam Palmisano to
convert to the Linux operating system and Palmisano has put him in
charge of its implementation throughout IBM. IBM's Linux strategy
represents more than a bold, and risky, step in the field of
software. The move is a textbook example of IBM's management style
under Gerstner, who has worked to overhaul the company and its
culture since he arrived in 1993. (Joyce Dopkeen/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
