<SLUG> BC-COIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOLDEN DOLLAR' ELUSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Mint says there are 350 million in circulation, but the
new dollar coin is turning out to be as elusive as a vending
machine that accepts your crumpled currency.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that's about to change. The ``golden dollar''
should start showing up any week now, mint spokesman Michael White
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes awhile for them to get into the pipeline,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first transaction nationally involving the new coin was at a
Wal-Mart Supercenter in north Scottsdale, when a cashier gave one
to a Mesa girl as change when she was buying a gift for her
grandparents. That was Jan. 27, a day after the coin was shipped
from the mint to the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   White predicts that the new dollar coin will be more successful
than the Susan B. Anthony dollar because it's easier to distinguish
from a quarter (a criticism on the Susan B.) and because it's being
distributed through major retailers, getting it into cash drawers
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The new coin, bearing the likeness of Sacagawea, the Shoshone
guide for explorers Lewis and Clark, has a plain edge, a wider
border and a golden color.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did extensive testing to see that you can pick it out from
other change and found people had no problem,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the mint sent 100 million coins to Wal-Mart stores
around the country and another 100 million to Federal Reserve
Banks, which sold them to commercial banks based on demand.
</P>
<P>
   This month, it shipped another 100 million to the Federal
Reserve and 50 million more to smaller financial institutions known
as correspondent banks.
</P>
<P>
   But finding the coin is difficult. Banks around the Phoenix area
have received very few.
</P>
<P>
   One place that still reports a stock is the same Wal-Mart that
made that first transaction. The store, near Hayden Road and Frank
Lloyd Wright Boulevard, routinely makes change with the coins, said
David Lamp, the store's co-manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stores are about out of them, so some people come
to our store specifically for the coin,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think you're going to stock up on the coins, think
again. Wal-Mart has set a $10 limit per customer on the coins.
</P>
<P>
   Lamp, a coin collector, also warned customers not to consider
the dollar coins as a collector item.
</P>
<P>
   White, of the mint, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect by the 14th week of manufacturing, we'll hit 500
million coins,'' he said. ``It took 14 years for the Susan B. to
hit that amount.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
