<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGDOME-MEMORIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGDOME MEMORABILIA GETS ANOTHER CHANCE AT BAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a brick building near Pioneer Square, Elizabeth Furlow hunts
for ghosts of the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   She slips inside a dimly lit storage room and locks eyes with
Jack Lelivelt, the late baseball manager for the Seattle Rainiers.
It's love at first sight. ``I'd like to take him,'' she says,
studying contours of the bronze plaque honoring the minor league
coach who led the Rainiers to two championships 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Furlow is part of a cadre on a mission to save Kingdome
memorabilia and souvenirs. The nostalgic pursuit has taken on
greater importance given the imminent demise of the landmark
stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say relics from the Kingdome _ including the Lelivelt
plaque, which was once housed in a stadium museum _ will provide
learning tools for future generations to study the sports and civic
life of Seattle in the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of items linked to the Dome _ from ticket stubs to a
wood architectural model of the stadium to old photographs of the
Seattle Metropolitans, Seattle's World Hockey Champions in 1917 _
have been cataloged, packed up and placed in five storage rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms, haunted by history, are a collector's dream: a framed
football jersey of Steve Largent, the Hall of Fame Seahawks
receiver; an old control panel for the Kingdome's scoreboard; a
baseball, blackened by age, that was used in an 1886 game; a
duplicate NBA trophy commemorating the Sonics's 1979 championship
season in the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are items that 50, 100 years from now people will look
at and say one thing _ Kingdome,'' said Furlow, curator of
collections for the Museum of History and Industry in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want things that are evocative,'' she said. ``Things that
will help people understand the Kingdome and its relevancy to
Seattle history.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the items will be donated to three places _ the Museum
of History and Industry, the Washington State Historical Society in
Tacoma and the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining relics and mementos will be made available to the
public during an auction this spring, said Carol Keaton, a
long-time Kingdome employee whose work has made it possible for the
items to find new homes. She has been stockpiling stuff since
December.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in the storage room is connected _ directly or
indirectly _ to the Dome. For example, the Lelivelt plaque was part
of old Sick's Stadium in south Seattle before it found a place in
the Kingdome museum. (Lelivelt led the Rainiers to Pacific Coast
League championships in 1939 and 1940.)
</P>
<P>
   Ticket stubs and media passes, framed in a glass and wood case,
are the result of more than 3,000 events in the 23-year history of
``Stonehenge in Seattle,'' as the Dome was dubbed.
</P>
<P>
   Some items were literally attached to the stadium. ``Now these I
remember!'' exclaimed Feliks Banel, a deputy director at the Museum
of History and Industry, who grabbed the back of an orange Kingdome
seat. The color, he said, signified the Kingdome's 300 level _
popularly referred to as the cheap seats. He let loose a knowing
chuckle. ``The nosebleeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Furlow and Banel have made two previous trips to the storehouse
of memories, which sits in a building shadowed by the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Their booty has included a ceiling tile that fell from the
interior roof of the Kingdome in 1994, a patch of artificial turf
and all four bases from opening day of 1999 _ the Mariners' last
season in the Dome. These items, which are on display at the museum
in the 2700 block of 24th Avenue East, are popular.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the museum generated about $20,000 in revenue. But in
little more than a week since the museum opened its Kingdome
collection, more than $4,000 has flooded in, in part because a
museum gift shop is selling pieces of Kingdome turf, T-shirts and a
sample of field dirt as part of a $40 ``Implosion Pack.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent afternoon, Keaton stepped into a storage room and
pulled out a piece of clothing _ a silk Haori coat presented in
1921 to Roscoe ``Torchy'' Torrance, a UW baseball player, during
the baseball team's tour of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   During that trip, the UW players had a brush with history.
Keaton said that one of the Japanese translators for the team was a
man who went on to bigger things _ Hirohito.
</P>
<P>
   As Keaton rummaged through one of the storage rooms, her eyes
darted to another item _ a baseball signed by members of the 1969
Seattle Pilots baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes darted again, locking onto a 1920 letterman jacket of
All American Husky football player Charles O. Carroll, who later
became a prosecuting attorney for King County. ``I'm going to have
to get in touch with his family today,'' Keaton whispered to
herself.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of monetary value, Keaton said, the items ranged from
``dime store to expensive.'' In terms of nostalgia, she called them
``priceless,'' and she hopes some of the mementos could be used in
a time capsule at the new football/soccer stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Furlow and Banel, connoisseurs of history both, relish stepping
into the warehouse, which they likened to passing through a time
machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kingdome was a big civic gathering place,'' Banel said.
``It was one of the few places to have hosted four major sports _
football, baseball, soccer and basketball. Stadiums these days are
not made to serve so many purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Furlow came to Seattle from Gainesville, Fla., in 1992. ``To me,
the Kingdome is as much part of the Seattle skyline as Mount
Rainier or the Space Needle. As soon as you see it,'' she said,
snapping her fingers, ``you think Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to the storage rooms last week, the pair hauled
away a bulky IVC 500A TV camera, which went out of style in the
1980s, as well as an aluminum bench; both items could soon be on
display at the museum. Furlow took a fan program from this year's
Seahawks-Miami Dolphins game, which was the final public event in
the stadium, and Kingdome computer screensavers, which the museum
plans to sell as souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``History moves so quickly,'' Banel said. ``Usually you get
something, and it takes a few years before it becomes part of an
exhibit. But items we took a week ago are already on display.
People want to see it _ they want to see it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the relic hunters called it quits for the day, an item
caught their attention _ a large green mat with words in white
letters that struck an ironic note given what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Kingdome,'' the mat read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
