<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN PUTS STARS' CUP AIM IN FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A playoff berth has been clinched by the Stars, likely
the No. 2 seed. Forty wins have been achieved for a franchise-best
fourth consecutive season. Only New Jersey has done likewise.
</P>
<P>
   The power play, the goal scorers, the goalie and the defense all
look to be coming together after a season that can be described as
tumultuous on its good days and hellish on its worst.
</P>
<P>
   So why, then, after a 5-3 thumping yesterday of potential
first-round opponent San Jose, did the Stars not sound like a team
on the top of its game?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because the Stars don't think they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still another level yet,'' Stars winger Brad Lukowich
said. ``You can't feel that it's there. It's like it's right there,
that next step to be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   They're playing really well.
</P>
<P>
   They say they can play better.
</P>
<P>
   They know, if they're going to repeat as Stanley Cup champions,
they will have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to do more,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor
said. ``It's just the little things we're trying to work on in our
own zone. I think we're taking little baby steps. Work on this,
work on that, get our power play going, keep our penalty kill
going, that's what keeps us going.''
</P>
<P>
   They're pretty close. Or, at least, they look to be after what
they did to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scored five goals, including four in a row after San
Jose took a 1-0 lead. The Stars had four in their four previous
games against the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of late, the guys have been playing offensive hockey more
and more and putting the puck in the net, and that's good to see,''
said Stars goalie Ed Belfour, who made 32 saves in his second game
back after missing five following his arrest March 8.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' usual suspects, Mike Modano and Jamie Langenbrunner,
scored. Add Brett Hull to that group, too. He got his second goal
in as many games. He has 608 goals in his career, tying him for
10th on the all-time list with Dino Ciccarelli and putting him two
behind his father, Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   Even Lukowich scored. His first goal as a winger turned out to
be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing well,'' Langenbrunner said. ``We're starting to
get things going.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner had two by himself, including a short-handed goal
to knot the game at 1-1. Not bad for a guy that until just a little
bit before game time wasn't going to play. His pinched nerve in his
neck flared up after Saturday's 2-2 tie with Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough stretch we've had, and I was feeling it,'' said
Langenbrunner, who received therapy on his neck and decided to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars finished a stretch of five games in eight days. They
were undefeated in that stretch. They scored 18 goals. Not that
goals haven't been easy to come by against San Jose lately. The
Sharks have allowed 17 goals in their past four games. Not even
their three goals, including two by captain Owen Nolan, could save
them against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still boils down to great defense, whether you like it or
not,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said. ``I think you can look at
the last four games and see what our goals against were. That
doesn't win you many games.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock couldn't agree more. He said defense
has been a key reason for the back-to-back-to-back-to-back 40-win
seasons for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown even though we've had a lot of players go through
here we've had that constant competitive nature about our group,''
Hitchcock said. Which is why as good as the Stars are playing now,
they say it isn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, they needed only to look to Saturday's game against
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could've really won big,'' Hitchcock said. ``We missed five
or six open nets. We were kind of tee-hee heeing, and we weren't
mad. That's the wrong attitude. We should've been really mad and
beared down.''
</P>
<P>
   No, that they saved for yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks felt the wrath for the Stars' inability to close on
the Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like `OK guys, we can leave everything out. Empty the
tank today,' '' Lukowich said. ``Whatever is left in the tank. We
were pretty empty as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   They've got four days to fill it up and another step to take.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
