r s BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SIDEBA     03-19 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE HAS BUILT THE FOUNDATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The sting from Pepperdine's 75-67 loss to
Oklahoma State in the second-round NCAA Tournament on Sunday was
beginning to fade a bit as the postgame media session wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense of pride for Tezale Archie, Tommie Prince,
Nick Sheppard and Brandon Armstrong as they filed out of the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   They came to Buffalo hoping to bring attention to the Waves'
nationally obscure program. They did so by routing Indiana in the
first round and keeping up with Oklahoma State in the second.
</P>
<P>
   People took notice, and one in particular wanted to make sure
they were aware of that. So a lone clap started as the Waves left
the interview room. A one-man ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry about that,'' Pepperdine coach Jan van Breda Kolff said
to no one in particular.
</P>
<P>
   It was van Breda Kolff, the Waves' first-year coach, who was
applauding.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am most proud about is the guys on this podium and the
guys inthe locker room,'' van Breda Kollf said. ``I've been
coaching for awhile and playing for awhile, and winning and losing
never gets old. Most of the time when you lose you are very
disappointed and you're usually madat yourself and players. This is
one of the few times in my career that there are no ill-effects. In
all my years of basketball, this is the team I've most enjoyed
being around on a day-to-day basis.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mutual feeling. All along the Waves have talked about van
Breda Kolff's impact. When he took over from Lorenzo Romar last
spring, van Breda Kolff replaced Romar's slow-down offense with an
uptempo, attacking system, giving them the freedom to play a style
they enjoyed more.
</P>
<P>
   He also let them express their individuality, allowing them to
grow their hair out and wear headbands.
</P>
<P>
   The players flourished, winning a school-record 25 games and
advancing to the second round of the NCAA Tournament for the first
time since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great the way coach van Breda Kolff has supported
us all the way,'' Tommie Prince said. ``He has been behind us
during the whole situation and has prepared us for each game. He
made sure that we were well prepared for anything we faced.''
</P>
<P>
   Archie, Sheppard and Prince graduate this year, leaving the
program to van Breda Kolff and underclassmen like Armstrong, Kelvin
Gibbs, Craig Lewis and David Lalazarian.
</P>
<P>
   After this weekend, there is something to build on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can start a dynasty,'' Archie said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
