<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2088 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-KNICKS-LAD     03-19 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KNICKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEAT KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a giddy commissioner in the stands, the NBC
marketing machine in overdrive and enough star power on the floor
to start a new galaxy, the NBA turned loose its Fantasy Finals on
Sunday afternoon. But just as the spotlights burned brightest came
the sudden, unexpected blackout.
</P>
<P>
   A Shaq-out, actually.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal made a mockery of the much-anticipated showdown
at sold-out Madison Square Garden, scoring 43 points and powering
the Los Angeles Lakers to a decidedly routine 92-85 victory over
the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the sizzle of a possible Finals preview, on the
NBA's grandest stage, with the league's marquee names playing
before a dozen stars (Spike Lee, Ice Cube, a Baldwin brother among
them) at courtside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the game lost energy,'' said Lakers coach Phil
Jackson. ``We were able to do kind of the mundane things to take
all of the excitement and the energy out of the game and get the
ball into Shaq, and he performed at a very high level.''
</P>
<P>
   For the ever-dominating Lakers (55-12), dull is good. Another
presumed test is brushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we sent a message to ourselves, more so than them,''
said Derek Fisher, ``that we can come into the mecca of basketball
against a good defensive team, a good basketball team as a whole,
and get a win. We didn't play perfect basketball, we didn't make
all our shots, we shot terrible from the free-throw line. We still
figured out a way to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   That proved to be as simple as feeding O'Neal, over and over and
over. Even with a sore right hamstring, even against Patrick Ewing,
O'Neal met little resistance, hitting 18 of 31 shots from the field
and 7 of 13 from the foul line to surpass the 40-point plateau for
the fourth time in the last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal appeared to wince a couple times, and asked out for a
short breather late in the third quarter, but if he's playing with
pain, ``I can't tell,'' said Glen Rice. ``If he is, he's doing a
great job of hiding it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been playing just unbelievable basketball,'' Rice said.
``You got a guy playing like that, you gotta continue to keep going
to him, and we're gonna go for that ride with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy decision. And a satisfying result for a Lakers team with
its eyes squarely on June, where the Knicks might be waiting for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets to that point, it will definitely give us a lot of
confidence,'' said Kobe Bryant, ``knowing that we can come in here,
a tough place to play, and win.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in doubt for only a half. Despite 24 points from
O'Neal, the Lakers trailed at halftime, 44-43, as the Knicks
enjoyed a 31-20 rebounding advantage and held Bryant and Rice in
check.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryant pumped in 17 of his 24 points in the second half and
combined with O'Neal to build an 11-point lead by the end of the
third. The Knicks never got closer than six points in the final
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe has been playing fabulous since the All-Star break,''
O'Neal said. ``We're going to be the one-two punch for a long time
to come. We're playing pretty good together right now. I'm proud of
Kobe.''
</P>
<P>
   No other Laker scored more than six points (Rice, Robert Horry)
as the team struggled to a 42.5 percent shooting day. But the
Lakers attacked the glass in the second half (outrebounding New
York, 28-15) and used their vaunted defense to hold the Knicks off.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing made just 6 of 20 shots for 12 points. Allan Houston
scored 20 points on 7-of-17 shooting. And Latrell Sprewell, guarded
primarily by Bryant, finished with 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   The teams meet again in two weeks at Staples Center, after which
they can ponder the ultimate rematch - ``I think the NBA would like
that very much,'' Bryant said of a Finals meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are certainly the team to beat,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van
Gundy said of the Lakers. ``At the same time, I think that in a
series they become tougher because of the dominance of O'Neal and
great team defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``How that plays out from here I don't know. But certainly and
clearly, they are the best team at this point of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
