<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2089 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-SEATT     03-19 1599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE CAPITAL MARKET BOOMING IN SEATTLE AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When George Clute founded Olympic Venture Partners in 1982, the
banker turned venture capitalist had to travel out of state to find
promising new start-up companies to fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just weren't enough quality deals in Seattle,'' said
Clute, whose Kirkland firm invested about 60 percent of its first
$25 million fund in California companies.
</P>
<P>
   Things have certainly changed. Partners at Olympic now spend
more time crossing the 520 bridge than buzzing down to San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume of projects and incredible depth of what is going
on in Seattle is so much beyond what it was a few years ago,'' said
Chad Waite, a partner at Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital, the gasoline that fuels technology,
communications and biotechnology start-ups, is growing at a furious
pace in the state. Privately held Washington companies pulled in
$1.2 billion in 1999, more than a 200 percent increase over the
prior year. Only New York, where companies attracted $1.8 billion,
had a faster growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   More money is on the way. And some say the Seattle metropolitan
area, where new home-grown venture funds are popping up like tulips
in the Skagit Valley sun, could become the fastest growth region in
the country for venture investments this year.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, more than $1 billion in new capital has been
raised by local venture capital firms.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ignition Corp., a Bellevue investment firm created by
former Microsoft and McCaw Cellular executives, began with $140
million in backing. Maveron, founded by former investment banker
Dan Levitan and Starbucks chief executive Howard Schultz, announced
a $340 million fund earlier this month. Madrona, a Seattle venture
capital firm and early backer of Amazon.com, pulled in $250 million
in December. And Voyager Capital is expected to announce a $212
million fund this month with 70 percent of the money to be invested
in Pacific Northwest companies.
</P>
<P>
   What does all of this new money mean?
</P>
<P>
   Those who follow the local high-tech economy say it could create
an even bigger technology boom in Seattle. After all, venture
investments have played a part in building nearly every one of
Seattle's publicly traded technology companies, from Amazon.com and
HomeGrocer.com to Avenue A and BSquare. And although not all of the
$1 billion will be invested locally, a good portion of the money
could find its way into Seattle start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The huge amounts of money being pooled in Seattle during the
past few months is a bit mind-boggling for old-time venture
capitalists like Clute. Partners at the firm's Carillon Point
office used to joke that they saw every business plan in town. Now
they can hardly keep up with the entrepreneurial activity. The firm
received about 1,200 new business plans last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved from single A ball into the major leagues,''
said Clute, whose firm raised a $150 million fund in December.
</P>
<P>
   With all of the new money, Seattle is on pace to surpass New
York this year as the fastest growth region in the country for
venture investments, said Kirk Walden, national director of venture
capital research at PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of oceans are being fished out, and Seattle is fresh
water,'' Walden said. ``Historically, Seattle has been a player in
the technology area but not necessarily in the financial area. ...
It is one of the natural places for the more formal venture capital
infrastructure to expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden says once the infrastructure is in place with ``half a
dozen brand name VCs,'' Seattle area entrepreneurs will come out of
the woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can act as a catalyst to get people to make that leap to
entrepreneurship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, the 15th most populous state, already leads the
nation in the formation of new companies. The rate of new company
growth is more than 20 percent higher than in California, according
to a report released earlier this month by the Washington
Technology Center. But Washington, the report found, has lagged
behind in the creation of venture capital funds to support those
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs have had to jump on commuter flights to San Jose,
San Francisco and New York if they wanted to raise money or seek
advice for their emerging businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's new crop of venture investors wants to plug up that
deal drain. ``The market opportunity (for new Seattle firms) is why
not fund Washington state companies with Washington state venture
funds,'' said Enrique Godreau, a managing director at Voyager
Capital.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just local funds establishing a presence in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Mohr Davidow Ventures, a Menlo Park, Calif.,
venture capital firm with stakes in Brocade Communications and
Onvia .com, announced that it would establish a branch office in
Seattle to be closer to the booming technology community here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Northwest has the entrepreneurs, the ideas and the
infrastructure necessary to be the next venture hotbed,'' said
Nancy Schoendorf, co-managing partner of the firm. ``MDV's strategy
of active involvement in the earliest stages of the business
require us to have a local presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Garage.com, a Palo Alto, Calif., company that links
entrepreneurs with investors, set up a Kirkland office last year.
Other Silicon Valley venture firms, such as Draper Fisher
Jurvetson, Oak Investment Partners and Red Leaf, are partnering
with Washington venture capital firms to ensure they get into the
early stage deals in the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Not every Silicon Valley money manager, however, feels the need
to have an office here. Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, an
investor in local companies such as Blue Nile, HomeGrocer.com and
Amazon.com, says it has no plans to open offices outside the San
Francisco Bay area. Neal Dempsey, a venture capitalist at Bay
Partners in Cupertino, said his firm, an investor in Bellevue-based
Wavtrace, would probably set up offices in Austin, Texas, or San
Diego before coming to Seattle. Still, the University of Washington
grad and native of Tacoma admits that Seattle's venture capital
community is booming and ``finally getting its just due?''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Audino has watched the venture capital infrastructure
develop in Seattle up close: first as a Microsoft manager then as a
co-founder of Voyager Capital. Audino, whose firm has backed Avenue
A, NetPodium and Tegic Communications, believes Seattle is
beginning to feel the effects of the venture capital boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area has the opportunity to be the No. 2 technology
center in the country because of the market leaders here in
software, telecommunications, e-commerce and streaming media,''
Audino said.
</P>
<P>
   But Audino also knows that it is important to have links to the
movers and shakers in California's technology community. That's a
big reason why Voyager Capital has hired a Stanford grad to set up
a branch office in Silicon Valley this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, more money means more competition. With talented
entrepreneurs leaving established companies like Microsoft, AT&AMP;T
Wireless and RealNetworks, Bill McAleer, a managing director at
Voyager Capital, predicts that Seattle venture capitalists will end
up competing vigorously to get into hot deals. The current
collaborative environment, where venture investors pass on hot tips
to other investors, could disappear, McAleer said. The new funds
also will continue to specialize in certain segments such as
business-to-business e-commerce or wireless communications in order
to differentiate themselves in an increasingly crowded market, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the strategy for the venture capital funds, the new
money pouring into the area is good news for entrepreneurs. For
those with a track record and a hot idea, venture dollars are
plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Sperry can attest to that. The former chief executive of
publicly traded Primus Knowledge Solutions, Sperry is now quickly
building a second start-up in Pioneer Square by the name of Acadio.
He has had no problem raising money from local investors and
venture capital firms to get the company off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredible place to raise money,'' said Sperry,
whose firm set out to raise a second venture round of $15 million
this winter and is expected to close on more than $30 million this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Tobias, founder of Seattle-based Loudeye Technologies,
said he is a big believer in the venture capital process. His
company, which raised $72 million in an IPO on Wednesday and now
has a market value of more than $1 billion, owes much of its
success to an early partnership with Olympic Venture Partners. A
former Microsoft manager, Tobias said money was not what he was
looking for when he started his streaming media company three years
ago. He needed the support, contacts and expertise of a local
venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the choice to go down to the Valley to raise money, but
I didn't because I wanted someone to be actively involved early on
in the daily running of the business,'' Tobias said. ``I couldn't
get that from a Bay Area firm.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobias, who has invested his own money in several local venture
firms, said it is about time that Seattle established a strong
venture capital infrastructure to support local entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting to the point where there's enough competition
among venture funds to give entrepreneurs a lot of opportunities
rather than a handful,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
