<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRYSDALE'S DERBY HOPES BEGINNING TO MULTIPLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The only time Neil Drysdale went to Churchill
Downs with plans to start a horse in the Kentucky Derby, the colt
named A.P. Indy bruised a hoof and had to be scratched on the
morning of the race.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Drysdale might be able to bring a spare.
</P>
<P>
   The English-born, Hollywood Park-based trainer, already
polishing one Derby contender in San Rafael Stakes winner War
Chant, displayed a second in the $250,000 San Felipe on Sunday when
Fusaichi Pegasus turned back The Deputy and left Anees a rusty
third at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus ($4.60), ridden confidently by Kent Desormeaux,
won the 1 1/16-mile race by three-quarters of a length in 1:42.66
without being whipped, satisfying the curiosity a $4 million horse
with bandages on all four ankles is bound to inspire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got there yet,'' Drysdale, with characteristic
caution, said of the May 6 Kentucky Derby. ``When we go into the
(starting) gate, we'll know we got there.''
</P>
<P>
   But after becoming the first trainer to win the two major Santa
Anita Derby preps with different horses, Drysdale can at least plot
his path to Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   He said Irving and Marjorie Cowan's War Chant, 3 for 3 after
leading the San Rafael gate to wire on March 4, will use the April
8 Santa Anita Derby as his steppingstone to Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding an intrabarn clash, Drysdale said Fusaichi Pegasus,
owned by retired high-tech executive Fusao Sekiguchi of Tokyo, will
go to the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct or the Blue Grass Stakes at
Keeneland. Both races are April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, 3 for 4 after winning his first try at the
stakes level, was bought at a Kentucky yearling auction for $4
million. Drysdale said the four wraps are merely precautionary,
``because he's such a big,heavy horse.''
</P>
<P>
   A.P. Indy cost $2.9 million. After Drysdale scratched him on
Derby day, he went on to win the 1992 Belmont Stakes and the Horse
of the Year title.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale's failure to run a horse in the Derby is the glaring
hole in a quarter-century career that has earned the 52-year-old a
spot on the 1999 and 2000 Hall of Fame ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back east: California connections did well in New
York too on Sunday as favored Red Bullet and jockey Alex Solis
outfinished Bobby Frankel-trained Aptitude to win the $200,000
Gotham Stakes at Aqueduct by a half-length. Red Bullet, owned by
Santa Anita chairman Frank Stronach, is unbeaten in only three
starts.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-mile Wood is next for the top two. They may have to face
Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: In a winner's-circle presentation ceremony, Mike Smith
thanked his fellow jockeys for voting him the 50th George Woolf
Award recipient, which annually honors a rider for his career and
character. ``You inspired me to be not only the best rider I could
be, but also the best person I could be,'' said the two-time
Eclipse Award winner, whose mother and brother traveled from New
Mexico to Santa Anita for the occasion. ... Wheelaway, the
favorite, won the Tampa Bay Derby. ... Although Drysdale is the
first trainer to win the San Rafael and San Felipe with different
horses, Bruce Headley (Variety Road, 1986) and Jerry Fanning
(Desert Wine, 1983) won both with one horse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
