<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-     03-19 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENGUINS NIP RANGERS, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Jaromir Jagr celebrated his return to the
Pittsburgh Penguins with three assists on Sunday night. But as big
a pain as Jagr was to the New York Rangers, one of their former
teammates proved to be even deadlier to their playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei Kovalev, traded to the Penguins in November 1998 in a
deal for Petr Nedved, scored his 21st goal of the season and
assisted on three others, including the tying goal, as the Penguins
rallied for a 5-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins, who triumphed after squandering three one-goal
leads, claimed sole possession of seventh place in the Eastern
Conference, with 74 points. Montreal, idle on Sunday, dropped to
eighth (the final playoff spot) with 73 points. With just eight
games left in their regular season, the Rangers are ninth with 72
points, followed by Buffalo with 71 and Carolina with 70.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalev and Jagr formed a joint wrecking crew on Sunday night.
Each right wing assisted on goals 43 seconds apart early in the
third period _ Martin Straka's second of the game at 6 minutes 19
seconds, tying it at 4-4, and Jiri Slegr's game-winner at 7:02.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalev, one of the heroes of the Rangers' 1994 Stanley Cup run,
tied a career high with his 4 points on Sunday night. In 13 games
against the Rangers, Kovalev has 6 goals and 8 assists. Jagr,
meanwhile, seemed to be getting stronger with every shift.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter returned in goal after sitting out the Rangers'
last two games because of a sore left knee that has bothered him
since the All-Star Game break. But Nedved (bruised ribs) and Jan
Hlavac (left hip pointer) _ two-thirds of the Rangers' vaunted
Czech line _ each missed their second straight game.
</P>
<P>
   And the Penguins, who had beaten the Rangers here, 3-1, eight
days earlier without their top two scorers, were back at full
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr was back after missing the last 12 games. Jagr, who now
leads the league in scoring with 88 points even though he had only
played 55 games, was playing for the first time since Feb. 21, when
he injured his left hamstring against Tampa Bay. Five days before
that, Jagr had been kneed in the left thigh by Buffalo's Mike Peca.
Complications from the charley horse that resulted from Peca's hit
kept Jagr out of the Pittsburgh lineup until Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr responded with a pair of second-period assists. It was
obvious he was not fully recovered, but his presence seemed to
motivate the Penguins, who scored just 3:13 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came not from Jagr's newly formed Czech line, which had
Josef Beranek at left wing and Jan Hrdina at center, but from a
setup by Kovalev.
</P>
<P>
   Straka, who was standing alone in the slot, took a centering
pass from Kovalev and beat Richter inside the right post. And for
the fifth consecutive game, the Rangers had allowed the game's
first goal, this time on the third shot.
</P>
<P>
   At least it had not come on the first shot, something that had
happened to the Rangers in their last two games. But Pittsburgh did
have the first seven shots of the game.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's 3-2 victory in Philadelphia, the Rangers kept the
Flyers at bay in the third period, even though New York failed to
register a shot on goal for the final 14:35. On Sunday night, the
Rangers did not record their first shot until 7:23 had elapsed,
meaning that they had gone without a shot for the equivalent of
more than a period.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who were 0 for 9 on the power play over their
previous three games, went 0 for 3 on the power play during the
first period, including the 1:29 of 5-on-3 action.
</P>
<P>
   They made it 1-1 on a goal from their checking line, Eric
Lacroix's clumsy backhander from just off the crease beat
Jean-Sebastien Aubin at 16:46.
</P>
<P>
   And then it became a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Janne Laukkanen blasted a power-play one-timer from between the
two circles and almost at the blue line at 5:29 of the second. At
13:35, Mike York blasted a slap shot from the right circle that
beat Aubin for York's 23d goal.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalev gave the Penguins their third one-goal lead at 16:27,
beating Richter with the teams skating four on a side. The Rangers
answered with goals 13 seconds apart. Valery Kamensky scored his
13th of the season, and fifth in his last 5 games, at 17:50,
sweeping the rebound of a Kim Johnsson shot past Aubin from off the
right post. And then John MacLean pounced on a loose puck in the
slot after Brian Leetch had pin-balled the puck into the offensive
zone. MacLean's shot went through Aubin's legs at 18:03.
</P>
<P>
   After rallying three times from one-goal deficits, the Rangers
took a 4-3 lead into the final period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
