<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2097 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-WYLY-AZR &LR;      03-19 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WYLY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA CLUB: WYLY ADS `FIRST SALVO IN GENERAL ELECTIONS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
   
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   didates, environmentalists most fear Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the $2 million in attack ads by Bush backers on the
environmental record of Arizona Sen. John McCain were sheer
hypocrisy _ and false to boot.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-Super Tuesday primary ads were paid for by Bush
supporter and fellow Texan Sam Wyly, a billionaire businessman who
is pushing clean energy after contributing to lawmakers who have
voted to weaken the federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could think of no better way to get the public's attention
. . . than to launch our cause in the key primary states where the
eyes of the world were focused,'' said Wyly, chairman of his
family's newly formed ``Republicans for Clean Air.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyly cited these goals: cleaner, renewable energy from solar,
wind, water and natural gas; pollution controls on older,
coal-fired power plants; and awareness of clean-air issues within
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But if the recent ads were any gauge for the future, Republicans
for Clean Air will be more about generating spin than eliminating
smog.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore can expect special interests to spend
millions to tar him in the same way Wyly did McCain, said Daniel
Weiss, political director of the 600,000-member Sierra Club. It's
the nation's most politically active environmental group, having
itself spent nearly $100,000 to criticize Bush's environmental
record, and more than $1 million in campaign contributions Bush has
received from polluting industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``One could look at this (Wyly) ad campaign not as the last ads
of the primaries but the first salvo in the general election,''
Weiss said, ``as Bush and his supporters attempt to paint his brown
record green.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sierra Club research, Texas leads the nation in
toxic releases, toxic air emissions from industries, toxic chemical
accidents and cancer-causing pollution, and it is home to Houston,
which last year surpassed Los Angeles as the nation's ``smog
capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Club president Carl Pope urged Wyly to pull the ads
because they ``paint a false picture of Gov. Bush's poor record
governing the most polluted state in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, President Clinton rode to a second White House
term with the mantra: ``Medicaid, Medicare, education and the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Nov. 7 general election, Gore's major points of division
with Bush will be: gun control, abortion rights, campaign-finance
reform and _ again _ the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyly campaign ads brought to the fore both campaign-finance
reform and the environment, though not necessarily in the way Wyly
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The ads criticized McCain and praised Bush but did not overtly
say ``Vote for Bush.'' Still, by running the ads in the key primary
states of New York, Ohio and California the week before the March 7
primaries, their timing brought into question their legality.
</P>
<P>
   Such an ad blitz, if done with the cooperation of the Bush
campaign, could be in violation of campaign-finance laws, and the
ads' failure to properly disclose their sponsors could be in
violation of Federal Communication Commission rules, according to
Roy Fletcher, deputy campaign manager for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far as we have been able to determine, this organization
(Republicans for Clean Air) has no legal existence other than as a
front for the Bush presidential campaign,'' Fletcher wrote in a
March 2 letter to the enforcement division of the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Republicans for Clean Air put out a press release
revealing their identities. On March 8, the day after the
primaries, Wyly mailed copies of the ads and a letter explaining
his group to reporters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rolling out the welcome mat to all Americans who care
about the good cause of clean air. This is only our first week, and
our family is the first to join. But we intend to build a permanent
nationwide Republicans for Clean Air advocacy organization,'' Wyly
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintained that his campaign had no prior knowledge of the
Wyly ads. Yet the commercials were funded by the same folks who
have been some of Bush's biggest campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly and his brother, Charles, gave Bush a total of $210,000 for
his 1994 and 1998 gubernatorial races. Charles Wyly is a Bush
``Pioneer,'' that is, one of 200 wealthy individuals who have
pledged to raise at least $100,000 for Bush's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's backers linked the placement of the Wyly ads to Tony
Fabrizio, who they said also placed ads last year slamming
publisher Steve Forbes in the name of the ``Republican Leadership
Council,'' which the McCain camp identified as a Bush campaign
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Bush . . . to claim ignorance of these ads is far beyond
incredible,'' said McCain 2000 campaign manager Rick Davis. ``It
miserably fails the political sniff test.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Wyly called the ads ``issues advocacy advertising,'' the
first action financed by Wyly following last month's $7.9 billion
sale of Sterling Software and Sterling Commerce, software and
e-commerce businesses that Wyly co-founded.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based Wyly got his start in the mining and
oil-refining businesses. Today, Wyly wears many hats: chairman of
Michaels Stores, the nation's largest chain of arts and crafts
stores; the founder of Maverick Capital, a hedge fund with several
billion in assets; and chairman of Green Mountain Energy, which he
describes as the nation's leading retailer of environmentally clean
electricity, serving 100,000 customers in California and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to the Sierra Club, Wyly and his family have
contributed more than $200,000 to ``dirty air'' members of
Congress. The latest Wyly ad campaign, the environmentalists say,
is filled with half-truths.
</P>
<P>
   As the Wyly ad showed a photo of smokestacks against a clear
dawn, the voice-over said, ``He (Bush) led one of the first states
in America to clamp down on old, coal-burning electric power
plants.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sierra Club, citing published sources, said Bush's
``clamp-down'' was a voluntary plan, written by industry; that only
33 of the 166 biggest industrial plants in Texas have volunteered
to participate, and of those only three have taken steps to cut
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   The Wyly ad showed a photo of Bush over a background of green
fields, as the narrator says, ``Bush clean-air laws will reduce air
pollution more than a quarter-million tons a year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sierra Club's analysis shows Bush's actions would reduce
pollution by less than half that amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frightening thing for democracy,'' said the Sierra Club's
Weiss, ``is that we've never seen a small set of individuals spend
so much money trying to defeat one candidate and get another
candidate elected.''
</P>
<P>
   But the worst is yet to come, Weiss predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wyly brothers will be the tip of the soft money iceberg''
in the 2000 presidential election. &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Steve.Yozwiak(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or at
(602) 444-8810. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
