<SLUG> BC-BOEING-STRIKE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING STRIKE IS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The longest engineering strike in the history of The Boeing Co.
is over.
</P>
<P>
   Striking Boeing engineers and technical workers Sunday said it
was time to return to work, voting by a more than two-to-one margin
to accept the company's latest offer and end a 40-day strike.
</P>
<P>
   The vote capped an unprecedented walkout by between 15,000 and
18,000 engineers and technical workers that backed up airplane
deliveries, slowed key defense work and took a chunk out of the
company's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   The striking workers begin returning this morning at 9 a.m.,
though the company agreed to give workers who need it as long as
two weeks to leave other jobs or commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technical community has found its strength and its voice
and we intend to continue to use it in powerful and positive
ways,'' said Charles Bofferding, executive director of the Society
of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps were feeling increasing pressure as the strike
entered its second month. Boeing customers were beginning to cancel
flights while union members were facing mounting financial
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides saw that this thing was about to escalate,'' said
Richard Trumka, the secretary-treasurer of the AFL-CIO, who both
said said played a key role in brokering an agreement in
Washington, D.C., last week.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers approved the contract by a vote of 3,825 to 1,526
or 71.5 percent in favor; technical workers approved it by 3,042 to
1,259 or 70.7 percent margin.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the two sides have settled their differences, they face
the daunting task of eliminating a backlog of work. They must also
repair relations between union members and management and between
those who crossed the picket lines and those who didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to get back to a family,'' Bofferding said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing must also untangle the snags on its production lines, in
its laboratories and elsewhere that the absence of most of its
engineers and technicians created. The company only recently
rebounded from production line problems that dogged it in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Boeing executives were still assessing the damage of the
strike and they could offer their initial estimate as early as
tomorrow, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Although union negotiators unanimously endorsed the contract
offer, and sold it to their members all weekend, it wasn't always
an easy sale.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance to the proposal fueled a desire for a greater show of
respect and better compensation from Boeing, some union members
said. They complained that they spent 40 days in the rain, sleet
and occasional sunlight for a contract that did little more than
preserve the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't accomplish anything,'' said Omar Zubi, an engineer
at Boeing's Renton plant who has spent three years at the company.
``If you take my jacket and I take it back I did not win.''
</P>
<P>
   But, others said they wouldn't gain much by staying on the
picket lines for another two weeks or longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides could have sustained significant further damage,''
said Craig Buckham, the president of the union.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the raft of concessions that Boeing made during the
last round of talks helped win over a majority of the striking
workers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the union fought off the company's drive to impose
healthcare premiums on engineers and technical workers. During the
last three months, Boeing executives repeatedly stressed the move
was a vital part of their plan to control expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The company also boosted the amount in guaranteed raises it was
willing to offer every year. Under the contract, technical
employees are guaranteed a four-percent raise in the first year, a
three-percent raise in the second and a three-percent raise in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers would receive at least a three-percent raise every
year.
</P>
<P>
   The company provided additional money for merit raises,
employees with special skills, such as software engineers, and
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders also secured a bonus for members. But the size and
structure of the payments left many members disappointed or angry.
</P>
<P>
   The company promised workers $1,000 if they ratified the pact.
But, workers would need to hit two separate airplane delivery
targets to collect another $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Once Boeing makes 225 deliveries this year, employees would
receive another $500. And they would collect an additional $1,000
if the company hits its target of 491 airplane deliveries by Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   The payments, however, fall far short of the bonuses that Boeing
handed to members of the International Association of Machinists
and Aerospace Workers last year. Those payments averaged $4,400.
</P>
<P>
   Other key provisions include:
</P>
<P>
   Allowing employees to cover same-sex domestic partners under
Boeing's medical benefits plan. No time is set for implementation.
</P>
<P>
   Boosting pension contributions to $50 per month from the current
$40 level.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a joint union-executive leadership council to examine
health care, quality efficiency and a host of other issues.
</P>
<P>
   As workers prepared to return to the job this morning, they were
unclear as to what management's priorities would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be everything at once,'' said Rick Plunkett,
contract administrator for the union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
