<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2101 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      03-19 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN FACES HOT SEAT IN SENATE; VETERANS ANGRY OVER HEALTH PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In returning to the U.S. Senate, John McCain of Arizona will
rejoin the national battle over health-care benefits for thousands
of veterans and current members of the military.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is sponsoring legislation to address complaints about
TRICARE, the military's experiment in managed care that has been
roundly criticized by active duty military and retirees alike.
</P>
<P>
   As it was during the GOP primaries, however, that the
politically active retiree community is divided over McCain's role
in the debate. &QL; 
 &UR; LOYALTY TO CAUSE CHALLENGED &QL; 
While the powerful Military Coalition has praised McCain for his
efforts on behalf of its constituents, others are challenging
McCain's loyalty to the cause of restoring lifetime health-care
benefits to career military people.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Slough, 60, of Huachuca City, an Army special forces
retiree who served in Vietnam, accused McCain and other early
TRICARE supporters of betraying a government promise to provide
lifetime health care to military retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we were expected to do _ and now we get the
shaft,'' Slough said.
</P>
<P>
   Slough's comments have been echoed by other retirees whose
benefits eroded and free health care disappeared after reform
legislation was ushered through Congress in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain has long been considered an advocate for
veterans, the hot-button issue of health care cost him some of
their votes during the presidential primaries. One group, the
Coalition of Retired Military Veterans, based in South Carolina,
repeatedly broadsided McCain during the race and backed his rival,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIDE'S MOTIVES QUESTIONED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its gripe with McCain: he helped craft legislation establishing
TRICARE, and he did it with the help of an aide whose motives they
suspect. &QL; 
The onetime aide, David McIntyre, 37, wrote some of the proposals
that became part of TRICARE before leaving McCain's staff in August
1993 to join Blue Cross Blue Shield of Arizona. There, he put
together a corporation composed mostly of Blue Cross organizations
to bid on a contract to manage TRICARE's health maintenance
organization in 16 central and Southwestern states including
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, TriWest Healthcare Alliance, won the $2.5
billion contract in June 1996. Headed by McIntyre, its bid was
challenged by a local competitor. The challenge was withdrawn when
TriWest negotiated a financial settlement and offered the
competitor a subcontract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you categorically that TriWest did not request any
type of congressional or senatorial intervention with the
Department of Defense,'' TriWest spokesman Bob Wolfersteig said.
``It would probably be the kiss of death if we got any sort of
senatorial interference.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't prevented top officers of TriWest and Blue Cross
from being politically active: they and their spouses have
contributed $18,000 to McCain's campaigns since 1997, according to
a database maintained by the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACTIONS SPLIT ON MCCAIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James F. Gunn, a retired Marine heading the Coalition of Retired
Military Veterans, believes McCain has lost credibility with some
retirees because of his role in promoting a health program that
many find offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet retired Air Force Col. Paul Arcari, director of government
relations for the 400,000-member Retired Officers Association, said
McCain has been ``a solid, consistent supporter of the uniformed
services community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to point a lot of fingers and blame people for
something that looked like a great idea at the time,'' Arcari said.
``But you can't blame any one person.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's office did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Senate Armed Services committee, McCain, a
former Navy flier and ex-prisoner of war, was among a number of
lawmakers in both chambers who haggled to forge the new military
health-care system. Based on a test program dating to the late
1980s, it was incrementally imposed in annual defense authorization
legislation between 1991 and 1994. It has been tinkered with ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department hired contractors in 11 &UR; regions to manage
a network of physicians and hospitals to provide private care
supplementing the shrinking number of military health-care
facilities. Costing roughly $17 billion a year, the military system
serves as many retirees as active service members.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPROVEMENT IS TOP PRIORITY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has been so widely criticized that Gen. Henry Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, vowed to make its
improvement a top priority in the coming budget year.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the past six years, they've torn the guts out of the
military health care system,'' complained retired Air Force Col.
Bruce Mikesell of Maryland, who has helped lobby Congress on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Until the early 1990s, lifelong health care for military members
was assured. Free care was available at military facilities. If
members went off base, the Civilian Health and Medical Program of
the Uniformed Services (CHAMPUS) covered 80 percent of costs.
</P>
<P>
   Dependents and retirees got free care at military facilities on
a space-available basis, and they could use CHAMPUS for private
care until age 65, when they moved onto Medicare rolls. Even then,
they were still eligible for free care at military facilities.
</P>
<P>
   By the early '90s, however, the system was forced to retool amid
spiraling health-care costs, deep cuts in defense spending, a
shrinking military and base closures. Military health facilities
were going out of business, crowding those that remained and making
access a huge issue for many of the insured. &QL; 
 &UR; VETERANS LOSING OUT ON CARE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, retirees were squeezed out of free care because
there was no longer space. Privatization became the buzzword.
</P>
<P>
   TRICARE offers three options: a traditional 80-20 insurance plan
for active military, and 75-25 coverage for retirees; a slightly
less expensive preferred provider plan operated through a network
of private caregivers; and the cheapest option, a health
maintenance organization administered by contractors through
TRICARE's network of providers. The latter uses remaining military
facilities and a network of private providers.
</P>
<P>
   Active service members and their families have free enrollment
in the HMO and pay nominal co-payments only if they go to private
physicians instead of military facilities. Even so, they face
numerous bureaucratic obstacles, key among them that the HMO
network is not available in some parts of the country or overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, retirees and their dependents must pay to belong to
any of the plans. Often, the cheapest HMO option isn't available,
and since most military medical facilities are jammed year-round,
free care at military facilities is largely gone. In most regions
of the country, retirees over 65 also are forced to leave TRICARE
and go onto Medicare rolls, losing pharmacy benefits and reducing
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after TRICARE was enacted, retiree organizations sued,
saying they'd been promised free lifetime benefits. A federal judge
ruled last year that only Congress could rectify the problem. The
U.S. Supreme Court has now been asked to review the case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONGRESS LOOKING AT CHANGES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate Armed Services committees are considering
legislation to make the plans cheaper _ or free _ and more
accessible for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Other bills would make affordable or free prescription drugs
readily available, cut TRICARE bureaucracy and help retirees over
65 find alternatives to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Military Coalition supports legislation sponsored by McCain
restoring free lifetime care to retirees who enlisted before
mid-1956 and giving retirees over 65 the option of enrolling in an
HMO or joining the civilian Federal Employee Health Benefits
Program.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Slough, the Huachuca City vet, wonders why McCain
and other lawmakers didn't see the disaster looming when TRICARE
was launched in the early '90s. He thinks the system's only effect
was to fatten health care contractors at the expense of those who
gave their best years to the military.
</P>
<P>
   Now living with debilitating effects of advanced-stage diabetes,
Slough is in danger of losing his legs. He refuses to seek medical
care under TRICARE. He buys his drugs in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will die before I pay again for something I already
earned,'' Slough said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-00 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
