<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-19 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2102 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-19 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA SHOWS IT'S NOT MERELY A CINDERELLA STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ Are there any more questions about Gonzaga? Can
there be?
</P>
<P>
   Are there any more doubts?
</P>
<P>
   Any more jokers who can't get off this Cinderella nonsense, such
as, for instance, CBS, which was seen displaying an ``If the
slipper fits ...'' graphic during its broadcast Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   What the so-called experts should really start doing is talking
about this Gonzaga team as one of the most tough, skilled,
versatile, fun and disciplined squads ever to hit the NCAA
hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't a Cinderella surprise. They're the poster boys for
what happens when skilled, athletic, hungry and determined
basketball players meld as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, some teams don't get along as much as ours does. It's a
shame,'' forward Casey Calvary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real fun sport when you really like your teammates and
everybody gets along and you are kind of rolling. That's why we've
had success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we'd have lost, we still wouldn't have been arguing
amongst ourselves. We just never do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely the nation's growing legion of Zag fans would have been
pleased if Gonzaga had managed to ``merely'' slip by St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what the Zags did against the fellas from the big, bad
Big East was nothing less than a textbook dress-down.
</P>
<P>
   With a killer game plan and impressive execution, the Zags
showed they were far more than senior guard Richie Frahm getting on
a hot shooting streak or Matt Santangelo bailing them out with his
clutch play.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Zags relentlessly attacked St. John's with an
inside-out game that, well, has helped turn the West Region inside
out.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Zags now the favorites in the West?
</P>
<P>
   The Zags play Thursday against Purdue, while LSU and Wisconsin
will join them from Salt Lake City after Arizona was crushed by the
Badgers and St. John's was drilled by the Zags Saturday, 82-76.
</P>
<P>
   But don't ask Gonzaga any of that stuff about who's the favorite
because you know what these guys are going to say:
</P>
<P>
   This coming weekend in Albuquerque at the West Region Finals is
a four-team tournament and that's the only way to look at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to be here. Happy to be a 10 seed or whatever,''
senior center Axel Dench said. ``There are 16 teams left and now
it's a more level playing field, but it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it doesn't matter. Not now, not after Dench teamed up with
Calvary on Saturday and displayed an inside power game that
completely overwhelmed St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   When Calvary went to the bench with two quick fouls early in the
first half, Dench was a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   He called for the ball. He backed down in the post and found
little resistance from a St. John's team whose lack of height
became a glaring weakness and worse when they made no adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga coach Mark Few said his 6-10 Australian center has been
the difference over the last month and half.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we hit that little lull late in the league season, he
started to understand that we needed his physical presence
inside,'' Few said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always had that nice 3 and, typical of an overseas
player, he always prefers to filter out there and explore that. He
did that again (against St. John's). I had to pull him out and
explain he's spending far too much time in the perimeter and we
needed him to slide in there and start going to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``To his credit, he did. And that might be as big a change as
we've had from the dog days of February to right now. He's become a
force.''
</P>
<P>
   With Calvary getting so much attention for his strong play
inside, Dench, too, realized he could ratchet up his power game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got beat by a couple of teams we shouldn't have,'' Dench
said. ``They just out-muscled us and the coaches challenged us to
not look to the referees for any help. During practice, we
literally beat each other up. Hey, no referees are calling fouls
here. So come game time, if I get the ball inside and no one sinks
down, if I get fouled, I get fouled. You have to answer the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a three-weapon attack with Richie, Matt and Casey
and I kind of slip in and have two big games. So now people have to
say, `Oh, now they have four weapons.'''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just on the offensive end of the floor, either. St.
John's continued to run the same schemes the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   Dench said he was surprised by St. John's eventual level of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if it was a team thing, but we kind of countered
their offense and found out how to shut that down,'' Dench said.
``But they continued to run the same offense, which kind of
surprised us. I said, `Well, if you're just going to keep running
into a brick wall, then we'll just happily let you keep doing
that.' Even when we took the lead, they didn't change things and
it's like `Hey, that's your loss.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're clicking, we're helping down. We're rotating
around. We can do some damage on man-to-man and plus the zone.
We've got that working finally.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Dench and the inside-out game that the Zags executed so
successfully against St. John's is heading down to New Mexico,
where someone reminded Dench that fellow Australian Luc Longley
played college hoops.
</P>
<P>
   For the Zags, a repeat of Dench's game against St. John's could
come in handy against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot that Luc went down there. But yeah, if his mojo is
still down there and working, I'll rub my head on the ground and
try and get some of that going for me,'' Dench said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the Zags, they'll all rub their heads in the dirt with
Dench. The team that gets down and dirty together usually has a
good time winning. Or at least that's the case when it comes to the
Zags.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
